u s BC-FBN-FAME-MONTANA-HNS &LR;      07-30 1603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FAME-MONTANA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Montana an extraordinary Joe
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN McCLAIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CANTON, Ohio _ When he was inducted into the Pro Football Hall of
Fame on Saturday, it would have been difficult to find anyone in
the record crowd of more than 20,000 who would have argued that Joe
Montana was not the greatest quarterback in football history.
</P>
<P>
   No quarterback in history has better credentials than Montana.
He was a Parade All-American, helped Notre Dame win a national
championship and led the San Francisco 49ers to four Super Bowl
victories.
</P>
<P>
   Montana was voted the NFL's Most Valuable Player three times. He
was a Super Bowl MVP three times. On Saturday, he was enshrined
with the game's greatest players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe had that El Cid aura,'' said former Raiders defensive end
Howie Long, who was enshrined with Montana. ``He could've been
dead, but they could've marched him out on a horse, and just the
sight of him would've made the enemy retreat.''
</P>
<P>
   In a 16-year career, including the first 14 with San Francisco,
Montana had a flair for the dramatic that made Hollywood
screenwriters envious. He was at his best when the pressure was on,
directing 31 come-from-behind victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe had the right stuff, and he wasn't afraid to make a
mistake,'' said former 49ers defensive back Ronnie Lott, who also
was inducted Saturday. ``In practice, we were competing against the
best, and we wanted to beat the heck out of him. Even though it was
practice, going against Joe so many times helped me understand why
players and coaches who played against us got so frustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   In four Super Bowl appearances, Montana never suffered an
interception, despite throwing 122 passes. He completed 83 of 122
passes for 1,142 yards and 11 touchdowns. His passer rating for
Super Bowls was 127.8.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe was the most fierce competitor I've ever been around, and
he's smarter than a lot of people give him credit for,'' said
Cleveland Browns vice president of football operations Dwight
Clark, who was one of Montana's favorite receivers. ``He was
relentless, and it didn't matter what he was doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early in our careers, we played things like video games and
pool. He was good at everything. If you could beat him at something
he hadn't played as much, he'd master it in a matter of hours. When
we played pool, Joe was always thinking ahead as if he was setting
up the next two shots. He was always that far ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   During a 10-year period _ 1981 through 1990 _ the 49ers finished
first in the NFC West eight times and second once.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Joe hadn't played football, I'm sure he would have used his
personality and competitiveness to prevail in whatever line of work
he chose,'' said Browns president Carmen Policy, who had the same
position with the 49ers during Montana's career. ``He could have
become a golf hustler. He's a pretty good golfer.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you can imagine, he's great in the clutch. When the money's
on the line, I'm going to bet on Joe to make that putt.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't Montana's physical stature that intimidated opponents.
He was 6 feet, 2 inches and 195 pounds during his career, which is
one reason he lasted until the third round of the 1979 NFL draft
and three quarterbacks _ Jack Thompson, Phil Simms and Steve Fuller
_ were selected ahead of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I saw him I was sitting at the counter in a
restaurant at our first minicamp,'' Clark said. ``In walked this
scrawny-looking guy with a Fu Manchu mustache. He looked like a
kicker. I was blown away when I found out that was Joe Montana.''
</P>
<P>
   Three seasons later, Montana and Clark would combine on one of
the most famous plays in NFL history.
</P>
<P>
   Under Bill Walsh, the 49ers had finished 3-13 in 1981. They
hosted the Dallas Cowboys in the NFC Championship Game. Trailing
27-21 in the final minutes, the 49ers had the ball at their 11-yard
line.
</P>
<P>
   With 51 seconds remaining, Clark caught Montana's desperation
pass in the end zone for the winning touchdown that would go down
in history as ``The Catch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That pass to Dwight was one of two plays that really stand out
for me,'' Montana said. ``It was a pivotal play in 49ers history
and a defining moment in my career.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other play was the touchdown pass to (John) Taylor in the
Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   In Super Bowl XXIII, the 49ers trailed Cincinnati 16-13 with
3:20 remaining. San Francisco got the ball at its eight-yard line.
With 34 seconds left, Montana threw a 10-yard touchdown pass to
Taylor that produced a 20-16 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to treat every minute of the game the same and not
worry whether it was the fourth quarter or the first quarter,''
Montana said. ``I tried to do that with my personality as well.
Whether we were behind or ahead, I tried to be the same person
until the game was over.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he grew up in Monongahela, Pa., which is about 25 miles
from Pittsburgh, and his family visited relatives in Canton often,
Montana never dreamed about making the Pro Football Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   However, his father Joe Sr. recalls a family trip to the Hall of
Fame when his son was 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked him, `Someday, how would you like to be here?''' the
elder Montana said. ``I said, `If you want to be here, it's going
to take a lot of work and dedication on your part.' And here he
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Montana, known as Joe Cool to his teammates, said, ``The Hall of
Fame was never something that was really tangible to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy for us _ players and coaches _ to say, `I'm going to
be in the NFL. I want to win the Super Bowl. Or I want to throw
this many touchdown passes.' Those are things you can achieve by
working hard and making it happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get in the Hall of Fame, you have to rely on what others
think about you. When I was a kid, we had family in Canton, and we
used to visit all the time. But I never let myself dream about
being in the Hall of Fame because it wasn't something tangible I
could work on.''
</P>
<P>
   University of Houston fans experienced Montana's magic before
the rest of the nation knew who he was.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1979 Cotton Bowl, the University of Houston played Notre
Dame in the worst conditions in the bowl's history. Sub-freezing
temperatures left the field covered with ice. Despite the horrible
weather, the Cougars built a 34-12 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Montana was so cold he had to be fed soup in the dressing room
to keep warm, but he rallied the Fighting Irish from the 22-point
deficit midway through the fourth quarter to an improbable 35-34
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``You knew there was something special because he worked hard,
and he wanted it,'' Clark said. ``He was a terrible loser. He had
to win. It was the only thing that mattered to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe had such great vision. He could always find the open guy.
If he had to throw a pass where you ended up getting smashed, he
would run down there, help you up and apologize.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew that offense so well and could see the field so well
that 95 percent of the time he would find the open guy. That's
probably why a lot of his receivers were able to play so long. They
didn't get killed after the catch.''
</P>
<P>
   Montana was always uncomfortable in the spotlight. On the field
with 10 other offensive players, he was magnificent. His actions
spoke more eloquently than anything he could have said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that huddle with your peers, he could get fired up when he
needed to,'' Clark said. ``He was very calm under pressure. With
people talking in the huddle, he could easily quiet the huddle
down. He had everybody's attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he started talking, everybody was listening to him. And
when he would give directions or change a little something about a
play or tell you, `Be ready, I might come to you,' you knew it
wasn't bull. You knew he had something up in his mind that he had
seen before, and he was going to take advantage of.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, Joe's easily the greatest quarterback of all time.
Obviously, I'm biased, but in that offense, he was unstoppable. I
think four Super Bowl rings validates the point.''
</P>
<P>
   Montana might get physically ill if he was forced to be drawn
into a long conversation about the best quarterback in NFL history.
He would never say he was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just happy to be mentioned in the same breath as a lot of
those guys,'' he said. ``It's impossible to compare quarterbacks
from different eras. The game has changed so much from when those
guys played and I played. In some cases, some of those guys had
almost a round ball to throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just honored to be in Canton with so many great players,
including all those great quarterbacks who got here before me.''
</P>
<P>
   Montana is a family man who doesn't have to worry about money.
He still does commercial endorsements, but you won't find him doing
anything that requires a lot of talking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still live life like a kid, and I hope I never have to grow
up,'' he said. ``The other day, Jennifer (his wife) told me to
straighten my shoulders, that I was slumping too much again.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most other members of the Hall of Fame, Montana wishes he
could still put on the pads and engineer one more miracle drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I wish I could still be playing,'' he said. ``Sunday
afternoons were special. You can't get that adrenaline rush, and
you can't find that camaraderie on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Football wasn't easy, but it was fun. When you have fun, a lot
of people perceive it as easy. I was fortunate to be on great teams
with a lot of great players. Without them, I wouldn't be lucky
enough to be where I am on this very special day.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
