 FAME-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Not by Long shot can 49ers hog induction ceremonies
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN McCLAIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CANTON, Ohio _ Even a late-morning torrential downpour _ the first
time it had rained in the 38-year history of the Pro Football Hall
of Fame _ could not spoil Pro Football's Greatest Reunion or
disrupt the Class of 2000's induction ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   With 111 of the 136 living members of the Pro Football Hall of
Fame returning to Canton, Saturday's ceremony was a walk down
memory lane for the record crowd of more than 20,000 and a national
television audience.
</P>
<P>
   After each member was introduced, the Class of 2000 was
officially enshrined among the greatest players in history. Because
quarterback Joe Montana, defensive back Ronnie Lott and linebacker
Dave Wilcox played for San Francisco, the overflow crowd was a sea
of 49ers red.
</P>
<P>
   Also inducted were former Raiders defensive end Howie Long and
Pittsburgh Steelers owner Dan Rooney, who joined his late father,
Art Rooney Sr., as a member of the Pro Football Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   After the ceremony, the consensus was that Long had given
perhaps the greatest acceptance speech in history.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, Long said that baseball may be America's
pastime, but football is America's passion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an out-of-body experience,'' Long said. ``It's like
it's not really happening to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just boggles the mind. The Hall of Fame has the greatest
team assembled in sports. It goes beyond divisions and conferences.
Where else would you see Steelers and Raiders embrace. I never
really hugged guys from San Francisco before I came here.''
</P>
<P>
   Long, who went to eight Pro Bowls and won a Super Bowl ring
during a 13-year career, invited his first defensive line coach,
Earl Leggett, to be his presenter.
</P>
<P>
   Montana, who won four Super Bowls with the 49ers, drew the
loudest ovations. He grew up in western Pennsylvania. Montana set a
Hall of Fame record by getting 352 credentials for family and
friends. The previous high was 310 by Don Shula in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you what an honor it is for me to go into the
Hall of Fame with two other 49ers, especially Ronnie,'' Montana
said. ``Ronnie was part of that initial flip of the page with the
49ers.''
</P>
<P>
   Montana invited former 49ers owner Eddie DeBartolo Jr., a native
of Youngstown, Ohio, to be his presenter.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo, who won five Super Bowls as an owner, was forced by
the NFL to sell his share of the team to his sister. He now resides
in Tampa, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Lott, who won four Super Bowls with the 49ers but also played
with the Raiders and Jets, was presented by his father, Roy Lott.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I put the (Hall of Fame) jacket on, a lot of people were
putting it on with me,'' Lott said. ``Being here today gives me a
tingle inside, kind of like the tingle I got when I really hit
somebody hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott was known as one of the hardest hitters in league history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I miss the feeling of hitting someone, but I know I
can't do it anymore,'' he said. ``I wanted to leave the game
exhausted. When they kicked me out _ took away my scholarship, so
to speak _ I didn't want to have a feeling that I had one more hit
in me. And I didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Each of this year's inductees said the most impressive thing
about the festivities was meeting the other members, especially
those they had grown up admiring and emulating.
</P>
<P>
   ``The movie Brian's Song showed me how you're supposed to treat
a teammate,'' Lott said about the 1970 film that showed the close
relationship between Bears running backs Gale Sayers and Brian
Piccolo, who died of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even know Gale Sayers, but he was a hero of mine, and
then I got to meet him. Man, I've just been so incredibly
fortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hall of Fame festivities continue today when the members
play a golf tournament at Firestone Country Club in Akron. San
Francisco and New England play the annual preseason game Monday
night in Canton.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
