<SLUG> BC-BBN--Astros-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Astros stumble after early fumbles
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ATLANTA _ An epidemic of amnesia apparently overcame the Astros on
Saturday as the team seemed to forget all the things that helped
put together a season-high five-game winning streak before arriving
in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros committed four errors _ not to mention a couple of
other botched plays _ and walked eight batters in a 13-5 loss to
the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of the ugliest _ if not the ugliest _ showings in a
season that has seen many.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the errors were the biggest part of our problems,''
manager Larry Dierker said. ``If we hadn't made all of those
errors, we might have been able to keep the game close enough to
play for the win. It was an extremely sloppy game.''
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, pitcher Shane Reynolds (7-8) had to leave
the game after the first inning because of recurring tightness in
his lower back. His status will be evaluated on a day-to-day basis.
</P>
<P>
   The injury obviously affected Reynolds' performance _ the Braves
got to him for four runs before his early exit. Atlanta scored four
more in the second inning and three in the third en route to a
blowout.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros tied a season high for runs allowed, surrendering 13
for the fifth time this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every team has days like this,'' second baseman Craig Biggio
said. ``You're probably going to have five games like this during
the course of the year, and about five of them are going to go your
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to expect to win when you make four errors and walk
a lot of guys. It was a tough day in general; it seemed like we
were standing out there a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Every member of the infield committed an error except for Julio
Lugo, who has been the Astros' most error-prone fielder this
season. Bagwell committed a fielding error in the first, Chris
Truby in the second and Biggio in the third, when catcher Tony
Eusebio chipped in with a throwing error.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves benefited from three unearned runs, and three of the
walks also led directly to runs. After winning five straight, the
Astros have dropped two in a row to fall to 8-8 since the All-Star
break.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is no shame in losing to the Braves, who own
the best record in the National League. Rafael Furcal, Andruw Jones
and Keith Lockhart led a 14-hit attack with three apiece, and Wally
Joyner drove in four runs.
</P>
<P>
   Braves starter John Burkett (8-4) spaced nine hits over seven
innings, allowing five runs.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of two-run homers _ by Javy Lopez and Joyner _
highlighted the Braves' four-run innings in the first and second.
Jones' two-run single gave Atlanta an eight-run lead after just
three innings.
</P>
<P>
   It would be easy to say the Astros were victims of fatigue
Saturday after Friday's rain-delayed game kept them on the field
until 1 a.m. But the Braves were in the same boat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't get much rest,'' Bagwell said. ``But neither did the
Braves. It's a little better when you get to be at home and sleep
in your own bed, but there is no excuse for the way we played. We
made a bunch of mistakes, and they capitalized.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros responded to the Braves' first-inning wakeup call by
scoring three runs with a two-out rally in the second. Eusebio hit
a solo homer, Daryle Ward had a pinch RBI triple and Lugo singled
home a run.
</P>
<P>
   But that was about as much noise as the offense could make all
day, and by then it already was too late.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie relievers Jason Green and Wayne Franklin were pressed
into emergency duty after Reynolds' exit, and neither responded to
the challenge. Green allowed seven runs (five earned) and walked
five batters in two innings. Franklin surrendered two runs on six
hits and three walks in three innings.
</P>
<P>
   Both walked Burkett, which perhaps says all you need to know
about what kind of day it was. Burkett was one of three batters
Green walked on four pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Burkett might be the worst-hitting pitcher in the league, and
we walked him twice,'' Dierker said. ``Our young guys might have
better arms than some of the other guys, but today they learned the
hard way about walks.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
