<HEADLINE>
GREEN TRYING TO END SLUMP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Los Angeles Dodgers right fielder Shawn Green
continues to work at his swing in the batting cage and keep a
positive mindset, but his frustration remains even though he's
beginning to show signs of breaking out of a funk.
</P>
<P>
   Immersed in the worst month of his career, Green's average is at
.282. He ended a longest-of-the-season 0-for-18 slump with a
sixth-inning single Saturday and has hit the ball hard lately, but
it isn't making the matter easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not locked in, but I know I've lined out I don't know how
many times,'' said Green, who went 2 for 4 in Saturday's loss to
the Phillies. ``It's a lot nicer to see hits falling. You hit a few
bloopers and you feel better at the end of the day than with two
line outs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' best string of the season _ nine wins in 12 games _
has somewhat masked Green's dismal month, but until he starts
hitting again, it means less quality pitches for left fielder Gary
Sheffield.
</P>
<P>
   During Green's 0-for-18 slide, Sheffield went 3 for 12 with
eight walks and saw few good pitches. Green, who batted .260 with
two homers and 18 RBI in June, is batting .198 (19 for 96) with
five homers and 13 RBI in July _ not exactly what the club had in
mind when they traded for him and signed him to a six-year, $84
million contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I get locked in, you'll know,'' Green said. ``Obviously,
I want to produce, drive in runs, do that stuff, get a lot of hits.
But sometimes you have to crawl before you can walk. I'm hitting
the ball hard. That's a good sign.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Dealin' Darren: After an awful stretch in which the Dodgers
wondered just when, if ever, things would click for right-hander
Darren Dreifort, the time apparently has arrived. Dreifort is 3-0
with a 1.29 ERA since the All-Star break, but manager Davey Johnson
said he will continue to monitor Dreifort's pitch count.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he went through a stretch where his elbow was bothering
him, and knowing Dreif, he maybe went through a period where his
knee was bothering him,'' Johnson said. ``I'm going to be careful
with him, keep his pitches to around 90 to 100.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort has had arm troubles that prematurely ended his last
two seasons. The right-hander has allowed two hits in seven innings
in each of his last two starts, but he's been held under 100
pitches each time.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is trying to limit Dreifort's innings, because he has an
eye for September, a place Dreifort hasn't seen often. His 43
innings pitched in September are half the number he's thrown in any
other month.
</P>
<P>
   And if Dreifort and the Dodgers remain in the race, it'll be
interesting to watch how Johnson uses his catchers. Dreifort is 3-5
with a 5.38 ERA when either Todd Hundley or Paul LoDuca start, 4-2
with a 2.78 ERA with Chad Kreuter catching.
</P>
<P>
   __ Looking left: The Dodgers' bullpen might be one of the best
in baseball, but it doesn't just lack the big-time lefty who could
be used late in games. It lacks a lefty, period.
</P>
<P>
   While Dodgers management continues to look, they believe the
situation isn't dire because there aren't any available
left-handers better than the right-handers the Dodgers possess.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd need to be good, real good, to fit into this bullpen,''
Dodgers assistant general manager Bill Geivett said. ``That's
really the issue. I think the classic bullpen has a dominant lefty
in it. But the way our bullpen is, it would be tough to find one
available who would be better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' current lot of relievers are holding left-handed
hitters to a .214 average, led by Mike Fetters. Lefties are hitting
.146 off Fetters, followed by Antonio Osuna (.172), Terry Adams
(.183), Matt Herges (.242) and Jeff Shaw (.328). Gregg Olson hasn't
yielded a hit in two at-bats.
</P>
</TEXT>
