r s BC-BBA-RANGERS-LEDEE-TEX     07-30 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-LEDEE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH RANGERS, LEDEE MIGHT BE IN RIGHT PLACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Ricky Ledee watched his new team from the
bench yesterday, but the seat was only temporary. Beginning today,
Ledee will get the opportunity to prove he's more than an
overvalued prospect.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee, acquired Friday from the Cleveland Indians in a trade for
David Segui, arrived at The Ballpark in Arlington yesterday.
Manager Johnny Oates wanted to give him a day to get acclimated and
meet his new teammates but said he'll play right field and bat
sixth today.
</P>
<P>
   And after that?
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll play a lot,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   The playing time could give the 26-year-old outfielder the
opportunity to match his potential with production.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they give me an opportunity I'm going to try to do my best,
play hard and whatever happens, happens,'' Ledee said. ``I want to
establish myself. I don't want to be just one more player. I want
to be somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   Ledee had the look of a future star when he hit .305 with 29
home runs and 101 runs batted in between Double-A Norwich and
Triple-A Columbus in the New York Yankees system in 1996. He
displayed good power and speed, and a strong arm in the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   That potential remains largely untapped.
</P>
<P>
   He made it to the majors in '98, and has shown flashes of his
talent with 19 home runs and 91 RBI in 583 career at-bats. But his
average is .254.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very talented,'' said Rangers outfielder Chad Curtis,
Ledee's teammate with the Yankees in '98 and '99. ``He's got one of
those sweet swings that everybody talks about, but he's struggled
being consistent with it in the big leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   After being a part-time player on the Yankees' World
Series-winning teams in '98 and '99, when he also spent time in the
minors, Ledee was supposed to have a chance to win the left-field
job outright this season.
</P>
<P>
   He failed to capitalize, and after hitting .241 in 62 games was
traded to the Indians on June 29.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee said the chance to win the job was an illusion, because
the Yankees wouldn't leave him in the lineup through good times and
bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played a lot, but if you had one bad game you were sitting
again,'' he said. ``It's not fair for any young player. If you have
a bad game, you're going to start wondering or trying to get a hit
to see if you can play the next day. It's frustrating to play like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   He played regularly with the Indians, but when general manager
John Hart decided to make a run at the wild-card position Ledee and
his potential were on the move to Texas for the proven bat of
Segui.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee is glad for the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want me to hit and start playing like I know how to,''
he said. ``That's what I want, too. I really don't feel like
waiting and waiting to see it happen. I want it to happen now.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll get his chance beginning tonight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
