<HEADER>
A7355 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLA     07-30 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS WASTE OPPORTUNITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The trading deadline remains a day away and
postseason roster setting is more than a month away.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Dodgers have 59 games remaining _ six against
Arizona and three against San Francisco. There is plenty of time
for the playoff race to be decided, but there is also something to
be said for wasted chances.
</P>
<P>
   With the Diamondbacks and Giants losing, the Dodgers did nothing
to move closer, losing to the Philadelphia Phillies 3-0 Saturday at
Veterans Stadium to remain in third place, 2 games out of first in
the National League West.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not too early (to scoreboard watch), but the fact of the
matter is you have to win it yourself,'' Dodgers right-hander Kevin
Brown said. ``You can't depend on somebody else losing.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest stunner for the Dodgers was losing a game Brown
started against a Phillies rookie making only his fifth start.
Brown (10-4) battled through six innings in which he allowed three
runs on six hits.
</P>
<P>
   Brown also walked four, equaling the number of walks he issued
in his last four starts (31 innings) and telling the story of what
kind of night it was for him.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, Phillies right-hander Cliff Politte (2-2),
recalled from the minors as an emergency starter because of an
injury to Paul Byrd, baffled Dodgers hitters. Politte yielded just
four hits and struck out six in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going against a guy who's 10-3 with some of the best
stuff in the game,'' Politte said. ``You try to match him pitch for
pitch, but I certainly don't have that kind of stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown didn't have his typical stuff, but he managed to keep the
Dodgers close. However, for the third time in his four losses, the
Dodgers failed to score a run.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies took a 1-0 lead in the first on Scott Rolen's RBI
groundout and made it 3-0 in the fifth on a run-scoring double by
Mickey Morandini and an RBI groundout from Bobby Abreu.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't do the job,'' Brown said. ``I need to pitch better. I
made a couple of mistakes and it cost us.`'
</P>
<P>
   Politte located his fastball well and kept his pitches on the
outer half of the plate. It didn't help that the Dodgers weren't
patient and failed in their few chances.
</P>
<P>
   The leadoff hitter reached twice, in the fifth and ninth
innings, but never got past second base. Left fielder Gary
Sheffield, fourth in the NL with 87 RBI, didn't have a runner on
base in all four of his plate appearances as Todd Hollandsworth and
Mark Grudzielanek combined to go 0 for 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much time left, you can't beat yourselves up over
something like this,'' Hollandsworth said. ``We have to come out
here (today) and win the series. That's what it's all about. We
definitely wanted to go out there and win this ballgame for Brownie
and for the team. We've been playing real well, but you have to
forget it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield was the only baserunner to reach to third, singling
with one out in the eighth, moving to second on Shawn Green's
single and to third on a two-out walk to Todd Hundley that loaded
the bases. But Adrian Beltre, who had three hits in his last three
at-bats with the bases loaded, grounded into a fielder's choice to
end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt the way things were stacking up around the league, this
is one we need to win and catch up a little bit, but we didn't get
it done and we had our chances,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson
said. ``That's why this game is so great. You can't always predict
the outcome.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
