<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-30 01:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7356 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-OLY-USGYMNASTICS-BOS &LR;      07-30 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAY, MALONEY VAULT TO TOP OF PODIUM 
</HEADLINE>
 GYMNASTICS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ For months, all the talk had been about the
Magnificent 7 minus 2. Could Shannon make it back? How about
Dominique? Awesome Dawesome? Et cetera, et cetera.
</P>
<P>
   Except this wasn't a trip down memory lane. It was the US
Gymnastics Championships, prelude to next month's Olympic trials at
the FleetCenter. And when the math was done Saturday &UR;  &LR; night on the
floor of the Kiel Center, the teenagers had grabbed the spotlight
away from the twentysomethings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The past Olympians are absolutely awesome for coming back,''
declared 18-year-old Elise Ray, after she'd dethroned two-time
all-around champion Kristen Maloney by less than three-10ths of a
point. ``But I think it's great that we can compete with them all
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray, Maloney, and the rest of last year's world team did more
than compete with the Class of 1996. They dominated them, sweeping
the top five places with Jamie Dantzscher, Vanessa Atler, and
Alyssa Beckerman.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Atlanta gold medalists were stunned. ``I'm not
surprised,'' said Dominique Moceanu. ``We haven't been training the
last four years the way those girls have. Most of us have only been
training for six months. To finish where we finished, that's pretty
impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Amy Chow, who withdrew from Stanford to try for a reprise at 22,
was sixth. Moceanu, who hadn't competed in two years before this
month, climbed up from 10th after the prelims to eighth. And
Dominique Dawes, bidding for her third Olympic team at 23, was
ninth after training seriously for only four months.
</P>
<P>
   All of them easily made the 12-woman cut for the trials, where
they may well be joined by fellow gold medalists Shannon Miller and
Jaycie Phelps, who withdrew after the prelims and are asking for
injury waivers.
</P>
<P>
   But unless the Magnificent 7 minus 2 can crank up their skills
during the next fortnight, they'll be hoping for one of the three
wild-card spots the selection committee will hand out in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Only the three gymnasts with the top combined scores from
nationals and trials are automatic and Ray and the 19-year-old
Maloney look like locks. They were separated by decimal points all
meet long (Maloney led by five-100ths after the prelims) and were
head to head in the same rotation Saturday &UR;  &LR; night. And it wasn't
until Ray hit both her vaults in the finale that she nailed it
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amazing,'' exulted Ray, who had knee arthroscopy last month.
``This is such a dream of mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray had been the top American finisher (eighth) at last year's
world championships, but Maloney had pulled out injured. Then
Maloney had missed four months of training after shoulder and leg
surgeries last fall. So she was expecting anything but a walkover
coronation here. ``It was my first event since worlds,'' Maloney
said. ``So I'm really happy with how I did and how I ended up.''
</P>
<P>
   If Ray hadn't botched her vault in the prelims, she would have
taken the lead into Saturday &UR;  &LR; night. As it was, she grabbed it
right from the start, icing her bars routine for a 9.85 before
Maloney got a 9.60. Then Ray added some padding on beam with a 9.70
to Maloney's 9.575. The floor was all but a wash _ 9.85 for
Maloney, 9.80 for Ray.
</P>
<P>
   So it came down to vault, Ray's weakest event. After Maloney hit
it for a 9.425, Ray needed only 9.2 to win _ but she didn't know
that. ``I'm glad I didn't know how much I needed,'' Ray said. ``I
knew I needed to do better than I did on Thursday, but I wasn't
sure by how much.''
</P>
<P>
   So she decided to attack. ``I wanted to go after it, no matter
what,'' Ray said. After scoring a 9.35 on her first bid, she needed
only to avoid a butt-landing to win. But Ray decided to go out
boldly and asked coach Kelli Hill if she could use a Yurchenko
double full, which she'd never tried in competition. Hill assented,
and watched Ray land it for a total of 9.425 _ the same as
Maloney's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just really happy for her,'' saluted Maloney, who would
have been the first woman since Kim Zmeskal (1990-92) to win three
straight titles. ``She's an awesome gymnast. She's come a long
way.''
</P>
<P>
   So has the rest of the Class of 1999, which came back sixth and
shaky from China last year. What they wanted to prove here was that
US women's gymnastics didn't end when the Magnificent 7 left
Atlanta with their gold medals. ``A lot of the attention was on
them,'' Maloney said. ``I think me and Elise and Jamie showed them
that we're still here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-00 0109EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
