<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-30 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7357 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-TEN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     07-30 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANG NO HELP TO YOUTH MARKETING CAMPAIGN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Obviously it is about time Michael Chang steps
aside and lets the younger players have the stage. Michael, here's
a gold watch. Don't let the door hit you. Check out that sunset.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, it's not Chang's tennis that suggests his moment has passed.
Saturday he defeated Justin Gimelstob in two of three sets to
advance to the final against Jan-Michael Gambill in the pro
tournament at UCLA. So he still has a game.
</P>
<P>
   It's the Association of Tennis Professionals that seems to have
decreed Chang is old news. Who are we to argue?
</P>
<P>
   The ATP has unveiled an ad campaign to familiarize the public
with ``the young players currently invigorating the men's game.''
You might have seen it this week in a national newspaper and a
national news magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Next to the winking headline, ``New Balls Please,'' stand seven
grim-faced young men with rackets. They're identified in a caption:
Gambill, Lleyton Hewitt, Tommy Haas, Gustavo Kuerten, Juan Carlos
Ferrero, Nicolas Lapentti and Roger Federer. Don't feel bad if
you've never heard of half of them. Each is 23 or younger and
Federer has never won a pro tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Let's let the ATP Tour newsletter explain what's going on here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Following a series of photo shoots taken during Wimbledon and
the UBS Open in Gstaad, phase one of the campaign, developed in
conjunction with the Tour's advertising and PR agency
Burson-Marsteller, shows the players striking gladiatorial poses on
imposing black and white backgrounds,'' International Tennis Weekly
reports.
</P>
<P>
   This is how athletes make their reputations these days
</P>
<P>
   in conjunction with an advertising and PR agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the `New Balls Please' campaign,'' ATP Tour
public-relations vice president Matt Rapp is quoted saying in the
newsletter, ``we have struck a balance between a classic tennis
statement and a touch of irreverence.''
</P>
<P>
   Burson-Marsteller's Johnathan Trimble adds that ``the players
all left (the photo shoot) with a sense that something really
exciting was happening. It is a great opportunity for fanatics and
those new to the game to see that these new players are enjoying
life both on and away from the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, from the looks on their mugs, they don't appear to be
enjoying themselves as much as they appear to be standing in
barrels full of spiders. But we'll take anybody's word for
anything.
</P>
<P>
   The point of all this, as an ATP official explained to me
Saturday, is that the tour is eager to prepare its fans for the day
when established stars Pete Sampras and Andre Agassi and Chang
retire. Agassi is 30, Sampras and Chang 28, but there's no use
waiting for the inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   There's also no use, the ATP must think, in waiting until the
young Turks (and Australians, Brazilians and Germans) accomplish
something worth celebrating.
</P>
<P>
   The ATP apparently thinks it's hopelessly old-school to let
athletes find fame and infamy based on their results, which is the
quaint way sports used to work, before the NBA pioneered a
different idea.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi's Australian Open victory, Sampras' seventh Wimbledon and
Chang's rebound apparently aren't invigorating enough for the men's
game. It needs to show off the ``intriguing personalities'' to whom
Rapp refers.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't do it like this when Chang was one of the
youngsters. He won the French Open (at age 17 in 1989), !ital!then
got his face in the ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel if it's deserved, they should be there,'' Chang said
Saturday of the players in the ads, without actually saying if he
thought it's deserved. ``Obviously, for the game to survive, you
need to have new faces and new talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Chang considers himself ``one of the young guys among the older
generation'' on tour.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend Chang is striking a blow for that older generation.
He humbled Gimelstob, who's 23. He ought to be favored over
Gambill, who's 23.
</P>
<P>
   If he wins, we can only hope he hasn't set back the ATP
marketing plan too badly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-00 0118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
