<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-30 02:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7360 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-LEBRETON-COL-LEDE     07-30 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-LEBRETON-COL-LEDEE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS WILL TAKE THEIR TIME JUDGING VALUE OF EX-YANKEE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Ricky Ledee wasn't born in Yankees
pinstripes, but the diaper service seems to have gotten there as
soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   He was a tender 16 years old when he played his first game for
the organization, debuting with Tampa of the Gulf Coast League in
1990. Ten years later _ 10 years, mind you _ Boss Steinbrenner
finally decided that Ricky was worth more leaving the Yankees than
playing left field for them.
</P>
<P>
   With a curiously brief intermediate stop in Cleveland, Ledee
became a Ranger Friday. Another pinstriped orphan, left in the
bulrushes.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, well. If you can't beat them, trade for them.
</P>
<P>
   Around baseball, that seems to be the trendy philosophy. The
market for ex-Yankees, for some reason, remains breathlessly
bullish. Give us your tired, your poor, your huddled Yankee masses.
</P>
<P>
   So how good is Ledee? The Rangers fully intend to see.
</P>
<P>
   The club thinks he's good enough that general manager Doug
Melvin preferred to roll the dice on Ledee's potential than to jump
on the Brett Tomko merry-go-round.
</P>
<P>
   Tomko, of course, is a starting pitcher, which means that his
rejection speaks volumes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to give our young pitchers a chance,'' Melvin
explained last night.
</P>
<P>
   The general manager, in other words, feels that the franchise is
better served presently by continuing to dispatch Ryan Glynn and
Matt Perisho, both 25, to the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Would Tomko be any more consistent than the two kid pitchers? I
don't think so. And given the current Pudge-less state of the
Rangers, why should the focus be on anything sooner than 2001?
</P>
<P>
   How good is Ledee? Melvin gave a hint yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had two calls today on him and turned them down,'' Melvin
reported. ``People were asking, `Did you get him to trade him?' Our
answer is no, we've decided the kid has moved enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, to be young and a New York Yankee.
</P>
<P>
   On June 29, Ledee was traded to the Indians for David Justice.
Minor leaguers were also involved in the deal, but the essence was
that Steinbrenner United swapped a guy who couldn't crack its
starting lineup for a solid, one-time All-Star.
</P>
<P>
   And now he has been traded again, this time for David Segui who,
for all he was not, was still a .336 hitter here with 29 doubles
and 57 RBI. Heading into this season, Ledee didn't have that many
doubles or runs batted in in his whole big-league career.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee reportedly was more than a little shaken when the Yanks
dealt him away last month. That might explain his modest totals _ a
.222 average with 8 RBI _ with the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   But he seems to be over the postpartum pinstripe blues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was given a good shot there,'' Ledee said. ``It was up to
me, and I couldn't put it together. They're trying to win it all,
and so they felt they had to make a change and went with Justice.''
</P>
<P>
   The thing that we can never really weigh is how much pressure
there is to be a relative youngster, wearing some of baseball's
sacred vestments, playing left field in one of its true cathedrals
_ and where the boss demands a World Series winner every year.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Kenny Rogers about the pressures of playing for the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different,'' Ledee admitted. ``It's like there, you never
really win. You always have to look over your shoulders. If you go
4-for-4 and make an error, somebody is going to want to talk about
the error. You really have to be strong mentally.''
</P>
<P>
   Ledee isn't the first ex-Yankee _ excuse me, pre-owned Yankee _
to say something like that.
</P>
<P>
   So how good is Ledee?
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates said that even he isn't sure. ``I've seen
maybe five at-bats his whole career,'' Oates said. ``It's a little
early. You're talking to the wrong guy.''
</P>
<P>
   But Oates added that he intends to find out. Ledee will be in
the lineup tonight, and lots more after that.
</P>
<P>
   Citing the scouting reports, Melvin is bullish about the newest
Ranger. And Melvin is well aware of the built-in pinstriped bias.
</P>
<P>
   The list includes, for starters, Ruben Rivera, Brien Taylor,
Russ Davis, Pat Kelly and Ed Yarnall.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers may be the only guy ever to don the Yankees pinstripes
and see his value go ``down.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Rangers, there is plenty of time to kick the
new guy's tires and to check Ledee's oil.
</P>
<P>
   David Segui, we hardly knew ye. But as an impending free agent,
Segui's stay probably was never going to be long, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   For the home team, the youth movement continues. And that isn't
all bad.
</P>
<P>
   You do trust that Steinbrenner guy, don't you?
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-00 0247EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
