<DOCNO> NYT20000730.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-30 02:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7361 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-XXX-SLUG-TEX     07-30 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-XXX-SLUG-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGERS START FAST, DUMP RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Gabe Kapler and Bill Haselman spent the first
two games of the series against the Detroit Tigers proving that the
Rangers did receive something of value in the off-season trade of
Juan Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Both played key roles as the Rangers won Thursday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
   It was Francisco Cordero's turn to defend the honor of general
manager Doug Melvin last night, and the young reliever responded
with his longest and perhaps best outing of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The circumstances were less than ideal. Rangers starter Kenny
Rogers was knocked out in the third inning of what became a 10-2
loss at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers (10-8) gave up eight runs (six earned) on nine hits and
three walks in 22/3 innings, putting the Rangers in a huge hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quick and painful,'' Rogers said. ``Today was just bad all
around. I wasn't too good.''
</P>
<P>
   With Tigers starter Hideo Nomo (4-10) pitching about as well as
he did when he started the 1995 All-Star Game in Arlington, the
Rangers had no chance to climb out. Nomo allowed two runs on seven
hits in eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, losing for the first time in five games, fell to
two games under .500 and 91/2 games behind the Seattle Mariners in
the American League West. They're 51/2 games out in the wild-card
standings, with five teams between them and first place.
</P>
<P>
   The chances of getting back into contention appear slim.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, naturally, still want to win as many games as
possible. But the real purpose of the final two months is likely to
be evaluating the talent on hand with an eye toward their roles for
next season.
</P>
<P>
   One job that could be open is that of closer.
</P>
<P>
   Even if incumbent John Wetteland isn't traded in the next couple
of days _ something that looks unlikely at this point _ the Rangers
still could need somebody new to finish off victories next season.
Wetteland can become a free agent at the end of the season, and
Melvin isn't close to signing him to a contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   Cordero came from the Tigers with the tag of future closer.
That's the kind of label they put on you when you throw in the
mid-90s with a hard slider.
</P>
<P>
   Cordero's arm hasn't yielded the results hoped for, though. He
had a 5.28 earned-run average, and had allowed 55 hits and walked
32 walks in 441/3 innings, before yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The raw stuff remains impressive, but Cordero usually tries to
throw the ball past hitters rather than setting them up. That
doesn't work at the major-league level.
</P>
<P>
   When Cordero came in last night, he at first suffered from the
same malady. He got off to a shaky start, allowing two runs in the
fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the first four batters reached, with the only out a
liner right back at Cordero. But after a visit to the mound by
pitching coach Dick Bosman, the young reliever settled down.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came out and told me that throwing as hard as I can wasn't
going to help me,'' Cordero said.
</P>
<P>
   He took a little off his fastball, and threw his slider for
strikes, and dominated his previous team for the next three
innings. He retired 11 of the last 12 batters he faced, four of
them by strikeout. He fanned five overall, a career high.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I would like to do every time I come into a
game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cordero's outing was important in the short term because he
saved the bullpen with his 41/3 innings. Doug Davis was the only
other reliever who had to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cordero pitched very well,'' manager Johnny Oates said. ``That
was the longest outing of his major-league career, and he saved our
bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   His outing could be more important in the long term if he
continues his success and becomes the pitcher the Rangers
envisioned when they made the trade.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-00 0247EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
