<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-30 03:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7363 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-ATHLETICS-     07-30 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX PHILOSOPHICAL AFTER 12-1 LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-ATHLETICS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ It was a night when men in cleats, with
remnants of sunflower seeds or tobacco in their teeth, sought
consolation in philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   What else can you do when you are humiliated, 12-1, before a
crowd of 36,325, about 10,000 of whom turned out for free yo-yos?
</P>
<P>
   How else could the Red Sox lay down their heads softly
Saturday &UR;  &LR; night after the thumping they took from the A's?
</P>
<P>
   Philosopher Rod Beck, a giant ice pack on his neck after
pitching the final inning of the beating: ``When I first started
playing this game professionally, they told me the difference
between winners and losers is that once a week you get your butt
kicked and once a week you kick some butt. It's what you do with
the other five days that makes the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Philosopher Jimy Williams, the manager, flashing a smile of
resignation: ``It's just one of 162 games, that's all I can say. We
just gotta move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Losing pitcher, Jeff Fassero, mixing art and science: ``It was
that kind of night, bad angles for me.'' Real bad.
</P>
<P>
   After taking the first two games of the four-game series, the
Sox gave and gave Saturday night. Before Fassero (7-4) succumbed
with no outs in the fifth, he was on his way to yielding eight runs
(seven earned) on six hits and five walks.
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Bryce Florie fared little better, getting knocked
around for three runs on four hits before the inning was over. And
Beck, who walked two of the first three batters he faced in the
eighth, gave up the 12th run.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Oakland starter Kevin Appier, whom the Red Sox have
coveted through the years, shut them out through seven innings
before he left the game to his bullpen. The righthander allowed
four hits, three walks, and permitted no Boston base runner past
second.
</P>
<P>
   The loss cost the Sox a chance to overtake Oakland for first
place in the American League wild-card race by a half-game.
Instead, they linger 1 1/2 games back. And they remained 2 1/2
games behind the Yankees in the AL East, as the Bombers also lost,
6-2.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox will send their new best hope, Rolando Arrojo, against
the A's Sunday as they try to vanquish the memory of Saturday
night's ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   Fassero, who expressed displeasure last week at being scheduled
to pitch Saturday night on a week's rest rather than his usual five
days, set himself up for pain throughout, walking five A's, three
of whom scored.
</P>
<P>
   After the loss, he said the extra rest made him a little
stronger than he prefers. He also said his delivery was affected by
the slope of the mound. And he said the A's benefited from a number
of strike calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were borderline pitches that just didn't go my way,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He also induced a number of grounders that other nights might
have turned into outs instead of singles, doubles, or triples. ``I
just didn't get any breaks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And the A's seized almost every opportunity. Oakland rookie Adam
Piatt struck the most menacing blows, a run-scoring single in the
first and a three-run homer in the third. Yet every Oakland player
but two in the starting lineup scored by the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very patient hitters,'' Williams said. ``They got
some walks and they took advantage of them.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of pending woe, Fassero walked the first batter of the
game, Ryan Christenson, who moved to second on Olmedo Saenz's
two-out single and scored on a single by Piatt.
</P>
<P>
   In the third inning, it was deja vu all over again _ and then
some. Oakland slugger Jason Giambi, handcuffed the night before by
Pedro Martinez, drew a one-out walk. Fassero then walked the next
batter, Saenz, and served up a three-run gopher to Piatt, spotting
the A's a 4-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Then he unraveled in the fifth. After throwing 84 pitches in the
first four innings (he hadn't thrown more than 98 in an outing all
year), he led off the fifth by yielding a double to Giambi, a
single to Saenz, and a walk to Piatt, loading the bases.
</P>
<P>
   An error then finished Fassero to the showers. Terrence Long hit
a soft grounder to first baseman Jose Offerman, who had all the
time he could want to throw out the lumbering Giambi at the plate.
But Offerman threw the ball wildly past catcher Scott Hatteberg,
letting two runs score to make it 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   Out went Fassero, in came Florie, whom the A's soon appeared to
use for batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   Miguel Tejada greeted Florie with a two-run double. After he
retired the next batter, Ramon Hernandez, on a grounder for the
first out, the A's all but eviscerated the righthanded reliever.
</P>
<P>
   The toll: a double by Eric Chavez, a triple by Christenson, a
single by Randy Velarde, and a walk to Saenz before the nightmare
ended with the Red Sox in an 11-0 hole. The A's sent 12 batters to
the plate in the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Appier had lost five in a row. But he faced little opposition
from the Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Only three Boston batters reached second base before the
seventh: Hatteberg on a two-out double in the second, Ed Sprague
with a two-out single and a walk to Trot Nixon in the fifth, and
Nomar Garciaparra in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra, who was 0 for 3, reached on a fielder's choice. He
advanced to second on Troy O'Leary's bloop single. But both were
stranded when second baseman Mike Lansing, in his first action with
the Sox, flied out to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   With the game slipping out of reach, Williams lifted Garciaparra
after the sixth, sending Manny Alexander to shortstop. He also
replaced Offerman with Izzy Alcantara.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox scored their only run in the eighth after Darren Lewis,
Brian Daubach, and Alcantara each singled to load the bases. Lewis
scored on Bernard Gilkey's fielder's choice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
