<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMBIA-DISPLACED0730-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fleeing war, refugees now victims of poverty
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia _ Libia Barahona remembers the day clearly _ a
Tuesday in July 1998 _ when the sound of the trucks echoed through
her small town of Mapiripan 200 miles southeast of Bogota,
Colombia's capital.
</P>
<P>
   The trucks carried about 100 armed paramilitaries, who had come
looking for leftist sympathizers _ families whose sons or fathers
might be supporters of the Marxist rebels trying to overthrow the
Colombian government.
</P>
<P>
   ``They rounded up everybody at 5:30 a.m.,'' said Barahona, 60, a
widowed mother of five who ran a small restaurant and store. ``They
stuck a machine gun in my chest and asked where the guerrillas and
the guns were. I told them I didn't know anything about this.''
</P>
<P>
   With no police and no army soldiers around, the paramilitaries
had their way in remote Mapiripan for weeks. Suspected informants
and sympathizers were rounded up, questioned and beaten.
</P>
<P>
   Barahona, her children and the other townspeople were told to
stay in their homes with the windows closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were torturing and killing people,'' she recalled. ``We
couldn't even count the number of the dead.''
</P>
<P>
   In Colombia, Barahona's story is all too common. The military
has ceded huge swaths of the countryside to guerrillas or
right-wing paramilitary gangs. Both groups sweep through rural
towns looking for recruits and enemies, conducting a reign of
terror funded by tribute they collect from Colombia's drug
smugglers.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle are poor campesinos like Barahona, most of whom
hide any political opinions they have in a bid for survival.
</P>
<P>
   Many flee the countryside, heading for larger cities.
</P>
<P>
   Government figures list more than 1 million Colombians as
displaced from their homes in the past five years, but human rights
advocates say the number of ``desplazados'' _ the displaced _ is
closer to 2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The war has spread over the last two years to areas not
traditionally affected,'' said Albeiro Salazar, a researcher at the
Center for Investigation and Education, a human rights group in
Bogota. ``The guerrillas and the paramilitaries want the civil
population to take sides, and they enforce their will through
massacres and torture. Now, we have whole regions of the
countryside that are depopulated.''
</P>
<P>
   While many of the poor have fled within Colombia's borders, the
better-off have fled the country altogether. As Colombia's woes
have grown, they have formed long lines outside foreign embassies,
applying for visas for Spain, Canada, the United States, Costa Rica
and other nations. Colombia is losing doctors, lawyers, engineers
and business owners.
</P>
<P>
   But for the poor like Barahona, the only escape is a bus ticket
to Bogota, Medellin or the like. Hoping to find work in the
relative peace of the cities, many stumble from the crisis of the
countryside into poverty and homelessness.
</P>
<P>
   Few find work; Colombia is enduring its worst economic crisis of
the last 70 years, with unemployment topping 20 percent and
unofficial estimates ranging up to 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not used to living in the city,'' Barahona said as she
stood aimlessly outside a building she occupies with more than 100
other displaced people. ``I feel trapped here. Where I lived
before, I knew everybody. Here, the rich people walk past and
insult us. We want to work and get on with our lives, but there are
no jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Barahona spends her days looking for work and applying for
government assistance. Her nights are spent reliving the terror of
recent years and longing for a home she fears she will never see
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the second of August, 1998, the guerrillas arrived and
there was a terrible shootout,'' she said. ``The paramilitaries
were dug in beside our house and the shooting went on for hours. It
started at 2 a.m. and went on until the afternoon.''
</P>
<P>
   Huddling in her house with her children, Barahona eventually
escaped, running for the nearby woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went back two days later and everything from the store and
restaurant was stolen,'' she said. ``I saw more than 40 dead,
guerrillas and paramilitary.''
</P>
<P>
   Shocked townspeople buried their dead and tried to go on, but
the war wouldn't leave them alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Nov. 3, the guerrillas came again and they killed three
young boys they said were accomplices of the paramilitaries,'' she
said. ``They told us then to leave or die. We left with just the
clothes we were wearing.''
</P>
<P>
   After living several months in a nearby town, Barahona returned
to Mapiripan when she heard that things had quieted down. She
stayed until the guerrillas returned in October 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted my three oldest children,'' she said. ``They
wanted them to join the fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   This time she fled all the way to Bogota, only to find thousands
of other refugees like herself.
</P>
<P>
   Barahona knows little of plans by Colombia's president, Andres
Pastrana, to fight the drug lords and the guerrillas with nearly $2
billion in foreign aid _ more than $1 billion of it from the United
States. She doesn't know that critics fear the pl
</P>
</TEXT>
