A7415 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-EZZARD-COLUMN0731-COX     07-30 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN0731-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Oh, for some rousing words that won't fit bumper sticker
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dear William Jennings Bryan,
</P>
<P>
   Could you return to Earth? We're desperate for a colorful
orator. Although you electrified the Democratic convention of 1896,
you might find the GOP a more comfortable home today.
</P>
<P>
   There's not a history book around that doesn't still recount
your words on the free coinage of silver: ``You shall not press
down upon the brow of labor this crown of thorns. You shall not
crucify mankind on a cross of gold.''
</P>
<P>
   Southerners, especially poor farmers, loved you for it.
</P>
<P>
   The reason we need more fiery orators is because today's
presidential nominating process is about as exciting as watching
paint dry. You helped put Woodrow Wilson's nomination over the top
on the 46th ballot at the 1912 Democratic convention, but we
already know Texas Gov. George W. Bush and former Secretary of
Defense Dick Cheney of Wyoming will be the GOP nominees for
president and vice president. Neither is going to say anything
memorable. But preordained Democratic presidential nominee Al Gore
won't either. He's taken to pounding on the podium and raising his
voice lately, which hardly makes him an orator.
</P>
<P>
   While the political conventions haven't produced any great
orators recently, there have been some great performers and some
shows of courage. Four years ago, Elizabeth Dole gave a new kind of
walking-talking speech for her husband, telling his life story by
greeting folks in the audience who had helped him along life's way.
Few could have pulled it off with such poise and grace. Colin
Powell, a former chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff and a
speaker this time, spoke with courage in support of affirmative
action and women's right to choose.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988 Ann Richards, who later became governor of Texas, gave a
rip-roaring keynote speech, too, but it was designed more to
entertain than to challenge our better selves. She started by
pointing out a sad truth _ that she and the late U.S. Rep. Barbara
Jordan of Texas were the only two women in 160 years to be
Democratic convention keynote speakers (although the Democrats
claim to be big supporters of women's rights).
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN'S WORDS RING OUT
</P>
<P>
   There have been some terrific women orators at conventions since
your day, when women weren't even allowed to vote. Jordan, the
first black elected to the Texas Senate, is the most memorable. Her
1976 Democratic keynote speech still rings in the ears of Americans
who worry about losing our sense of community in the materialistic
Internet age:
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the great danger that America faces, that we will
cease to be one nation and become instead a collection of interest
groups, each seeking to fulfill private dreams. Each seeking to
satisfy private wants. If this occurs, who will speak for America?
Who will speak for the common good?''
</P>
<P>
   Some things haven't changed in the last 100 years. There's still
little humility among politicians. Humility doesn't always mark
Jesse Jackson's speeches, but passion does. And in 1984, the civil
rights leader quit his quest to be the nation's first black
president with a humble confession and a plea for party unity:
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not a perfect servant. I am a public servant doing my
best against the odds. Be patient. God is not finished with me yet.
This campaign has taught me much: That leaders must be tough enough
to fight, tender enough to cry, humble enough to make mistakes,
humble enough to admit them, strong enough to absorb the pain and
resilient enough to bounce back.''
</P>
<P>
   The mark of a great orator is one who can deliver a timeless
message with passion, a substantive message that inspires the
democratic dialogue. Kathleen Hall Jamieson, dean of the University
of Pennsylvania's Annenberg School for Communication, says the
television age has caused us to elevate what amounts to a string of
bumper stickers to great oratory. She thought Richards' 1988
speech, which included the line about former President Bush being
born with ``a silver foot in his mouth,'' fell into that category.
Still, you have to hand it to Richards _ she delivers great bumper
stickers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
