<HEADER>
A7416 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN0731     07-30 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN0731-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CBS head Moonves rationalizes 'Big Brother' abuse
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The reality TV business is cheap and creepy.
That's a given.
</P>
<P>
   But until ``Big Brother'' came along, it wasn't criminal. Yes,
criminal. How else to describe the child abuse that CBS, led by
Leslie Moonves, and ``Big Brother'' are inflicting on the teen-age
offspring of one of the house's unstable inmates?
</P>
<P>
   Little more than a week into the every-night-but-Sunday saga,
Karen, a 43-year-old Indiana mother of four, had a meltdown and
began dissing her husband, Tom. As far as she's concerned, their
22-year marriage is finished. Between racking sobs, Karen said Tom
has major intimacy problems, including an aversion to kissing
because he doesn't like his face touched.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so ugly about so many things,'' Karen whined to fellow
inmates _ and viewers.
</P>
<P>
   That excruciating installment was followed by a live studio
interview with the vilified husband, who said in the show's opener
that he thought his wife had ``lost her mind'' for joining the
10-member group. Tom seemed hesitant to discuss his ruined
marriage, but prodded by perky host Julie Chen, he gave in.
</P>
<P>
   If two adults want to make fools of themselves on national
television, fine. They both signed release forms. They're free to
expose themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But back home in Indiana, the four children of Karen and Tom are
watching. Karen's online bio says she considers her children ``her
greatest accomplishment.'' If that's true, why did she cause them
so much pain? When they return to school in a few weeks, ``Big
Brother'' will still be on, and Karen will still be babbling about
her domestic hell. Stares and whispers will rain upon these poor
kids like acid-dipped confetti.
</P>
<P>
   Release forms or not, CBS should be held accountable for these
children's misery. No, the network certainly didn't cause the
marriage to collapse, but by agreeing to broadcast the parents'
revelations, they invaded the children's privacy, to put it mildly.
And the damage may go much deeper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've thought about the children,'' CBS president Leslie
Moonves told TV critics in Los Angeles last week. ``Do we have a
responsibility for Karen talking about her marital problems? I
don't believe so. If it hadn't happened on the air, it would have
happened somewhere else. . . . We have nothing to apologize for.''
</P>
<P>
   How's that for smug and cold hearted? As long as ``Big Brother''
is pulling big ratings (not blockbuster but healthy), Moonves
doesn't care who gets hurt. His weak defense was that PBS had a
similar tragedy in 1973 with ``An American Family,'' a multipart
documentary about the Louds of California. That marriage collapsed
by the end of filming, too.
</P>
<P>
   But there was an important difference. ``An American Family''
was filmed over a period of many months and then edited into a
documentary. By the time it aired, a good deal of time had elapsed,
and the Louds all knew what would be in the film. In fact, they had
all participated in the filming. Nobody was caught off guard.
Everybody agreed to the broadcast beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, CBS should have been more careful about
screening applicants for ``Big Brother.'' From the get-go, Karen
seemed like an explosion ready to happen, and it didn't take a
genius to see that her marriage was shaky.
</P>
<P>
   Karen isn't the only resident cruising toward an emotional
breakdown _ and serious repercussions back home. It has been
revealed that George, a 41-year-old father of three, accidentally
shot and killed a friend in a hunting accident years ago. George's
wife, Teresa, has said the event traumatized her husband, and she
told Chen that he will be ``destroyed'' when he finds out his
tragic past was exposed.
</P>
<P>
   Even a perfunctory background check should have uncovered this
trauma, allowing CBS to warn George that the information would be
revealed or reject him from the guest list. Ditto the show's first
official celebrity, William ``Mega'' Collins, the Philadelphia
fellow who was found to be a past member of the New Black Panther
Party, which espouses hatred and violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent $100,000 on background checks,'' Moonves said. ``I
don't know how better we could have done it. A lot of people have
skeletons.''
</P>
<P>
   The goal, of course, is to have high drama among the residents
while the ever-present cameras are whirring. If everybody got along
and happy-talked, life would get boring. But ``Big Brother'' needs
to draw the line when children are affected. Karen's kids should
not pay for their mother's emotional turmoil, and CBS should not
compound the abuse by serving it up as prime-time entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a helpful hint for political convention coverage, which
begins tonight:
</P>
<P>
   Every four years the broadcast networks are faced with low
ratings for their prime-time coverage. Viewers, it seems, are as
apathetic as voters.
</P>
<P>
   But since networks have a responsibility to cover them somehow,
they should try a pool arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   Let ABC take the first night, CBS the second, NBC the third, and
then all three can do their own analyses/coverage of the nominee's
speech on the final night. (PBS, which isn't a slave to ratings,
can stick with its same nightly plans.)
</P>
<P>
   That way, viewers who want to watch will have a free, noncable
outlet each night, and other viewers will have more entertainment
choices. Good thinking, right?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
