<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-30 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7418 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-BUYING-ART0731-COX     07-30 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUYING-ART0731-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How to buy art when you have no idea what to buy and limited
cash
 &HT;    By Jane A. Black
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ You look at your bare living room walls. You
wonder: What can I put on them that will look great?
</P>
<P>
   You look at your wallet. You ask: How can I afford art that I'll
like, and that will be good?
</P>
<P>
   You look around. You think: Wouldn't it be nice to support local
artists, as long as I'm shopping?
</P>
<P>
   And now, you wonder: Where do I start?
</P>
<P>
   Say you had a bit of money to invest in local artworks. Suppose
you had $500. We asked a number of local observers and authorities
on the Dayton-area art scene what they would do.
</P>
<P>
   We add, first, two things, right off the bat: $500 isn't much _
in this context, anyway _ and nobody is going to tell you what to
buy.
</P>
<P>
   Also, some of the folks we asked feel squeamish about the
question, hesitating to single out artists as worthy or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``On one hand, this is a no-brainer, and on another hand it is
very difficult,'' says Jud Yalkut, an internationally recognized
video artist who runs the Miami Valley Cooperative Galleries.
</P>
<P>
   He specifies that his answer is offered in the context of his
own collection. And that's one of the main things to remember: You
have to look at an artwork in your own context, as well as that of
the ``art world.''
</P>
<P>
   What is a good value for one person, or a good piece of art, is
not the same for the next. Keep in mind what you have, what you
like and where the piece will be placed. It is vital to trust one's
own instincts and think big picture. And despite the disdain of
some, it's OK to buy something because it goes with your couch.
Remember, you have to live with it. You should love it.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't have to be one style and/or one medium. We, for
instance, have a large abstract and a traditional oil-on-canvas
still life not far from some watercolors by my mother-in-law.
Nearby are two small needlepoint pictures of wildflowers we got for
a wedding present next to a large calligraphy-and-colored-pencil
drawing. It all works together, though it's hard to say exactly
why. It helps that the large pieces all have dark frames.
</P>
<P>
   I look at every piece of art in my house every day. That's the
great thing about buying original art _ it is ever so much more
lovable than a poster. It's not that posters are bad art _ but can
they really engage your eye, your mind and your heart the way an
original artwork can? Usually not.
</P>
<P>
   So where do you go to find real art? One place are annual spring
art festivals. They are fun events and you can see the range and
depth of work being produced by regional artists. You can expect to
get good value for your money.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, too, that buying what you like doesn't preclude the
idea of educating yourself. The more you look, the more you will
understand what really excites you, and holds your interest. For an
overview anytime of year, visit the galleries that carry a variety
of local artists.
</P>
<P>
   Artists' cooperatives are a popular way for individuals to get
their work out in front of the public. A group will finance and run
the business, allotting space for each person's work.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial galleries represent artists, showing their work and
taking a commission from the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Once you have looked a bit, you will probably find an artist or
two who appeals to you. At that point, you may want to follow the
lead of Terry Welker, a local architect who has run Archetype
Gallery for the past few years. He recommends taking a bottle of
good wine to the artist's studio to share while you look over their
body of work and talk with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it's not just about owning a piece of art work, its
about having a relationship with the artist. I'm fascinated by
other people's view of the world. Ownership is not an end in itself
but a means of sharing the artist's view,'' says Welker.
</P>
<P>
   Some artists will sell to you directly, especially if you found
them through a group show and they are not represented locally. An
artist who has work in a commercial or cooperative gallery should,
and probably will, complete the sale through that entity.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Clift, president of the board of trustees for the Dayton
Visual Arts Center, says she would probably ``search for a
watercolor because it is one of my favorite techniques . . . and I
think I would be able to secure a smallish one depending on the
complexity of the work.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Caron, professor of art history at Wright State University
and head of Dayton's Public Arts Commission, also suggests thinking
about it in terms of media. ``Because $500 is not a whole lot, I'd
probably look at purchasing prints, drawings or photographs rather
than paintings or sculptures. An interesting possibility might be
to approach established painters or sculptors and ask if their
drawings are for sale. Often such works are compelling glimpses
into the creative process and have an immediacy that is very
appealing.''
</P>
<P>
   Vicky Smith, local artist and president of the Riverbend Board
of Regents, has a different idea. ``I wouldn't necessarily buy
things based on who the artist is, but rather on how much I was
drawn to the individual piece of work.''
</P>
<P>
   So, taking into account that you have to decide for yourself,
and you are going to have to fill those empty walls slowly if you
want to buy original work, who might you consider buying? The
following artists are those who were named by the gallery owners,
artists, and art professionals quoted in this article. Check them
out!
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
