</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRYER0731-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New system cuts down on drying time
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The average load of laundry takes about 30
minutes to wash in a residential model automatic washing machine,
but the same load takes abut 50 minutes to dry, according to the
Whirlpool Corp.'s Institute of Fabric Science.
</P>
<P>
   That means on the day more than one load is being washed, when
the second load of clothes is ready to come out of the washer it
has to wait 20 minutes while the first load finishes drying before
it can go into the dryer.
</P>
<P>
   Whirlpool has introduced a line of high-tech clothes dryers that
the company claims eliminates the lag time by drying an average
load of laundry in 30 minutes instead of 50. The Senseon Drying
System uses moisture and temperature sensors to dry clothes as
quickly as possible without overdrying or excessive shrinkage.
</P>
<P>
   Lucinda Ottusch, Whirlpool's senior home economist, said the
Senseon Drying System uses two types of sensors: strips that
monitor the amount of moisture in the clothes and a ``thermister,''
a heat-sensing device to track the temperature in the dryer
chamber.
</P>
<P>
   The user sets the dryer to a category, such as permanent press,
and the sensor array monitors the progress of the drying process
cutting off the cycle as soon as the clothes are sufficiently dry.
The sensors can tell the type of laundry being dried _ denim pants
vs. blouses, for example _ and adjust the drying cycle
appropriately.
</P>
<P>
   Ottusch said the average homemaker tends to keep clothes in the
dryer until they are bone dry; that takes extra time and can damage
the fabric. The Senseon Drying System, she said, lets clothes keep
some of their natural moisture while reducing drying times.
</P>
<P>
   Whirlpool started shipping its new Senseon dryers to retailers
this month.
</P>
<P>
   Several dryers are available with the Senseon Drying System, and
their manufacturer's suggested retail prices go up to about $599.
</P>
<P>
   Whirlpool offers Senseon dryers in electric and gas models and
with either digital or mechanical (dial) controls, and one model
has a ``Resource Saver Cycle'' that reduces energy consumption.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
