<DOCNO> NYT20000730.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-30 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7420 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-LOVE-CONNECTION0731-C     07-30 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOVE-CONNECTION0731-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Looking for the love connection
 &HT;    By Lori Cumpston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ There's nothing worse than being set up
on a blind date, am I right?
</P>
<P>
   First of all, it's hard enough being on a date with someone you
know, but the tension is only compounded when meeting somebody for
the first time on a first date.
</P>
<P>
   There is always the fear of getting lettuce stuck between your
teeth while eating dinner, which isn't exactly a good thing when
negotiating a second date.
</P>
<P>
   Or you worry that your palms are all sweaty, which only makes
the problem worse. And then there is the issue of a goodnight kiss
provided your date hasn't escaped out the bathroom window of the
restaurant sometime during the evening.
</P>
<P>
   I am proud to report that none of the above happened in The
Grand Junction Daily Sentinel's experiment called, ``The Dating
Game.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, we matched up singles in the valley on the basis of
compatibility and interests. The idea came after hearing single
people complain that there aren't any singles in the valley. We
sent out questionnaires to those who are unattached and selected 10
people from a pool of dating candidates.
</P>
<P>
   It's time now to reveal who was matched up with whom and what
happened on the da open to meeting lots of people because that's
the only way to meet someone interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Couple No. 2: Sandy Miller, 48, and George Kelly, 47.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy is an assistant executive director for a nonprofit and
George is a general contractor.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy's motto is, ``Life's short, make the most of it.'' So when
she heard that The Daily Sentinel was looking for singles, she
filled out a questionnaire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like a little adventure,'' said Sandy. ``Why pass up the
opportunity to meet someone new?''
</P>
<P>
   One of the characteristics Sandy looks for in the opposite sex
is a good sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   George describes his sense of humor as zany and he loves to make
others laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy and George met at Bailey's in the Grand Vista Hotel for a
glass of wine and then went to Applebee's for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, George and Sandy didn't really have that much
in common and probably won't go out again, although she did admit
George was ``pretty entertaining.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to meet people, but it's that `right' person that is
more difficult to find,'' said Sandy.
</P>
<P>
   Couple No. 3: Chris Herrman, 37, and Raphael Allred, 27.
</P>
<P>
   Raphael is a family practice resident and Chris is the western
region director of a land conservation nonprofit.
</P>
<P>
   When Chris picked up Raphael at her house, he noticed she had a
jukebox _ a good sign since they are both music lovers. The date
started with dinner at Suehiro, a sushi bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about all kinds of stuff,'' said Chris. ``All
evening the conversation flowed easily. We talked about Greek,
Roman and Biblical history because I had just been to Turkey.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Really good conversation,'' added Raphael. ``I had a good
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The date concluded with ice cream and tunes from the jukebox
where they both ended up talking over the music.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no problem being single, so I don't think it's hard
being single here,'' said Chris. ``But it's challenging to connect
with like-minded single people, especially if you don't do the bar
scene. The sports that I do tend to be solitary kinds of things, so
it's unlikely to meet somebody after you've just hiked an hour into
the Black Canyon.''
</P>
<P>
   Couple No. 4: Blanche Means, 23, and Allen Gemaehlich, 26.
</P>
<P>
   Blanche is a page coordinator and Allen is a sports writer for
The Daily Sentinel.
</P>
<P>
   Blanche and Allen's date started at the Rockslide Brew Pub for
lunch, which was followed up by an evening showing of ``The
Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle'' at the Carmike Cinema.
</P>
<P>
   The date went pretty well with the basic getting-to-know-you
stuff and that's when they discovered they really didn't have a
whole lot in common and their viewpoints differed on being single.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that meeting people is hard,'' said Blanche,
``especially for shy people like me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as hard (being single in Grand Junction) as other
places I've been,'' said Allen. ``I'm optimistic about meeting
someone here. There's a good range of people my age, so I feel the
possibilities are there and it's just a matter of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though there wasn't a love connection, Allen is teaching
Blanche how to play tennis and their ``chance'' meeting could be
the beginning of a new friendship.
</P>
<P>
   Couple No. 5: Ann Winterholter, 26, and Scott Poindexter, 36.
</P>
<P>
   Ann is a copy editor at The Daily Sentinel and Scott is a
chiropractor.
</P>
<P>
   Scott says it's challenging to meet single people in Grand
Junction who are in his age range because ``Most single people are
in Denver trying to make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether it's difficult being single in Grand Junction, Ann
said, ``It depends on who you are. I think it's harder if you
absolutely know what you want and it's absolutely not here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty Cap Trail was the setting for Scott and Ann's
evening hike. The open trail gave them a chance to talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a date like that, you have no idea who that person is,''
said Ann. ``So on the first date, if you can at least be friends,
that's important.''
</P>
<P>
   On the hike down, Ann talked about her interest in music and
Scott described his adventures working at a steakhouse in Japan.
They also discovered they attend the same church.
</P>
<P>
   The hike was followed by dinner at Suehiro.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really think about (being single),'' said Ann. ``I
enjoy hanging out with my friends and I have plenty to do. When I'm
ready to fall in love, I will.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
