A7478 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-INSURE-EARNINGS-NYT &LR;      07-30 0437
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSURE-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS TAKE NOTE OF INSURERS' EARNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Good earnings reports for some of the biggest names in American
commercial insurance last week suggested that long-depressed prices
for coverage were beginning to rise. And that caught the attention
of investors.
</P>
<P>
   Share prices rose sharply for American International Group, the
biggest and strongest of the group, as well as for Chubb Corp.; St.
Paul Cos.; Marsh &AMP; McLennan Cos., the world's largest insurance
brokerage, and Hartford Financial Services Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prospects are clearly improving,'' said Weston Hicks, an
analyst at J.P. Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   Marsh McLennan &AMP; Cos., the world's largest insurance broker,
reported a 17 percent rise in operating earnings, to $506 million,
for the second quarter. American International Group, widely known
as AIG, posted an increase of 13 percent, to $1.43 billion.
Hartford Financial Services also reported an increase of 13
percent, to $239 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Chubb Group reported a 10.5 percent rise in operating
income, to $180.7 million, but its per-share earnings remained flat
at $1, reflecting an issue of stock for the recent purchase of
Executive Risk, a company specializing in liability coverage for
company executives and board members.
</P>
<P>
   But, as did the St. Paul Cos., which reported a 9 percent
decline in operating income, to $158.9 million, Chubb reported
improvements in profits in its commercial lines. At Hartford Group,
earnings from life insurance offset heavy property-casualty claims.
But the company reported a 7 percent increase in worldwide property
casualty premiums, to $1.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is so excited because it is seeing things happening
that are going to lead to better results in the future,'' Hicks
said.
</P>
<P>
   The stocks had extra spring in them, he said, because, in terms
of revenue and net assets, they have been trading at extremely
cheap prices.
</P>
<P>
   Maurice R. Greenberg, the chief executive of AIG, which operates
in more than 130 countries, said that in his company's domestic
business ``there is an increasingly better tone to the commercial
property-casualty market as rates continue to firm.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Frank, an analyst at Salomon Smith Barney, noted that
several of the property-casualty companies had negotiated higher
prices with customers. Frank upgraded his rating on St. Paul Cos.
from neutral to buy and increased his price targets for St. Paul as
well as AIG and Chubb.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing the commercial insurance market improving
virtually across the board,'' Frank said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-00 1606EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000730.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-30 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7479 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CNV-GOP-SHOW0731-COX     07-30 1314
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNV-GOP-SHOW0731-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush strives for 'different' convention
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ He turned to his father's Cabinet for a running
mate and his father's friends for a boatload of campaign cash. Now,
George W. Bush is choreographing a Republican National Convention,
which begins today, aimed at showing that this is not his father's
GOP.
</P>
<P>
   It's something of a political high-wire act, balancing reverence
for his family's and party's past while promising something new.
Behind the scenes, Bush and the party that will nominate him for
president this week have decided on a strategy that uses the word
``different'' as often as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since Governor Bush is a different kind of Republican it
should come as no surprise that this will be a different kind of
Republican convention,'' Bush campaign spokesman Ray Sullivan said
as the team geared up for tonight's opening of the Republican
National Convention's four-night run.
</P>
<P>
   Different could be a hurdle for a candidate who is Bush-born and
bred, right down to his beloved dog Spot, the offspring of the late
Millie, a White House pet. The effort begins early on opening
night. Eager to put a new, more inclusive face on the GOP,
convention officials have loaded the program with people of color
and others not usually associated with the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's first half-hour will include Mari Griego, a
10-year-old New Mexico girl who has won honors for her art work.
The invocation will be offered by Rabbi Victor Weisburg of
Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have the usual parade of elected officials,'' said
Bush, noting a schedule filled with ordinary people who have done
extraordinary things.
</P>
<P>
   Running mate Dick Cheney, who served as defense secretary for
the elder Bush, also has gotten the word that ``different'' is an
important part of the message.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many respects he is different than his dad,'' Cheney said
on Fox News Sunday. ``I know them both pretty well now. Governor
Bush is very much a Texan, a lot more like his mother in some
respects.''
</P>
<P>
   Also different will be the way Bush is nominated. Instead of
saving the roll call vote for the convention's third night, the
process will begin with a group of states tonight and continue
through Wednesday. Currently, there are not plans to take Bush's
home state of Texas out of order to put him over the top the moment
that he officially secures his party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The great state of Alabama is scheduled to begin the voting
tonight. The great state of Iowa is scheduled to end tonight's
portion of the voting.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the voting, Bush's name will be placed in nomination
today by one of the 2,066 delegates who are converging on this
city.
</P>
<P>
   It's all been concocted to come off as a four-night live-action
miniseries to launch the general election campaign of a candidate
who knows that the old way _ which led to Republican defeats in
1992 and 1996 _ won't get it done this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Viewers should expect to see real people representing
educators, working families, senior citizens, people with
disabilities and new Americans,'' said Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Different'' being the operative, oft-repeated word.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ours will be a different kind of convention for a different
kind of Republican,'' said Andy Card, convention co-chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Different will be measured by the standard set by the GOP
conventions in Houston in 1992, when the elder George Bush was
re-nominated, and in San Diego in 1996, when Bob Dole got the nod.
Both went on to lose their elections to President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The 1992 convention, especially Pat Buchanan's speech, gave the
GOP a right-wing face it is still battling to shed. Buchanan, who
had blistered the elder Bush during the 1992 primaries, urged
delegates to join a ``religious war for the soul of America.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan is gone this year, self-exiled to the Reform Party
after his candidacy went nowhere in early GOP contests.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's attempt to put an inclusive face on the GOP will be
helped by events such as today's gay and lesbian luncheon,
highlighted by Bush adviser Mary Matalin. Organizers are billing
the meeting as ``the first time the gay and lesbian community has
joined together at a Republican National Convention in such large
numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   It may well end up highlighting how the party, especially its
influential conservative faction, will react to the fact that one
of Cheney's two daughters is openly gay.
</P>
<P>
   Also on hand will be Rep. Jon Kolbe of Arizona, the only openly
gay Republican in Congress. Tuesday night, Kolbe will speak at the
convention, though his topic is international trade, not gay
rights.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush inclusion message will take on its bi-partisan face
Thursday night when he is introduced by Jan Bullock, widow of
Democratic Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock, who befriended Bush, endorsed him
for re-election in 1998 and talked about him as a presidential
candidate long before other officials did.
</P>
<P>
   But mixed in with the new will be links to the GOP past. Tuesday
night, retired Gen. Norman Schwarzkopf will speak to delegates from
the USS New Jersey on the eve of the 10th anniversary of Iraq's
invasion of Kuwait, which sparked Operation Desert Storm.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Gen. Colin Powell, another key figure in Desert Storm,
speaks tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Also speaking Tuesday night will be Elizabeth Dole and John
McCain, both of whom endorsed Bush after he beat them in the
primaries. McCain, who never settled his differences with Bush over
campaign finance reform, is prepared to play good soldier,
according to an early draft of his speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many years ago, the governor's father fought for our country,
with distinction, under the command of my grandfather. Now it is my
turn to serve under the son of my grandfather's subordinate,'' the
draft said.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night speeches by Elizabeth Dole and husband Bob will
offer critics a handy tie to the GOP past. You have to go back to
1972 to find a GOP ticket that did not include a Bush or a Dole.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, it all adds up to an ambitious effort to re-package
his party. University of Texas presidential scholar Bruce Buchanan
is waiting to see if the GOP can pull it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to rally his troops, which is an internal matter, and
it means avoiding any kind of unpleasant disharmony on the floor
that gets televised concerning abortion or anything else
controversial,'' said Buchanan. ``This is his first opportunity
with a large national TV audience to introduce himself and set a
tone. What he has got to do is portray himself and (running mate
Dick) Cheney as authentic purveyors of compassionate conservatism
and deflect this effort to portray the ticket, through Cheney, as
exceptionally right wing.''
</P>
<P>
   That effort is sure to become a constant theme for Al Gore, who
will pick up the Democratic nomination next month in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said the GOP ticket has ``concocted a strategy of phrases
and photo opportunities to convey the impression of inclusion and
moderation. But you and I know this is not about show business.''
</P>
<P>
   As he campaigns his way toward a Wednesday arrival here, Bush
understands the challenge of trying to honor the past and craft a
new course for the future.
</P>
<P>
   He denies a ``political relationship'' with his father, but said
he plans to use the convention to proclaim his love for his
parents.
</P>
<P>
   And Bush made clear in an interview with ABC television how deep
that love runs: ``If I catch anybody in my campaign saying, `Well
the boy better distance himself from his father,' they're not going
to be around much because this is a relationship that's way beyond
politics.''
</P>
