<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-30 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7483 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-PHOTOS-COMPETE-MEDIA-     07-30 1351
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTOS-COMPETE-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ORGANIZATIONS SPAR FOR THE PERFECT, INCIDENTAL PHOTO 
</HEADLINE>
   By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What am I bid for an image of a supersonic airliner, airborne,
spitting the flames that signaled disaster? Last week, after a
couple of auctions _ consisting of flurries of phone calls and
e-mails on both sides of the Atlantic _ the take for the photograph
snapped by a Japanese businessman was $75,000 and counting.
</P>
<P>
   The price, in part, reflected the economics of scarcity. On
Tuesday afternoon, as firefighters and rescue vehicles streamed
toward the village of Gonesse and the burning shards of the
Concorde airliner, the photographers of agencies like Corbis-Sygma,
Gamma/FHM and SIPA were jumping onto motorcycles and rushing to the
scene, while agency executives were contacting photo editors around
the world, making deals.
</P>
<P>
   But it was three amateurs _ a Hungarian aviation buff, the wife
of a Spanish truck driver, and the Japanese businessman sitting on
another plane at Charles de Gaulle airport in Roissy _ whose luck
and reflexes produced the signature images that news audiences
would carry in their minds' eye.
</P>
<P>
   Their work immediately spawned mini-markets, some as frenetic as
they were ghoulish. There was little consistency in the economics.
Disasters spawn whirlwind negotiations; the process is as
idiosyncratic as a cyclone's path.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are a few standing principles, the same ones that
govern markets everywhere. The fewer the images, the more leverage
the sellers have. The more the photo editors buying know about all
the images available, the more leverage they have.
</P>
<P>
   Wire services tend to pay less than news magazines; tabloids
tend to pay more. And in most cases, auctions and other
negotiations are opened and closed within an hour. Editors and
producers have only that much time to calculate how much to pay to
deprive rivals of an image _ and then calculate whether it is worth
swallowing the cost and possibly ponying up more should a better
image come along before deadline.
</P>
<P>
   The route the Japanese businessman's photo took to become part
of the media bloodstream does not provide a map to future profits
by lucky amateurs. But it does illustrate the system in action.
</P>
<P>
   Buzz, a small new London-based photo agency, heard about the
photo a day after the crash. The businessman, whose name Buzz
executives agreed to keep confidential, reached a member of the
agency through intermediaries, and e-mailed the image to his home
computer, said Steve Lake, a partner in Buzz.
</P>
<P>
   Hearing that the photograph was taken through a plane window
with a disposable camera, Lake's Buzz colleague felt no urgency.
But when he opened the e-mail after returning from work on
Wednesday evening, he turned around. ``He stuck them on a disk,
hopped on a scooter,'' Lake said. ``We popped them on a disk here
and said, `Yes, these are good.'''
</P>
<P>
   It was 8 p.m. in London; newspapers were an hour, more or less,
from their early deadlines. The crash was still big news, but it
was a second-day story. The first day, the young Hungarian's grainy
image of the plane in flight, which had been purchased and
distributed by Reuters, had dominated front pages around the world.
Was there a new still image, or was the Japanese snapshot the lone
new image?
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a few discreet inquiries,'' Lake said. ``There was
nothing on the wire services. We thought, `Well, that gives us a
bit more leverage.'''
</P>
<P>
   They started making calls to newspaper picture desks around
Britain. ``We weren't sure how to price it,'' he added. Their
opening suggestion was 4,000 pounds to 5,000 pounds, or from $6,000
to around $7,500. By the time The Daily Mail, The Mirror, The Sun
and The Express had finished bidding, the price was 16,000 pounds,
or close to $25,000, he said. The auction had taken an hour; when
the Mirror closed the the deal, its presses were ready to start.
</P>
<P>
   The Mirror had purchased the rights to print the image in the
United Kingdom. Thursday morning, the image dominated the tabloid's
cover, under the headline ``NO CHANCE.''
</P>
<P>
   By that time, Lake was on the phone to Germany, selling the
German print rights to the publication Bild. And several photo
agencies, including Gamma and Sygma, were on the phone to Lake,
suggesting that a tiny photo agency with one phone line might not
be equipped to do the large deals for international rights.
</P>
<P>
   Lake agreed. After an auction among photo agencies Thursday
morning, London time, he agreed that Sygma would negotiate further
deals; Buzz would get a percentage. By late morning, New York time,
J.P. Pappis, Sygma's formidable New York-based negotiator, was on
the phone to Sarah Harbutt, the photography director for Newsweek
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Harbutt, like her counterparts, Michele Stephenson at Time,
Bronwen Latimer at U.S. News &AMP; World Report, and Maura Foley at
People, was looking for new images.
</P>
<P>
   The rush of photographers to the crash scene had already
produced some wrenching photos. Some of these were spoken for: Time
had a deal with Gamma/FHM giving it rights to the work of Eric
Bouvet. Bouvet, who had been on a long-term assignment illustrating
the work of French firefighters, got access to the crash scene
through his fire contacts. But Bouvet's best pictures were also the
hardest for viewers to take: They showed charred corpses. ``It
looks almost like Hiroshima,'' Stephenson said. ``Very strong. But
it was too much to ask people to look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Newsweek had struck its deal with Sygma. On Tuesday, Harbutt
said, she had paid $5,000 to underwrite the cost of eight Sygma
photographers at the scene, in return for first refusal on their
images.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Pappis called Newsweek to offer first crack at the
Japanese businessman's snapshot, an image new to the United States.
For that, Harbutt said, Pappis proposed Newsweek pay $25,000. After
``lots of back and forth'' the two settled on a fee closer to
$15,000 _ if you count the $5,000 Newsweek kicked in earlier,
closer to $20,000. Pappis said he never discusses the terms of his
deals.
</P>
<P>
   Pappis, Harbutt said, ``makes you feel like the whole world
wants this image and you are about to lose this image.'' But buying
it is making a bet that there is no better image out there, at
least none that will surface before the magazine goes to press
Saturday. ``When I buy at the beginning of the week, I run the risk
of being trumped,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Quality is another consideration. Harbutt said she considers
whether an image is good enough to carry the cover, or whether it
could be displayed across two inside pages.
</P>
<P>
   How much will the Japanese businessman earn? It depends on his
deal with Buzz, and Buzz's deal with Sygma. ``He could have
negotiated for himself,'' Harbutt said, ``but John Q. Public
wouldn't know how.''
</P>
<P>
   When amateurs have some business acumen, she said, they can
drive prices up. Stephenson said that one of the higher prices Time
ever paid for an image went to a young business student who had, in
a shoebox, the now-famous photograph of a photograph of Monica
Lewinsky, in a beret, smiling up at President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   How fast do photographs lose their value? ``It depends on the
newsworthiness of the story,'' said Latimer of U.S. News. ``The
amateur photographs taken in the Oklahoma bombing were iconic.'' As
for the Concorde disaster, she said, the Hungarian student's image
``will remain in people's minds a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Reuters will not disclose how much it paid for that first image
of the Concorde in flight; printed accounts in Britain put the
figure at under $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   If those figures are anywhere close to accurate, the image that
thus far defined the Concorde crash, the image that had the widest
audience, earned a small fraction of the fees that the Japanese
businessman's image will attract.
</P>
<P>
   As Stephenson explained it, ``People want to know how much you
can make from a photo like this. But there's no way to put a value
on it, because the value depends so much on the timing, and on what
else is out there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
