<P>
   PHOTOS-COMPETE-MEDIA (Undated) _ What am I bid for an image of a
supersonic airliner, airborne, spitting the flames that signaled
disaster? Last week, after a couple of auctions _ consisting of
flurries of phone calls and e-mails on both sides of the Atlantic _
the take for the photograph of the Concorde crash, snapped by a
Japanese businessman, was $75,000 and counting. The route the photo
took to become part of the media bloodstream does not provide a map
to future profits by lucky amateurs. But it does illustrate the
system in action. By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved.)
</P>
