<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-PROTESTS31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PARADE IS A PATCHWORK QUILT OF PROTEST
 &HT;    540&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Merrily anti-Republican, they cavorted for a
collage of causes on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   At least on this sunny day, peace and humor prevailed for the
thousands of protesters who rallied several miles from the First
Union Center, where the Republican National Convention officially
opens Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrators danced down the Benjamin Franklin Parkway while
GOP delegates looked down from the balconies of high-rise hotels.
At the end of their march, they staged a street festival near the
steps of the Philadelphia Museum of Art, where ``Rocky'' ended his
triumphant training run.
</P>
<P>
   Police watched from sidewalks, squad cars and motorcycles all
along the route, but the march attracted fewer than half of the
expected 20,000 demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   Anarchist and anti-globalist groups have threatened more
confrontation and disruption after the convention convenes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want people to know that they are going to have every
opportunity to say what they want to say _ no matter what words
they want to use,'' Police Commissioner John Timoney told the
Associated Press after riding his bicycle alongside the protesters.
``We're fair, we're equitable, but we're also prepared to keep
everyone safe.''
</P>
<P>
   The Unity 2000 gathering brought together scores of groups with
a myriad of causes and grievances.
</P>
<P>
   Only the satirical ``Billionaires for Bush'' carried signs
supporting the Republican nominee, and they were really advocating
campaign reform.
</P>
<P>
   There were placards for abortion rights, animal rights, freeing
Tibet and Burma, gay rights, universal health care, reparations for
the descendants of slaves, the death penalty and organized labor.
There were signs against rich people, the Star Wars missile
defense, suburban sprawl, police brutality, Latin American death
squads, capitalism, multinational corporations and lynching.
</P>
<P>
   ``More good. Less evil,'' summed up a bunch of chanting guys in
orange T-shirts with a big ``L'' for libertarian.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oink. Oink,'' said somebody dressed as a pink pig in protest
of the ``greed'' of the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Stu Chaifetz, a Green Party congressional candidate in New
Jersey, wore a ``Go Vegan'' tank top and campaigned against bear
hunting in his home state. Some Asian Americans rallied against
Philadelphia's plan to build a new baseball park in Chinatown. A
group of Mohawks in ``Warpath'' T-shirts jogged by without slowing
to explain why.
</P>
<P>
   Merchants of many movements set up tables and sold radical
wares. For $10, you could buy a T-shirt that said ``Dubya. Dubya.
Dubya. Bushoncrack.com'' or ``Support Organic Farmers'' or
``Veterans for Peace.'' Fittingly, they were giving away bumper
stickers that said ``If God Existed, Capitalism Wouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Chute, the author of the critically praised novel, ``The
Beans of Egypt, Maine,'' carried a ``Border Mountain Militia'' flag
but tied her camouflage jacket around her waist in the midday sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a no-wing militia. We don't believe in capitalistic or
socialistic power,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many of the demonstrators said they dislike Democrats as
much as they loathe Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties are corrupt and the political system has to be
scrapped, declared Matt Prescott, an anarchist and student at the
University of New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the system is utterly unreformable and that the
only solution is armed revolution,'' said Frank Rochencio, an
avowed communist who lives in Philadelphia. ``That's what our
organization is training for.''
</P>
<P>
   Rochencio marched in cadence with the Revolutionary Communist
Youth Brigade, who wore red bandanas on their heads and black
T-shirts that read, ``I was born in this sewer called capitalism
but now I'm living for revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming from New York City, Laura Short wore the black-and-white
striped suit of a convict and had a ball and chain attached to her
ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corrections Corporation of America,'' was written on her back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real corporation,'' he said. ``It's scary. Prisons for
profit. Captive labor. I came because of the Republicans, but if I
lived in the West, I would have gone for the Democrats. There are
no differences. Behind the masks, they're the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Minor clashes erupted between anti-abortion and abortion rights
activists, including an injury to an abortion rights protester and
a shouting match between a police captain and the leader of an
anti-abortion group, AP reported. Tim Troxler, 34, received minor
injuries when he fell off a truck with anti-abortion messages on it
while he tried to cloak the truck in an abortion rights banner.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the rare moments of argument came in the name of
Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   A group of gay activists shouted ``We're Here! We're Queer!''
after surrounding a man in a purple shirt and straw hat who carried
a sign listing lesbians as among a long list of folks destined to
``burn in a lake of fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, Tom Franklin, who said he had a fundamentalist ministry
in Los Angeles, preached fire and brimstone from the curb.
</P>
<P>
   ``The death penalty was established by God,'' he shouted at the
passing protesters. ``You people need to read the Bible. Don't be
atheist, communist fools all your lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Jesus was a victim of the death penalty, responded a marcher,
among a group chanting ``You say death row. We say hell no.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
