<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Monday, July 31. The N.Y. Times News Service
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken; phone: (888) 346-9867 or (212)
556-1927.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA-VOTE (Caracas) _ A test of strength for Latin
America's newest strongman, Hugo Chavez, who seems assured of
winning the presidency in ``mega elections,'' but whose opponents
may fare better in congressional and gubernatorial races. By Larry
Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-HEBRON (Hebron) _ A talk with the most radical settlers
in Israel. By John F. Burns.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GOP-RDP (Philadelphia) _ A ledeall on the doings. Length TK. By
Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-LAURA-BUSH (Undated) _ A profile of Laura Bush. 3200 words.
By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-POLL (Philadelphia) _ Despite the trappings of a new, more
diverse and inclusive Republican Party, a poll of the delegates
shows that they are mostly white, male, middle-aged, and wealthy.
With comments from delegates. 1300 words. By Adam Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   COPYRIGHT-SUIT (New York) _ The trial in Manhattan in which
eight movie studios are suing a hacker magazine for copyright
infringement is about much more than whether publishing the
software code for cracking DVD security is a copyright violation.
The case, like the one involving Napster, is actually a broader
stage for playing out the rights of media companies to control
access to their digital content. By Amy Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-ECONOMY-LABOR (Undated) _ It is a faceoff between Old-Line
Labor and the New Economy. Verizon (formerly Bell Atlantic and
GTE), which does business in 30 states and is the nation's largest
telecommunications employer, is facing a contract deadline on
Sunday, Aug. 6, with its two biggest unions. And one of the key
issues is whether and how to give tens of thousands of non-union
wireless network employees around the nation the opportunity to
join the unions that have long represented the nation's wired
telephone industry: the Communications Workers of America and the
International Brotherhood of Electrical workers. Here's a look at
the issues and the chances of a strike next weekend. By Steven
Greenhouse.
</P>
</TEXT>
