<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAIN, CHAIN, CHENEYISMS
</HEADLINE>
  
By LEAH GARCHIK 
Copyright 2000 Hearst Corporation
<TEXT>
<P>
   How out of it is &UR; T.S. Bolton &LR; ? ``I hear George W. picked  &UR; Lon &LR; 
 &UR; Chaney &LR;  as his running mate,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   And the mean old MoJo wire, www.motherjones.com, which comes
from a different political side than the vice presidential
candidate, has collected some of his pronouncements: ``I had other
priorities in the '60s than military service,'' he told the
Washington Post in 1989, explaining why he escaped serving in
Vietnam. ``I flunked out,'' he said in 1991 of his career at Yale.
``I set out to be a political science teacher,'' he said in 1978.
``My years in Washington sort of got in the way of that, but it all
ties in. What I want to do is political stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. In regard to the candidate's running mate,
georgewbush.comologist  &UR; Roy Freborg &LR;  points out that in the site's
weekend trivia contest, `` &UR; Willie Mayes &LR; '' (didn't he run an Oyster
House in San Francisco?) is named as  &UR; George W. &LR; 's childhood sports
hero.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Personals has received several suggestions for George
W.'s campaign plane names: ``Airhead One'' ( &UR; Gar Smith &LR; ); ``Phony
Express'' ( &UR; Bob Lacey &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DRY SPELL FOR GOSSIP &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Gossip columnist &UR; Diana McLellan &LR; , who went from the Washington
Star to the Post to Washingtonian, a monthly, says that gossiping
in the nation's capital isn't as much fun nowadays as it used to
be. ``One big change is that people in their forties, fifties and
sixties are on the wagon _ both the characters in the political
mill and the reporters who cover it. I saw a middle-aged couple at
a funeral the other day sucking on bottled water during the service
to `stay hydrated.' ...
</P>
<P>
   ``People can't relax. Because of the drunk-driver crackdown,
nobody gets drunk except  &UR; Christopher Hitchens &LR; , and I'm sure
that's just to make everyone else seem interesting. One
politician's wife described Washington as like an Ivy League
university during a never-ending week of finals.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IF YOU HAVE A LEMON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Alex Behr &LR; 's sorry she lost out on Item No. 384361276, a
``Moldy Lemon'' auctioned on eBay last week by her friend, &LR; 
 &UR; Geoff &LR; , drummer of Supreme Reality. Starting price was eight cents;
21 bids later, it sold for $6.75.
</P>
<P>
   The seller's description of this fetching item, which was
pictured from several angles: ``I bought this lemon at the Pak N
Save and at that time it was not moldy. After several weeks it
started to get a little moldy so I put it in the window. Now it is
quite moldy. I've recently replaced the lemon with some that aren't
so moldy ... but for what it is it's a pretty good moldy lemon. You
pay shipping.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOW THINGS LOOK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Karl Lagerfeld &LR; 's planned Chanel exhibit for the costume
division of the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York was called
off when he butted heads with  &UR; Philippe de Montebello &LR; , boss of the
Met. ``The museum has such old-fashioned ideas,'' the designer told
W. ``It became entirely hopeless. They wanted an exhibit of a bunch
of old clothes. I am not interested in a retrospective of a bunch
of old clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   Next on the Met's costume agenda: a retrospective of  &UR; Jackie &LR; 
 &UR; O &LR; 's clothing.
</P>
<P>
   - In an homage to  &UR; Dolly Parton &LR;  in the Southern music issue of
the Oxford American,  &UR; Hal Crowther &LR;  calls her ``one of the most
engagingly authentic individuals in the Nashville pantheon.
Restoring her parents' old home place in the Smoky Mountains, Dolly
designed her new toilets as a faux outhouse _ an irony she
understands on the same level  &UR; Robert Penn Warren  &LR; would have
understood it.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Ken Maley &LR;  saw them, and heard the judge officiating, but
couldn't figure out which two of the five people dressed in Santa
Claus suits and wearing dark glasses were getting married on the
balcony over City Hall's grand staircase on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't be bothered writing my name on the ballot, then
you don't deserve to have me.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; - Perennial presidential candidate  &UR; Michael Levinson &LR; , who
has run 12 times and whose name will not appear on the ballot in
any state. Levinson was quoted in the Hill.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
