<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-30 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7501 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-VIVENDI-MARKETPLACE-N     07-30 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIVENDI-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: LACK OF DATA ON VIVENDI-SEAGRAM LEAVES ANALYSTS
PUZZLED
</HEADLINE>
  By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``What is a Vivendi?'' That is what some bewildered Wall Street
media analysts were asking last month when Vivendi SA announced
that it was buying the Seagram Co. for what was then $34 billion in
stock.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those analysts are still trying to figure out what
Vivendi is _ or at least what it is up to with Seagram. And their
puzzlement has made them reluctant to offer investors guidance on
whether to buy or avoid the shares of both companies.
</P>
<P>
   That reluctance has translated into listless stock prices for
both Seagram and Vivendi. Seagram shares are trading well below the
premium Vivendi has agreed to pay. And in Europe, Vivendi shares
have dropped roughly 27 percent since rumors of the deal first
circulated.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, a core group of analysts say they have
received little insight into the economics of the merger between
Seagram, a liquor and media company based in Montreal, and Vivendi,
a diversified French company that has stakes in the water,
environmental, industrial, telecommunications and entertainment
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The folks at Vivendi have gotten very ham-handed advice from
their bankers,'' said Christopher Dixon, media analyst at
PaineWebber, who is one of those frustrated by how little guidance
he said Vivendi had been giving to analysts and institutional
investors. Lazard Freres in Paris represented Vivendi in the
merger, while Goldman, Sachs represented Seagram. Both investment
banks, and the merging companies, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Dixon and other analysts say that Vivendi, which until the
announcement of this deal was not well known in the United States,
had been adding and spinning off assets at a dizzying pace. This
makes the company's financial performance and growth prospects hard
to calculate, even before the Seagram deal. And since the deal,
they say, Vivendi has done little to explain the value of acquiring
Seagram or to articulate a growth plan.
</P>
<P>
   The communications gap stems in part from the trend toward
global mergers. Investment analysts in this country are accustomed
to receiving detailed financial data from each partner in a merger.
They expected Vivendi and Seagram to provide the data that would
enable them to make projections. While some of those figures are
public, much of Vivendi's data remains veiled, an analyst said,
because ``French accounting rules do not necessarily disclose how
things are being consolidated.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, such projections are produced by enthusiastic and
aggressive investment bankers and chief executives eager to
consummate mergers. Whether or not the future proves them accurate,
they are at least a basis for analysts to start building their own
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   But in this case, there is little to build upon. More than a
month after the deal was announced, on June 20, there are few
specifics, according to several analysts. ``If you call the
company, they will tell you they are anticipating 40 percent
growth,'' one analyst said. ``But they don't tell you how they will
get that growth. They tell you it will come from telephone and
entertainment, and then tell you they will get back to you.''
</P>
<P>
   An executive close to Vivendi and its bankers at Lazard Freres
responded that Vivendi had been forthcoming with financial data and
that much of the information was publicly available. But an analyst
pointed out that because Vivendi was now projecting faster growth
than the company's historical growth rates, past data were not all
that enlightening.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem in global deals lies in logistics and
geography. When Vivendi announced the purchase on June 20, it was
8:45 a.m. in Paris _ 2:45 a.m. in New York _ an hour when few
analysts are glued to their television sets or computer screens.
Vivendi officials flew to New York that day and held a news
conference. But a subsequent conference call with analysts seemed
only to annoy Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came on the phone and never really described the deal,''
Dixon recalled. ``They just took questions.'' It was a stark
contrast to the custom of executives at American companies, who
typically make detailed presentations of merger plans.
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks later, Vivendi and Seagram held a conference call.
This time, Seagram's chief executive, Edgar Bronfman Jr., fielded
questions solo for 45 minutes, because Vivendi's chairman,
Jean-Marie Messier, was late, compounding Wall Street analysts'
irritation. Ed Hatch, an entertainment analyst at SG Cowen, said,
``The call was a big feel-good meeting, but it was totally
useless.''
</P>
<P>
   Some believe that the scarcity of data is having a negative
effect on the two companies' stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal, each Seagram share would be
exchanged for 0.8 Vivendi share _ assuming Vivendi's stock remains
below $96.69.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Friday's closing price in Paris for Vivendi of 86.5
euros a share, or $79.84, the 0.8-to-1 ratio means that Seagram
theoretically should be trading at $63.87. But Seagram shares on
the New York Stock Exchange closed Friday at $56.50 _ or an 11.5
percent discount to the deal's valuation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the merger is expected to close by the end of the year,
that discount could be compelling for investors if they could have
confidence in the Vivendi story,'' said Scott Davis, who follows
Seagram for First Union Securities. But, he added, ``the
information on Vivendi is still forthcoming.''
</P>
<P>
   Dixon of PaineWebber attributes the two stocks' performance to
the lack of guidance from the companies. ``The net result,'' he
said, ``is that everyone has shrugged their shoulders, walked away
and said, `Who needs this now?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Dixon is among the shruggers. ``If you are going to invest in
the entertainment industry,'' he said, ``remember Woody Allen's
famous line, `The secret to success is showing up.' They haven't
even done that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
