<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-30 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7506 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CONVENTIONS-TV31-COX     07-30 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONVENTIONS-TV31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NETWORKS' CONVENTION SNUB ANGERS POLITICIANS
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The Republican and Democratic party chairmen
Sunday jointly accused the three major television networks of
evading their civic duty by sharply limiting their convention
coverage this year.
</P>
<P>
   But network anchors and news executives said the cutbacks, which
are even more severe than in 1996, were justified.
</P>
<P>
   They have occurred, they said, largely because the political
parties have leached nearly all the controversy out of their
quadrennial conventions, turning them instead into tightly scripted
events that the viewing public finds boring.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the parties want to put on a week-long infomercial, they
have the right to do that,'' Tom Brokaw, anchor of the NBC Nightly
News, told a Harvard-sponsored forum held at Philadelphia's
historic City Hall. ``But we don't have to cover it.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Brokaw added, ``there are many more layers of media out
there that give people more choices than ever before in how to
access the conventions.''
</P>
<P>
   He predicted that by 2008, most Americans will be getting much
of their political news via real-time streaming video on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   CBS News President Andrew Heyward said it was a ``surprise that
we're devoting as much resources as we do.
</P>
<P>
   ``In making the conventions perfect enough to be TV shows, all
the interest has been drained out of them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   CBS and ABC will each air five hours of coverage from the
Republican National Convention, which opens here Monday, while NBC
will limit its air time to half that amount. All three, however,
intend to offer in full the 45-minute acceptance speech that the
GOP nominee, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, will deliver in prime
time on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers fall far short of what Jim Nicholson, the
Republican National Chairman, found acceptable. The networks need
to do much better, he said, for two reasons:
</P>
<P>
   _ Surveys how that one in five voters decides whom to support in
November on the basis on what happens at the conventions.
</P>
<P>
   _ Some 25 million registered voters lack access to either cable
or satellite services, relying on the over-the-air networks for
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a social and moral responsibility to do better,''
Nicholson said. ``Everything doesn't have to be (controversial)
news,'' he added. ``Some of it can be simply information.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson's views were echoed by Edward Rendell, the Democrats'
general chairman. ``What they are doing is flat-out inexcusable,''
said Rendell, who called on the Big Three to air four hours of
convention coverage of each of the four nights.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Brokaw, pressed by the panel moderator, Marvin
Kalb, former director of Harvard's Shorenstein Center for Press,
Politics and Public Policy, conceded that his personal views do not
hold much sway at the network that employs him.
</P>
<P>
   If he were running NBC, he said, it would be doing a lot more
political coverage here, instead of shunting much of his work to
MSNBC, the cable outlet that NBC owns jointly with Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Brokaw criticized the convention planners of both parties
for ``draining all the excitement'' out of these events. ``The
issues have been all worked out in advance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another panelist, Chris Bury, a correspondent for ABC's
``Nightline,'' found it ironic that ``the slicker these shows have
been, the more of the audience gets turned off. I know the
political parties are always looking to get a big bounce out of
their conventions. But we're under no obligation to inflate that
balloon.''
</P>
<P>
   Judy Woodruff, who co-anchors Atlanta-based CNN's election
coverage, aligned herself with the politicians on the
lack-of-coverage issue. The Atlanta-based cable news network will
employ more than 400 staffers to present an extensive convention
report.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: For more information: www.vanishvingvoter.org
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass' e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
