<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: NEW _ AND CURIOUS _ CEASE-FIRE IN KASHMIR MAY BE
SHORT-LIVED 
</HEADLINE>
   By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI _ The conflict between India and Pakistan over the
Himalayan territory of Kashmir is one of the most volatile and
intractable in the world, but the past week has brought the first
tentative signs since intense fighting last summer that tensions
may be lessening, if only for a while.
</P>
<P>
   Hizbul Mujahideen, the largest anti-India militant group
operating in the part of Kashmir controlled by India, announced a
unilateral three-month cease-fire last Monday that is intended, one
of its leaders said, to give ``peace a chance.'' Hizbul has been
fighting for years so that Kashmir, India's only majority Muslim
state, would have the right to join the Islamic nation of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   India, which insists Kashmir is an integral part of India,
reciprocated the Hizbul offer Friday by inviting its leaders and
those of all other militant groups in Kashmir for talks. And the
Indian army followed up Saturday with an announcement that it was
suspending all military operations against Hizbul Mujahideen,
though not against other militant groups.
</P>
<P>
   But the fragility of this peace initiative became apparent
Sunday: Hizbul was already threatening to revoke its cease-fire
offer unless India agreed to make the talks ``unconditional.''
</P>
<P>
   When it invited Hizbul to negotiate, India left out its usual
requirement that such talks occur within the context of the Indian
constitution, which defines Kashmir as an inalienable part of
India. But Brajesh Mishra, India's national security adviser, said
in a television interview Saturday night that the constitution
would still define the conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Mishra's statement apparently outraged Hizbul, which said in a
handwritten statement from Islamabad Sunday, ``India is once again
using its traditional deception and duplicity. Unless New Delhi
announces in unequivocal and categorical terms that talks will be
unconditional and not under the Indian constitution, the Hizbul
will not honor the cease-fire promise.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear what is behind the Hizbul Mujahideen's initiative,
which was denounced by other militant groups, as well as by the
head of Pakistan's main religious political party, the
Jamaat-e-Islami, such as whether the cease-fire was conceived by
Hizbul or the result of behind-the-scenes negotiations with
Pakistan, India, or both.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, there seems to be no evidence that either the
Hizbul or India has a solution in mind that would be acceptable to
both parties.
</P>
<P>
   In the past decade, other efforts toward a peaceful solution to
the insurgency in Kashmir have been unsuccessful. And India and
Pakistan have fought two of their three wars since 1947 over
Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   India's Lt. Gen. John Ray Mukherjee, who announced the Indian
army's cessation of operations against Hizbul, said that a majority
of the estimated 1,500 militants in the overwhelmingly Muslim
valley of Kashmir are part of Hizbul. He said that most of them are
from Kashmir, not Pakistan or Afghanistan, but that Hizbul receives
money from Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   India's Home Minister L.K. Advani said on Saturday that the
amount of violence in Kashmir has decreased since Hizbul's
cease-fire announcement.
</P>
<P>
   There is a broad range of speculation about who convinced Hizbul
Mujahideen to declare the cease-fire _ all of which assumes that
Hizbul did not make the decision on its own. India Today, a news
magazine, reported last week that Indian intelligence sources said
it was their agency that had persuaded leaders of Hizbul, who have
been looking to establish supremacy over the other militant groups
operating in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   Some military analysts in Pakistan and India said they find it
difficult to believe that Hizbul would have taken such a dramatic
step without the tacit approval of its supporters in the Pakistani
government.
</P>
<P>
   They said Hizbul's initiative could be part of a Pakistani
effort to regain the international standing lost last summer when
military forces backed by Pakistan crossed into the Indian-held
portion of Kashmir and occupied some mountain passes, setting off
weeks of heavy fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Once India discovered the incursion, it abruptly ended peace
talks with Pakistan and launched an intensive military assault and
diplomatic efforts that led to the withdrawal of Pakistan-backed
forces from the Kashmir heights. In the West and in India, Pakistan
was seen as the aggressor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could it be that Islamabad was not in the loop? This does not
sound plausible,'' wrote Friday Times military columnist Ejaz
Haider of the Hizbul cease-fire offer. The Friday Times is a weekly
publication based in Lahore, Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   The Pakistan foreign office denied that Pakistan has any
influence with militant groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pakistan does not exercise any control over freedom
fighters,'' the spokesman, Riaz Muhammad Khan, said Saturday at a
press conference in Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about Hizbul's cease-fire offer, he said, ``That is a
matter for Kashmiri leadership to decide as part of the dynamics of
their struggle. We do not wish to comment on that further.''
</P>
<P>
   Since last summer, India has repeatedly refused Pakistan's
offers to resume peace talks, maintaining that it will not
negotiate again with Pakistan until there is a marked decline in
the Pakistan-sponsored militancy in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent decline in violence in Kashmir, India's offer
last week to talk with militant groups, notably, did not include
Pakistan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
