<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-30 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7512 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NEW-ECONOMY-COLUMN-NY     07-30 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-ECONOMY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ECONOMY: AOL'S RIVALS CALL FOR ACCESS TO ITS INSTANT MESSAGING
SYSTEM  
</HEADLINE>
  By LAURIE J. FLYNN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To hear some rivals of America Online talk about it, the case
for opening up its instant messaging service _ or IM, as it is
known in the trenches _ is a struggle between the forces of
democracy and those of autocratic rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Case, on behalf of the IM industry and users everywhere,
tear down this wall!'' Ross Bagully, chief executive of Tribal
Voice, said in testimony before the Federal Communications
Commission last Thursday, after a speech by AOL's chairman, Steve
Case. ``Users of IM, like users of e-mail and the telephone,''
Bagully said, ``deserve the right to free and open communication.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the FCC building a handful of protesters marched with
signs that read, ``Free IM!''
</P>
<P>
   The ``wall'' that Bagully referred to is the partition that
keeps AOL's instant messaging service a closed system _ one that
prevents users of other companies' instant messaging services from
exchanging messages with users of AOL's service. Instant messaging
enables people to send messages over the Internet that pop up on a
recipient's screen almost instantly, allowing people to communicate
in ``real time.''
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual twist, the Microsoft Corp. is among a dozen or so
smaller players in the IM market that decry what they consider to
be AOL's market-dominating behavior in instant messaging, and they
are demanding that it step up efforts to make its system interact
with theirs. Among the other companies that share the 10 percent of
the IM market not occupied by AOL are Yahoo, Odigo, iCast and
Tribal Voice.
</P>
<P>
   It was the outcry by competitors that landed instant messaging
on the agenda of the FCC's hearing, along with other issues _ most
notably the question of equal access to Time Warner's giant cable
network _ as the commission reviews the pending merger of AOL and
Time Warner. As far as instant messaging is concerned, competitors
contend that AOL's closed network stifles innovation and stymies
growth in their industry.
</P>
<P>
   With nearly 180 million registered users so far, IM is
particularly popular with teens and families. But analysts predict
that within a few years business people will account for nearly
half of all IM users.
</P>
<P>
   It is important to note that the debate is not about whether the
various IM systems will ever work together, but about when and how.
Even AOL does not dispute the need for an interconnection standard.
But like most market leaders, the company would prefer to control
the standard.
</P>
<P>
   At last week's FCC hearing, Barry Schuler, president of AOL
Interactive Services, said that the development and testing of an
instant messaging standard would take over a year. AOL has
continually insisted it needs this much time to ensure the privacy
and security of its customers, particularly against spammers _
people or advertisers that blast unsolicited messages to hundreds
or thousands of recipients. But AOL's critics accuse the company of
stalling in order to better solidify its market position.
</P>
<P>
   Schuler said AOL's competitors in instant messaging did not
understand _ or have sufficient sympathy for _ the scope of the
spam problem and how it might impact instant messaging. ``Nobody
else has 23 million people paying them to provide an environment
that's monitored,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the company said, it has already ``opened'' its
network through royalty-free licensing agreements that allow
Internet service providers and Web companies to use AOL Instant
Messenger technology to create their own messaging software.
</P>
<P>
   But AOL's competitors see the spamming and security argument as
a smoke screen. ``They've been saying that the last few months, but
they've never backed it up with facts,'' said Avner Ronen, chairman
of Odigo, which is based in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, when AOL submitted its proposal for an IM
specification to the Internet Engineering Task Force, the industry
committee whose job it is to create a technical standard,
competitors criticized its plan as unacceptably vague _ and a
further sign of foot dragging.
</P>
<P>
   A year can seem an eternity on the Internet. So last week, a few
days before the FCC hearing, IM companies formed a new group to
hasten the arrival of a standard, even if only a temporary one. The
group, which calls itself IMUnified and is led by Microsoft, plans
to release a temporary specification next month that would permit
IM systems to talk to one another while a long-term solution is
developed.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ronen said, ``We hope AOL will come to its senses and
cooperate.''
</P>
<P>
   The IM dispute has been fraught with nastiness and distrust from
the outset. Starting last year, Microsoft and other AOL rivals
began using technical loopholes to interact with AOL's IM users.
Each time, AOL technicians have quickly patched the holes. Odigo, a
small IM provider with about a million users, says that it found a
way to connect its customers to AOL's on 17 recent occasions and
that each time AOL blocked it.
</P>
<P>
   AOL considers these efforts ``attacks'' on its system and vows
to defend itself against security breaches; its competitors contend
their IM customers deserve to be able to freely exchange instant
messages with users of other services.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the AOL-Time Warner merger probably does not hinge
on resolution of the instant messaging dispute. Certainly of
greater concern to the FCC last week seemed to be whether the
merged company would make good on its promise to give all Internet
content providers open access to its cable systems.
</P>
<P>
   But AOL's critics fear that open IM access will arrive even more
slowly if it does not happen before the world's largest Internet
service provider becomes part of the nation's largest Internet and
media company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know from history,'' Bagully said, ``that those who
unfairly exploit a market dominance don't get nicer as they get
bigger.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-00 1800EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
