 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FILM-EASTWOOD &HT;    FILM LEGEND REMAINS A TOUGH GUY WITH A SOFT TOUCH
 &HT;    With optional trim
 &HT;    By LOUIS B. PARKS,
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPACE CENTER, Houston _ The tour groups tromping through
Building 9 at NASA's Johnson Space Center have come to see
astronauts and spaceships. Some also see stars.
</P>
<P>
   Promoting his summer adventure comedy ``Space Cowboys'', which
opens Friday, Clint Eastwood has brought his cast of movie veterans
_ Donald Sutherland, James Garner and Tommy Lee Jones _ to meet the
press at JSC.
</P>
<P>
   It's a return trip for the crew. Last year they filmed several
scenes here for ``Space Cowboys'', a story of vintage test pilots
who finally get a chance to go into space 40 years after their
prime.
</P>
<P>
   It's late now; there's a thunderstorm outside; and Eastwood's
young family _ his wife, Dina Ruiz, and their daughter, Morgan, age
3 _ is waiting for Eastwood to join them in a limousine to a
private plane.
</P>
<P>
   For a guy who is 70 _ yes, Dirty Harry is a senior citizen _
Eastwood looks remarkably fit. True, age lines surround the eyes.
The hair has thinned and grayed.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there's nothing fragile about the tall, thin frame. His eyes
are still steely. He's still the guy who has punched out or blown
away hundreds of villains while playing some of the roughest,
baddest-tempered good guys in movie history.
</P>
<P>
   (start ital)``Do you feel lucky, punk? Well, do ya?''(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   There's no temper or attitude here, however. Eastwood is
soft-spoken, thoughtful, even chatty. His tone is casual.
Welcoming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Space Cowboys'' is an ideal vehicle for Eastwood. He's still
playing a determined, tough guy. (He and Jones exchange friendly
punches.) He's still in the middle of the action, though this time
it's in space.
</P>
<P>
   But he's not packing heat or shooting anybody. The script
emphasizes his age rather than pretending he's still a young buck.
He insists neither he nor his co-stars had a problem playing old
characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``No reluctance at all,'' he says. ``These guys are all very
realistic. That's why I hired 'em.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are other actors sitting around getting cosmetic
surgery, wearing toupees, and maybe those actors, that's fine for
them. But I wanted guys who weren't afraid to be normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd play a grandfather in a second. Because I am a
grandfather. People are more realistic nowadays. There are
grandfathers who are hip, vital people.''
</P>
<P>
   In the movie, Eastwood and his pals were all 1950s Air Force
test pilots who expected to be among the first men in space but
were passed over.
</P>
<P>
   When the movie's unlikely scenario gives these old-timers
another chance to blast into orbit, they jump at it. Unfortunately,
they can no longer jump very high. The film gets great mileage from
the humor in their attempts to get into shape. Eastwood steps aside
and lets the rest of the cast steal most of the laughs, especially
Sutherland as an amorous old boy still chasing everyone in skirts,
including NASA doctors, engineers and astronauts.
</P>
<P>
   When a woman arrives to give the naked flyboys an examination,
everyone ducks and covers _ except Sutherland, who proudly shows he
has the right stuff.
</P>
<P>
   The stars are asked if they wanted stunt doubles for their
backside nude scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Didn't need one,'' the grinning Garner says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our butts were already doubled,'' Sutherland adds.
</P>
<P>
   The movie gets around to slightly more serious stuff as the
septuagenarian astronauts blast off to save the world.
</P>
<P>
   Eastwood had this project in mind even before 77-year-old John
Glenn returned to space in 1998. He picked it because he thought it
would be fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``And (for) the whole idea of resurrection, the chance of guys
coming back,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood movies court a youthful audience, so a big-budget film
in which almost all the stars are well over 50 is a gamble.
</P>
<P>
   ``They go for fads,'' Eastwood says. ``Right now there's sort of
an obsession about making young films, and that's great, that's
cool. I guess they feel (that way) because the audience is younger.
But they don't credit the audience with wanting to see a lot of
different things.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of older audiences are going to see `The Perfect Storm,'
things like that. I've done pictures that appeal to younger
audiences, but I'm not making it for any audience, I'm making it
for everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a little kid watching movies, I always identified
with the grown-up. I wanted to be the gunslinger or the fireman,
the cop, whatever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think young people are sitting there saying, `When I'm 70,
I'd love to be doing an adventure like that.' Not `Grumpy Old Men,'
but guys performing at that age in life. It's kind of a fantasy
thing, but that's what films are all about, fantasy. Granddads in
space.''
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONAL TRIM STARTS HERE
</P>
<P>
   You could also say legends in space, but calling Eastwood a
legend is an understatement. His career spans an incredible 47
years. He started at Universal in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I did was loop (dub) other people that they were too cheap
to bring back and pay for looping,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He had bit parts for several years, but made no impression and
considered giving up acting.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then I did the `Rawhide' series in the late '50s and
'60s,'' he says.``I guess I've been around as long as about
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1964 Sergio Leone spaghetti Western `A Fistful of Dollars'
made Eastwood a star. (He has been Hollywood's No. 1 box-office
attraction of the year five times.) It also ended forever the
traditional American style of Western, which placed clean,
wholesome cowpokes in a tidy, moral West. It was a movie Eastwood
almost didn't make.
</P>
<P>
   ``My agent said, `Do you want to go to Italy and do this
Spanish-German-Italian co-production of a (reworked) Japanese
film?' It's real low-budget. And I said, `No, I really don't. Who's
the director?' Sergio Leone. `Never heard of him.' He did a picture
called `Colossus of Rhodes.' `I said, `Oh, yeah, I saw that. Piece
of (junk).'''
</P>
<P>
   ``A Fistful of Dollars'' is a Western remake of Akira Kurosawa's
samurai movie ``Yojimbo.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I read the script. I loved `Yojimbo,' and I loved Kurosawa.
And they said this guy Leone was clever,'' Eastwood says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd never been to Italy or Germany or Spain, so I said, `Why
not? I'll go over there, I'll get a trip; nobody will ever see the
film.'''
</P>
<P>
   That's not exactly what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``The film came out and surprised everybody, caught them on
their heels,'' Eastwood says, sounding almost wistful.
</P>
<P>
   Shot in Spain with a European cast and crew (except Eastwood),
``A Fistful of Dollars'' was such a hit overseas that it led to two
sequels with Eastwood playing the same role, ``The Man With No
Name,'' in ``For a Few Dollars More'' and ``The Good, The Bad and
the Ugly.'' All three finally made it to the United States in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   ``So sometimes a little dream like that can come true,''
Eastwood says.
</P>
<P>
   Eastwood formed his own company, Malpaso, and made ``Hang 'Em
High,'' which became his first American hit. He's never looked
back.
</P>
<P>
   Westerns remained his metier for years, but Eastwood soon moved
into contemporary crime (``Coogan's Bluff,'' 1968), taking the high
level of screen violence with him. By the time he made ``Dirty
Harry'' (1971), he was clearly a star who would last.
</P>
<P>
   He also became the poster boy for film mayhem, for which he was
soundly criticized. The political attitude of ``Dirty Harry'' (it
was often called a fascist film because of the behavior of
Eastwood's police character) no doubt tempered critics' view of
Eastwood. It was as a director that his work was first taken
seriously by most critics. Since directing himself in ``Play Misty
for Me'' (1971), Eastwood has directed 22 films, starring in all
but three (``Breezy,'' ``Bird'' and ``Midnight in the Garden of
Good and Evil'').
</P>
<P>
   Since 1990, he has directed eight of his nine films. (Wolfgang
Peterson directed ``In the Line of Fire'' when Eastwood wanted a
break after ``Unforgiven.'') He won best director and best picture
Oscars and got his only acting nomination for Unforgiven. He also
directed Meryl Streep when she was nominated for ``The Bridges of
Madison County.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point in his career, Eastwood says, directing gives him
the most satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been interested in the total and not just the one
component,'' he says, quickly adding, ``But I enjoy acting.''
</P>
<P>
   He's still willing to be directed by someone else if the project
is right.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone said, `Let's do a big special-effects movie right
now,''' he says, thinking of all he went through preparing ``Space
Cowboys,'' ``I'd say, `Let's get another director.'''
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS HERE
</P>
<P>
   Eastwood may be a granddad in space, but he's a daddy at home.
He married Ruiz, 34 and his second wife, four years ago. They had
Morgan that same year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep joking that I didn't have any grandchildren, so I had
my own grandchildren,'' Eastwood says.
</P>
<P>
   Eastwood actually is a grandfather. He has two grown children,
Kyle and Allison, with his first wife, Maggie Johnson, and another
daughter, age 6, with Frances Fisher, his co-star in
``Unforgiven.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great,'' Eastwood says of his family life. ``It's one of
the nice things, and unfair about the male gender, that you can
have children at a fairly old age where you can really appreciate
it, and you're not obsessed by a lot of other things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it. I love family, and I'm much more attentive to it
now than I ever was in my life. I know all the `Scooby Doo' tapes
backwards and forwards.''
</P>
<P>
   Family has even replaced moviemaking as the most important thing
in his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get obsessed by work,'' Eastwood says. ``Which I'm not
now. And I thank God for that. If anybody wanted to know the best
part of aging, it's losing that obsession for work. And spending a
little more time with family and personal life. I think it is great
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   He isn't ready to retire, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``I (still) have the passion, but I don't want to do as many
projects.''
</P>
<P>
   He believes that he's getting better at his job as he gets
older.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every experience you have every day goes to making you a
better actor,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an intellectual art form. It's an emotional art form.
A gut-reaction art form. The more you allow your inner guts and
emotion to drive you, the more fun you can have with it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging by ``Space Cowboys,'' Eastwood is still having lots of
fun.
</P>
<P>
   X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
