<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLISH-LIFEGUARDS0731-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pools reflect Poles' summer adventure
 &HT;    By Clint Williams
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The shrill trill of a lifeguard's whistle is the
universal language of public pools the world over. It allows Konrad
Balabuch to maintain order despite a limited command of English.
</P>
<P>
   ``You must jump straight,'' Balabuch says after a sharp, short
blow of his whistle. Then with a sweep of his arms he shows a
cluster of children how they must jump from the diving board to the
middle of the pool, not the side.
</P>
<P>
   Balabuch is one of three college students from Warsaw working as
lifeguards this summer at the Lawrence Street Pool in Marietta, Ga.
The three are among the 30 or so Polish students working as
lifeguards in metro Atlanta for USA Pools, a pool management
company.
</P>
<P>
   The boom in better-paying jobs _ even for high school and
college students _ has made finding enough lifeguards a problem in
metro Atlanta this summer, as it has for the past five years. Most
lifeguards make less than $8 an hour. So for the second straight
year USA Pools recruited lifeguards from Europe and Central America
to work here under four-month visas.
</P>
<P>
   International lifeguards must be at least 20 years old, and they
must pass a Red Cross certification course before donning their
whistle.
</P>
<P>
   His poolside position provides Balabuch, 23, with intensive
practice with English, one of the principal reasons he took the
job. ``But the first reason is to have adventure in America,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   That includes learning what a catfish is and hitting the
nightclubs in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really keen on dancing,'' says 22-year-old Katarzyna
Ostrowicz who during her stay here goes by ``Kathy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ostrowicz spent last summer as a lifeguard at a water park in
Wisconsin, so her English is the best of the group. Still, American
slang _ especially the ubiquitous `wazzzup' _ baffles them all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were learning British English, so it is difficult to
understand slang,'' says Magdalena Rapinczuk.
</P>
<P>
   But the Poles have quickly caught to the importance of a set of
wheels. ``Life in the U.S.A. is impossible without a car,'' says
Rapinczuk.
</P>
<P>
   After renting a car for a month, Ostrowicz and Rapinczuk chipped
in to buy a 1980 Honda Prelude for $800. Balabuch recently went to
an auto auction to buy a car. Pool supervisor John Galloway has
helped the new car owners navigate the paper maze of emissions
testing and getting a car tag.
</P>
<P>
   People who gripe about Atlanta traffic lack global perspective,
the lifeguards say. Traffic here is a breeze compared to Warsaw,
the urban Polish capital where traffic regularly slows to a 2 mph
crawl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traffic,'' Rapinczuk says dismissively. ``I can't see traffic
here.''
</P>
<P>
   But American food is worse _ especially the bread. ``I can't eat
this bread,'' Balabuch says.
</P>
<P>
   Any cultural exchange is mostly one-way at the city pool. The
children playing at the Lawrence Street pool pay attention to the
lifeguards only when the whistle blows. The children at the
Marietta Community School Summer Camp come to the pool each Friday
and most were unaware the lifeguards were from Poland.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently mistaking Polish for Spanish, 8-year-old Geoffrey
Fontenot thought Balabuch was from someplace else altogether. ``I
think he is Mexican 'cause I heard him speaking,'' Geoffrey
explains.
</P>
<P>
   The lifeguards will be working here until September and all
three plan to return to the states, in part because Americans smile
more than Poles.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here are not so serious,'' says Ostrowicz, ``so it's
easy to have fun. People here are really keen on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
