<P>
   CVN-GOPBUSH _ PHILADELPHIA _ George W. Bush crept closer to the
nominating convention Sunday while his running mate, Dick Cheney,
arrived and defended his voting record in Congress on several
Sunday talk shows. (Herman and Heath, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   CVN-MCCAIN _ PHILADELPHIA _ John McCain discovered Sunday how
hard it is to be both a reformer and party loyalist. When the
Arizona senator asked activists at the ``shadow convention'' to
support George W. Bush, he was almost drowned out
</P>
<P>
   by boos and hisses. (Sherman, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   CVN-PROTESTS _ PHILADELPHIA _ More than 200 groups, including a
broad labor union contingent and an array of left-wing
organizations, take part in a Unity 2000 march and rally. (Dart,
Cox News Service) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-CONVENTIONS-TV _ PHILADELPHIA _ The chairmen of the main two
political parties accused the heads of the TV networks Sunday of
shirking their responsibility to educate the American public by
failing to shore more of the
</P>
<P>
   national conventions. At a panel discussion sponsored by the
Shorenstein Center at Harvard's Kennedy School of Government, the
networks responded that such a role is no longer necessary because
of all the alternative ways people can get political information.
(Glass, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   CVN-NOTEBOOK _ PHILADELPHIA _ A reporter's notebook of
Republican National Convention briefs.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-GOP-THEME _ PHILADELPHIA _ He turned to his father's cabinet
for a running mate and his father's friends for a boatload of
campaign cash. Now, George W. Bush is choreographing a Republican
National Convention, which begins Monday,
</P>
<P>
   aimed at showing that this is not his father's GOP. It's
something of a political high-wire act, balancing reverence for his
family's and party's past while promising something new. Behind the
scenes, Bush and the party that will nominate him for president
this week have decided on a strategy that uses the word
``different'' as often as possible. (Herman, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   CONVENTIONS-TV _ PHILADELPHIA _ The Shorenstein Center at
Harvard's Kennedy School of Government holds a panel discussion,
``Is There a Future for On-the-Air Televised Conventions?'' Both
party chairmen and leading representatives of the major TV networks
participate. (Glass, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WITHGOPADVANCER _ It once was a logical point to gather the
masses from different parts of the country to hash out their
differences and agree on the strongest candidate to represent their
party. Now it's an elaborately crafted commercial leading into the
fall campaign. We examine how this year's show will be presented
and what is being done to send out Bush in the best possible light.
It will also include a look at how Bush will handle the possible
spoilers, such as the ant-abortion crowd, John McCain and Alan
Keyes, who is still running for president. (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   BARTON-MEMORIAL _ Covering the memorial service to honor those
killed or wounded in Mark Barton's rampage a year ago. About 2,000
are expected to attend the ceremony. (Shelton, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   EZZARD-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ Dear William Jennings Bryan, Could you
return to Earth? We're desperate for a colorful orator. Although
you electrified the Democratic convention of 1896, you might find
the GOP a more comfortable home today. There's not a history book
around that doesn't still recount your words on the free coinage of
silver: ``You shall not press down upon the brow of labor this
crown of thorns. You shall not crucify mankind on a cross of
gold.'' (Ezzard, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   POLISH-LIFEGUARDS _ ATLANTA _ The shrill trill of a lifeguard's
whistle is the universal language of public pools the world over.
It allows Konrad Balabuch to maintain order despite a limited
command of English. ``You must jump straight,'' Balabuch says after
a sharp, short blow of his whistle. Then with a sweep of his arms
he shows a cluster of children how they must jump from the diving
board to the middle of the pool, not the side. Balabuch is one of
three college students from Warsaw working as lifeguards this
summer at the Lawrence Street Pool in Marietta, Ga. The three are
among the 30 or so Polish students working as lifeguards in metro
Atlanta for USA Pools, a pool management company. (Williams,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BEER-FESTIVAL _ PORTLAND, Ore. _ ``The air is better, the water
is cleaner and the beer is way better.'' Glen Falconer might not
rank them in that order, but he wants you to know that life is
sweeter in Oregon than in Atlanta, where he grew up, attended
college and still visits friends and family. ``In 1971,'' he says,
``I was 10 years old and Atlanta was 1 million people. Today it's _
what? _ 3.2 million.'' There were only 85,000 or so at Portland's
Tom McCall Waterfront Park, where Falconer was among the minor
celebrities this weekend at the 13th Oregon Brewers Festival.
Artisan-in-residence at the popular Wild Duck brewpub in Eugene,
Ore., Falconer was one of 72 brewers whose beer was represented in
the largest gathering of its kind in North America. (Skube, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GOTHS-RELIGION _ Goths wearing black lipstick, white face paint
and bondage gear attended church with regular congregants at the
International Gospel Outreach Family Church in Smyrna, Ga. Sunday,
filling two rows in the back of the church in a silent protest.
They wanted to make a point that they should not be judged on
appearance. Since their pastor equated their kind of music with
devil worship. (MacDonald, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   LOVE-CONNECTION _ GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ There's nothing worse
than being set up on a blind date, am I right? First of all, it's
hard enough being on a date with someone you know, but the tension
is only compounded when meeting somebody for the first time on a
first date. There is always the fear of getting lettuce stuck
between your teeth while eating dinner, which isn't exactly a good
thing when negotiating a second date. (Cumpston, Grand Junction
Daily Sentinel) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   DRYER _ DAYTON, Ohio _ The average load of laundry takes about
30 minutes to wash in a residential model automatic washing
machine, but the same load takes abut 50 minutes to dry, according
to the Whirlpool Corp.'s Institute of Fabric Science. (Cummings,
Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BUYING-ART_ You look at your bare living-room walls. You wonder:
What can I put on them that will look great? You look at your
wallet. You ask: How can I afford art that I'll like, and that will
be good? You look around. You think: Wouldn't it be nice to support
local artists, as long as I'm shopping? And now, you wonder: Where
do I start? Say you had a bit of money to invest in local artworks.
Suppose you had $500. We asked a number of local observers and
authorities on the Dayton-area art scene what they would do.
(Black, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT
</P>
<P>
   ROCK-TV _ From the moment Elvis wiggled his way into America's
living rooms to the advent of cable and MTV, rock music and
television have been powerful partners in shaping American pop
culture. Each night this week, VH1 will air ``The Greatest Rock and
Roll Moments on TV.'' We analyze how the tube has affected the
making of music, and the shaping of our culture. (Longino, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   TV-HOLLOWAY-COLUMN _ CBS is engaging in child abuse, pure and
simple. When Karen dissed her husband and announced her marriage
was kaput on ``Big Brother,'' the adults may have agreed to the
exposure, but the minor children certainly did not. Abused by their
parents with this public display of unhappiness, the kids were
further abused by CBS when it chose to broadcast the family's
collapse. We'll take the net to task _ and let exec. Les Moonves
hang himself with his pathetic excuses. (Holloway, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
