<DOCNO> NYT20000730.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-30 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7519 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-PATENTS-NYT &LR;      07-30 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATENTS: EARLY DETECTION OF MELANOMA; PINPOINTING LETHAL BURIED
OBJECTS; NEW TWIST FOR BOWLING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Miss., Fla.)   By SABRA CHARTRAND   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Skin cancer rates are rapidly increasing, and many aging baby
boomers may discover that sun exposure in early childhood lead to
dangerous lesions in adulthood. Health-care providers and the
public have been taught in recent years to follow the A B C D rule
_ to watch for and inspect skin spots that are Asymmetrical, have
Border irregularities, Color variations and a Diameter greater than
6 millimeters.
</P>
<P>
   But those features are not always visible to the naked eye. Dr.
Marek Elbaum, a New York physicist and engineer, says he thinks a
computer with a light-and-vision system that he and a group of
colleagues have patented will be much better at detecting melanoma
in its earliest stages.
</P>
<P>
   ``A clinician has to be trained in differentiating between
malignancy patterns of tissue and benign patterns,'' said Elbaum,
who is also president of Electro-Optical Sciences, in Irvington,
N.Y. ``With melanoma,'' he said, ``that is very difficult indeed,
so difficult that thousands of patients die because the melanoma is
not detected early enough. And there is a huge overbiopsy rate
because physicians try to play it safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Elbaum said 4 million people had high risk factors for melanoma
and must have moles and other growths tested once or twice a year.
Those patients, he said, would be better served by a computer
system that doctors could use as an outpatient tool to determine
whether a lesion is cancerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Central to the computer vision system are ways of analyzing
melanoma lesions, imaging them and then quantifying those images,''
Elbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   First, a sensor shines light from the visible, invisible and
infrared spectra onto a lesion. Light from these different
wavelengths is reflected back from the skin. Ten images are taken
of each lesion.
</P>
<P>
   Software based on a mathematical formula called wavelet maxima
processes the data from those images to weed out irrelevant
information. The software creates a score for each lesion,
indicating the probability of cancer, Elbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   Elbaum's company is conducting clinical trials in hopes of
winning approval for the device from the Food and Drug
Administration. He wants to have a device on the market that can be
used by specialists or even nonspecialists by the end of the year.
Elbaum and his colleagues _ Dina Gutkowicz-Krusin, of Princeton,
N.J.; Michael Greenebaum of New York; Adam Jacobs of Glen Ridge,
N.J.; and Alexandru Bogdan of New York _ won patent number
6,081,612.
</P>
<P>
   Lasers That Pinpoint Lethal Buried Objects
</P>
<P>
   Bell Laboratories was in the news last week with the
announcement of the first so-called plastic laser _ one that could
be less expensive and have a wider variety of uses than the metal
semiconductor lasers commonly used in consumer electronics and
commercial products.
</P>
<P>
   But two inventors from Mississippi recently received a patent
more in keeping with the original, matter-piercing, science-fiction
notion of lasers.
</P>
<P>
   When introduced in the 1950s, lasers _ the word is shorthand for
``light amplification by stimulated emission of radiation'' _ were
popularly conceived as scorching rays of red light that could slice
through sheer rock or solid steel.
</P>
<P>
   Yet nearly half a century later, the most common use of lasers
is to read digitally stored media like compact discs, CD-ROMs or
DVDs. And lasers have found their way into countless medical,
engineering, computer and agricultural devices.
</P>
<P>
   But the one patented last week by James Sabatier and Kenneth
Gilbert of Oxford, Miss., is intended to find what may be millions
of land mines buried in war zones and former battlefields around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   The patent covers a method of using lasers and sound signals to
detect buried objects. The system is based on the fact that sound
is reflected from hard objects buried a few inches to a few feet
under a porous surface like dirt. Sound signals bounce between such
buried objects and the surface, and off the objects into the air.
</P>
<P>
   The inventors say the vibrations generated by an object like a
land mine are three to 20 times as strong as those coming out of
empty soil. A laser is used to detect those vibrations from a
distance, and to reveal the location of the buried object.
</P>
<P>
   First, a beam of laser light from a sensor called a
laser-Doppler vibrometer is scanned over the ground. The seismic
vibrations cause upper- and lower-side band signals to form in the
laser's frequency, and those signals increase in strength when the
laser passes over a hard, buried object. Laser light is scattered
back to the sensor, where the frequencies are separated and
analyzed to pinpoint the buried object's location.
</P>
<P>
   ``The presence of a buried object, such as a mine, is detected
by the increase in the amplitude of the side bands,'' the inventors
write in their patent. They say their device can be mounted on a
tower or an airplane, so wide areas can be surveyed. Sabatier and
Gilbert received patent 6,081,481.
</P>
<P>
   Lasers That May Add New Twist to Bowling
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ciniello says that lasers will help bowling compete with
interactive electronic and computer games. He has patented a method
of using lasers projected across a bowling lane to increase the
number of points a player can win for a strike or a spare, and to
make the speed and timing of a rolling ball a factor.
</P>
<P>
   The object is to win additional points by timing the roll of the
ball so that it keeps pace with moving spots of laser light. The
spots, from a laser suspended from the bowling-alley ceiling, are
beamed across the lane in a sequence as the ball rolls toward the
pins.
</P>
<P>
   A sensor along the side of the lane detects the ball as it
moves, and a bowler wins the extra points if his ball passes that
spot at the same time the laser lights hit it. Various spots along
the lane are given extra points to add to the traditional strike or
spare score.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the lights can be varied depending on the skill of
the bowler, so, for example, better bowlers might be challenged by
faster light sequences.
</P>
<P>
   Ciniello, who lives in Bonita Springs, Fla., won patent number
6,077,167.
</P>
<P>
   Patents may be viewed on the Web at www.uspto.gov or may be
ordered through the mail, by patent number, for $3 from the Patent
and Trademark Office, Washington, DC 20231.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
