<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, July 31, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Only small changes are expected in the weather pattern across
the eastern half of the nation. A flow of warm, very humid air will
occupy much of the Atlantic seaboard with varying amounts of clouds
and thundershowers. A cluster of storms may drench the eastern
Carolinas. High pressure near Maine will circulate cool, moist air
into much of the Northeast leading to thick clouds and rain from
New York to southern Maine.
</P>
<P>
   A weak cool front approaching the Appalachians and the Gulf
coast will trigger thunderstorms, some with flooding rains. Low
pressure in the southern Great Lakes will keep the Midwest
unsettled with showers.
</P>
<P>
   A wedge of hot air from the Rockies will move to the Plains.
Isolated thunderstorms will precede the heat in the eastern
Dakotas. Record heat will dominate the interior West, with high
temperature records being challenged in Idaho. Tropical storm winds
and rain will lash Hawaii as Daniel passes Oahu.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: SMOKEHOUSE
</P>
<P>
   Montana is known as Big Sky Country, but travelers around Great
Falls on Saturday must have wondered if they were caught in a
smokehouse. Fires raging in the Lolo National Forest spilled plumes
of dense smoke across central Montana lowering visibility to just a
few miles. Meanwhile, a heat wave crested over the central sections
sending the temperature above 100 degrees at Great Falls for the
first time since Aug. 11, 1996. The heat and smoke will persist
much of this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
