<SLUG> BC-CVN-CONVENTION-CHENEY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
CHENEY SAYS HE MIGHT DO CONTROVERSIAL VOTES DIFFERENTLY (For use by
New York Times News Service clients.) By DAN FREEDMAN c.2000 Hearst
Newspapers PHILADELPHIA Republican vice presidential hopeful Dick
Cheney said Sunday that if he were in Congress now, he might vote
differently than he did as a conservative House member from Wyoming
in the 1970s and 1980s. Cheney's backpedals on his conservative
voting record came as Democrats prepared an ad blitz depicting him
as a conservative extremist and focusing on his votes against the
Head Start pre-school program for impoverished children and
environmental protection programs. Cheney mostly took a ``no
regrets'' approach to his voting record during appearances on the
Sunday morning TV talk shows. But he also suggested that he would
think twice now about some of his controversial votes if he had a
chance to do it all over again. Cheney was greeted by a welcome
rally when he arrived here the day before the opening of the
Republican national convention. At the rally, Cheney again defended
his record and said that ``most of all we want to make Americans
proud again by giving them a president they can respect.'' As the
state of Wyoming's lone House member from 1979 to 1989, Cheney
amassed a strongly conservative voting record, including votes
against a resolution urging freedom for then-imprisoned South
African leader Nelson Mandela and against legislation to ban easily
concealed plastic weapons. On ABC's ``This Week,'' Cheney said ``I
cast 2,000 to 3,000 votes'' in Congress. ``I'm happy to defend my
record.'' He described media questions on his votes as ``trivial.''
Nevertheless, Cheney said on CBS' ``Face the Nation'' that were he
in Congress today, ``I might find a couple I would do
differently.'' Cheney spoke the day before a Democratic National
Committee television ad on his record begins airing. The 30-second
spot singles out Cheney as ``one of only eight members of Congress
to oppose the Clean Water Act, one of the few to vote against Head
Start.'' It continues: ``He even voted against the school lunch
program, against health insurance for people who lost their jobs.''
Cheney shrugged when asked to explain these votes. ``I frequently
voted against measures because I thought funding was excessive,''
he said on ``Meet the Press'' on NBC. ``We had big deficits in the
1980s.'' Cheney dismissed the Democratic attack ad. ``I think the
American people want to hear about the future, not the past,'' he
said. On CBS Cheney said he now supports federal funding for Head
Start. And although he initially opposed creation of the U.S.
Department of Education, he now supports its continued existence, a
position that Bush also endorses. On ABC he defended his votes
against bans on armor-piercing ``cop-killer'' bullets and plastic
guns, which are easy to smuggle through metal detectors. Cheney
cited the Constitution's Second Amendment as guaranteeing Americans
the right to bear arms. ``I'm a strong believer in the Second
Amendment,'' he said. Asked whether that protection was
``absolute'' no matter what kind of weapon, Cheney responded ``it's
pretty absolute when it's in the Constitution.'' Still, on NBC, he
said he voted against the bans because House procedural rules
barred amendments and limited debate. Cheney said he'd be ``happy
to entertain'' the idea of banning the bullets and guns now. On the
Nelson Mandela vote, Cheney said on ABC that while he did not want
the enigmatic South African leader to stay in prison, the
resolution calling for his freedom was coupled with language
calling for recognition of the African National Congress. At the
time of the vote 1986 the ANC was considered a ``terrorist
organization.'' Cheney acknowledged that now the ANC is a
mainstream political organization.(Dan Freedman can be contacted at
202-298-6920 or via e-mail: dan(at)hearstdc.com)
