<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-30 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7532 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-ROCK-TV0731-COX     07-30 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCK-TV0731-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When life changed: TV recalls great moments in rock
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ VH1 researchers have roamed through the television
vaults to compile this five-hour flashback through rock 'n' roll
history.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the moment that best captures the pure joy of watching
``The 100 Greatest Rock &AMP; Roll Moments on TV'' _ shown by ranking
of importance rather than in chronological order _ isn't clip No.
100 on the countdown (clue word: ``Chastity'') or even, five hours
later, clip No. 1 (clue word: ``Moptops''). No. 16 (clue word:
``higher'') is the vignette that cuts to the point.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 17, 1967, Ed Sullivan, looking like a protege of J.
Edgar Hoover, introduces a new singing sensation rock group, the
Doors. Standing on a set literally decorated with suspended doors,
lead singer Jim Morrison appears like a Greek god in black leather.
</P>
<P>
   In an era of Brylcreem, his tousled, curly hair defiantly
tumbles below the collar. His pants are so tight that they leave
little to the imagination. While the other guys roll their heads
Zenlike with the beat, Morrison closes his eyes and utters a scream
that sounds like adolescent angst incarnate: ``Come on baby, light
my fie-yer.''
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, millions of teenagers, sitting trancelike in
front of their black-and-white TV sets, had a jolting, communal
thought: Life as they knew it was going to be different.
</P>
<P>
   If you had to pick the common theme underlying these 100
television clips _ and why they often evoke deeply personal
memories for the people who watched them _ it's change. Changing
fashion. Changing music. Changing sexual mores. Brazen challenges
to authority, meant to disrupt political agendas and points of
view. The moment when what is meets what's going to be.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's Elvis Presley shaking his hips in front of
Eisenhower-era conservatives, the Beatles shamelessly flirting into
Ed Sullivan's cameras or Kurt Cobain screaming ``Smells Like Teen
Spirit'' in a pep rally video from hell, great rock moments on
television have often been the times when an artist boldly broke
the rules.
</P>
<P>
   There's an undulating Madonna rolling around onstage in a
wedding dress at the first MTV Music Awards. The Who blowing up
Keith Moon's drum kit on ``The Smothers Brothers Comedy Hour.'' An
avant-garde John Lennon and Yoko Ono co-hosting the strait-laced
``Mike Douglas Show'' with countercultural guests such as Bobby
Seale and Jerry Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   Though some moments come from the 1980s and '90s _ such as Ricky
Martin's explosive performance at the 1999 Grammy Awards or Whitney
Houston singing the national anthem at Super Bowl XXV _ the vast
majority come from the '60s and '70s.
</P>
<P>
   That may be more because of changing technology than the tastes
of the producers.
</P>
<P>
   Let us remember: During the rise of rock, there were only three
network television channels. No cable. No VCRs. No MTV or Napster.
Hearing tunes on the radio was a random experience; seeing the acts
perform them live was even more fleeting. Throughout the pre-cable
era of the 1950s, '60s and much of the '70s, it was likely that a
televised broadcast of a rock artist was the only opportunity in
the world at that moment to see the performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you wanted to see the Beatles on TV, you only had one
choice,'' notes VH1 Senior Vice President Lauren Zalaznick, who
oversaw production of this week's show. ``Everything has become
diluted. Now you can see an act on 30 different channels. It's a
good thing and a not-so-good thing. You can hear from musicians all
the time; the music is accessible. The flip side of that is that
people are not driven in the same way to become part of the
frenzy.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's plugged-in teenagers may not understand the former
novelty of seeing a favorite act on television. But anyone who
loves rock music should pop a tape into the VCR. This show's a
keeper.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
