<DOCNO> NYT20000730.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-30 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7533 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CVN-MCCAIN-REFORM-HNS     07-30 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-MCCAIN-REFORM-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
'McCAIN URGES SUPPORTERS TO `KEEP FIGHTING' FOR CAMPAIGN REFORM AND
TO BACK BUSH &HT;    By TIMOTHY SPENCE
 &HT;    c.2000 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Sen. John McCain, arriving here on the eve of the
Republican National Convention, urged his cheering supporters to
``keep fighting, keep fighting'' to overhaul campaign financing,
and at the same time he encouraged them to back George W. Bush for
president.
</P>
<P>
   Stressing the same themes that propelled him to victories in the
early GOP primaries, he reaffirmed his support for Bush _ an
endorsement that unleashed boos as well as applause from an
audience of more than 500 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican Party is my home,'' the Arizona senator said.
``I am obliged not by party loyalty, but by sincere conviction, to
urge all Americans to support my party's nominee, Gov. George Bush
of Texas. ... It is quite clear that he is the candidate who offers
change and that the vice president (Al Gore) is the candidate of
the status quo.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain _ citing education, national defense and Social Security
_ said he and Bush share many of the same goals.
</P>
<P>
   The senator's 16-minute speech at a so-called ``shadow
convention,'' organized by several nonpartisan groups and held
across town from the Republican convention site, touched on issues
that attracted independent as well as Democratic voters during the
primaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the beneficiaries of a campaign finance systhem that is
nothing more than an elaborate influence-peddling scheme in which
both parties aspire to stay in office by selling the country to the
highest bidder,'' he told the crowd. ``For our sake and for our
children's sake, and for the sake of America, keep fighting, keep
fighting. .. ''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who sent the Bush campaign reeling with his victory in
the New Hampshire primary, discovered that at least for this
audience, his call for limiting political contributions from
corporations and special interest groups remained very much alive.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of the shadow convention blame voter apathy on the
influence of contributions to the parties.
</P>
<P>
   The syndicated columnist Arianna Huffington kicked off the event
with a wry reference to the $63 million Republican National
Convention, largely financed by corporate contributions. In
contrast, she said, ``our convention is being brought to you by a
collective longing to fix our political system.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of two nonpartisan public policy organizations denounced
both Democrats and Republicans for accepting record amounts of cash
to finance their campaigns, conventions and partisan advertisements
that are mostly paid for by the unregulated donations commonly
known as ``soft money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The parties have become glorified money drops for special
interests,'' Common Cause President Scott Harshbarger told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen S. Miller, president of the Public Campaign, which
advocates public financing of political campaigns, said, ``There
are two sets of constituencies in this country _ cash constituents
and ordinary constituents _ and the ones who come first are cash
constituents.''
</P>
<P>
   After winning the New Hampshire primary, he captured six other
states for a total of 231 delegates before conceding to Bush
following the March 7 ``Super Tuesday'' contest that included New
York and California.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those delegates have pledged their support for Bush, and
on Sunday McCain has urged the remainder to vote for him on the
first ballot Thursday night, when the party is expected to nominate
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-00 1829EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
