<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: ABC 20/20 REPORT ON ORGANIC FOODS IS CHALLENGED 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Bylines at end of items) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Feb. 4, the ABC News correspondent John Stossel hosted a
report on ``20/20'' that probably surprised many viewers. It made
the case that organic food is not necessarily healthier than
conventional food _ and might actually be dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Citing research that he said was commissioned by ABC News,
Stossel said that organic food seemed more likely than conventional
food to be contaminated by E. coli bacteria. He also said that
conventional produce does not necessarily have more pesticide
residue than organic produce, contradicting one of organic food's
primary selling points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our tests, surprisingly, found no pesticide residue on the
conventional samples or the organic,'' he said in the report.
</P>
<P>
   But the two researchers who were commissioned to do the testing
_ Dr. Michael Doyle, a scientist with the University of Georgia,
and Dr. Lester Crawford, director of Georgetown University's Center
for Food and Nutrition Policy _ said they never tested produce for
pesticide residue for ABC. ABC executives are now looking into
whether the statement about produce, a key premise on which Stossel
built his case, was made without any basis in fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I agreed to do was test for indications of pathogens,''
Doyle said. ``I didn't do tests for pesticides.''
</P>
<P>
   Crawford said that while he did not test produce for pesticides,
he did test chicken _ and found residue on the samples of
conventional poultry, but not on samples of organic poultry. Those
findings were not mentioned in Stossel's report.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors' denials were first brought to light by the
Environmental Working Group, which supports the consumption of
organic produce. Members talked to the doctors after the report. In
a letter to Stossel, the group asked for an explanation.
</P>
<P>
   The producer of the segment, David Fitzpatrick, responded in a
letter by saying that the pesticide tests were done and that the
results had been forwarded to the Organic Trade Association, a
group that spoke in defense of organic produce in the segment. The
executive director of the association, Katherine DiMatteo, said
Friday that the organization had not received results from any
tests for pesticide residue on produce.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being told by the environmentalists of the doctors'
denials, ABC showed the report again on July 7. During an
on-the-air conversation with Cynthia McFadden, a ``20/20''
anchorwoman, Stossel said, ``It's logical to worry about pesticide
residues, but in our tests, we found none on either organic or
regular produce.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, ABC News executives still could not address the
questions raised in February. They at first said pesticide tests
were performed on produce by Crawford. Told that Crawford maintains
he did not do such testing, they later released a statement saying
they would look into the matter and ``if a mistake was made, we
will correct it.'' Stossel had no comment and Fitzpatrick was on
assignment in Africa and unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   _ JIM RUTENBERG
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   lST QUESTIONABLE LETTER FOR A LIAR'S MEMOIR
</P>
<P>
   Lauren Slater is a self-professed liar. But this time she really
wants you to believe her.
</P>
<P>
   Slater, a 36-year-old psychologist in Boston, is the author of
the recently released ``Lying: A Metaphorical Memoir.'' The book is
billed as a memoir but is actually a blending of fact and fiction,
in which the main character, Slater, thinks she has epilepsy but
may be imagining her condition.
</P>
<P>
   The book begins with a preface written by a Hayward Krieger,
Ph.D., who is described as a philosophy professor at the University
of Southern California. He calls the memoir ``a new kind of
Heideggerian truth, the truth of the liminal.''
</P>
<P>
   Some reviewers, including Rebecca Mead in The New York Times
Book Review, found Krieger a bit much. She called the university,
found there was no Krieger, and described the stunt and the book as
``unrewardingly wearing.''
</P>
<P>
   But Slater was not quite done. Last week, The Times Book Review
received a letter to the editor from Krieger. ``Identity has always
been a fragile phenomenon,'' the letter admonished, ``but that it
now rests upon the report of overworked operators at a university
switchboard is perturbing, and we should all beware.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter reported that Krieger had merely left the university.
The return address was Slater's Boston clinic, along with a phone
number belonging to her husband. There is no Dr. Krieger.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Schneider, executive director of publicity for Random
House, which published Slater's book, said she is not sure if
Slater's editors knew that Krieger was fictitious. They were
unavailable for comment, but Slater says they knew. Schneider said
she finds the letter ``pretty amusing,'' adding that it was clever
publicity for the book.
</P>
<P>
   But Slater insists she had no such intentions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Publicity?'' she said. ``I am shocked. I can't believe anyone
would say that. I know it is hard to believe me, but I am being
totally honest with you _ I just thought that letter was very, very
funny. I was sure that whoever gets it at the time would think
Lauren Slater is immature and throw it away. You have got to
believe me.'' Her next book, she says, will be true nonfiction,
about the effect of prescription drugs during pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   _ DAVID D. KIRKPATRICK
</P>
<P>
   NOT UPN ANYMORE, IT'S PARAMOUNT
</P>
<P>
   Next year, Viacom's UPN television network is changing its name.
As of January, it will be called the Paramount Network.
</P>
<P>
   Executives made the change to go with the corporate flow.
Chris-Craft Industries Inc. has sold its 50 percent share of the
network, which was originally named for Viacom's Paramount
Television Group and Chris-Craft's United Stations.
</P>
<P>
   But executives say they did not like the way UPN sounded anyway.
And, according to their research, it did not mean anything to
viewers. Paramount seemed a better fit because of its
identification with a major movie studio, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Ware, the network's chief financial officer, said, ``
`Paramount' meant Hollywood, it meant movies, it meant
television.''
</P>
<P>
   The timing for the name change would seem strange. After years
of struggling, UPN finally saw a big increase in ratings this past
year, thanks in large part to its Thursday night World Wrestling
Federation program. By changing names, executives admit, they run
the risk of confusing viewers.
</P>
<P>
   But Ware said that every effort will be made to make viewers
aware of the change before it happens.
</P>
<P>
   He added that executives hope that the change helps attract more
advertising. Though its ratings have improved, the network is still
not profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Viacom's new chief executive, Mel Karmazin, has said that if it
does not become profitable soon, he will get rid of it.
</P>
<P>
   _ JIM RUTENBERG
</P>
</TEXT>
