<DOCNO> NYT20000730.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-30 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7542 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CANADA-VIKINGS-ART-NY     07-30 1203
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-VIKINGS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWFOUNDLAND CELEBRATING ITS HERITAGE AND HOPING FOR TOURISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   L'ANSE AUX MEADOWS, Newfoundland _ Out of the cold gray mists of
the North Atlantic, the small flotilla appeared, tiny boats with
fierce prows, propelled by billowing sails and protected by
circular shields of oak and cowhide. Arriving in this rocky cove on
Friday, Icelandic-speaking men with sun-creased faces and unkempt
hair strode to this unfamiliar shore, their first time on dry land
since sailing south from Greenland.
</P>
<P>
   One thousand years ago, there was a similar scene, seen by some
as a defining moment in human history, as Leif Ericson arrived here
on Newfoundland's northernmost tip. Here, in the only authenticated
Viking settlement in the Americas, historians believe, the first
Christian rites were celebrated in the Americas and the first
European child, Snorri, was born.
</P>
<P>
   The sagas say that Indian attacks forced the Vikings to abandon
their colony within a decade. This resistance helped postpone
European conquest and settlement of the Americas for 500 years.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday's historical vignette on this windy strait facing
Labrador, where whales mingle with icebergs, modern reality quickly
intruded on the magical moment. The cameras caught little girls
clutching Snorri dolls, their brothers strutting in plastic horned
helmets and their parents tapping time to the rock version of a
Newfoundland fishing chanty, ``Your Daddy's a Sailor Who Never
Comes Home.''
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting modern fascination with the Norse, a seafaring people
whose medieval trade routes stretched from here to Baghdad, about
15,000 tourists from North America and Europe crammed into this
tiny fishing village, winter population 44, over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Newfoundland, a craggy island nicknamed ``The Rock,'' is newly
determined to shake off its label as Canada's poorest province.
Long isolated from the rest of North America, it is well on its way
to meeting a self-imposed goal of attracting one tourist each year
for each of its 540,000 residents, a ratio long enjoyed by such
tourism powers as France and Spain. This weekend, tourists driving
up the ``Viking Trail'' found no-vacancy signs at the Vinland
Motel, the Viking Nest Bed and Breakfast, and the Valhalla Lodge.
</P>
<P>
   Watson Tucker, a 59-year-old former welder and fisherman, said
as he watched the festival unfold that the whole world seemed to be
there. A graduate of a course in Viking culture offered by the
local branch of the College of the North Atlantic, Tucker sported a
thick beard, deerhide shoes, and heavy green tunic for his summer
job acting the role of a Norse poet.
</P>
<P>
   After half a century under Canada's wing, this onetime British
colony is also rediscovering its North Atlantic neighborhood. St.
John's, the provincial capital, is equidistant in flying time from
Toronto and Reykjavik, Iceland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The North Atlantic is our pond,'' Brian Tobin, premier of
Newfoundland and Labrador, said after buttonholing the visiting
president of Icelandair about starting flights linking the island
communities.
</P>
<P>
   Iceland's national airline now flies three times a day to
Halifax, Nova Scotia. With more and more Icelanders coming here for
business and shopping, the company wants to increase flights to
five a week and to add stops in St. John's. Iceland plans to open
an embassy in Ottawa next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be said that 1,000 years ago, Iceland opened the first
of all embassies in America, here in L'Anse aux Meadows,'' Halldor
Asgrimsson, Iceland's foreign minister, said as the celebration
here was broadcast live on Icelandic television. ``Now, a
millennium later, Iceland is to open another embassy. This time we
have to do it in Ottawa.''
</P>
<P>
   A visiting Norwegian newspaper reporter noted the absence of a
high-level Norwegian delegation and said that Norway, Denmark, and
Sweden increasingly looked east to the Baltics, rather than west
toward their old North Atlantic colonies _ the Faeroe Islands,
Iceland and Greenland. As a result, these islands increasingly are
knitting trade ties with their Canadian neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Josef Motzfeldt, Greenland's deputy prime minister, agreed,
marveling in an interview that, in only three hours, he was able to
fly from Nuuk, Greenland's capital, to St. John's, a modern city of
150,000, three times the population of Greenland.
</P>
<P>
   The Viking re-enactment, with a cruise ship bringing hundreds of
Scandinavian tourists ashore to watch, is the most visible face of
a growing relationship with the North Atlantic. Half an hour down
the road from where two Norwegian archaeologists, Helge Instad and
Anne Stine, discovered the Norse ruins here in 1960, an Icelandic
company is managing a new shrimp processing plant, providing needed
employment to people laid off after the cod fishery collapsed in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   In Notre Dame Bay, 130 miles south of here, Jonas Kristjansson,
an Iceland saga scholar, is searching this summer for more Viking
ruins.
</P>
<P>
   In St. John's, where plans are under way to triple
Newfoundland's oil production, to 500,000 barrels a day in 2005,
oil executives talk easily of friendships and professional ties
forged in recent years with Scottish and Norwegian engineers as
Newfoundlanders learned skills for building oil platforms in the
iceberg infested North Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of this decade, oil royalties are expected to help
end Newfoundland's dependence on aid from Ottawa. But, provincial
planners are betting heavily on tourism to reduce Newfoundland's
double digit unemployment rates, the highest of any state or
province in North America.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the number of tourists is expected to hit 450,000, a
50 percent jump in five years, attributable in part to the low
Canadian dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Newfoundland has aggressively promoted itself with a series of
events: in 1997, the 500th anniversary of the arrival here of John
Cabot, the explorer; in 1999, the 50th anniversary of
Newfoundland's joining Canada; and this year, the Viking
millennium. An event next summer will revolve around the centennial
of Guglielmo Marconi's reception in St. John's of a trans-Atlantic
radio transmission from England.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see 1 million visitors a year,'' Charles Furey,
the provincial tourism minister, said as he strode past the
sod-covered church, chieftain's hall, the smithy and the boat shed
of Norstead, the replica Norse port that opened here two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   These living villages populated with re-enactors turn dry
historical sites into family attractions. Nearby, at the ruins of
the real Viking village, a UNESCO World Heritage Site, attendance
jumped by 50 percent, to 29,000 last year, after Parks Canada hired
re-enactors.
</P>
<P>
   At Norstead, local actors will be rotated with groups from
Britain, Denmark, Maryland, Sweden and Ontario. Belying the new,
kinder image of the Norse as peaceable farmers, a group of English
re-enactors on Thursday practiced throwing axes at a target wall,
then engaged in mock fights _ a sword in one hand and an ax in the
other.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
