<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-30 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7545 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-WINTOUR-BETTS-MEDIA-A     07-30 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINTOUR-BETTS-MEDIA-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP JOB AT HARPER'S BAZAAR LOOKS SECURE, FOR NOW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeats to add photo note to art advisory.)  (ART ADV: Graphic and photos NYT 1,2 are being sent to NYT
photo/graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase
by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There are few areas of modern society that are as
nasty, brutish and just plain catty as the world of fashion
magazines. Fueled by skim cappuccinos infused with Sweet 'n Low and
the rather desperate illusion that this month's hemline length is a
matter of grave importance to the world's population, the
fashion-editor's world is a place that embraces the casual morsel
of malicious gossip and recycles it over and over again until it
snowballs, in a frenzied crescendo of hushed cell-phone
conversations and secret e-mail messages, into something resembling
truth _ which, of course, it rarely is.
</P>
<P>
   Take a recent episode: Katherine Betts became editor in chief of
Harper's Bazaar in August of last year. Less than a year later _ or
faster than you can say ``Waiter, a saucer of milk for this table,
please!'' _ a competing editor, Bonnie Fuller of Conde Nast's
Glamour, buoyed by reports of Bazaar's sluggish newsstand sales,
was angling for her job. She had even created sample page spreads
illustrating her vision for Harper's Bazaar, said one former
Glamour editorial staff member who saw the spreads and one current
staff member. A Conde Nast spokeswoman, Maurie Perl, disputed the
story.
</P>
<P>
   The episode wound up in Inside.com and The New York Post. But
what is more important is that the reports kicked off weeks of
industry speculation about the safety of Betts' job _ which is, by
the way, perfectly secure, said Hearst executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things can become very personal very quickly,'' Betts said,
discussing her world in an interview in her 37th-floor office last
week.
</P>
<P>
   But apart from dealing with the day-to-day slings and arrows of
the magazine world, Betts faces several other challenges, some
arguably greater than sidestepping the droppings of the rumor mill.
For starters, she had to take over from Liz Tilberis, a well-liked
editor who died of ovarian cancer last year. Now, Betts must make a
historic fashion magazine relevant and appealing to readers in a
crowded field that includes W magazine, Vogue, Elle and Bazaar. All
four fashion magazines must now also compete with fast-growing
titles like Time Inc.'s In Style and Hearst's O: The Oprah
Magazine, which have found readers by showing less concern with
fashion than with celebrities (In Style) or self-improvement and
lifestyle (O: The Oprah Magazine).
</P>
<P>
   Betts must also reconcile Bazaar's core philosophy, which has
for much of its 134-year history been to document the evolution of
high-end fashion and couture clothing, with changing American
tastes at the retail level: Americans are less likely to spend
money on formal clothing; they are buying casual wear at cheap-chic
chain stores like H &AMP; M and Banana Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Cathleen P. Black, chief executive of Hearst Magazines, said
that part of the reason she hired Betts, who at 36 is the youngest
editor in chief in Bazaar's history, was because she felt she could
reconcile those issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beautiful thing is that women can buy couture now, and
they can also shop at Banana Republic,'' Black said. ``An editor
does not have to make choices for all American women. Kate is a
young, modern woman who can bring those concepts together in the
magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   Betts must recast Bazaar after a year that has not been the
smoothest sailing. During her first 11 months, she changed
three-quarters of the magazine's editorial departments and
supervised a redesign that was criticized for streamlining the
distinctive cover typeface conceived by the fabled art director
Alexey Brodovitch. On a more personal level, Betts allowed the
Lifetime network to film a documentary about her first few months
on the job; while it showed several poignant moments of her
balancing motherhood and work, the documentary, ``Putting Baby to
Bed,'' also portrayed her at times as frosty and domineering.
</P>
<P>
   But as much as fashion-world habitues hope for more such morsels
to chew over in lieu of lunch, they may be sorry to learn that from
all outward appearances, Bazaar appears to be taking baby steps
forward under Betts. Advertising pages are up 10 percent for the
year, according to Cynthia R. Lewis, the publisher of Bazaar since
April, as compared with last year, which was one of the worst in
the magazine's history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are No. 4 in our competitive set, which is Elle, Vogue, W
and Bazaar, in terms of advertising,'' Lewis said, adding that she
believed ``the window between us and W is closing.'' The September
issue will have around 354 pages, Lewis said, the second largest
September issue in the magazine's history. The February issue had
148 ad pages, and March, 263, both the largest ever for those
months.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the picture is less clear. Overall circulation is
steady; newsstand sales are up slightly, and subscriptions are down
slightly.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Publisher's Statement filed with the Audit
Bureau of Circulation, the February 2000 issue, which was Betts'
first, sold less than its 1999 predecessors on the newsstand. But
March, April, May and June all sold more than the comparable issues
the previous year. Subscriptions were down by 6.6 percent during
the first six months of 2000, which Hearst executives said they
expected with the redesign.
</P>
<P>
   Bazaar's refashioning comes at a time when all four of the
fashion magazines appear to be in transition. W's publisher, Susan
Blank, resigned unexpectedly two weeks ago; she was the third
publisher in six months. W's ad pages in the all-important
September issue will be less than last year's, said a Fairchild
executive.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-00 1853EDT &QL; 
