<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-30 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7546 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CVN-BUSH-HNS &LR;      07-30 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-BUSH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
BUSH REACHES OUT TO SWING VOTERS IN OHIO (EDS: Stands for
CINCINNATI-dated story on budget.) (For use by New York Times News
Service clients.) By STEWART M. POWELL c.2000 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLUE ASH, Ohio Republican George W. Bush reached out to
independents and crossover Democrats in the swing state of Ohio on
Sunday with promises to bring the upward mobility of the American
dream within reach of everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, working his way toward the GOP convention in Philadelphia,
promised to tackle ``tough issues''' in order to overhaul the
education system, bolster defense spending, cut taxes and provide
younger workers the option of privately investing part of their
Social Security deductions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on our way to Philadelphia and we're on our way to
victory,'' Bush told several thousand men, women and children who
stood patiently on a freshly mowed baseball field in intermittent
rain showers to hear from the prospective GOP presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had delayed his arrival at the event to give paramedics
time to evacuate an elderly woman who suffered an apparent heart
attack. Ohio Gov. Robert Taft III called for a moment of silence by
the crowd after the woman was taken away. Officials later said
Helen Geiger, 73, of Cincinnati, had died at a local hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he believes he can carry Ohio a state won by every
Republican who has captured the White House on the strength of his
plans for the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got the ideas on our side,'' Bush said. ``We want to
make sure the American dream, the great American experience,
touches every willing heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he is offering America ``good conservative ideas that
will have compassionate results for our country.''
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that some Americans are disillusioned and don't
feel part of the nation. Bush said his education overhaul would
help bring the American dream within reach of millions of
Americans, including ``kids in some neighborhoods where despair is
the common way.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's conciliatory remarks contrasted with some of the warm-up
speakers who addressed the audience, made up mostly of families
accompanied by children.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State Treasurer Joe Deters challenged the crowd: ``Would
you let your daughter be a White House intern?'' And local radio
talk-show host Bill Cunningham ignited the rain-drenched crowd
before Bush's arrival with a fiery diatribe against the Clinton
White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``After eight years of Clinton-Gore, I think America needs a
bath and I think we got it now,'' Cunningham told the enthusiastic
audience, referring to the rain.
</P>
<P>
   Likening Bush to Ronald Reagan, a former California governor who
ousted Democrat Jimmy Carter from the White House in 1980,
Cunningham said: ``Let's elect another governor form the West to
scour out the White House of the filth and degradation. God bless
America.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Hughes, Bush's campaign spokeswoman, said she hoped
supporters of Bush would echo his ``positive tone'' and ``join him
in trying to raise the level of public debate.'' She said she had
not heard the hard-edged comments by some speakers, including
Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, striking centrist themes, portrayed his commitment to
returning a portion of the federal budget surplus in the form of
tax cuts as a sign of his willingness to defy public opinion. Bush
said many polls show that American voters would rather see the
federal budget surplus devoted to purposes other than a tax cut.
``Polls don't say that's what you should be for,'' Bush boasted.
``But you've got to understand about George W. I don't take polls
to tell me what to think. I do what I think is right and I trust
the American people.'' On Social Security, Bush said he wanted
America's younger workers ``to hear something.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You better be worried about when the Baby Boomers start
retiring because there's either going to be a big tax increase or a
huge benefit reduction,'' he continued. If elected Bush said he
would rally Republicans and Democrats in Congress to ``make sure
there's a Social Security system for the younger worker.'' The Bush
campaign signaled that it would strike back when attacked.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic National Committee released a broadcast campaign
aid aired on Sunday that targeted the 10-year congressional voting
record of GOP vice presidential running mate Dick Cheney. The ad
began airing in at least 15 states.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does Cheney's record say about their plans?'' the ad
asks. ``What are their plans for working families?'' Bush spokesman
Ari Fleischer said the ``first attack ad'' of the Gore campaign
``lives up to his staff's boast that they will 'cook things up' as
part of a 'slaughterhouse' style of campaigning.''' Fleischer
added: ``We need a leader who will bring people together to get
things done and that's why selectively distorting a good man's
record will hurt Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address stewarthearstdc.com )
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-00 1853EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
