<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Political tidbits from the Republican National
Convention:
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign is known for keeping on message. To help
delegates do the same, Republican National Convention officials are
giving each a 435-page copy of George W. Bush's speeches, policy
positions and campaign fact sheets.
</P>
<P>
   Convention Chairman Andrew Card said Sunday the book, entitled
``Renewing America's Purpose,'' includes all Bush's policy speeches
and position papers for the past year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our road map of the governor's key principles and
policies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats plan to hold a daily media briefing at the Sheet
Metal Hall every day during the convention to counter the
Republican message, and one of the main targets will be the record
of vice-presidential nominee Dick Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   Former Philadelphia Mayor Ed Rendell, general chairman of the
Democratic Party, asked if he's taking Cheney's voting record out
of context, said:
</P>
<P>
   ``What's out of context about not voting to not ban bullets
whose sole purpose is to pierce bulletproof vests and kill
policemen? ... What's out of context about that (or) voting against
additional funding for head start, against additional funding for
immunization of children? ... Those votes speak for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now remember, George Bush keeps telling us he's
compassionate,'' Rendell said. ``And his first deed ... was to pick
a vice president. And he picked a vice president who voted .
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign is known for keeping on message. To help
delegates do the same, Republican National Convention officials are
giving each a 435-page copy of George W. Bush's speeches, policy
positions and campaign fact sheets.
</P>
<P>
   Convention Chairman Andrew Card said Sunday the book, entitled
``Renewing America's Purpose,'' includes all Bush's policy speeches
and position papers for the past year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our road map of the governor's key principles and
policies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats plan to hold a daily media briefing at the Sheet
Metal Hall every day during the convention to counter the
Republican message, and one of the main targets will be the record
of vice-presidential nominee Dick Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   Former Philadelphia Mayor Ed Rendell, general chairman of the
Democratic Party, asked if he's taking Cheney's voting record out
of context, said:
</P>
<P>
   ``What's out of context about not voting to not ban bullets
whose sole purpose is to pierce bulletproof vests and kill
policemen? ... What's out of context about that (or) voting against
additional funding for head start, against additional funding for
immunization of children? ... Those votes speak for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now remember, George Bush keeps telling us he's
compassionate,'' Rendell said. ``And his first deed ... was to pick
a vice president. And he picked a vice president who voted ...
against the interests of the American people over and over and over
again.''
</P>
<P>
   In memory of Sen. Paul Coverdell, who was to lead the Georgia
contingent in Philadelphia, delegates and alternates have donned
blue lapel ribbons. State party chairman Chuck Clay has succeeded
Coverdell as chairman. Rather than advance one alternate into
Coverdell's spot, the delegation plans to rotate the late senator's
floor credentials among several alternates, to give as many as
possible a chance to sit in the delegation's No. 1 spot.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
