</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000730.0090 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-30 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7549 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-E-COMMERCE-COLUMN-ART     07-30 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-COMMERCE-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E-COMMERCE: DOT-COM EMPLOYEES GROWING IN NUMBER AND BECOMING MORE
SELECTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By BOB TEDESCHI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If executives of e-commerce companies thought they were having a
hard time finding employees last year, this year's Summer of the
Dot-Com Shakeout has brought even more misery to the group.
</P>
<P>
   The number of available workers has grown, but as employees jump
off sinking ships or swim away from ones already capsized, they are
being much more selective about where they dock next. Gone are the
days when Internet retailers could dangle 10,000-share stock
options, utter a few words about revolutionizing the process of
buying gravel, say, and then get a prospective employee to sign on
for a galley slave's salary and 16-hour days in close quarters with
24-year-olds and their Labradors.
</P>
<P>
   Now the words ``stock options'' and ``revolutionize'' are more
likely to set a job applicant's eyes to rolling. Recruiters and
executives say employees now want two things from prospective
employers: a good salary and, perhaps more important, good
prospects for corporate longevity. In the short term, at least,
that means that traditional companies with Internet divisions could
have a substantial advantage in the recruiting wars, thereby
putting additional pressure on their dot-com competitors.
</P>
<P>
   One company that has benefited greatly from the consolidation
among Internet merchants is BlueLight.com, Kmart's online store.
The company successfully recruited employees from Petstore.com, an
online retailer that was recently purchased by Pets.com, as well
the Internet Shopping Network, which merged with Styleclick.com
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least 50 resumes per week are pouring in from Reel.com,
Homewarehouse.com and other dot-coms that have either failed or are
failing,'' said David Karraker, a BlueLight spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Homewarehouse.com, an online retailer of home improvement goods,
shut down operations earlier this summer, while Reel.com recently
stopped selling DVDs, videos and other goods on its site and scaled
back to an information site about the movie industry.
</P>
<P>
   Pippa Manley, BlueLight's director of human resources, said the
shifting fortunes of Internet companies had saved BlueLight money,
because she now relies less on pricey corporate recruiters to fill
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are very inexpensive hires for me, because if I find
them, I don't have to pay 25 percent of a person's salary to a
headhunter,'' Manley said.
</P>
<P>
   As for their demands, Manley said people were less eager to
discuss stock options as part of their compensation, even though
BlueLight's business is structured so that it could eventually sell
its shares to the public. ``A lot of people are saying, `I don't
care about the options _ let's talk salary,''' she said. ``So
there's been more negotiations on that point.
</P>
<P>
   Manley said such negotiations were frustrating, because she
still saw good potential for BlueLight to have successful stock
offerings someday. ``But then again,'' she said, ``I haven't been
through what they've been through, so it's easy for me to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Kimberly Lyons, BlueLight's manager of marketing partnerships,
joined the company in June from Xoom.com, a unit of NBCi, NBC's
Internet division. ``Options weren't a big priority at all because
of what happened at NBC,'' Lyons said.
</P>
<P>
   She noted that the NBCi stock reached $85 on its first day of
trading last November, but has plummeted since. (The shares closed
at $22 on Friday.) ``So I was more aggressive on salary,'' Lyons
said. ``Other companies I interviewed with were still giving low
salaries and trying to compensate with umpteen options, which was
so unappealing.''
</P>
<P>
   Compensation aside, Kmart's online operation had its own appeal,
Lyons said: ``I also knew that by coming here, I'd be getting
offline experience, which is important. And I'd be exposed to more
than a desk made out of a door, or bagel Fridays, so that was very
attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   Spike Anderson, a principal with Monday Technology Solutions, an
executive recruitment firm in San Francisco, said he, too, had
recently been hearing job seekers express a preference for Internet
sites that are affiliated with traditional companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're hedging their bets,'' he said. ``They might not get as
many stock options, but the chances are they'll at least be worth
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, such sentiments would make it more difficult for
Internet-only companies to compete, because they cannot afford to
increase their salaries to match those offered by traditional
companies. William Chen, chief executive of OnePage.com, an
Internet-only company that allows users to assemble several sites
on one screen, said such a prospect was more theory than fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over time, there may be a decline in what pure plays can
afford to pay,'' he said. ``But for now, it's still a race to pay
whatever we can, especially to the top people.''
</P>
<P>
   If the emphasis continues to be placed on salary _ and
bricks-and-mortar pedigree _ instead of equity, Chen said, ``we
might have to spend more to hire better people, but then just not
hire as many people to do all the work.''
</P>
<P>
   Myteam.com, an information and commerce site for people involved
in youth sports programs, recently bought air time on a Boston-area
radio station to advertise open positions.
</P>
<P>
   Elliot Katzman, the company's chief executive, said Myteam, too,
had recently seen an increase in the number of candidates who
stressed salary over stock options. But he said that change could
be attributed to the Internet labor shortage, which has been so
protracted that recruiters are more actively lobbying workers at
traditional companies, where people are less prone to jump at
equity-heavy compensation packages.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we've had to have more conversations about salary lately,''
Katzman said. ``But it still has to work in the context of the
company, and this is a start-up, so you have to be very careful
about how you spend money.''
</P>
<P>
   Compensation packages with stock options also motivate workers
``to build the company's value,'' Katzman said. ``Everyone's got to
have some skin in the game for this to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, traditional companies with Web operations are
enjoying the fact that dot-com executives are asking to work for
them, rather than raiding them. ``We take some consolation in
knowing we've populated the dot-coms,'' said Christopher McCormick,
senior vice president of L.L. Bean, which has lost senior-level
executives to Send.com, Diamonds.com, Dell.com and eToys, among
others. ``But I've got to tell you, it hurt morale for people to
see folks leave for stock packages worth a zillion dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   More recently, the tide has turned, McCormick said, noting for
instance that the company's vice president for operations, Mike
Perkins, recently joined L.L. Bean from Amazon.com. ``And we've
gotten dozens of resumes from people at dot-coms who want out
because their stock is under water, and they see Bean's staying
power and the quality of life here in Maine,'' McCormick said. ``I
do get some pleasure out of this, to be honest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-00 1857EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000730.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-30 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7550 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-CVN-MURRAY-SPEECH31-C     07-30 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-MURRAY-SPEECH31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: A real convention speech
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Philadelphia
</P>
<P>
   I've been talking with my dear friend Ima Source, every
journalist's best buddy, the mother of all scoops.
</P>
<P>
   And I've got a dandy!
</P>
<P>
   Ima, whom I've been on a first-name basis with for many years,
has supplied me with an advance copy of George W. Bush' acceptance
speech set for Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   And, like every other journalist, I'm a sucker for Ima.
</P>
<P>
   Here it is, word-for word. Bush speaks, the world listens...
</P>
<P>
   ``There are four major food groups in Washington: The
Administration, the Congress, the media and the lobbyists.'' He
pauses for emphasis. ``And we are eating each other alive!''
</P>
<P>
   Scattered applause, some nervous laughter. The delegates seem
confused. Where is this coming from? Where's he going with it?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we all know the way things work in Washington. Now I want
to tell you how I think it ought to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ought to be able to come together to discuss ideas that
will make everyone's easier, perhaps through less government ...''
</P>
<P>
   Great cheering, whistling, stomping from the delegates.
</P>
<P>
   ``but sometimes, too, by having more government.''
</P>
<P>
   Silence falls on the convention hall like a sledge hammer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is, a lot of those decisions _ whether more or
less _ are made because the Democratic Party or the Republican
Party decides they do or don't like something.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then everyone falls into lock step behind them without ever
stopping to talk about, or think about, what the other side is
suggesting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody will say, 'Oh, Barney Frank proposed that,' or 'John
McCain is for that' ... 'Then I can't possibly be for that.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an automatic knee-jerk that boots out a lot of good ideas
_ a wholesale dismissal of ideas because you don't the party or the
person behind them.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point Bush turns toward the media gallery.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it happens, if you will forgive me for saying so, as much
in the media as it does in the political parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, here's something the delegates can understand. Our
candidate criticizes the media, and we cheer wildly. Always have,
always will.
</P>
<P>
   Bush shakes his head and holds up his hands for quiet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stay with me on this, please,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``A huge bill is introduced. Reporters immediately want to know
what key leaders think about it. An honest response would be, 'I
don't know, I haven't read it yet.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The media won't accept that, and politicians who don't know
any better _ and I mean that quite literally _ will simply ask
party leaders, 'How does our party feel about it?' Told that the
party is against it, that gives him, or her, an easy answer: 'OK,
then I'm against it ... Won't work, won't fly.'
</P>
<P>
   ``What we need instead,'' Bush says, rapping his knuckles on the
podium for emphasis, ``is a concerted effort by everyone not to
knock the other person's ideas until you have actually looked at
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that includes the media not asking us for instant
reaction!
</P>
<P>
   ``Too much is at stake,'' he continues, ignoring the applause
and speaking over it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're losing good ideas and good policy for America's critical
needs _ from housing to transportation to energy, you name it ...
Ideas that never get a chance to be heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me tell you a story, a true story. A couple of Republican
staffers were going over a piece of proposed legislation. One of
them was puzzled by a some particularly harsh language.
</P>
<P>
   ```Why's that in there?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``'Oh, to stick it to the Democrats,''' he said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``'Why would you want to do that?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``'Why not?''' he said, genuinely puzzled by her response.
</P>
<P>
   ``' Well, this is a good bill without putting it in there. No
reason to be vicious.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly he understood. He sneered at her.'' Bush manages to
do an excellent imitation of a sneer.
</P>
<P>
   ``'You're not here because you believe in Republican causes,''
the staffer said. He pointed an accusing finger at his colleague
and began backing out of the room as if she had a loathsome
disease.
</P>
<P>
   ```You're a ...' He all but cloaked on the word. 'You're a
PROFESSIONAL!'''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, a dropped pin would have all the impact of an
exploding grenade.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a great nation America is,'' Bush says in conclusion.
``Just think how much greater she could be if it weren't for us!''
</P>
<P>
   I was beside myself. ``That's it?'' I asked Ima Source. ``That's
what the speech will be?!''
</P>
<P>
   Ima nodded her assurance. ``Word for word,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terrific,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   I was already starting to write the story in my head and halfway
out the door when I paused.
</P>
<P>
   ``Er, is there anything else spectacular going to happen at the
convention this week?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just this,'' Ima confided, looking around to make sure no one
else was listening and lowering his voice to a whisper: ``Pigs will
fly.''
</P>
<P>
   Remember. You read it here first.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(AT)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915; Website, http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
