<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-30 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7552 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-RDP-NYT     07-30 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-RDP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINISTER WITHDRAWS THREAT TO QUIT, GIVING BARAK SOME BREATHING
ROOM 
</HEADLINE>
  By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Thanks to complex back-room maneuvering on the eve
of a no-confidence vote in parliament, it appeared Sunday that
Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel would be able to keep his
battered government afloat for the next three months.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the speculation in the last few days centered on whether
Foreign Minister David Levy _ who has a history of changing sides _
would resign over the Camp David peace talks and return to his
roots in the rightist Likud Party. That could have triggered a
voting shift to the opposition in the 120-seat Knesset, or
parliament, that would have forced new elections.
</P>
<P>
   But early Sunday evening Levy announced, after meeting with
Barak, that he would remain in the cabinet for now and abstain from
Monday's no-confidence vote.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of trying to topple Barak, Levy said, he would try to
persuade him to create a broad-based government of national unity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am making all possible efforts to create a unity government
and if by Wednesday I do not succeed, I will resign from the
cabinet and support the bill for early elections,'' Levy said on
Israel radio.
</P>
<P>
   But the threat to resign on Wednesday has little practical
weight because that is the last day parliament is to meet before
adjourning for a three-month vacation that so regular a part of
Israeli political life that it is unlikely to be interrupted.
</P>
<P>
   Levy could vote on Wednesday for a Likud bill that calls for
dissolution of parliament and new elections. But that also would
count for little because the bill is to be referred to a committee
controlled by Barak's One Israel party, which can bottle it up.
</P>
<P>
   Levy has criticized Barak for offering concessions to the
Palestinians on Jerusalem and other issues while, Levy contends,
Barak has been offered nothing in return. Levy also has complained
that he has been left out of the loop on this, the major foreign
policy issue. During the Camp David summit meeting, Levy, who
stayed home as acting prime minister, made a sympathetic visit to a
hunger strike by Jewish settlers protesting the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, in an apparent gesture Sunday to Levy, said after Levy's
announcement that, ``I have to make peace, or at least an interim
agreement, with the opposition.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he needed to work with the opposition on the economy,
education and social problems, issues that even his supporters have
criticized him for neglecting in his concentration on peace
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   But he quickly returned to his main focus, saying he would work
with the opposition ``so that we may be able to try, not at any
price, but, yes, with all our strength, to bring to the state of
Israel security and peace and a different future for all our
children.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Barak won a strong mandate in the general election
for prime minister. But electoral changes introduced in 1996 _
under which Israelis vote directly for the prime minister as well
as, separately, for the parliament _ have produced a fractured
parliament with a profusion of narrow-interest parties and the need
for coalitions, which have proved unstable. Barak lost his
parliamentary majority in the legislature on the eve of the Camp
David talks, when three religious and rightist parties quit to
protest the peace talks. That reduced his core support from 69
seats to 42 in the 120-seat body.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has not ruled out a national unity government,
particularly should there be an outbreak of Palestinian violence.
But bringing Likud or the religious parties into his coalition
would probably halt peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Likud, for its part, said in a statement Sunday that it had
decided against joining a government of national unity and that it
intended to topple Barak, whom it accused of lying to the people
and breaking his promises to the public not to surrender any part
of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is only one way now to stop the danger _ hold early
elections,'' said the Likud leader, Ariel Sharon.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon, a hawkish former general, said that Israel needs a
national government that could reach ``a peace that was safer, a
peace that was better, a peace that would last generations, a peace
with a united, undivided Jerusalem as Israel's capital.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Under no circumstances should we succumb to any
temptation to form a national unity government because today we
know exactly where things stand. There is only one option: to
replace the government as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Efforts continued on both the Israeli and Palestinian sides to
keep the peace talks alive.
</P>
<P>
   Senior negotiators from Camp David, Saeb Erekat for the
Palestinians and Oded Eran for the Israelis, met in Jericho on
Sunday for the first time since the breakup of the 15-day meeting
in a symbolic show that the effort was continuing. Their
discussions were said to have included such unresolved issues as a
long-declared plan to move Israeli troops and the release of
prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Ranking Israeli and Palestinian security officials also met in
Gaza in the early evening, part of a joint effort to keep a lid on
violence by extremists on each side.
</P>
<P>
   Before dawn Sunday, Palestinian police in Gaza arrested the
second-ranking leader of the radical Islamic group Hamas,
Abdel-Aziz al-Rantissi, in his home. There was no immediate
official explanation, but he and other Hamas officials have been
vocal in their criticism of the Camp David talks.
</P>
<P>
   During a demonstration last week in Gaza, Rantissi called on
Arafat to abandon the peace talks and resume an armed struggle, or
jihad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes to the rifle,'' he exhorted the crowd. ``Yes to jihad.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, for his part, arrived in Saudi Arabia on Sunday and met
with Crown Prince Abdullah and other members of the Saudi royal
family for talks apparently aimed at building support for some kind
of Arab summit meeting to work out a joint position on issues in
the peace talks, particularly the critical question of the status
of Jerusalem and its holy places. President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt
was in Libya on Sunday on a similar mission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
