<SLUG> BC-SANFRAN-WEATHER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMER IN SAN FRANCISCO: IS IT COOL ENOUGH FOR YOU? 
</HEADLINE>
   By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A gray, windy morning, late November to the
core.
</P>
<P>
   Office workers on downtown Market Street push through the
billows of fog, holding their trench coats against the chill.
Newspaper vendors keep their kiosk windows closed. An old man
selling red roses ($2 a stem) outside the Bay Area Rapid Transit
train station is wearing wool gloves and a ski cap pulled way down.
</P>
<P>
   Courtney Schirmer is standing on a corner of First and Market
Streets, waiting for a bus to ferry her across town to her job at a
graphics design company. She is wearing a leather motorcycle
jacket, Army green corduroys and heavy black boots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate being cold,'' she says, pulling a canvas hat and a
pullover sweater from her backpack to show she means it. ``I'm from
Orange County. Three summers here, and I've learned how to pile
dress.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it is summer in San Francisco, the country's capital of
cool. That's cool as in temperatures, in the 50s morning and night,
60s at high noon. Cool as in a daily mist that gnaws at old bones
and bum knees. The cool justifies the cafes at nearly every corner
and the sweatshirts in the souvenir shops off Union Square.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, it has been so cool in the city _ 4 or 5 degrees cooler,
at an average of 63 degrees, than is typical in July _ that the
heat that has scorched much of the South seems as foreign as beach
days and backyard pools. Planes get fogged in at the airport and
there is no going out at night without a jacket. A hat is a good
move, too. But San Franciscans simply say ``groovy'' and stroll
along.
</P>
<P>
   They say this is just the way it is here. Summer bypasses this
place as if there is not enough heat to go around. In Oakland, 10
minutes over the Bay Bridge, it is 10 degrees warmer, with the sun
a notch brighter and the breeze as light as baby's breath. And for
every 10 miles inland from San Francisco, the conventional wisdom
goes, the weather gets warmer and warmer.
</P>
<P>
   Yet San Franciscans worth their chest-thumping civic pride are
proud of this paradise of perpetual spring. They boast about the
city's foggy bottom as though there were nothing to be said for the
tropical sun of Oahu or the autumn leaf show in upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best weather in the country,'' said Skye
Fernandez, a Web page designer who has lived in San Francisco
virtually all her 30 years. She was standing on trendy Valencia
Street in the city's Mission District, wearing a furry wool sweater
as she waited for a lunch table. Her friend Bobbi Greene braved the
breeze in a T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who complain about the summer here have forgotten how
bad it is everywhere else,'' said Greene, who moved here from West
Hartford, Conn., 12 years ago. ``The fog burns off by late morning,
usually. It doesn't come back until late afternoon. In between,
it's perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Tourists beg to differ. ``Horrible,'' said Corinne Gulon of
Lyons, France, as she surveyed the day in Chinatown. ``I arrived
here, and no one can swim. I tried yesterday at 12 and had no luck
because of the fog.''
</P>
<P>
   Locals love trotting out the line Mark Twain supposedly said
about the coldest winter he ever spent being a summer in San
Francisco. (Historians say he never said it, but it is too good to
resist. Every San Francisco weather story uses it.)
</P>
<P>
   All city residents have learned (as Jan Null, a meteorologist
with the Golden Gate Weather Service, explained) that the natural
air-conditioning is caused when California's interior Central
Valley heats up in the summer, creating lower air pressure that
causes a sea breeze as air flows from low to high pressure. The
water off the coast is about 55 degrees, and as the air blows over
the top of the water it creates the cool city residents love.
</P>
<P>
   ``You must be from the East Coast if you think you miss 90
degrees,'' said J.J. Bunce, a software engineer and recovering New
Yorker who has lived here 15 years. ``Summer is just a state of
mind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
