<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFORM-PARTY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUCHANAN IGNORES ATTEMPT TO KNOCK HIM OFF REFORM BALLOT 
</HEADLINE>
  By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan has vowed to disregard a vote by Reform Party
leaders to remove his name from their presidential ballot because
of how he collected voters' signatures in the nominating process.
</P>
<P>
   ``We plan to ignore it,'' Bay Buchanan, chief strategist for her
brother's campaign, said Sunday, responding to a unanimous vote
taken on Saturday in Dallas by a group of party officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is of no consequence to us, and we plan to stand very, very
strongly against the handful of mean-spirited dissidents who have
refused to recognize that at every single turn of the process, they
have been whupped,'' Ms. Buchanan said, signaling that conflict
within the party is likely to endure.
</P>
<P>
   The vote to disqualify Buchanan came just over a week before the
scheduled start of the Reform nominating convention in Long Beach,
Calif., on Aug. 9. This latest controversy almost ensures that the
convention will unfold in an atmosphere of contention and
uncertainty with two distinct camps fighting for control of the
party and the $12.6 million in federal campaign money that will be
available to the party's nominee.
</P>
<P>
   One side has lined up behind Buchanan, who bolted from the
Republican Party last year to expand his right-wing conservative
base as a Reform Party leader. The other is not so much aligned
behind his only rival, John Hagelin, as it is united in its zeal to
stop Buchanan from using a party founded eight years ago by Ross
Perot as a platform for Buchanan's own conservative agenda.
</P>
<P>
   The result has become something of a political train wreck for a
party that once projected pride in offering a platform of
government reform and optimism in a belief that Reform Party
members could change a system dominated by the two mainstream
parties.
</P>
<P>
   This latest round of intrigue follows accusations that Buchanan
defrauded the process of collecting signatures for his nomination
by turning in names of people who would otherwise not be qualified
to vote in the Reform primary. Unlike Democrats and Republicans,
who choose their nominee through a series of state primaries, the
Reform Party counts votes cast during a five-week period by party
members, people who have requested a ballot or people who have
signed petitions for the current election year.
</P>
<P>
   To investigate accusations of impropriety by the Buchanan
campaign that first came from Hagelin's supporters, the party's
Presidential Nomination Committee appointed a subcommittee to audit
names submitted by both campaigns, along with supporting material.
The Hagelin campaign complied with requests for information; the
Buchanan campaign refused, asserting that the mere appointment of
such a subcommittee violated party rules.
</P>
<P>
   Without all the necessary paperwork, the committee adjourned
without voting, leaving the matter to the three members of the full
committee. With two other party leaders unexpectedly joining them
on Friday in an ex-officio capacity _ the acting chairman, Gerald
R. Moan, and the treasurer, Tom McLaughlin, both of whom are
Buchanan supporters _ the committee voted 3-2 against imposing
sanctions on the Buchanan campaign.
</P>
<P>
   A day later, a group of party officers, which was enough for a
quorum but did not include Moan and McLaughlin, met in Dallas,
where they reversed the committee vote by saying Buchanan's failure
to cooperate with the subcommittee was grounds for removing him
from the primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The burden to prove the names are valid rests with the
candidate,'' said Russell J. Verney, the original party chairman
who no longer holds a leadership position but remains as a leading
force against Buchanan by virtue of his close association with
Perot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Therefore,'' he added, ``the candidate disqualified himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Buchanan denied that her brother's campaign did anything
wrong, unethical or illegal. ``There was absolutely no fraud,'' she
said. ``I dealt very closely with the nominating committee and
followed its instructions to the letter. To come back now and say
anything we did was flawed is a malicious and outrageous
representation of the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Both camps agree that the swirl of activity last week is by no
means fatal to Buchanan's quest for the nomination and the federal
campaign money. Ultimately, a vote by delegates at the convention
may be the deciding factor in the nomination. By party rules, a
two-thirds vote of delegates could suspend the primary process,
after which the delegates would vote, with a simple majority
determining the nominee.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not clear whether the Buchanan forces have the
necessary delegate votes yet. A final count will not be possible
before a meeting on Aug. 8, a day before the convention is to
start, when forces for and against Buchanan are expected to fight
over challenges to seat delegates that could affect hundreds of
them _ and set the tone for the days that follow.
</P>
</TEXT>
