<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-30 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7560 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-BEER-FESTIVAL0731-COX     07-30 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEER-FESTIVAL0731-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Go west, young man - and brew beer
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ ``The air is better, the water is cleaner and
the beer is way better.''
</P>
<P>
   Glen Falconer might not rank them in that order, but he wants
you to know that life is sweeter in Oregon than in Atlanta, where
he grew up, attended college and still visits friends and family.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1971,'' he says, ``I was 10 years old and Atlanta was 1
million people. Today it's _ what? _ 3.2 million.''
</P>
<P>
   There were only 90,000 or so at Portland's Tom McCall Waterfront
Park, where Falconer was among the minor celebrities this weekend
at the 13th Oregon Brewers Festival. Artisan-in-residence at the
popular Wild Duck brewpub in Eugene, Ore., Falconer was one of 72
brewers whose beer was represented in the largest gathering of its
kind in North America.
</P>
<P>
   For beer lovers, Portland is mecca, with more brewpubs per
capita than any other city in the country. Andy Klubock, proprietor
of Taco Mac megatap bars in the metro Atlanta are, puts it in more
secular terms. ``Portland's the Munich of craft brewing in North
America,'' he says. ``It's one of the top markets in the country,
not just for beer but coffee, too. One of the things about
Oregonians is that they're very protective about their products.
Vermonters are the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   Oregon's geography ranges from desert in the east to rolling
farmland in the central Willamette Valley to spectacular beaches on
the Pacific coast. But only about 4 million people live there, and
they'd rather be better than bigger.
</P>
<P>
   For Falconer, it's the more assertive pale ales that define the
Oregon palate. ``There are some good ales in Atlanta,'' he says,
``but they're the exception. Here, it's part of the culture.''
</P>
<P>
   His parents still live in Atlanta, but Falconer seems of another
time and place. He looks like one of the Smith Bros. cough-drop
patriarchs reincarnated at Woodstock. The extravagance of his
salt-and-pepper beard would tempt the wrong person with hedge
clippers in his hands, and so might the pony tail that hangs
halfway down his back.
</P>
<P>
   In an earlier day, there might have been starch in his collar
and a certain rectitude in his bearing, but on a balmy Friday
afternoon his sneakers are unlaced and his wire-rim glasses are the
only hint of his scientific training at Emory University.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Velasco, an Atlanta native who knows the Portland scene,
laughs when he recalls Falconer's introduction to brewing. ``It was
1987 and I had just started homebrewing,'' says Velasco, a reporter
for The State newspaper in Columbia, S.C. ``I met Glen through some
friends. I had gone to Georgia State and he was working in asbestos
abatement in Atlanta. I brought over some of my homebrew and he
said, 'Hey, this is really good.' He decided he was going to do it,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the first few times he homebrewed, he must have
called me a dozen times. 'Eric, am I doing this right?' 'Am I doing
that right?' Every time the phone rang, I thought, 'Oh,. that's
Glen again.' But here he's become one of the best brewers in a
brewery-rich state.''
</P>
<P>
   Many craft brewers boast credentials from the University of
California at Davis or the 125-year-old Siebel Institute in
Chicago, but Falconer's degree is OTJ. ``On the job,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He apprenticed under Terri Fahrendorf, one of the best-known
female brewers in the country, in Eugene and then under John Maier,
award-winning brewer of Rogue Ales in Newport, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Glen became a protege of John's,'' Velasco says. ``Maier's got
a saying: 'When in doubt, add more hops.' Glen's of that school.''
</P>
<P>
   Many _ but hardly all _ of the milling crowd were of the same
school. These were hopheads, some of them wearing wreathed crowns
of hop flowers to affirm their allegiance.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that strike me about Oregon,'' Velasco says,
``is that it's got some of the hippest little towns anywhere.
(``One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest`` author) Ken Kesey lives in
Springfield, a twin-city of Eugene's, making yogurt.''
</P>
<P>
   You want diversity? There was diversity aplenty at this park
along the Columbia River _ so much so that the attendees who were
conspicuous were the suits. Two men in loosened ties and
button-down Oxford cloth shirts, relaxing at a table Friday night,
might as well have been full-dress Native Americans at a suburban
block party.
</P>
<P>
   An earring was more likely to be found on a man than a woman.
Minors were not admitted but infants in strollers were, and their
numbers were considerable.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon Mahar and Elizabeth Moskowitz weren't wearing flowers in
their hair, but they came all the way from Raleigh, N.C., and
brought with them definite opinions. ``You can taste everything in
it. It's very intense,'' Mahar, an engineer in her late 20s, said
of her sample of Maier's Incinerator Doppelbock, a strong
German-style lager aged much longer than most.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon Lowry, who moved from Marietta, Ga. last year and works
at the Rogue Public House in Newport, doesn't rule out going back
to Atlanta but says she won't go back to mass-market beer. ``If you
like beer at all and you've tried this, there's no going back,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   Falconer rules out going back in any way. ``One of the things
about living out here,'' he says,''is that you can be yourself. How
can you beat that?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
