<HEADER>
A7564 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-GOPBUSH-0731-COX     07-30 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-GOPBUSH-0731-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHENEY DEFENDS HIS RECORD AS DEMOCRATS ATTACK HIM AS AN
EXTREMIST
 &HT;    By KEN HERMAN AND JENA HEATH
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Former defense secretary Dick Cheney arrived here
Sunday and defended his record as Democrats raised the volume on
their push to portray George W. Bush's running mate as a
conservative extremist.
</P>
<P>
   As the Republican National Convention begins Monday, voters in
at least 15 states will see a Democratic National Committee
television ad documenting Cheney's long-ago votes against the Clean
Water Act, Head Start and several other programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are their plans for working families?'' the Democrats ask
in the ad's closing line.
</P>
<P>
   While Cheney was defending his record, Bush was in Ohio on a
swing-state tour that will bring him to the convention on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, a former Wyoming congressman, spent the day saying he
isn't running from his record, though he might vote differently on
some issues today. And he invoked the name of one of the GOP's
great icons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent a lot of time in Washington, some 25 years. I'm proud
of those years there,'' he told cheering supporters at a welcoming
rally in a downtown hotel. ``I'm especially proud of my record
voting to support smaller government, lower taxes, stronger
national defense _ the politics of Ronald Reagan.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his long service in Washington, Cheney on Sunday tried
to craft an outsider image for himself, as befuddled as the next
guy by what goes on inside the Beltway.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get out there and you look back on Washington, I must
say you frequently end up scratching your head and wondering what
the hell are they doing back there,'' he told the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who preaches campaign-trail civility, brought his usual
message to a Sunday rally in Hamilton County, Ohio, about 15 miles
north of Cincinnati. He was introduced by political fire-breathing
locals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you ready to let your daughter serve as an intern?'' said
Jim Sumner, mayor of the town of Blue Ash, referring to the Monica
Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   GOP Rep. Steve Chabot of Ohio said politics has taught him the
danger of making predictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, who would have thought, for example, that you'd see
Microsoft split up and the Clintons still together?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   The start of the rally was delayed when 83-year-old Helen
Geiger, a Cincinnati resident attending the event, collapsed and
later died. The cause of death was not immediately disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney began his day with appearances on the Sunday morning talk
shows. At each stop, he defended a congressional voting record that
Democrats say proves that the GOP ticket is too far right for
moderate voters who could make the difference in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dick Cheney will say anything to hide his extreme record and
obscure the truth behind George W. Bush's rhetoric,'' said Doug
Hattaway, spokesman for Al Gore, who the Democrats will nominate
next month.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney said some of the votes now under attack by Democrats _
including votes against banning armor-piercing bullets and plastic
weapons that elude metal detectors _ were cast because they came in
a format in which debate was limited and amendments were barred.
</P>
<P>
   On NBC's ``Meet the Press,'' Cheney said he would now vote to
ban armor-piercing bullets and plastic weapons, though he is a
strong supporter of the right to bear arms.
</P>
<P>
   On CBS, he said he voted against the Equal Rights Amendment
because he believed it would make women eligible for the military
draft.
</P>
<P>
   On ``Fox News Sunday,'' Cheney was asked about his lesbian
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got two daughters,'' he said. ``They are fine women. I'm
very proud of both of them and I think their private lives are
private. And I firmly believe that I'm running for public office
(and) they're entitled to their privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney also jabbed back at the Democrats, branding President
Clinton as ``an enormous embarrassment to the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite those harsh words, Cheney said he would not become the
ticket's bad cop.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're looking for a slash-and-burn artist who is somebody
who can get up and give a stirring, tub-thumping stump speech, I'm
not your guy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney backed up that comment with a less-than-rousing
four-minute speech at the welcome rally that included loud music
and a full-fledged confetti drop.
</P>
<P>
   Once during his remarks, Cheney ran into a Y2K glitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we're trying to re-establish in Washington with
the 19. . . , excuse me, with the 2000 campaign,'' he said. ``I
forgot it is the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman can be e-mailed at: kherman(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Jena Heath can be e-mailed at: jenah(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
