<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-NOTEBOOK-0731-1stLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eds: Adds item and deletes duplicated item.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Political tidbits from the Republican National
Convention:
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign is known for keeping on message. To help
delegates do the same, Republican National Convention officials are
giving each a 435-page copy of George W. Bush's speeches, policy
positions and campaign fact sheets.
</P>
<P>
   Convention Chairman Andrew Card said Sunday the book, entitled
``Renewing America's Purpose,'' includes all Bush's policy speeches
and position papers for the past year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our road map of the governor's key principles and
policies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats plan to hold a daily media briefing at the Sheet
Metal Hall every day during the convention to counter the
Republican message, and one of the main targets will be the record
of vice-presidential nominee Dick Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   Former Philadelphia Mayor Ed Rendell, general chairman of the
Democratic Party, asked if he's taking Cheney's voting record out
of context, said:
</P>
<P>
   ``What's out of context about not voting to not ban bullets
whose sole purpose is to pierce bulletproof vests and kill
policemen? ... What's out of context about that (or) voting against
additional funding for head start, against additional funding for
immunization of children? ... Those votes speak for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now remember, George Bush keeps telling us he's
compassionate,'' Rendell said. ``And his first deed ... was to pick
a vice president. And he picked a vice president who voted ...
against the interests of the American people over and over and over
again.''
</P>
<P>
   In memory of Sen. Paul Coverdell, who was to lead the Georgia
contingent in Philadelphia, delegates and alternates have donned
blue lapel ribbons. Georgia state party chairman Chuck Clay has
succeeded Coverdell as chairman. Rather than advance one alternate
into Coverdell's spot, the delegation plans to rotate the late
senator's floor credentials among several alternates, to give as
many as possible a chance to sit in the delegation's No. 1 spot.
Coverdell died several weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors rolled around Philadelphia Sunday about politically
picturesque toilet paper decorating a couple of the restrooms at
Philadelphia International Airport. To be exact, the tales involved
toilet paper bearing the likeness of former president Jimmy Carter.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, the rumored toilet paper was on display at the
airport, but not in the restroom, and not just featuring Carter. In
fact, the paper was part of an exhibit put on by the airport titled
``Political Memorabilia.'' For those who use the bathroom but may
not favor Carter, the exhibit also featured toilet paper bearing
the likenesses of Hubert Humphrey, George McGovern and Richard
Nixon. In fact, all sorts of memorabilia is on display at the
airport's Terminal B, including a teapot shaped like Nixon's head.
</P>
<P>
   ``People love it,'' said Mark Pesce, airport spokesman.
``Walking through the airport, people just stop and look at this
stuff and they smile and laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   For Eva Folse, an alternate convention delegate from
Warner-Robins, Ga., life has been like the movie ``Life is
Beautiful.'' The woman who grew up in England and later settled in
the U.S. says the tragedy and poverty she has seen is part of what
drew her to the Republican party.
</P>
<P>
   Folse's parents married in Poland. Her father was captured by
the Bolsheviks and as a prison train carted him to Siberia, Folse's
mother demanded to go to the prison with her husband. Later, as the
couple settled in Great Britain, Folse says she saw how dependency
on public assistance can destroy people and how socialized medicine
can kill. In fact, she blames the system for her mother's death
from diabetes in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Folse married and she has lived here in the states 30 years, her
southern twang giving no clue of her background. The Republican
Party teaches independence and cares about people, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life has molded my opinion,'' said Folse, 53.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
