<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-PREPARE-485&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP CONVENTION WILL BE POP-CULTURE EXTRAVAGANZA 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ If there was any doubt that the Republicans were
reaching out to new constituencies this year, consider the
celebrity to whom they have given the honor of delivering the
introduction on Wednesday night of the House speaker, Dennis
Hastert.
</P>
<P>
   He goes by a stage name, The Rock, and for a living, he hammers
opponents in a ring. The idea of this World Wrestling Federation
superstar hobnobbing onstage with heavyweights of the Grand Old
Party is but one sign that in terms of unity of message and
show-biz pizazz, these proceedings will diverge in marked ways from
past conventions.
</P>
<P>
   The most often repeated phrase from party officials and
convention planners here in recent days is not the convention's
official slogan _ ``Renewing America's Purpose. Together'' _ but
``This is a different kind of convention.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be hard to get less Republican than The Rock, a New
Media star who would seem as unlikely a presence on stage at the
First Union Center as Trent Lott, the Republican Senate majority
leader, would be as a house guest on ``Big Brother.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's exactly the idea. The bridge that the Republicans
wanted to build was not so much to the 21st century as to
20th-Century Fox and its ilk. The energy of the media age in all
its manifestations _ music, film, video, the Web, and even
prime-time professional wrestling _ is the aura that the
Republicans wanted. And it is lost on no one here that a pro
wrestler by the name of Jesse Ventura ignited the imagination of
Minnesota voters and won the governorship as a third-party
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans seem to have concluded that most Americans dwell
in this multimedia-driven, pop-cultural world, as opposed to the
sharper-edged political one that was conjured by what many in the
party have come to view as the off-putting ideological shows that
were staged before. At the 1992 convention, for example, speeches
by hard-right proponents like Pat Buchanan left a bad taste in the
mouths of many voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want people to come away with the feeling that Governor
Bush is going to do things a little bit differently,'' said Russell
Schriefer, a Bush media consultant who has been working on the
convention videos and programs for months.
</P>
<P>
   But when Republicans say ``different,'' they really mean
something else. They are trying to say that by being different
onstage here, they are acting more like the voting majority.
</P>
<P>
   The message is being managed to such a degree that the same
mantras are repeated over and over by officials, as if the
candidate and his minions were circulating them on some
high-security e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a new kind of leader, and this is a different kind of
convention,'' the Republican governor of Pennsylvania, Tom Ridge,
said Saturday on ``Larry King Live'' _ an almost verbatim
repetition of the favorite sound bite of the convention's general
co-chairman, Andy Card.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The convention's program is another reflection of the lock-step
approach to message management. On Monday night, for instance, when
the focus on the stage turns to education issues, so will the
satellite feed to three jumbo Liquid Crystal Display screens.
</P>
<P>
   The image of Gov. George W. Bush, speaking live at a school
event in Ohio, will be beamed into the First Union Center. On
Tuesday, when the program calls for talk of defense policy _ and a
speech by a war hero, Sen. John McCain of Arizona _ Bush is again
to appear by satellite, from a site brimming with military
symbolism: Gettysburg, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   For each night's program, there will be a heavy emphasis on
narrative flow and emotional crescendo: ``Most of the lighthearted
moments are early in the evening, and the evenings will build,''
Schriefer said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, at a planning meeting here last week, Card and his staff
_ many of whom have extensive experience in producing television
shows _ went painstakingly through charts of each night's
prime-time offerings, blocked out in five-minute segments, from
7:30 to 11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   If the session had the feel of a meeting of network programmers,
the similarities were intentional: This convention is expected to
put to rest any pretense the party had to producing anything but a
television spectacle. The ``show'' begins much the way an Emmy or
Oscar special might _ from a remote location, using actors _ and
the stage has been designed to look as if it were intended as much
for Brooks and Dunn, a country western group, as for Jennifer Dunn,
a Republican House member from Washington who is to have a featured
role one evening.
</P>
<P>
   As explained by Republican officials, the production will begin
with a satellite feed from Carpenters' Hall, part of the historic
Independence Hall complex in Philadelphia's Olde City, where an
actor in Colonial garb will ring in the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Another actor playing Thomas Jefferson will also be featured,
and a few moments later a camera in the First Union Center will
focus on Paul C. Harris Sr., a Virginia state assemblyman who
occupies the seat once held by Jefferson. Harris also happens to be
black.
</P>
<P>
   The thrust is not appreciated by everyone. Among others, Richard
Lowry, the editor of the National Review, a conservative journal,
appeared on CNN the other night to express disappointment that the
issues of the day are being shoved out of the television picture.
And Democrats are clearly trying to cloud the upbeat focus on Bush
with a 17-state advertising campaign criticizing the congressional
voting record of his running mate, Dick Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans who have been pushing for a mainstream appeal
seem buoyant. ``An inclusive message is a winning message,'' said
Mark Miller, executive director of the Republican Leadership
Council, a centrist group based in Washington. Even a former
adversary, Greg Stevens, who was McCain's media consultant during
the primaries, said he is impressed by how faithfully the Bush camp
has tried to marry Bush's personal style to the convention's
themes.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to like who they vote for,'' Stevens said. ``And
their greatest advantage is the likability factor.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans appear to have niceness at the top of their
list. ``The problem Republicans have had in the past is we've been
all serious,'' Schriefer said. ``It didn't look like we were having
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not everyone wants to see The Rock. The party hopes
it has taken care of that too. The first night will close with a
black-and-white appearance on the screens of that icon of the past
Kate Smith.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-00 1950EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
