u e BC-TALENT-FORSAKEN-2TAKE     07-30 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TALENT-FORSAKEN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: A PRODIGY WHO USED HER TALENTS BEHIND THE
SCENES 
</HEADLINE>
  By ANTHONY TOMMASINI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   People who wish they had artistic talent usually find it hard to
understand why anyone with such a gift would not use it. But there
can be many complex reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a talented young person is pointedly discouraged from
a professional career, as was Mozart's older sister, Maria Anna,
called Nannerl, who was thought to be hardly less talented than he.
Typical of women of the period, she was not permitted to make
music, except at home, after she turned 18. She married a
magistrate, had three children, gave piano lessons and after her
brother's death became a valued resource for Mozart biographers.
</P>
<P>
   Others may be stymied by internal conflicts, a situation
poignantly captured by David Auburn's play ``Proof,'' which just
closed at the Manhattan Theater Club in New York. The central
character, Catherine, whose father is an ingenious mathematics
professor, drops out of college to care for him after he suffers a
mental breakdown. As she turns sullen, cynical and isolated, it
becomes clear that she, too, is a mathematical genius, although she
has kept her work secret and shuns a career.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, most cases of forsaken talent rarely become public.
Until now this has been true of the pioneering record producer
Teresa Sterne, 73, Tracey to her friends and colleagues. From 1965
to 1979, as the director of Nonesuch Records, Sterne turned a
budget classical label into one of the most adventurous companies
in the business. But most of the young artists she nurtured, and
even many of her close friends, had no idea that in her own youth
she had been a piano prodigy.
</P>
<P>
   While keeping her past musical life to herself, Sterne made news
at Nonesuch. She recorded repertory that other, bigger companies
ignored: vernacular American song, world music and, especially,
works by living composers. She set off a nationwide craze for
ragtime with some popular recordings of Scott Joplin, performed by
Joshua Rifkin. She sought out great though less well-known artists
and helped establish their careers, among them the pianist Paul
Jacobs, the mezzo-soprano Jan DeGaetani and the pianist Gilbert
Kalish.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1979 she was dismissed, in a move that anticipated the
current cutback on classical labels, in which innovative, smaller
companies have been gobbled up by profit-minded conglomerates. The
action brought howls of protest from critics and musicians in the
United States and Europe and turned her into a sacrificial symbol
of artistic principle.
</P>
<P>
   Some of her colleagues knew that Sterne had once been a serious
pianist but assumed that she was a talented young musician who
could not make it professionally and had wisely chosen another
path.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Sterne was a spectacularly gifted prodigy who made a
notable New York debut at age 12, playing Grieg's Piano Concerto
with the NBC Symphony Orchestra in a benefit concert at Madison
Square Garden in 1939.
</P>
<P>
   For her debut with the New York Philharmonic the next year, she
played Tchaikovsky's daunting Piano Concerto No. 1 at Lewisohn
Stadium in Harlem before nearly 6,000 cheering people. And although
several critics noted that the 13-year-old Sterne lacked the
strength to fully handle the work's thundering octave passages,
they uniformly praised her temperament, singing tone and impressive
technique.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, thanks to the loyalty of a small group of friends and the
commitment of Robert Hurwitz, the current director of Nonesuch
Records, Sterne's early work as a pianist may become better known.
In October, Nonesuch, the company from which she was once so
publicly ousted, will release a two-disk recording in her honor.
One disk will feature selections from some of the important albums
she produced while directing the label. The other will present her
as a young pianist in live performances. The deteriorating original
tapes have been in Sterne's private collection for years. Although
this archive is not large, it makes clear the depth of her gifts.
</P>
<P>
   There is a vibrant performance of Bach's ``Italian'' Concerto,
made in 1939 when she was 11, and a mature and fleet account of
Mozart's Piano Concerto No. 20, made just after she had turned 14.
There is also an entire recital at the Brooklyn Museum in 1944,
when she was 16, with works by Bach-von Buelow, Medtner, Debussy,
Chopin and Beethoven, capped by a brilliant performance of Liszt's
Hungarian Rhapsody No. 13.
</P>
<P>
   There is a confident and rhapsodically lyrical Rachmaninoff
Second Piano Concerto, performed with the New York Philharmonic,
again at Lewisohn Stadium, when she was 19. And more.
</P>
<P>
   Sterne and Hurwitz have been considering which performances to
include on the fall recording. But Sterne has insisted on one: the
sonata written for her by David Broekman, a Dutch-born composer and
conductor who became her most important mentor. The recording is
from a WNYC live studio recital in 1951, essentially her last
public performance.
</P>
<P>
   So why did she not continue a career that had begun so
splendidly? Sadly, she is now unable to explain.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sterne is suffering from amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, the
progressive deterioration of the motor nerves commonly known as Lou
Gehrig's disease. She is confined to her apartment on the Upper
West Side, with its Oriental carpets, rows of books and records, a
grand piano stacked with music, photographs on the walls of
grateful artists she has recorded and a letter from President Jimmy
Carter, thanking her for championing American music, that hangs
inconspicuously in the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   Other than health care aides, she will see no one except a small
circle of close friends. Having never married, and with no
surviving relatives, she has appointed a longtime friend, Norma
Hurlburt, who recently became the executive director of the Chamber
Music Society of Lincoln Center, as her health-care proxy. The once
voluble Sterne, who was famous among her friends and colleagues for
filling up their telephone answering machine tapes, is now barely
able to speak.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously she is unable to take part in interviews. But in a
letter she wrote a few years ago to a friend, the music critic
Richard Freed, which was passed on to this reporter, she spoke at
length about what led her to abandon a concert career. And during a
series of talks with Hurlburt, who visits daily, Sterne was able to
articulate a few answers to questions posed for this article.
</P>
<P>
   She was born in Brooklyn to a cultured family with a toehold on
the middle class. Her mother was a cellist who had been part of a
trio that played in movie houses and fancy restaurants, but she
stopped working to devote herself to her talented daughter's
development. Sterne's father, a violinist, deserted the family when
she was 14. Her paternal uncle, Robert Sterne, also a professional
violinist, provided musical counseling and financial support.
</P>
<P>
   Sterne studied piano with a series of local teachers and from
the age of 10 was educated at home by private tutors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We managed to live in a kind of aristocratic poverty,'' Sterne
wrote to Freed. ``The Brooklyn house was long paid off, and
expenses like oil heat, etc., were quite minimal. My little aunt,
who lived also at that beautiful house, was `moonlighting' after
her daytime job at the New York State Attorney General's office as
a legal secretary.'' Sterne's ``poor dear mama,'' she added, did
what she could, working as a nanny or sewing and taking odd jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The program booklets and faded press clippings from Sterne's
years as a prodigy are contained in a large scrapbook with
crumbling black pages. Several early profiles indicate how
constrained her childhood was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teresa looks not very different from a thousand other pretty,
chubby 12-year-olds in Brooklyn,'' one article in PM's Weekly
reported. ``But she doesn't go to school and doesn't play with the
other girls in her neighborhood.'' The interviewer also noted that
young Teresa did not have time to pay attention to ``the modern
swing music,'' then the rage.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all right for children who don't understand the
classics,'' young Teresa is quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Sterne's career progressed steadily through her teen-age years.
At 20 she auditioned for the powerful manager Arthur Judson, who
offered to arrange a European tour for her, at a cost: $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in our circumstance couldn't even visualize that much
money,'' she wrote in the letter to Freed. Still, it was not just
the expense that stymied her, as she explained recently to
Hurlburt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lacked the sophistication about how to build a career,''
Sterne said. ``My conscience drove me to join the working world. I
didn't want to be a parasite.''
</P>
<P>
   She took courses in touch-typing and stenography and decided to
``change her image'' by enrolling in a low-budget modeling school,
where she learned to walk like a lady and wear makeup. ``I had
grown up not knowing there were boys and girls, just people and
pianists,'' she wrote in the letter. ``I needed terribly to get out
into `the city' and find some kind of life for myself.''
</P>
<P>
   She took a job as a secretary and model in a knitwear showroom
in the garment district, where she typed ``about 100 letters a day
and got propositioned by various young fellows,'' she wrote. For a
time she worked in the offices of Sol Hurok, the famous manager,
helping to promote the careers of other young pianists. Eventually
she spent six years at Vanguard Records, ending up as personal
secretary to the director.
</P>
<P>
   So in 1965, when Jac Holzman, the head of Elektra, the parent
company of Nonesuch Records, offered her the directorship of the
Nonesuch label, she was full of idealism, hardened by the realities
of the record business and ready.
</P>
<P>
   In an elegant assessment of Sterne's missionary zeal as a record
producer, written in 1980 following her dismissal, the New Yorker
critic Andrew Porter commented, ``When a promising new composition
has been billed, when a new ensemble _ Renaissance, Baroque or
contemporary _ has made its debut, Teresa Sterne has been there in
the hall, eager to ensure that the best of what and who deserve
recording and dissemination do get recorded.''
</P>
<P>
   But during her tenure in the 1970s, Elektra and Nonesuch were
acquired by Warner Communications. Nonesuch, the company's only
classical label, was losing money, Joe Smith, the head of
Elektra/Asylum/Nonesuch, declared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nonesuch is in business, and it is losing its credibility in
its marketplace,'' he said in a blunt interview with The Boston
Globe. ``We can't make records that sell only outside the Russian
Tea Room.''
</P>
<P>
   Sterne's defenders argued that sales of Nonesuch recordings had
suffered from poor marketing and distribution by the parent
company. Yet rather than oust the marketing director, the company
dismissed Sterne and put the marketing director in charge.
</P>
<P>
   The label drifted for several years, until late 1984, when
Hurwitz took over. Today, he asserted in a recent interview, he
works with popular artists like the soprano Dawn Upshaw and the
Kronos Quartet and has the freedom to record unusual fare, like
Louis Andriessen's opera ``Rosa'' and Stephen Sondheim's first
musical, ``Saturday Night.'' Still, he acknowledges that he has not
matched Sterne's commitment to the most complex, serious
contemporary music.
</P>
<P>
   Though she never would have anticipated becoming a record
executive when she was an adolescent pianist practicing for five
and six hours a day, Sterne now sees her Nonesuch work as a logical
outgrowth of her artistry and idealism.
</P>
<P>
   As she recently told Hurlburt, ``I felt I could do more to
disseminate music at the highest level through recording artists I
felt the whole world had to hear than through my own
performances.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
