<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-SCANDAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE LEADER EMBARRASSED AGAIN; FINANCIAL CHIEF QUITS IN
SCANDAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Dealing yet another blow to Prime Minister Yoshiro
Mori's faltering government, the head of the government agency
charged with overhauling Japan's faltering financial system
resigned Sunday amid a fast-escalating scandal over his
relationship with one of Japan's largest financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Kimitaka Kuze, the chairman of the Financial Reconstruction
Agency, submitted his resignation Sunday afternoon as Mori cut
short a trip to Ishikawa prefecture to return to Tokyo to deal with
yet another crisis in his short but crisis-plagued administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided to resign because I thought my personal problems
might disrupt parliamentary deliberations,'' Kuze said at a news
conference. ``This is a time when the government is facing
important domestic and foreign relations issues, and I wanted to
ensure there were no misunderstandings about the financial
administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuze acknowledged on Friday that he received 230 million yen, or
$2.1 million at current exchange rates, in cash and benefits from
the Mitsubishi Trust &AMP; Banking Corp. for advisory work he did over
13 years that ended in 1996. He refused to resign then, contending
that he did nothing illegal under the laws at the time, a
contention he continued to maintain Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   But his critics in the opposition party, which is gaining
strength at the expense of the long-ruling Liberal Democratic
Party, insisted that the payments were a bribe from the industry
Kuze was charged with overseeing. And Mitsubishi Trust issued a
statement saying it had indeed hired him for his political
connections, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   Reports Saturday that Kuze had accepted 100 million yen, or
$920,000, from a condominium developer only further fueled doubts
about his ability to serve as the head of the agency. More and more
companies are seeking debt waivers, a trend that may mean the
government ends up holding the fate of several debt-laden real
estate and construction companies in its hands.
</P>
<P>
   He was the second head of the agency to resign under a cloud
this year, and his departure is likely to raise further doubts
about the government's ability and commitment to restructuring the
financial system, which two years ago was poised to collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Michio Ochi was forced to step down in February after he made
remarks that suggested he would intervene to water down bank
inspections.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the agency, which was established in the fall of 1998, has
had three different chairmen in less than a year, and found itself
unable to withstand outside pressure. It has been forced into two
embarrassing retreats, first on the issue of whether to use public
money to bail out a department store owner and most recently over
the terms of the agreement it made to sell the bankrupt Nippon
Credit Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Mori has demonstrated an almost uncanny knack for political
blunders since taking over as prime minister after Keizo Obuchi was
incapacitated by a stroke and later died in May. The prime
minister, a veteran LDP politician who was battered by surprising
losses for the party in parliamentary elections in June, had
recently been bolstered by presiding over a trouble-free summit
meeting of the leaders of the world's industrialized countries.
</P>
<P>
   He has misspoken so many times since he became prime minister in
April that, during the news conference that closed the summit
meeting, he shuffled through a stack of cards printed with answers
to anticipated questions before saying anything.
</P>
<P>
   He is widely blamed within his own party for the heavy losses it
suffered in the June elections _ criticism that increased when the
drubbing was followed by another bribery scandal involving the
former construction minister, Eiichi Nakao.
</P>
<P>
   Now Mori's knowledge of Kuze's relationship with Mitsubishi
Trust will come under scrutiny. He and other leaders of the ruling
Liberal Democratic Party were tipped to the relationship by an
anonymous letter threatening to expose the matter to the media
should Kuze win a Cabinet post.
</P>
<P>
   The party insists it conducted a thorough investigation and
determined that Kuze had not violated any laws.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The main opposition party, which itself has been on the
defensive over the last few weeks for its role in drafting the laws
that govern the sputtering resurrection of Japan's financial
system, had seized on the appointment of Kuze to renew demands for
Mori to step down. Mori ``knew the situation when he made the
appointment and thought it was OK,'' Yukio Hatoyama, the head of
the Democratic Party, said in an interview with NHK television.
``So of course he has responsibility for the appointment and
responsibility to explain it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mori replaced Kuze with Hideyuki Aizawa, a member of parliament
who heads the Lower House finance committee and has been a harsh
critic of the commission.
</P>
<P>
   Aizawa, a financial bureaucrat who was a prisoner of war in
Russia after World War II, has objected to the agency's desire to
allow nonbanks to operate in the banking sector, so his appointment
would likely delay the plans of companies like the Sony Corp. and
Ito-Yokado to set up banks. He is also at the forefront of a
current move in parliament to curtail the use of government
guarantees in rehabilitating the financial industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
