u p BC-GOP-RDP-2TAKES(TRIMS)     07-30 1256
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-RDP-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAIN TOPIC ON EVE OF GOP CONVENTION: CHENEY'S VOTING RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
  By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Dick Cheney, the Republican choice for vice
president, arrived here on the eve of the party's national
convention, after appearing on four national television programs to
smooth the more conservative edges of his House voting record.
</P>
<P>
   Once here, Cheney called for the election of Gov. George W. Bush
of Texas, promising ``most of all to make America proud again by
giving them a president they can respect.'' Cheney spoke for only
four minutes at the hotel where he will be joined by Bush on
Wednesday, and he seemed overwhelmed by his reception from a crowd
organized by the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's more important task came on the morning talk shows.
While he called questions about his votes ``trivial'' and
``irrelevant to the important issues of the day,'' he discussed
some of the reasons behind his record.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney said he voted in 1986 against freedom for Nelson Mandela
because he believed the African National Congress was a
``terrorist'' group. He said he opposed banning cop-killer bullets
and plastic guns that could pass metal detectors because of the
no-amendment procedure under which they were considered. And he
said he voted against Head Start and the Older Americans Act
because they were too costly; on both, he said his position was
different today.
</P>
<P>
   Unimpressed, the Democratic National Committee began showing a
television advertisement Sunday attacking Cheney over votes against
Head Start, the Clean Water Act, the school lunch program and
health insurance for people who lost coverage when they lost their
jobs, and for praising OPEC for cutting oil production. Referring
to Gov. George W. Bush, the presumptive presidential nominee, and
Cheney, the ad said: ``What are their plans for working families?''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's former challenger for the nomination, Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., appeared Sunday before the reformist-to-radical ``shadow
convention,'' and gamely asked the audience to vote for Bush, in
terms that were less than ecstatic. He was soundly booed. Then he
formally released his own delegates, from commitments to vote for
him. Many groaned.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush camp's plans for a conflict-free convention, meanwhile,
chugged along without serious difficulty. Abortion rights advocates
insisted they were working to find the required six states to
support new language in the platform acknowledging diverse views on
the subject, but they had yet to find them. One minor rules
squabble shaping up was over an attempt to make all 165 members of
the Republican National Committee automatic delegates at the next
national convention.
</P>
<P>
   Bush himself campaigned Sunday at the replica of the historic
Crosley Field in the suburbs of Cincinnati. Several thousand people
withstood a driving rain to see him. Fireworks popped as he drove
up in a campaign bus emblazened with the slogan, ``Renewing
America's Purpose,'' the theme of his five-day tour through several
battleground states. He told the Republican members of Congress
sharing the stage with him, ``Be patient. Help is on the way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working our way to the convention,'' he said, ``And
we're going to states that the Republican candidate hasn't done so
well in lately. See we started off in Arkansas. And then we went to
Kentucky. Now we're here in Ohio. The last two elections we haven't
done so well, but that's going to change come November. We're going
to carry the great state of Ohio.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no formal convention business Sunday beyond the
arrival of 2,066 delegates _ mostly middle-aged white males and
generally more conservative than the voters who gave Bush the
nomination _ assembled in the city where Republicans have nominated
five previous candidates, from John C. Fremont in 1856 to Thomas E.
Dewey in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   But it became increasingly clear that despite the shadow
convention and occasional minor demonstrations like Sunday's
peaceful march by 7,000 for a variety of causes, the four-day show
beginning Monday is all about Bush and Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The party's congressional wing gets barely an hour at center
stage, yet Rep. Tom Davis of Virginia, who, as chairman of the
House Republican Campaign Committee, is striving mightily to retain
control of the House, pronounced himself happy with the time given
House candidates at the podium: two segments of fifteen one-minute
speeches during the day Tuesday. Nor did the senators complain at
the opportunity for six four-minute speeches around lunchtime.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said, ``This convention is about electing George W. Bush.
It's not about the House and Senate.'' He said Republican hopes of
retaining the House, where they hold a 13-seat majority, would be
aided by Bush's ``creating an updraft that our candidates can take
advantage of.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   It was also clear that the campaign has settled on a strategy
for dealing with the problems it obviously did not anticipate from
Cheney's voting record. On one television show after another, he
said the votes did not matter, but that he was not wedded to them
today.
</P>
<P>
   On ABC's This Week, Cheney complained of ``so much time and
energy and effort devoted to this kind of trivia'' and ``the
trivial aspect of the debates that rage in Washington now.''
</P>
<P>
   On CBS's ``Face the Nation,'' he said, ``The campaign that
Governor Bush and I will run is very much oriented towards the
future, it's focused on trying to restore a degree of civility in
Washington, to end the kind of partisan backbiting that has been so
much a part of the tone and tenor in this city for all too many
years.''
</P>
<P>
   On NBC's ``Meet the Press,'' he said, ``I think the American
people want to hear about the future, not about the past.'' That
choice of phrase recalled what Bill Clinton, then a candidate for
president, said on Jan. 26, 1992, about accusations that he had
conducted an affair with Jennifer Flowers.
</P>
<P>
   On CNN's ``Late Edition,'' Cheney said, ``I hope the Democrats
spend the next three months going after my voting record; I'll be
happy to defend it. But in the meantime, we're going to talk about
the future of the country, and we're going to win the election.''
</P>
<P>
   His argument about how his pro-gun votes were dictated by House
procedures banning amendments was also consistent from one program
to the next. He put it this way on ABC:
</P>
<P>
   ``Debate was limited. No amendments were allowed. And I often
voted against measures that I thought deserved more serious
coverage and debate than was permitted when the majority brought it
up under the procedure.''
</P>
<P>
   But he gave different answers when asked what he would do now on
the measure attacking cop-killer bullets that can penetrate
policemen's bullet-proof vests. He told CBS's Bob Schieffer, ``It
would depend.'' When NBC's Tim Russert asked, ``Would you authorize
money to ban cop-killer bullets and ban plastic weapons?'' Cheney
replied ``Ah, yes.''
</P>
<P>
   On ABC he said he voted in 1987 against the Older Americans Act,
which provided $1.6 billion for programs including health centers,
Meals on Wheels and Alzheimer's research by saying ``probably
because it was excessive in terms of the funding.'' He said, ``When
we had big deficits I voted against bills that I thought either
authorized or appropriated too much funds.''
</P>
<P>
   He was also interviewed on Fox News Sunday, but was not asked
about his House votes.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He continued the anti-Washington theme here, saying ``For the
last five years, I've been outside Washington, I've been out in the
real world where people are building companies, creating jobs,
inventing new technologies that are transforming our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, who has been the chairman and chief executive of the
Halliburton Co., a large oil services company based in Dallas,
said, ``When I look back at Washington, I scratch my head and ask
what the hell are they doing back there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   On the platform, Republican abortion rights supporters said they
had yet to concede defeat, and were still trying to get the
majority of six state delegations necessary to bring the issue to
the floor. But by evening, they had yet to get them. Asked if the
Bush forces were blocking their efforts, Lynn S. Grefe, national
director of the Republican Pro-Choice Coalition, replied, ``The
GOP, somewhere, is pushing against us, and it's very strong.'' The
word had clearly gone out, she said, ``Don't sign anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Abortion rights supporters filled a ballroom at a downtown
hotel, where speakers assailed the platform but argued that over
the long haul, they would prevail. ``I do believe that ultimately
reason will prevail and the Republican Party will finally eliminate
that anti-choice, anti-woman, and antediluvian plank from our party
platform and we will once again represent the values of personal
freedom and choice,'' declared Roselyn O'Connell, a Republican and
president of the National Women's Political Caucus.
</P>
<P>
   But a fight did loom over the plan, recommended Saturday by the
convention rules committee, to make all national committee members
automatic delegates. Morton Blackwell of Virginia, organizing the
challenge, said that unless the Bush campaign squelched it, he
thought he could win a floor right against ``a bad, bad idea all
over. It's an elitist notion.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For McCain, it was a tough day. Ariana Huffington, the
commentator who is the chief organizer of the shadow convention,
which is focused on campaign finance reform, lingering poverty and
a drug war seen as aimed mostly at filling up prisons, had to
intervene to quiet the booing crowd. When the catcalls continued,
intermittently, McCain canceled a promised question and answer
session.
</P>
<P>
   One participant, Emily Hagopian of Los Angeles, who came with a
group called Youth Vote 2000, said, ``Everybody saw him as our hope
for change and then he came in here with that endorsement. He
disgusted us. He betrayed us.''
</P>
<P>
   Then tears came to McCain's eyes when he met with his own
delegates. ``I need every one of you to give this campaign the same
amount of enthusiasm and participation you did for our primary
campaign,'' he told them, warning, ``American doesn't like sore
losers.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   No one gathering here was anxious to recall the last GOP
convention in this city, in 1948, when the party, which had
regained Congress two years before, met in sweltering heat to
nominate Dewey, and was confident of victory. But some of the
rhetoric of Dewey's acceptance speech could work as well for Bush's
speech, scheduled for Thursday. Dewey said on June 24, 1948:
</P>
<P>
   ``The unity we seek is more than material. It is more than a
matter of things and measures. It is most of all spiritual. Our
problem is not outside ourselves. Our problem is within ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have found the means to blow the world, physically, apart.
Spiritually, we have yet to find the means to put together the
world's broken pieces, to bind up its wounds, to make a good
society, a community of men of good-will that fits our dreams. We
have devised noble plans for a new world. Without a new spirit, our
noblest plans will come to naught. We pray that, in the days ahead,
a full measure of that spirit may be ours.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
