u p BC-CLINTON-LAWYERS-NYT &LR;      07-30 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LAWYERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON WOOS THE LAWYER AND BLASTS GOP INACTION ON JUDGES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill., N.Y., S.C.)   By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ President Clinton said Sunday that the Republican
majority in the Senate was purposely slowing down action on his
nominees to federal appeals courts and, in some cases, blocking
people solely because they are black or Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   In a pair of speeches before trial lawyers who are holding a
convention here, Clinton compared what he said was the Republicans'
refusal to consider some minority nominees to the 1986 vote in
Congress when Dick Cheney, now the Republican vice presidential
candidate, and other conservatives voted against a resolution
asking, among other things, that Nelson Mandela be released from
jail in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that Cheney's vote on the Mandela resolution was so
amazing, ``it takes your breath away.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said that Mandela had managed to get out of jail and
helped transform South Africa despite that vote. ``I'm worried
about the people now whom I've tried to put on the court of appeals
who are African-American and Hispanic who are being held in
political jail because they can't get a hearing from this
Republican Senate,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   In complaining about the refusal of the Senate Judiciary
Committee to schedule a hearing on a Hispanic nominee from Texas,
Clinton also managed to criticize Gov. George W. Bush for not
supporting the nominee to the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   The president said that the Republicans had refused to consider
two black nominees to the 4th Circuit, based in Richmond, Va.
Although the circuit contains more black residents than any of the
nation's 11 regional appeals courts, Clinton said, it has never had
a black judge.
</P>
<P>
   As often happens in presidential election years, the party that
controls the Senate and not the White House, in this case the
Republicans, slows down the confirmation process hoping to preserve
judicial slots that carry lifetime tenure for their own candidates.
</P>
<P>
   In choosing to appear before the Association of Trial Lawyers of
America, the first president to do so since Lyndon B. Johnson in
1964, Clinton paid tribute to a group that has been one of the
Democratic Party's most reliable sources of campaign donations over
the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who has been the party's principal fund-raiser in
recent years, will soon leave office and told an audience in New
York on Saturday that he would never run again. But his appearance
before the annual convention of the trial lawyers group was not
only about gratitude for the recent past but about the importance
of the trial lawyers in the current election.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, figures show that trial lawyers' donations to
Democrats have served as a counterforce to the corporate donations
that go largely to Republicans, producing a kind of complicated
financial ecosystem.
</P>
<P>
   In this election cycle, law firms have donated more than $57
million, according to Sheila Krumholz, the research director of the
Center for Responsive Politics. Of that, more than $38 million went
to Democrats with less than $19 million to Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trial lawyers are somewhat critical to Gore,'' Krumholz
said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Harshbarger, the president of Common Cause, a group that
monitors campaign spending, said the trial lawyers' money had
brought some balance to the enormous battle in state legislatures
and Congress over the issue of limiting lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're having fundamental values being played out here and the
trial lawyers are only trying to level the playing field,''
Harshbarger said in an interview. And there is no more stark
difference between the presidential candidates than on the issue of
so-called civil justice reform.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has made attacks on trial lawyers a centerpiece of his
campaign and has vowed that if elected, he will push a program
similar to the one he helped enact in Texas.He has pointed with
pride to his record in Texas of curbing civil litigation, capping
legal fees and limiting jury awards.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Alexander, a San Francisco trial lawyer who is the vice
president designate of the trial lawyers association, said Sunday
that Gore, on the other hand, had been a reliable supporter of the
trial lawyers' interest in maintaining the right to sue
corporations as a counterweight to corporate power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Gore is someone who believes in consumers, someone who
believes they should have their day in court,'' she said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Gore did not address the convention and has
seemingly resisted emphasizing the issue. Harshbarger said that
corporations had been successful in their effort to ``paint lawyers
as the bad guys.'' He said it was unsurprising that Gore had tried
to keep some distance between himself and the lawyers in the public
mind.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's appearance before the trial lawyers is, in a sense, as
a surrogate for Gore and, to a lesser extent, for other Democrats,
notably Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Nader, the longtime consumer advocate who has been closely
allied with the trial lawyers on the issue of civil litigation
rules, said Gore was allowing the president to take the heat of
associating with the lawyers while he was reaping the benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just slinking around taking money like crazy from these
guys, and at the same time he's not really standing up for the
civil justice system,'' Nader said. He cited as an example, that
Gore did not respond to a speech last February in which Bush
promised a South Carolina audience of business people that he would
immediately seek changes in the litigation rules.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-00 2015EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
