<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-30 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7591 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TURKEY-TAX-CHEATS-ART     07-30 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-TAX-CHEATS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAX AVOIDANCE IN TURKEY HAMPERING ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) By DOUGLAS FRANTZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ Almost everything for sale in Turkey has two
prices: a sticker price for goods sold with an invoice or receipt
reported to government, and a much lower price if the buyer pays
cash: The consumer avoids the 17 percent sales tax and the seller
can hide the income and escape corporate and income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The losses to Turkey's treasury from the flourishing cash
economy and other schemes to conceal income are impossible to
calculate, officials said, but new government statistics hint at a
vast scale of tax evasion among business owners and the
self-employed in this country of 65 million.
</P>
<P>
   Based on income reported to the government, the best-paid
professionals in Turkey are notaries, who certify official
documents. Last year, the average income declared by the country's
576 notaries was about $53,000, more than 10 times earnings
reported by lawyers and doctors, nearly 30 times as high as
dentists. And artists, too, have said they were paid more than
engineers, lawyers, doctors and dentists, if income reports to
government are to be believed.
</P>
<P>
   Shoe manufacturers, furniture dealers and clothing store owners
were among the categories in which people reported earning less
than the minimum wage of about $138 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Few are likely to believe the figures, given that notaries are
required by law to provide a receipt for every transaction, just as
artists must provide proof of the value of their works.
</P>
<P>
   Other self-employed people routinely accept cash without an
invoice or shift payments to offshore bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Another government statistic raised questions about how many
people report earnings. In the last 15 years, Turkey's population
has grown 30 percent and the number of taxpayers has risen only 1
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Tax evasion is certainly not unique to Turkey, but it is
hampering the country's efforts to complete the transformation from
developing to developed nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a government can't raise taxes, they can't run a proper
government or pay their civil servants enough to keep them
honest,'' said Jeremy Pope, executive director of Transparency
International, an organization that tracks government corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Corporation income is taxed at about 40 percent, and individual
income tax rates go as high as 55 percent. The Ministry of Finance
has estimated in recent years that 5 percent to 10 percent of taxes
due go unpaid, but most experts view those figures as conservative.
</P>
<P>
   Under prodding from the International Monetary Fund as a
condition for a $3.9 billion loan, Turkey is working on reforms.
New rules were adopted in 1998 to increase compliance by basing
taxes on declared earnings instead of the former assessment of
standard of living, but the results are widely ridiculed.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Ministry of Finance agreed that tax evasion
is a serious problem and that reported income is often far lower
than actual earnings.
</P>
<P>
   For now, cash transactions _ and accompanying discounts _ are
prevalent, from the restaurant owner who increases the bill for
patrons paying by credit card to the lawyer who instructs foreign
clients to pay fees into an offshore bank account.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commercial ethic has disappeared and honesty is called
stupidity,'' said Mehmet Yildirim, chairman of the Istanbul Chamber
of Commerce, quoted in a local newspaper recently.
</P>
<P>
   From the doorway of his men's clothing shop near the bustling
Misir Carsisi, or spice bazaar, Sabri Kefeli said he sees the issue
in terms of economic survival. Facing competitors and surrounded by
sidewalk vendors with no overhead, he said he has little choice but
to please the customer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customers say: `I am not going to take a receipt. What can you
do for me on price?''' he said. ``I must go along.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the day, Kefeli said, he is left to make up
receipts to account for his sales.
</P>
<P>
   As a notary, Metin Tozlu has no such options, he explained as he
sat in his second-floor office on the same street. Unlike his
neighbor, Tozlu must provide receipts for every transaction and
make detailed reports to the authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if notaries make more than doctors and lawyers, Tozlu,
chairman of the city's 193 notaries, gestured to his modest
quarters. ``What do you think?'' he asked. ``If everybody paid as a
notary pays, then we wouldn't be at the top of list.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a dispute about who avoid taxes most: Some labor union
representatives argue that civil servants and other types of
workers whose taxes are deducted from their paychecks pay more than
their share, while representatives of corporations often blame
small shop owners and the self-employed for shifting too much of
the burden to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many segments of society lack the discipline of paying
taxes,'' said Erkut Yucaoglu, chairman of an association
representing the country's 2,000 largest businesses. ``The problem
is creating the resources to enlarge the tax base through
enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer at an Istanbul firm said that in addition to many
lawyers' asking that fees be paid into offshore accounts, proceeds
from major business transactions are often deposited in foreign
banks, but proffered government some advice: ``My suggestion is to
audit everyone who bought a Jeep Cherokee or Range Rover last
year,'' the lawyer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
