<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-30 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7592 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GOP-MCCAIN-NYT &LR;      07-30 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-MCCAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR MCCAIN, IT'S BACK TO POLITICS AS USUAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES BENNET   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Politics as usual _ with its compromises,
casualties, and emotional costs _ caught up with Sen. John McCain
this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters repeatedly tested his appetite for his own words,
asking, item by item, if he still believed all those nasty things
he had said about his former opponent for the Republican
nomination, Gov. George W. Bush. Over and over, he endorsed the man
he once derided as a phony reformer unprepared for the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, one youthful audience here responded with boos,
derisive laughter, and cries of ``Drag him off!'' to what he
insisted was his ``sincere conviction'' that ``all Americans''
should support Bush. On the eve of Bush's National Convention,
McCain was beginning to seem downright conventional, a quality he
despises in politics.
</P>
<P>
   As the senator gathered on Sunday afternoon at a reception with
senior officials of the Bush campaign to formally release his
delegates to the governor, the moment and the message proved too
much. McCain had praised Bush for running a ``centrist, inclusive
campaign.'' He had urged his supporters to give the Bush campaign
``the same kind of enthusiasm and participation'' they had given
him, that had made him believe, for a time, he might be president.
Then he tried to say thanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will always be grateful,'' McCain told the packed room,
before stopping to harshly clear his throat. He tried again: ``I
will never be able to _ I'll never be able to thank.'' He gave up,
eyes shining, as the room erupted in a full minute's applause
despite his repeated efforts to get back to business. At his side,
his wife Cindy began weeping, along with some of the delegates and
campaign staff, who had never seen tears from their boss.
</P>
<P>
   When he regained control of himself and the room and at last
expressed his gratitude, McCain declared ``This is a time for
celebration.'' Then, to groans and cries, he released his remaining
delegates _ roughly 150 _ to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Coming before the four days of processed emotion that is a
modern political convention, McCain's raw moment left some
delegates shaken, even as rock music blared and confetti cannons
blasted the room. ``People really believed in him,'' said Ric
Barros, a lawyer from Massachusetts. ``It's like a death in the
family.'' Asked if he would support Bush, Barros said: ``In time.
Today, I just want to think about John McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   Appearing before McCain, Don Evans, the chairman of Bush's
campaign, praised the senator as ``my American hero'' _ though at
least one McCain aide rolled his eyes. Joe Allbaugh, the Bush
campaign manager, was also present, though he did not address the
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush camp can afford to be gracious. Trailing McCain around
the margins of the convention here is like watching an episode of
``Survivor'' while knowing who has been voted off the island. The
only sense of suspense surrounding his appearances hangs over the
question of how far he will go in endorsing Bush _ and the only
surprise registered by his audiences has been over how far he has
gone.
</P>
<P>
   For his full-throated endorsement, McCain was booed on Sunday by
the sort of audience he usually enraptures, an uneasy assortment of
the disgruntled _ critics of the campaign finance system,
politics-as-usual, and much else _ gathered for a ``shadow
convention.'' Head down, McCain soldiered through his prepared
speech until the noise became too loud, and he looked up. ``If you
like I do not need to continue,'' he said evenly. But a wave of
applause from the generally supportive audience kept him going.
</P>
<P>
   McCain rode his ``Straight Talk Express'' up here on Saturday
for what he insisted was a fun reminder of how his campaign
``caught lightening in a bottle.'' It seemed more like a rolling
test of his humility. Asked on his bus if he still believed Bush
was a ``Pat Robertson Republican,'' McCain said quietly, ``No, no,
I don't believe that.'' To another oft-repeated question, he
insisted that his relationship with Bush was ``cordial'' or even
``very good.'' Repeatedly, he said that he expected to be
supporting Bush's re-election in 2004 and not running himself.
</P>
<P>
   But the Arizona senator's self-sacrifice had its limits. He
bristled when asked, for perhaps the hundredth time, whether he had
checked with the Bush campaign before putting his bus back on the
road. ``No,'' he shot back, ``because the last time I checked, I'm
a United States senator.'' He repeatedly reminded questioners that
he always promised to support his party's nominee _ a caveat that
made his endorsement sound more dutiful than heartfelt. But his
sense of humor stayed intact. When asked if he would accept a
position in a Bush cabinet, he said, as he contended with an
enormous soft-serve vanilla waffle cone, that the only job he
wanted was emperor.
</P>
<P>
   McCain still admits to differences with Bush, including over
campaign finance reform. But he no longer declares that Bush should
adopt his position, instead noting, as he did at the shadow
convention, that ``we agree on many more issues than we disagree
on.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain has repeatedly acknowledged that he is walking a
tightrope, trying to retain an insurgent appeal while playing by
the rules of party politics. He remains extremely popular, which is
why Bush and scores of congressmen are clamoring for public shows
of his support.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters who turned out for the senator during the weekend
said that they understood. ``Everybody who's reasonable knows that
in order to make any change, you have to be incremental,'' said
George Leslie, who stood outside the shadow convention on Sunday
waiting for the senator and wearing a black T-shirt declaring
``Thank God I'm an Atheist.'' ``You have to support the system
you're in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
