<HEADER>
A7594 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BARTON-MEMORIAL0731-C     07-30 0505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARTON-MEMORIAL0731-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Barton victims memorialized one year later
 &HT;    By Stacy Shelton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A year later, tears were shed anew.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's memorial service for nine people killed in a gunman's
office rampage gave those who lost the most a place to share their
grief. Sons, daughters, spouses and parents cried again and felt
the sharp pang of absence that started the day Mark Barton shot up
two Atlanta day-trading firms.
</P>
<P>
   But the ecumenical service, attended by close to 1,000 people,
also gave peripheral acquaintances and even strangers a chance to
mark the day they won't forget.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just needed to come by and see everybody,'' said Terri
Brown, one of the first paramedics to respond to the carnage on
July 29, 1999. ``To see (the survivors), it makes me glad to be
doing what I'm doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown and half a dozen other paramedics from American Medical
Response wore their white and blue uniforms to the service. Some
shared hugs with those they saved.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bolaji Odusina went to Sunday's service at the Cathedral of
the Holy Spirit at Chapel Hill to remember a woman she barely knew.
She'd only met Vadewattee Muralidhara, a mother and devout Hindu, a
few times but felt a strong bond.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the brief interval I knew her, she made such a big impact
on my life,'' she said. Odusina, a pediatrician, and Muralidhara's
husband had considered going into practice together. ``She was just
an incredible person.''
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the hour-long service, family members came
forward one-by-one to light 12 candles in front of the pulpit. One
candle for each of Barton's victims, including Barton's wife, Leigh
Ann, and two children, Matthew and Michelle, whom he bludgeoned to
death before the Atlanta shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Barton, who killed himself, was not represented with a candle,
and his name was not mentioned. It didn't need to be. The violence
he loosed on Atlanta was apparent in every message.
</P>
<P>
   From the pulpit, DeKalb CEO Liane Levetan told the mourners,
``We all experienced a sense of shock and uneasiness that something
like this can happen in our home community. . . Feel our
community's arms around you.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Earl Paulk, the church's pastor told families and friends
to let themselves grieve, because ``sometimes survival depends on
our ability to cry.''
</P>
<P>
   He also told them to share their grief with others, find
forgiveness, and love the people still in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Replace negative feelings with positive action,'' Paulk said.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, there was more than just tears. At a reception
following the service, there were also smiles and laughter _ signs
that life continues for families and friends who lost the people
they didn't think they could live without.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is your heart filled up? Mine is,'' said service organizer Dr.
Gulshan Harjee, who's husband, Dean Delawalla, was among the
victims. ``The empty place is full.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
