<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-30 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7595 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-TRADES0731-COX     07-30 0409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-TRADES0731-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rocker rumor shot down
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Baseball moved up today's trading deadline from
midnight to 4 p.m. this year to save general managers from staying
up half the night to monitor deals that never happen.
</P>
<P>
   In that spirit, the game may have gotten a head start on itself.
After Friday's flurry of deals, the deadline is expected to pass
quietly.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a Philadelphia-Anaheim trade involved ex-Braves
outfielder Ron Gant and right-handed pitcher Kent Bottenfield, and
a deal that gave the Cardinals left-handed pitcher Jason
Christiansen, Sunday was subdued. The Braves were involved in the
day's best rumor _ closer John Rocker to Cleveland _ but general
manager John Schuerholz scoffed at the report, reiterating he is
seeking middle infield help or a left-handed hitting outfielder.
</P>
<P>
   And he implied he was not seeking them too hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the acquisition of (starting pitcher) Andy Ashby, we
dealt with the area that we felt we needed to strengthen
ourselves,'' Schuerholz said. ``I felt that was an area we had to
do something. Other than that, there's just a desire to increase
our depth, but not a need to.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Post reported Rocker's trade to the Indians was
imminent, with the Braves given an option of picking one reliever
from Paul Shuey, Steve Karsay or newly-acquired Bob Wickman, even
though Shuey is supposedly unavailable for trade. Indians GM John
Hart, a close Schuerholz friend, denied the story.
</P>
<P>
   After bouts of control problems, Rocker finally appears to have
reclaimed his fastball, walking no one in his last five innings
while recording his first two saves in over a month. While that
might make him marketable, Schuerholz did not sound eager to alter
the mix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our bullpen has regained its strength,'' he said, ``with the
continued improvement of (Kerry) Ligtenberg, the healthy return of
(Mike) Remlinger and the continued improvement of Rocker.''
</P>
<P>
   Gant, batting .254 with 20 homers, moves to his fifth team
because the Angels needed a right-handed alternative to Edgard
Clemente at DH. The Phillies, after dealing Curt Schilling and Andy
Ashby and losing Paul Byrd to injury, were strapped for starters.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals acquired Christiansen from the Pirates in exchange
for minor league infielder Jack Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
