<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-HEBRON-ART-715(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPECTERS OF UNCERTAIN POLITICS AND PALESTINIAN RULE HAUNT JEWISH
SETTLERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) By JOHN F. BURNS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEBRON, West Bank _ With the words of the Old Testament to guide
them, Jewish settlers on the West Bank have never been much
concerned about their image in the world, nor even, for the most
part, how their ways and beliefs are viewed by their fellow
Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Avoiding provocation of their adversaries _ whether
Palestinians, fellow Jews or American peacemakers _ has rarely been
their way.
</P>
<P>
   So when Avi Dobuler strapped his pistol on his waist Sunday and
led a family of American tourists to the marble-topped grave of Dr.
Baruch Goldstein, the settler who massacred 29 Palestinians in a
hail of rifle fire in one of Islam's holiest places of prayer in
February 1994 and who was then shot to death himself, Dobuler was
not minded to be politically correct.
</P>
<P>
   To him, and to many of the 200,000 settlers on the West Bank, it
has mattered little that Israeli and Palestinian negotiators are
moving closer to decisions on the settlements' future.
</P>
<P>
   Although the negotiations faltered last week at Camp David, the
issue that caused the impasse was not so much the settlements as
the future Palestinian role in Jerusalem, about 25 miles north of
here.
</P>
<P>
   On the settlements, according to Israeli, Palestinian and
American versions of the discussions, the two sides moved closer
than ever to agreement, and part of that consensus was that the
7,000 Jews living in and around Hebron, the most explosive of all
the West Bank hot spots, will be among about 40,000 Jewish settlers
who will have to live under Palestinian rule in any final peace
pact.
</P>
<P>
   Dobuler, a 45-year-old settler, came to Israel in 1970 from his
home in New York, and now lives in Beit-El, a settlement near the
West Bank town of Ramallah that may also be marked for eventual
Palestinian rule. To him, the news from Camp David seemed like a
good text for a homily at the grave of Goldstein, whom he called a
good man and a friend, on ``a make-believe peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   The grave and its graveled surroundings, carefully tended by the
settlers, have become a shrine since the massacre in the Tomb of
the Patriarchs, a sacred place for Jews and Muslims that lies close
by the settlement at Qiryat Arba where Goldstein lived and lies
buried.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say we've no right to be here, but the purchase of this
land by Abraham nearly 4,000 years ago is in the Bible,'' Dobuler
said, raising the carefully-annotated Old Testament he carries on
his guided tours.
</P>
<P>
   To David and Nonie Vonnegut-Gabovitch from Indianapolis touring
Israel with their four children, Dobuler's version of the massacre,
and his exculpation of Goldstein, seemed deeply disturbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had I known that the grave was on the itinerary beforehand, I
would have said no,'' said Vonnegut-Gabovitch, a 41-year-old real
estate agent.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the occasion served as a powerful illustration of the
complex and darkening world in which the settlers in places like
Qiryat Arba live as the moment nears when they will have to choose
whether to stay on under eventual Palestinian rule, or accept
whatever compensation a final peace agreement offers for returning
inside the sovereign borders of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   It is a world that may be easy for some outsiders, including
other Israelis, to disparage, but it is also one that, at first
hand, lends a powerful element of poignancy to the settlers'
plight.
</P>
<P>
   In a day spent touring Qiryat Arba, on heights to the east of
Hebron, and the three tiny Jewish communities beleaguered inside
the town itself, the complaint most frequently heard from the
settlers was that outsiders, particularly the news media, have
represented them as out of touch with reality and extremist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is it that people always represent us as some kind of
loonies?'' said David Wilder, the spokesman for the Association for
the Renewal of the Jewish Community in Hebron.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, I'm not crazy, and neither are any of the settlers
living here,'' said Wilder, 46, an immigrant from New Jersey. ``We
are living an ideal. We are not criminals or killers. We came here
to re-establish a Jewish community that existed in Hebron for 2,000
years, and we did so in the face of enormous hostility from our
Palestinian neighbors, and that's no more crazy than somebody who
takes the subway in New York at 11:30 at night.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The other side of the settlers' story, as set out by Wilder and
a dozen other settlers, is one of courage in pursuit of a biblical
vision, of moving into the inhospitable terrain made accessible by
Israeli conquests in the Six Day War of 1967, of building
communities from scratch, of growing large families and deep
attachments to neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in Hebron and perhaps 20 or 30 other settlements that seem
likely to become part of an eventual Palestinian state, the
settlers sense that an Israel that once saw them as pioneers
rejects them as liabilities.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the Camp David talks last week, members of
Prime Minister Ehud Barak's government took few pains to disguise
their readiness to abandon settlements like Qiryat Arba.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the maps put forward, and what this would mean for
the settlements, appeared on the front pages of Israeli newspapers,
and sympathy for the settlers was scant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The settlements are towns of Israelis and not Israeli towns,''
Justice Minister Yossi Beilin told the newspaper Ma'ariv.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``The option that 20 percent of the settlers are going
to have in the end is either to stay there under full Palestinian
sovereignty or accept compensation and leave.''
</P>
<P>
   To the settlers' argument that previous Israeli governments
encouraged them to establish their communities, Beilin replied:
``We aren't dealing with historic justice at present.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak, who faces chronic political problems in winning
acceptance for a peace pact even if his shaky coalition government
survives a no-confidence vote on Monday, is calculating that the
settlements saved would weigh decisively with Israeli opinion,
against those that would be lost.
</P>
<P>
   But to many Israelis, even those who favor the Camp David
proposals, the attempt to anchor settlements that would remain part
of Israel _ perhaps 120 of the 145 settlements, according to Camp
David negotiators _ have a distinctly chimerical, not to mention
expensive, touch.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the settlements are armed encampments on the rocky
hillsides, often close by or even inside the West Bank towns and
villages where more than 1 million Palestinians live.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli settlements would be linked, as now, to the rest of
the country by a spaghetti of ``security roads'' patrolled by
Israeli troops, with each settlement likewise provided with its own
defense units, as well as with secure water and electricity
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs, higher education, and even limited recreation, would
involve a commute to cities like Jerusalem, through territory that,
as today, could remain vulnerable for years, or even decades, to
attack by renegade Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   In Qiryat Arba and the Jewish communities in Hebron, opinions
differed as to whether staying on under Palestinian rule would be
possible.
</P>
<P>
   A 16-year-old high school student, Lital Danon, pausing to eat
an ice-cream at Elitzur's, a bakery and soda fountain that is a
favorite Qiryat Arba meeting place, hailed an approaching stranger:
``Welcome to Zion!'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the Barak plan to hand over Qiryat Arba to a
Palestinian state, she replied briskly: ``It's ugly. It would be
impossible to live with Arabs. But it's also not so easy to find a
place to flee to.''
</P>
<P>
   Dobuler, leading his tour, offered an apocalyptic vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``To stay here would be a death sentence, because the
Palestinians would pick us off one by one,'' he said. Wilder, in
his role as the settlers' spokesman, concurred on the risks, but
said most settlers would remain anyway, doing whatever was
necessary to protect themselves against Palestinian threats.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli paratroopers patrolling Qiryat Arba, within earshot of
the settlers, endorsed the settlers' sense of biblical purpose. But
as soon as the settlers moved away, young conscripts from cities
like Jerusalem and Tel Aviv reverted to the more common view among
Israelis, that the settlers have been living an unsustainable
dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course they'll have to go,'' said a 21-year-old sergeant
who gave his name as Oren. A companion said: ``There's no religious
significance here. They are Jews, like us, and they can live in
Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   In Hebron, the prospects of the settlements surviving a peace
agreement seemed still more improbable. The 600 Jews living in the
city, surrounded by at least 150,000 Palestinians, rely on SWAT
teams of Israeli police and jeep-loads of soldiers on 24-hour
patrols _ together with the men deployed around Qiryat Arba, an
armed force of about 2,500 men, according to published Israeli
accounts _ to protect them.
</P>
<P>
   On one short street divided between Jews and Palestinians, the
Jewish homes are protected with a 60-foot high, street-wide fence
against the stones and firebombs that have occurred in the past.
</P>
<P>
   In these neighborhoods, mentioning Barak invites torrents of
vituperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a traitor through and through,'' said one old woman
tending a flower-box on the windowsill of her home, who declined to
give her name. ``Barak thinks he can play God, but he is not God,
and God will punish him.''
</P>
<P>
   A block away, in the teeming Kazazeen bazaar, Palestinians waved
away talk of the Jewish settlements coming under Palestinian rule,
saying they had little faith that Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian
leader, could deliver on his promises.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jews have treated us like donkeys, not like men,'' said
Amer Zalloum, a 19-year-old tending his father's food stall. ``But
they won't go, anyway. Have you seen Qiryat Arba? It's a city, and
the Jews will never give it up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
