<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-EVANGELISTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DAUGHTER OF GRAHAM IS TO ADDRESS EVANGELISTS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Tenn., Texas, Ga., Calif.)  By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMSTERDAM, Netherlands _ When the Rev. Billy Graham wanted to
call attention to another religious figure not long ago, he took
the relatively rare step among evangelists of singling out a woman:
the second of his three daughters, Anne Graham Lotz.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what he said, that I'm the best preacher in the
family,'' Lotz said in an interview here, where she will be one of
only two women to address a convention on Monday of 10,000
evangelists, overwhelmingly men, being sponsored this week by
Graham's organization. ``I take that as my father's blessing on me,
as my father's blessing on my ministry. And I'm humbled by it, and
very grateful for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lotz, 52, who lives in Raleigh, N.C., does not have the public
profile of her 48-year-old brother, Franklin, the designated
successor to their father as the head of the Billy Graham
Evangelistic Association. But she has gained increasing visibility
among evangelical Christians. She arrived here from England, where
she had been the first woman in at least a century to speak to an
annual Bible conference that draws thousands of British
evangelicals.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of places I go, I'm the first woman,'' she said. ``And I
would pray that they're not inviting me because I'm a woman, but
because of the message I bring.''
</P>
<P>
   The world of evangelical Christianity is geographically broad
and can be ideologically diverse. But there is widespread
resistance to the suggestion that Scripture might allow men and
women an equal religious authority. In June, the Southern Baptist
Convention revised its statement of faith to declare that the Bible
does not permit a woman to serve as senior pastor of a church.
</P>
<P>
   Lotz does not challenge that. ``For myself,'' she said, ``I feel
God has forbidden me to be ordained or be a senior pastor.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she calls herself a Bible teacher, and in that capacity
she can draw a crowd. As the head of a small organization, AnGeL
Ministries (the name incorporates her initials), she began this
year to lead a series of two-day events called ``Just Give Me
Jesus'' in arenas across the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The events are smaller than her father's ``crusades,'' which run
for three or four days each, can draw upward of 100,000 people and
are intended to convert people.
</P>
<P>
   Her events, she said, are intended to inspire born-again
Christians to make a new commitment to their faith. By her
estimate, 25,000 attended the first one, in April in Knoxville,
Tenn. The next month, she spoke in a Fort Worth arena. Events are
also planned this year for cities including Atlanta and San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   The events were at least partly inspired by recent experiences,
she said. During the past two years, a fire destroyed the building
where her husband, Dan, a dentist, had long had his office; her
three children married within eight months; her mother, Ruth
Graham, has been hospitalized several times and undergone hip
replacement surgery; and her father, 81, also has been ailing.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if it was difficult being Billy Graham's daughter, she
said no, and called him the best preacher around. ``It's harder to
be Ruth Graham's daughter,'' Lotz said with a laugh. She listed her
mother's accomplishments: ``A very spiritual, very intellectual''
woman who paints, reads, knows music and talks easily with people.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether she herself is conscious of breaking gender
barriers, Lotz said: ``Oh, sure. But that's not my goal.'' She said
her goal was not to put women in ministry, but rather to ``set a
high standard for presenting Bible teaching. In the end, it
shouldn't matter if it's a man or a woman giving a message.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
