<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-30 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7614 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-PHILLIES-     07-30 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-PHILLIES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON STAYS WITH PARK TOO LONG IN DODGERS LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ When management points the finger at the manager
and questions the strategic style in which games are played, every
move seems to have a little more relevance, either in reality or
just in one's mind.
</P>
<P>
   The moves that work are passed over, the decisions made when a
team wins 10 of 14 aren't questioned. But when a one-run loss is
the subject, look out.
</P>
<P>
   On a hot, sultry East Coast kind of humid day, right-hander Chan
Ho Park may have overstayed his outing by one batter and walked in
the eventual game-winning run in the seventh inning of Sunday's 3-2
Los Angeles Dodgers loss to Philadelphia at Veterans Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   And in the ninth inning, after Dave Hansen led off with a walk
against erratic Phillies right-handed closer Jeff Brantley, manager
Davey Johnson elected to go with left-handed power rather than bunt
over pinch-runner Alex Cora.
</P>
<P>
   Pinch-hitters Chris Donnels and Todd Hundley, both with home run
power, lined out and switch-hitter Devon White was called out on
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   In losing two out of three to the last-place Phillies, the
Dodgers had 17 hits and scored four runs. It came after the Dodgers
had 20 hits and scored 16 runs in a Thursday win at Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Both situations, it seems, are fair game considering the
backdrop that's painted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about bunting him over, but the way we've been
hitting, I said, `I better wish for just one big fly rather than
try to bunch a couple hits to get the lead,' '', Johnson said. ``I
had the right people up. Certainly, I could have bunted him over,
but Brantley's not a threat to throw a double play. He's a fly-ball
guy, and I have some guys who can take it out of the yard.''
</P>
<P>
   The Book of Baseball suggests playing for the win on the road
and a tie at home, but sometimes Johnson doesn't mind throwing that
away and winging it.
</P>
<P>
   This time Johnson stuck to the book.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll play for a tie on the road at times, but not very
often,'' Johnson said. ``If I had some guys that couldn't take
(Brantley) out of the yard right behind him with a man on. ... But
four hits, it's not a lot of offense.''
</P>
<P>
   There's also the issue of Park, weary from an 81-degree day,
though the temperature wasn't reflective of the mugginess brought
on by the suffocating humidity.
</P>
<P>
   Park, who had won two straight, began tiring in the seventh
inning. He allowed a leadoff single to pitcher Randy Wolf, who was
stranded on second with two outs. However, Park (11-8) walked the
next three batters, including Pat Burrell on four pitches with the
bases loaded. Johnson said he wanted to stay with Park because he
pitched well to that point and deserved to be a part of the
outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if I'm tired, it was just mistake pitches,'' said
Park, who threw 12 balls in his final 14 pitches. ``It was hot, but
that's OK. I didn't think I was tired, just missed pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Eric Karros said the heat was the worst it's been
at any point this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get fatigued a little quicker,'' Karros said. ``I was
talking to their first-base coach (Brad Mills) and he said this was
easily the hottest day of the year, and they were fortunate to what
they had weather-wise up to this point. You could see before the
game the heat coming off the dugout.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, when the Dodgers win. everything is nice. But on days
in which they lose close games, contemplation and explanation are
needed especially since Dodgers managing general partner and CEO
Bob Daly and general manager Kevin Malone stated the club needed to
do more of the little things in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Laying down more sacrifice bunts was one of the points
mentioned, though it's obviously subjective and the merits can be
debated case by case.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf, an El Camino Real High of Woodland Hills product, capped a
masterful pitching weekend by the Phillies as the Dodgers lost a
series for the first time in five tries. He allowed four hits and
two runs, both coming on Chad Kreuter's two-run bases loaded single
in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kinds of games here are the ones that sneak up and bite
you on the butt at the end of the year,'' Hundley said.
``Hopefully, these won't. We don't want them. These guys and the
freakin' Marlins, man.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
