<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS DON'T HAVE ENOUGH TO MAKE A DEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ As the minutes until today's 1 p.m. trading
deadline tick down, Los Angeles Dodgers general manager Kevin
Malone is experiencing even more frustration this season than a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Already unable to come up with a starting pitcher the magnitude
of Andy Ashby, Curt Schilling or Denny Neagle because of limited
prospects in the minors, thus having to settle for Ismael Valdes,
the Dodgers are also coming up short in their bid to find a marquee
bench player or a left-hander for the bullpen as the deadline
approaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still talking to people,'' Malone said. ``What's good.
Who are we going to replace? You're looking around to see who you
can replace. There's definitely no position players available.
We're not looking for a starting pitcher. We're always looking to
get something done.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the Dodgers continue to run into the same problem when
Malone tries to engage in serious talks. Either he's told the
Dodgers don't have the firepower to make a huge move, or clubs are
asking for the Dodgers' top prospects at the lower minor-league
levels when the Dodgers inquire about bench help or speed for pinch
running.
</P>
<P>
   That was the case when the Dodgers talked to the Colorado
Rockies about reacquiring right-handed starter Pedro Astacio before
settling on Valdes, baseball sources said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of clubs don't like our prospects,'' Malone said. ``It's
a little frustrating at times when people tell you that you don't
have enough. It's different from last year. We weren't in the same
position (last season) as we are this season.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocket's debut: Valdes, nicknamed ``Rocket,'' makes his debut
five days after being acquired by the Dodgers from the Chicago
Cubs. And while his reputation is that of someone not fighting
through adverse times, which the club roundly criticized him for a
year ago, expectations are high that he'll pitch well, despite a
2-4 mark and 5.37 ERA in 12 starts with the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember him having a lot of bad starts,'' Johnson
said. ``I know he can pitch, and I know circumstances, injuries,
dealing with another club, I know how all those things can affect
your performance. I know he was happy here, and I expect him to
pitch good, not just (today), but from here on in.''
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Playing three games in Philadelphia and three
more in Pittsburgh on artificial turf concerns Johnson some,
particularly the left knee of center fielder Devon White. White has
fluid on the knee, which he doesn't think will be a problem, but
Johnson will watch it closely. However, White, who returned a week
ago after missing 71 games with a partially torn left rotator cuff,
did start the series finale against the Phillies. ... After getting
two hits Saturday, Shawn Green went 0 for 3 with a walk and two
strikeouts and is 4 for 27 (.148) on the road trip.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
