<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUIT-INSURANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENERIC CAR PARTS MAKERS FIGHTING BACK
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill., Calif.)  By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After losing a court battle over replacement parts for damaged
cars last October, State Farm Insurance stopped requiring body
shops to use lower-priced generic car parts. And the companies that
supply these parts went into a tailspin.
</P>
<P>
   Several other big auto insurers, facing their own lawsuits,
followed State Farm's lead, and sales in the $1.5 billion generic
car parts business plunged by 30 percent. Some small suppliers even
went out of business.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the generic parts industry is fighting back.
</P>
<P>
   In a suit filed Thursday in state superior court in Fresno,
Calif., a local company that distributes generic parts statewide
and that is backed by the industry's trade group, the Auto Body
Parts Association, is asking that the Illinois decision against
State Farm be declared invalid in California.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald S. Katz, the lawyer who filed the suit on behalf of the
Fresno company, Collision Parts Network, argues that California law
specifically permits insurers to use generic replacement parts and
that an Illinois court lacks the authority to countermand
California law. He also raises several procedural questions that he
says undermine the class action suit in Illinois, in which State
Farm was ordered to pay a $1.2 billion judgment.
</P>
<P>
   If the California court accepts its argument, the Auto Body
Parts Association says it plans to try to undo the Illinois ruling
in other states.
</P>
<P>
   But Patricia Littleton, one of the lawyers in the original State
Farm case, said she thought there was little chance the challenge
would succeed.
</P>
<P>
   There is no dispute over whether generic parts can be used, she
said; in most states, they can. But in California and most other
states, she said, the generic parts must be of ``like kind and
quality'' to those that are being replaced. The main issue with
State Farm, she said, was that the company had promised in its
policy contracts to meet this standard.
</P>
<P>
   The court and jury decided that the generic parts, sometimes
referred to as aftermarket or OEM _ for original equipment
manufacturer _ parts, were inferior to original factory parts and
that State Farm had breached its contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court in Illinois is not telling the other states what to
do,'' Littleton said. ``It just said that State Farm lied and that
that was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   So the California challenge, sets the stage for a re-run of the
Illinois case and its debate over quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're saying these parts can be as good and that they are as
good and that they often come off the same assembly line as OEM
parts,'' Katz said.
</P>
<P>
   That has been State Farm's contention all along. State Farm says
it uses generic parts because they are indistinguishable from
others, and their lower cost has enabled State Farm to keep
premiums from soaring. A number of consumer advocates, including
Ralph Nader, have sided with State Farm, saying that without
generic parts, the auto manufacturers would have a monopoly on
replacement parts.
</P>
<P>
   The price difference is substantial. Ford charges $192 for a
fender for a 1995 Explorer; the generic fender costs $79. State
Farm and other insurers say that to assemble a 1997 Ford Taurus
from factory spare parts would cost $72,000. The cost of the car
new was $19,000.
</P>
<P>
   To restrain costs, New York, Massachusetts and Hawaii encourage
or require the use of generic parts. But the lawyers suing State
Farm say that, until now, the states have simply assumed high
quality. In fact, the lawyers say, generic parts often do not fit
right and can reduce the appearance, functioning and resale value
of a car.
</P>
<P>
   Littleton and her colleagues in the State Farm case have filed
additional suits on similar grounds against eight other insurers:
Allstate, Safeco, USAA, Liberty Mutual, Geico, Farmers, Progressive
and Country Companies, which has a significant share of the auto
insurance market in Illinois. The lawyers have also filed a second
suit against State Farm to cover customers whose cars were repaired
with generic parts since early 1998, the cut-off date for customers
to be included in the original suit.
</P>
<P>
   State Farm filed papers on an appeal of last October's ruling in
May, said Dave Hurst, a spokesman. The response from the opponents
is due next Friday. The two sides are expected to face off in
Illinois' 5th District Court of Appeals in Mount Vernon, near St.
Louis, in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Until the State Farm decision, said Scot Hansen, the owner of
the generic parts company in whose name the new suit is being
brought, ``business was going gang busters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then,'' he said, ``we began to see a downturn. We had a lot of
calls from body shops asking us to pick up these parts and give
back their money. Some of the insured wanted parts already
installed on their vehicles replaced. Basically, the market
evaporated.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
