<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-30 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7624 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GOP-DIARY-NYT &LR;      07-30 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-DIARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILADELPHIA DIARY: EX-MAYOR HAS DIVIDED LOYALTIES; A LITERAL
SETBACK FOR NEW HAMPSHIRE; HUFFINGTON STAGES A PEP RALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX KUCZYNSKI and MATTHEW PURDY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ed Rendell is trying to wear two hats. Two party hats, that is.
</P>
<P>
   The former Democratic mayor of Philadelphia is the man who
successfully lobbied the Republicans to hold their convention in
his city. He even promised Jim Nicholson, the Republican National
Committee chairman, that he would wear an elephant tie every day of
the convention.
</P>
<P>
   But that was before he was named Democratic National Committee
general chairman last January. So when Rendell appeared with
Nicholson at a panel discussion on convention media coverage at
City Hall on Sunday, he wasn't wearing the tie. But Rendell said he
would put it on for the official beginning of the convention on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he was the ebullient tour guide, plying his guest
with (what else?) Philly cheese steaks. ``This is great!'' he said.
``We want the delegates to have a great time in Philadelphia.''
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean he wants their ticket to win.
</P>
<P>
   Rendell is thrilled to show off his city and his own record as
mayor, since he helped coax Philadelphia back from near-bankruptcy,
guided its Center City building boom and conceived of snagging a
political convention as a coming-out party for his reinvigorated
city.
</P>
<P>
   And it's a bit awkward for him to join in the festivities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm like a guy standing out in the rain, looking through the
window at the party inside,'' Rendell said, after walking into the
lobby of the grand, new Ritz-Carlton Hotel on Saturday night to
find it thick with happy Republicans. Rendell worked the room,
back-slapping bipartisanly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans are more of an affirmation of how far we've
come as a city,'' he said. ``If the Democrats had chosen us, people
would have said it's political.''
</P>
<P>
   An impresario and frustrated caterer, Rendell worked hard to
make it a grand party for the Republicans. He even dreamed up
Political Fest, the expansive, hands-on political exhibit with
everything from a mock Oval Office to a cruise missile, which is
drawing raves here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an A-minus,'' he said. It would have been better if the
Republicans hadn't vetoed a couple of his ideas, the former mayor
said, such as a stage for political comics. ``Too left-wing,'' he
sniffed.
</P>
<P>
   Then he caught himself. ``I don't want to bash the R's,'' he
said. He wants those Republicans to see and spend and spread the
word about the new Philadelphia. Then he wants them to go home and
lose.
</P>
<P>
   A Literal Setback for New Hampshire
</P>
<P>
   Is New Hampshire the Rodney Dangerfield of the Republican
Convention?
</P>
<P>
   You might think the state that hosts the first primary would get
a little respect on the convention-floor seating plan. But New
Hampshire's 24 seats are way at the back and way to the side of the
floor, behind Utah and Arkansas, next to North Dakota, Guam and the
Virgin Islands _ not exactly powerhouses in presidential politics.
</P>
<P>
   Could New Hampshire's faraway seats, _ apparently, one security
guard observed Sunday, not even near the good bathrooms, but the
ones with low-pressure flushing mechanisms _ all because George W.
Bush lost the critical New Hampshire primary to Sen. John McCain?
</P>
<P>
   Tim Fitzpatrick, a spokesman for the convention, said it was not
politics, but real estate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is New Hampshire being punished for voting for McCain?'' he
asked. ``No.'' Can you hear that in the back of the room?
</P>
<P>
   Huffington Stages a Pep Rally
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday morning, Arianna Huffington, all pancake makeup and
dove-gray silk pantsuit, had the air of the high school pep-squad
leader who, with stars in her eyes and a Broadway ditty in her
heart, has decided to string up some lights in the gym and put on a
show starring all of her new best friends.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first day of Huffington's five-day pep rally billed
as the Shadow Convention, which opened its doors Sunday morning at
the University of Pennsylvania's Annenberg Center.
</P>
<P>
   First on the agenda was Sen. John McCain, Huffington's buddy
with the biggest marquee draw _ that is, if you don't include Chuck
D of the rap group Public Enemy, who is scheduled to speak later in
the week. (Rep. Christopher Shays of Connecticut and Jack Kemp both
bowed out over a week ago.) But the senator did not stay to make
small talk with the omnipresent talk-show guest; he rushed grumpily
through the stage door after the audience booed him for endorsing
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Ethan A. Nadelmann, the director of The Lindesmith Center, a New
York drug-policy center financed by the billionaire George Soros,
hobnobbed backstage with Huffington's daughters, ages 9 and 13.
Huffington is passionate about the drug issue; her convention even
placed a two-page ad in last week's edition of The Philadelphia
Weekly, an alternative newspaper, that implied that George W. Bush
used drugs in his younger days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about Bush getting away with doing drugs all those years,
if he did,'' she said. ``The message is that if you're white and do
drugs, you can become president, and if you're black and do drugs,
you go to prison.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's not all that bothers Huffington about Bush. She said,
for example, that Bush has appropriated her theory of
``compassionate conservatism'' _ it's a theme he has mercilessly
pounded on the campaign trail _ and that positively rankles with
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wrote speeches going back to '90, '92 about that very
topic,'' she said. ``In 1993 I gave a speech titled `Can
Conservatism have a Social Conscience?' I mean, I laid out the
concept.''
</P>
<P>
   But enough of weighty matters. It was time for Huffington and Al
Franken, the political comedian, to run lines for their upcoming
speech on political satire. Kozol listened to a few and did not
laugh. Franken tried out a joke about attending a Democratic
fund-raising event in 1996. ``Fifty thousand dollars got you a slow
waltz with Hillary Clinton,'' he said. ``Twenty-five thousand got
you a tango with Tipper Gore.'' Then he reached the punch line,
which was about Janet Reno. Huffington groaned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope there are no feminists in the audience,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the press attention, Huffington still wants more,
said her spokeswoman, Megan Colligan. Colligan gestured to the
green room of Comedy Central's program The Daily Show, which
happens to abut the stage door of Huffington's convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't even get the Daily Show to book us, and they're right
here,'' Colligan said. ``It's so ironic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
