r s BC-GEN-WALL-COLUMN-LADN     07-30 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-WALL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NO ICEBERG, IT'S P'BURGH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When Ismael ``Exxon'' Valdes starts losing his
emotional payload on the mound today in Pittsburgh, his old Dodgers
teammates aren't gonna be real keen on mopping up the Titanic-sized
mess this time.
</P>
<P>
   The reason he was dealt before the season started was to
eliminate a bad vibe from the locker room. Did a half season with
the dead-end Cubs in Wrigley provide him with some magical
intestinal fortitude? Did his dead arm suddenly heal? Did his
blister problem go away?
</P>
<P>
   Look at his record. Gotta doubt that. Otherwise, the Cubs woulda
fought harder to keep him.
</P>
<P>
   The sad thing isn't that the Dodgers were able to reacquire
Valdes this late in the season. No, what's worse is that they can
actually use him in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   It was either him or a return of Fernando. ...
</P>
<P>
   --What would each team have to lose today if the Yankees sent
David Cone to the Dodgers for Carlos Perez? ...
</P>
<P>
   --And ya know, Jack McDowell hasn't officially retired. ...
</P>
<P>
   --And if they knew the Angels were gonna just give away Kent
Bottenfield. ....
</P>
<P>
   --Enlightening information in the August issue of GQ. Not from
the cover story on Anna ``Don't Call Me Lolita'' Kournikova, which
that quote is never mentioned in the vapid three-page story.
</P>
<P>
   It's Dodgers first baseman Eric Karros, revealing in a ``Why I
Wear What I Wear'' feature that his clothier is named Alex
Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Good karma. ...
</P>
<P>
   --ARod, by the way, just turned a quarter of a century. ...
