<HEADLINE>
THESE LINKS MAY STINK, BUT FARMER HAS NET ON HIS SIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ What business does a Web site called
www.pigfarmer.com have in a sports section?
</P>
<P>
   Those who golf in Stuart, Fla., know.
</P>
<P>
   A course development company is in the middle of litigation
against Paul Thompson, whose 200-head pig farm borders the Florida
Club layout.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1957, Thompson has been farming his land. And since the
mid- '70s, he's been playing country music loudly because he claims
his pigs like hearing it while they eat, and that makes them
fatter.
</P>
<P>
   And when golfers hear the music, they get frazzled.
</P>
<P>
   In the suit, according to the Reuters news service, the farmer's
choice of songs, along with the ``malodorous nature'' of his
business, is hurting the development company's multimillion
investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you built a house next to a railroad track, would you
expect the trains to stop coming?'' asked Thompson. ``This is
farmland.''
</P>
<P>
   So getting back to the Web site - it's something Thompson has
posted to help set up a legal defense fund.
</P>
<P>
   --The domain name as well as the entire inventory for
SportsPlayBooks.com is up for auction on ebay.com.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas-based company caused a wave of fear when it began
selling old playbooks from college and pro football teams. All it
was trying to do, the Web operators said, was allow high school
coaches a chance to try formations and such that others have used.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 playbooks are part of the sale, which is item
number 394765821 on ebay. Bidding, which started at $100, ends next
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   --An auction with the starting bid of $2,500 for the chance to
be a ballboy or ballgirl at Magic Johnson's All-Star Charity
Basketball Game on Sunday at Pauley Pavilion is taking place on
ebay, through the Athletes Direct.com Web site. Two packages are
available, and they come with two VIP seats and a ball autographed
by Magic. Proceeds go to the Magic Johnson Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   --Major League Baseball has finally secured the Internet domain
www.mlb.com, and should relaunch under the name in the next few
months. The name had been owned by the law firm of Morgan, Lewis
and Bockius.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
