<HEADER>
A7630 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-GREECE-TREASURE-NYT     07-30 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREECE-TREASURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN GREECE, `PHANTOM' TALE OF TREASURE HIDDEN BY NAZI SETS OFF A
HUNT 
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Greece _ After months of dispute and delays, Greek and
French divers are hoping to plunge this week into nearly 300 feet
of water off the southwest Peloponnese, near Kalamata, on an
expedition to salvage what they believe to be a $2 billion fortune
consisting of 50 sealed chests full of gold coins and jewels
hoarded by a Nazi officer.
</P>
<P>
   The wealth was reputedly stripped from Jews sent to labor and
death camps, then stashed at a secret underwater location by the
notorious Nazi, Max Merten, who served as Hitler's senior
administrator in Salonika, in northern Greece, during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   But even before a single ounce of gold has been raised, the
prospect of such a fortune has set Greece's famous bureaucracy in
motion and sent a long line of claimants jostling for their stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation is crazy,'' said Gregoire Koulbanis, the
40-year-old Swiss diver of Greek descent who is to lead and film
the expedition. ``Such chaos, delays and state of hysteria, I've
never witnessed in my 20-year career.''
</P>
<P>
   Koulbanis, who gained fame heading some of the most daring
expeditions of the late oceanographer Jacques-Yves Cousteau, says
he was told of the treasure 10 months ago by a 63-year-old man he
refuses to name but whom the Greek media have dubbed ``Phantom X.''
</P>
<P>
   The man, who is currently serving prison time for a string of
felonies, says that he first learned of the treasure when he shared
a Greek prison cell with Merten in 1958. The former Nazi officer
fled to Germany after World War II, but returned to Greece that
year supposedly to check up on his fortune. He was arrested, tried
for war crimes and jailed in Athens, according to the Greek Foreign
Ministry and the Central Jewish Council, which represents this
country's 3,000 Jews.
</P>
<P>
   The informant claims that Merten confessed to stowing 50 cases
of gold he intended to retrieve after the war, which a Nazi
submarine ferried from northern Greece to the southern Peloponnese.
From there, Merten commissioned a fishing boat named ``Sofia'' to
carry the cases to a designated site and sank the vessel.
</P>
<P>
   A presidential decree in 1959 allowed Merten to return to
Germany, where he practiced law and died in 1976. It is unclear if
he ever tried to retrieve the treasure.
</P>
<P>
   The current expedition, which was supposed to take place over
the weekend, is now scheduled for Friday after being put off by
local officials in Kalamata, who said that the summer holiday
season had left them short-handed to oversee a multi-million-dollar
search by 30 divers and crew members.
</P>
<P>
   Koulbanis, the head of the expedition, attributes the delays to
``outrageous demands'' by the local authorities and a marsh of
bureaucracy, despite having gained approval for the dive from
Foreign Minister George Papandreou earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   The Kalamata authorities say they want extra assurances that the
state will get the 50 percent share it has claimed if the fortune
is found. Kalamata authorities are demanding that a special state
committee climb aboard the search vessel to monitor every inch of
the dive by video-link from the deep.
</P>
<P>
   They also want a fleet of coast guard vessels to be placed on
alert, a team of archaeologists ready to appraise the fortune,
which is to be handled by Greek divers only, and a host of finance
ministry experts to store whatever is recovered in special vaults
at the National Bank of Greece. Since the operation may sweep
through a strategic military shooting range, Greek Air Force units
will also be at the ready.
</P>
<P>
   Holocaust survivors argue that at least a portion of the
treasure is rightfully theirs, particularly since much of it
appears to have been taken from the families of some 9,000 Jews who
were later rounded up under Merten to work at Nazi labor camps in
Greece.
</P>
<P>
   ``I alone had to pay him 1,000 gold British Sterling in hope of
winning my father's release from one of those camps,'' said Andreas
Sefihas, a Holocaust survivor and president of the Jewish Council
in Salonika, where 50,000 Jews _ 95 percent of the city's Jewish
community _ eventually perished in Nazi death camps.
</P>
<P>
   But the Greek state's claim may leave Greece's 1,950 living
Holocaust survivors with less than a 25 percent share, with the
remaining 25 percent going to the man who says he knows where the
treasure can be found. Their agreement was negotiated by the
informant's lawyer, Alexandros Lykourezos, the country's star
criminal attorney whose clients have also included the most
notorious men wanted for war crimes in Bosnia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
