<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: LISTENING TO WOMEN'S VOICES
</HEADLINE>
  By BOB HERBERT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom says most Americans are happy in these best
of economic times. Jobs are plentiful. Wages are increasing.
Inflation is low. And even the traditionally hard-core unemployed
are finding work.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone is happy. And a lot of those who are unhappy
are women.
</P>
<P>
   A nationwide series of focus groups conducted jointly by leading
Democratic and Republican pollsters largely contradicts
conventional wisdom and could change the way the presidential race
is viewed.
</P>
<P>
   The focus groups show that ``women are largely pessimistic about
the present state of the nation,'' and, to a surprising degree,
feel they are not benefiting significantly from the improved
economy. They feel they are working longer and longer hours just to
make ends meet, and that the increasing demands of work leave them
less and less time to spend with their families.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the focus group participants expressed deep
concern over the moral direction of the country, and what they
perceived as the absence of a solid sense of values being passed on
to the nation's children.
</P>
<P>
   The economy may be breaking statistical records, but it has not
been able to offset this deep discontent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think women are asking, `What if this is as good as it
gets?''' said Celinda Lake, a prominent Democratic pollster who is
surveying U.S. women in the joint project with Republican pollster
Linda DiVall.
</P>
<P>
   From coast to coast, at gatherings of women from widely varied
backgrounds, the focus group leaders heard heartfelt and poignant
expressions of frustration, disappointment and even discouragement.
</P>
<P>
   A common theme was that while there certainly were big winners
in the booming economy, there were many more ordinary families that
were working hard but barely holding on from week to week.
</P>
<P>
   A detailed report on the focus groups said women were worried
about their children growing up in environments that are entirely
different from their own backgrounds. It said: ``With the rise of
single parent and dual income households, they are concerned about
children's lack of guidance and their loss of appropriate role
models. With parents busy meeting financial demands, participants
believe children have few sources from which to learn family values
or a sense of morality besides from television and the streets.''
</P>
<P>
   Lake and DiVall organized the focus groups and are conducting a
series of nonpartisan national polls to determine _ as the election
season unfolds _ what issues are of most concern to women. The
project is called ``Women's Voices 2000'' and is sponsored by the
Center for Policy Alternatives, a nonpartisan public policy group,
and Lifetime Television, a cable network that bills itself as
``Television for Women.''
</P>
<P>
   The report on the focus groups will be released Tuesday at a
press briefing in Philadelphia, where the Republican National
Convention is being held. ``We're hoping the candidates see this as
a wake-up call,'' said Carole Black, president and chief executive
of Lifetime. ``They need to hear what women are saying.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most heart-wrenching comments at the focus groups
came from African-American women. They shared the concerns of other
participants, but also spoke movingly about the personal impact of
violence and deteriorating values, and their very real fear that
their children _ their sons, especially _ might not even survive
adolescence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very sobering and very depressing,'' said DiVall. ``A
lot of them feel they are doing absolutely the best they can to
protect their kids, but it's the outside environment that is
pressing in on them and they feel they have no control over it.''
</P>
<P>
   Politicians have tended to argue economic issues and values
issues as if they were separate categories that could be addressed
independently. But the women who participated in the focus groups
seemed to be saying that economic pressures made it more difficult
for their families to deal with the many outside influences shaping
the values of their children.
</P>
<P>
   The interrelationship of values and the economy is a difficult
theme for politicians to articulate. But it is close to the core of
the real world of working Americans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
