<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-30 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7635 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     07-30 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VISITING THE WORLD OF COLLECTIBLES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The erratic nature of today's stock market has nothing on the
world of sports collectibles.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of slow-growth, always-valuable collectibles,
like anything autographed by Babe Ruth, that rival the security of
Coca-Cola stock or mutual funds. There are several hobby niches
that ebb-and-flow like tech stocks. And there is plenty of what one
might call the junk bonds of collecting, which is 90 percent of
everything produced in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   The 21st National Sportscard Collectors Convention came and went
this weekend at the Anaheim Convention Center, and all of those
trends were as obvious as the fragile nature of an Internet IPO.
</P>
<P>
   Coming off the 1999 convention in Atlanta, which was considered
a disaster, most dealers and collectors left L.A. content. Those
dealers asked about their long weekend in Anaheim graded the show
from fair- to-good. Business was better than expected on Thursday
and Friday and disappointing on Saturday, usually the busiest day.
No official attendance mark was available, but estimates ranged
around 20,000 for the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   From at least one hobby perspective, things were encouraging. If
the show was any kind of indicator, today's collectors are more
savvy than ever. There weren't a lot of looky-loos walking the
floor, which was the case nine years ago, when the 1991 convention
in Anaheim was hit with a tidal wave of collectors salivating for
free promotional handouts.
</P>
<P>
   Collectors this year seemed to know exactly what they wanted,
and with only a few exceptions, there was plenty of everything to
meet their needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a good show,'' said Phil Panacci of Chino, a
collector/dealer of vintage publications and tickets. ``I know a
few dealers weren't very happy, but if you talk to people and are
willing to negotiate, there was plenty of business here.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the trends, based on personal collecting experience and
feedback from dealers and collectors:
</P>
<P>
   High-end memorabilia remains the most coveted of items, the true
investment-quality material in the hobby, and more collectors
seemed willing to pay the money to make it theirs.
</P>
<P>
   Some prices were steep, but that's a reflection of last year's
Barry Halper auction, which put a lot of terrific material on the
market. But when one trading card sells for $1.27 million (the
recent sale price of a Honus Wagner tobacco card), then paying
$2,000 or more for something signed by Ruth, Ty Cobb or Lou Gehrig
looks like a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in memorabilia in general is up, as collectors turn to
tickets, game-used jerseys, old contracts, and other items of
vintage at a time when there is no shortage of trading cards.
</P>
<P>
   The graded card phenomenon -- the process of a third party
company grading cards on a 1-to-10 scale, thereby placing a premium
on flawless cards (a 10) -- has hit a crucial turning point. There
was no shortage of graded cards available, but there was a shortage
of buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Those who did buy were only focused on cards with legs, older
tobacco cards in short supply, boomer favorites like Mickey Mantle,
and rookie cards of modern stars. By Sunday, many dealers were
blowing out cards graded 7 and 8 and higher-graded commons.
</P>
<P>
   Two disappointing spinoffs of graded cards were dealers who
tried to get graded card prices for cards that hadn't been graded,
and those who overpriced lesser condition cards.
</P>
<P>
   Many dealers were also trying to get 70-to-80 percent of ``book
value'' (Beckett price guides) for modern cards when half-book is
standard at the twice-weekly warehouse show in Walnut. But as one
dealer noted, the cost of buying a table and flying inventory west
made some stubborn when it came to pricing.
</P>
<P>
   Baby boomers will be happy to know there is no shortage of cards
from their adolescent years. Every third table appeared to have
binders or stacks of cards from the '50s, '60s and '70s. Complete
sets were available in all price and condition ranges.
</P>
<P>
   Set collectors from the '90s are simply out of luck. Singles are
not available because the cost for dealers to crack boxes is
prohibitive and outweighs the demand. Except for rookie cards and
the aforementioned lottery cards, the market for current cards is
softer than yogurt, and even some of the lottery cards weren't
moving. One dealer with memorabilia cards featuring cut autographs
of Walter Johnson, Cy Young, Ruth, Gehrig and others still had them
in his case as of Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball cards still swing the biggest stick. Football and
basketball cards are stagnating. While the number of hockey card
collectors is even smaller, they're much more passionate. And
one-time non-sport titan Pokemon is dead.
</P>
<P>
   Business was brisk at the autograph booths. More than a dozen
Hall of Famers (Reggie Jackson) and local heroes (John Wooden)
signed for fees ranging from $10 to $50. If visitors were bummed by
the prices, they weren't saying so.
</P>
<P>
   And despite negative publicity about the veracity of autographed
material, there was plenty of it available. It was surprising to
see so many vendors with autographed baseball cards, a
traditionally low-interest item. The payoff here for the discreet
collector may be lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   All of the major card companies, distributors and dealers were
advertising their websites, gearing up for the biggest change in
the hobby. The buying, selling, promoting and auctioning of cards
and memorabilia on the Internet is seen as a must-do for everyone
involved.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that many collectors and dealers make use of the
Internet -- sports items are one of eBay's strongest areas -- is
more proof that the hobby has legs. The 2000 National may not have
attracted as many bodies as the 1991 National, but the ones it did
appear smarter, and that's not a bad thing. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-00 2136EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
