<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-VOTE-770(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENEZUELAN VOTE IS SEEN AS VICTORY FOR PRESIDENT
</HEADLINE>
  By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela _ Rallying to President Hugo Chavez's call
for radical social and political change, Venezuelans Sunday granted
the former paratrooper a new six-year term with enhanced powers,
top officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez has promised to use his time in power to sweep away the
last remnants of the traditional political order in this nation of
23 million people that in recent years has been the United States'
top oil supplier.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after the polls were supposed to close, there were no
official results. However, both the head of the outgoing
legislature and the interior minister, Luis Davila, said on
national television that preliminary official results showed that
Chavez had won handily. Voter surveys posted by the the newspaper
El Nacional gave Chavez as much as a 20-point margin over his main
challenger, Francisco Arias Cardenas.
</P>
<P>
   In the past 18 months, Venezuela's poor, disillusioned by
decades of corrupt and unresponsive government, have united around
Chavez and his plan for a complete overhaul of society.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a day of revolution,'' Chavez, 46, who in 1992 led an
unsuccessful military coup attempt, said after casting his ballot
Sunday morning at a suburban polling station. ``Today a new
republic is being born.''
</P>
<P>
   The ease with which Chavez will be able to implement his
revolution, however, depends on the outcome of races to elect 165
members of congress and 23 state governors. Results of those races
were expected only later in the evening or early Monday. Supporters
of the president are expected to win a majority of the posts, but
polls indicate that Chavez may fall short of the two-thirds
majority he needs in the National Assembly in order to govern
without constraints.
</P>
<P>
   The vote Sunday was the culmination of a contentious process of
sweeping political change that began with Chavez's landslide
victory in a December 1998 presidential vote. As a candidate, he
promised voters a ``peaceful social revolution'' if elected, but
also said he would need a new constitution with expanded powers in
order to carry out the transformation the country needed.
</P>
<P>
   In three elections last year, a constitutional assembly was
first convoked and next selected and then finally submitted a new
charter to voters for approval in December. As a result, Chavez's
term of office was expanded from five to six years, and a ban on
sitting presidents seeking immediate re-election for one more term
was removed _ creating the possibility that Chavez could remain in
office until 2013.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the changes were approved, though, the Congress,
dominated by discredited opposition parties, and the Supreme Court
were eliminated and replaced by weakened entities that have proven
subservient to Chavez and his leftist Patriotic Pole coalition. The
authority of governors and mayors was also reduced, the role of the
armed forces was vastly expanded and a Chavez loyalist placed in
charge of the powerful state oil company after it was purged.
</P>
<P>
   With the new constitution in hand, Chavez called a vote to elect
a new unicameral congress, as well as governors, mayors and state
and municipal legislators, a total of more than 6,200 elected
posts. In what he described as an attempt to ``relegitimize'' his
own rule, he also submitted the presidency to a new vote,
anticipating no real challenge to his popularity.
</P>
<P>
   But in February, Cardenas, a former army colonel who was
Chavez's second-in-command during the 1992 coup and spent two years
in jail with him afterward, broke with the president and announced
his own candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez, he charged, was assuming dictatorial powers, tolerating
the corruption he had pledged to eradicate, alienating the United
States and forging an undesirable alliance with President Fidel
Castro of Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual last-minute incursion into the campaign, Castro
invited a group of Venezuelan journalists to Cuba on Saturday and
issued a ringing endorsement of Chavez, wishing him ``good luck and
lots of votes'' during a rambling news conference that was
televised live here. ``Hugo, I am sure that nothing or no one can
hold you back,'' the Cuban leader said.
</P>
<P>
   Castro's remarks, which appeared to violate a ban on politicking
here after the formal close of the campaign, came days after a man
turned up claiming to be a Cuban intelligence agent and said that
Castro had sent 1,500 operatives here to infiltrate the Venezuelan
government. As the news conference was taking place, Chavez called
Castro, and the two men discussed baseball before ridiculing the
accusations of a Cuban spy network operating here.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   Since taking office 18 months ago, Chavez has consistently
praised Castro and the Cuban Revolution while attacking his
domestic critics as ``a rancid oligarchy'' and pursuing a
nationalist and populist political line. The resulting polarization
of Venezuelan society, with the poor overwhelmingly lining up
behind Chavez and the middle class reluctantly supporting Arias,
was once again on display during Sunday's balloting.
</P>
<P>
   One of Chavez's strongholds here is a working-class neighborhood
called 23 de Enero, the site of a popular uprising in which
hundreds of people died in 1989, after the government raised
gasoline prices. The area voted heavily for Chavez in 1998, and
appeared Sunday to have rallied to his side again, with scarcely a
supporter of Arias to be found during interviews with voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Venezuela has awakened, and we will never let ourselves be
fooled again,'' said Julia de Tirado, 61, who described Chavez as
the antidote to 40 years of corruption and misgovernment under a
pair of traditional parties. She praised him for being ``honest and
hard-working'' and said that ``if he were not our president, things
would be disastrous.''
</P>
<P>
   Estelita Colmenares, a social worker, added that while her hopes
that ``this country will move ahead and become prosperous,'' have
yet to be realized, she continues to have faith in Chavez and his
government. ``At least they are listening to us, and not belittling
us,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But across town, at a polling place at a private high school in
the middle-class neighborhood of Chacao, a woman conducting an exit
poll for a local firm said Arias appeared to have a 2-1 advantage
over Chavez. Among the the most vociferous of those voting against
the president was Irma Galindo de Baez, 50, who was wearing a
button that proclaimed ``throw the crazy man out.''
</P>
<P>
   Baez said she voted for Chavez in 1998 because ``Venezuela
needed a change _ it couldn't go on with the dictatorship of the
political parties.'' But ``this government has been a disaster,''
she said. ``This guy has really scared us'' with his incendiary
language, ``there has been a lot of corruption,'' and the police
have allowed a farm owned by her family to be seized by peasants.
</P>
<P>
   A 48-year-old engineer who declined to give his name faulted
Chavez for the deep recession Venezuela has been experiencing
despite record high prices for its oil. ``If you build a house or
shopping center, who is there to sell it to?'' he complained,
adding that the country would be better of if Chavez were ``not
fighting all the time with everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavez himself voted early, thanked Venezuelans for choosing ``a
new horizon, a new path,'' and then spent several hours playing
baseball. Later, though, he met with his economic team to draw up
what he described as ``measures of great impact for the first 100
days of the new government.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
