<HEADLINE>
JONES PUTS FINISHING TOUCH ON TRAMMELL'S MAGIC MOMENT
</HEADLINE>
  By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bobby J. Jones' final pitch of the game looked so
tantalizing, leaving his sweaty fingers and floating to the plate
as if it were a Frisbee. Fernando Tatis might as well have been a
character in a Bugs Bunny cartoon since he could have waved his bat
once and then twice as he waited for the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually it reached him, and Tatis swung mightily and missed.
The pitch was a curveball, and the scoreboard said it had traveled
65 mph.
</P>
<P>
   But Jones is that kind of baffling pitcher, someone who can toy
with hitters when he is at his most effective. Jones, who had a
stint in the minor leagues last month, tossed a complete game, and
Bubba Trammell did a splendid imitation of Mike Bordick by smashing
a three-run homer in his first at-bat with the New York Mets to
guide them past the St. Louis Cardinals, 4-2, Sunday at Shea
Stadium for their sixth straight victory.
</P>
<P>
   Jones struck out nine, including Jim Edmonds three times, walked
one and gave up four hits.
</P>
<P>
   Trammell heard New Yorkers chant: ``Bub-ba! Bub-ba!'' for the
first time. ``Sure, it's special,'' Jones said. ``I'm just glad I
showed them the good Bobby Jones and not the early on, struggling
Bobby Jones.''
</P>
<P>
   Trammell, who played right field while Derek Bell rested, joined
the party a day later than Bordick and Rick White, and earned the
first curtain call of his Mets career in the second.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' Benny Agbayani led off the first with a homer off
Garrett Stephenson , but it was quickly overshadowed by what
happened in the bottom of the second. With runners on first and
second, Trammell became the seventh Met to homer in his first
at-bat in the team's 39-year history and the second in two days.
</P>
<P>
   After Trammell rounded the bases, he gave high-fives to everyone
in the dugout except Bordick. The two new players, owners of homers
in their first at-bats with the Mets only 24 hours apart, hugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew what each other was thinking,'' Trammell said.
</P>
<P>
   When Valentine was asked the odds of what Bordick and Trammell
had achieved, he said: ``Kind of like getting in early on an IPO.
Immediate returns. It's great.''
</P>
<P>
   With a 4-0 lead, Jones avoided a speed bump in the fifth, gave
up one run in the sixth and then stifled the Cardinals until Ray
Lankford homered with two outs in the ninth. That merely gave him
the chance to mesmerize Tatis one final time. Jones threw the
fluttering 65-mph curveball, Tatis missed it and the Mets had one
more important moment in this evolving season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long time,'' Jones said, ``since I got the last
out in a game.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
