<HEADLINE>
CONVENTION PROTESTERS TAKE TO THE STREETS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LISA TEACHEY 
and LETITIA STEIN 
c.2000 HOUSTON CHRONICLE 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ As thousands of protesters took to the streets
here Sunday the only real confrontation was among themselves,
despite concerns that police might use force to keep demonstrators
at bay during the Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, throughout the day of scheduled and unscheduled
protests, it seemed as if the Philadelphia police were going out of
their way to accommodate the participants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Sunday, there isn't much traffic,'' said Philadelphia
Police Commissioner John Timoney.
</P>
<P>
   Timoney quickly added that officers may not be so accommodating
Monday, the official start of the convention when an unpermitted
group plans to march down a busy street to the convention site.
</P>
<P>
   During Sunday's demonstrations, police allowed a last-minute
march by abortion rights advocates along a line of anti-abortion
picketers stretched over five blocks in the city's museum district,
miles from convention site at the First Union Center.
</P>
<P>
   That led to the minor confrontation between protesters.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of officers stood guard as the abortion rights group
protesters marched up and down the street taunting their
counterparts. They yelled, pointed and ripped placards from the
anti-abortion group's hands.
</P>
<P>
   Most in the anti-abortion line stood silently as verbal assaults
were hurled at them. Some prayed aloud when a few in the abortion
rights group yelled ``Keep your rosaries off my ovaries.''
</P>
<P>
   A few anti-abortion activists shouted back ``murderer'' as the
taunting group yelled at them nose-to-nose.
</P>
<P>
   Later there was a brief standoff between anti-police
demonstrators and about 40 uniformed officers wielding batons, but
after only minutes the officers turned and walked away.
</P>
<P>
   Police spokesman David Yarnell said the show of batons was not
meant to engage the protesters, only to warn that officers were
moving in.
</P>
<P>
   It was not until later that officers appeared wearing full riot
gear to reinforce police lines as the protesters left the police
station.
</P>
<P>
   These demonstrators did not have a permit, either. Earlier they
had been part of a massive peaceful march in a day when several
hundred groups _ including environmentalists, anti-death penalty
advocates, anarchists, anti-war groups, health care advocates _
gathered as Unity 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Timoney estimated as many as 5,000 people took part in the march
and carnival-like rally afterward. But event organizer Leon Oboler
said park officials estimated as many as 25,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just so exciting to be a part of these people who are not
rich Republicans,'' said Cindy Beringer who drove from Austin,
Texas, to march Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Beringer, who opposes the death penalty, carried a life-size
cardboard picture of Gov. George W. Bush holding a gun. A card
pasted on the front read ``Stop me before I kill again,'' in
reference to the number of executions in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Vaught, part of the Austin group planning to drive back
Sunday and Monday, said the long trip was worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want Bush to know that we're willing to come all the way to
Philadelphia to let him know we want a moratorium on the death
penalty,'' Vaught said.
</P>
<P>
   The marchers converged on a cordoned off block where vendors
hawked Philly cheesesteaks, pretzels and plenty of bottled water.
Those at the rally listened to speeches and music during the
daylong event that seemed more like a festival.
</P>
<P>
   Teen-age protesters danced around a wagon, drumming on empty
water coolers and tin pans. Aboard a float designed to look like a
missile, anti-nuclear weapon protesters hosted a mudwrestling
match-up featuring actors wearing caricatures masks of Republican
presidential candidate Bush and Democratic rival Vice President Al
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrators with the Revolutionary Communist Youth Brigade
burned an American flag.
</P>
<P>
   A group of about a dozen libertarians showed up to counter
protest the Unity 2000 march. To the other groups demands for
government-sponsored health care and stricter gun control laws, the
libertarian protesters shouted back, ``Government is evil'' and
chanted for ``More guns, less people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to show that not all young people are anti-corporation
and anti-trade,'' said Rhys Southan, a student at the University of
Texas in Austin here for the counterprotest.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
