<HEADER>
A7651 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GOP-SHADOW-HNS &LR;      07-30 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-SHADOW-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
McCAIN GREETED BY HOSTILE REACTION FOR SUPPORTING BUSH 
 
By BENNETT ROTH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ John McCain drew choruses of boos and hisses
Sunday when he tried to play loyal supporter to his former
Republican presidential opponent, Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The hostile reactions came from groups of McCain supporters and
political activists who were drawn to the Arizona senator's push
for government reform, both in Congress and during his spirited
campaign for the GOP nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need every one of you to give (Bush's) campaign the same
amount of enthusiasm and participation you did for our primary
campaign,'' McCain said during a meeting with his convention
delegates.
</P>
<P>
   When he said he was releasing them to support Bush, some
delegates applauded. Others booed or cried out: ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain was confronted by an even more hostile reaction earlier
when he praised Bush during a speech before the so-called Shadow
Convention, a gathering organized to air topics _ like campaign
finance reform _ that are likely to go unmentioned during this
week's GOP convention.
</P>
<P>
   On the agenda for the alternative convention were a wide range
of issues, including global warming, campaign finance reform, and
American Indian rights.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd responded enthusiastically and uniformly when McCain
spoke of change but was divided in its reaction when he launched
into a defense of Bush's bid for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am obliged not by party loyalty but by sincere conviction to
urge all Americans to support my party's nominee, Gov. George
Bush,'' McCain said. He tried to continue but was drowned out by a
mixture of applause and loud boos.
</P>
<P>
   When McCain said he agreed with Bush on such issues as repairing
a flawed education system and reforming Social Security, several in
the audience started laughing and jeering.
</P>
<P>
   And as the senator praised Bush for challenging his opponent to
run a positive campaign, he was heckled by some in the crowd who
claimed he supported moving a Navajo tribe off their land to make
way for coal mining operation. Some protesters yelled: ``Save Black
Mesa.''
</P>
<P>
   Visibly annoyed, McCain told the crowd: ``If you'd like, I do
not need to continue.''
</P>
<P>
   At that point, convention sponsor Arianna Huffington walked onto
the stage, urged an end to the heckling and reminded the audience
of the forum's purpose. ``You know this is the convention where we
can hear everything with respect,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain returned to the microphone and toward the end of his
address appeared to win over the crowd when he returned to the
issue of campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the beneficiaries of a campaign finance system that is
nothing more than an elaborate influence-peddling scheme in which
both parties conspire to stay in office by selling the country to
the highest bidder,'' he said, eliciting applause.
</P>
<P>
   The day's events underscored the difficult balancing act McCain
has been trying to perform by claiming to be both a loyal
conservative Republican and a reformer who appeals to independent
voters.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's announcement later that he was releasing his more than
200 delegates to support Bush, a move that was largely symbolic,
was an emotional moment for the former candidate and his most
committed supporters.
</P>
<P>
   McCain told the crowd that they had waged the ``good fight'' and
that the primary race had made ``Gov. Bush a better candidate.''
When McCain, a former Vietnam War hero, tried to thank the
delegates he choked up, eliciting loud cheers and applause.
</P>
<P>
   As a sign that the Bush and McCain campaigns had been working to
overcome lingering anomosities from the hard fought primary
campaign, top Bush campaign officials were on hand for McCain's
release of delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Don Evans, Bush's campaign chairman, called McCain ``a true
American hero.''
</P>
<P>
   But not all McCain supporters and aides were as willing to put
aside their anger. As Bush officials heaped praise on McCain, one
of the senator's aides walked past reporters and muttered loudly:
``I think I'm going to throw up.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorardeynne Drozdowski, one of McCain's alternate delegates from
Michigan, said she still may cast her vote during the convention
for McCain. ``He's a candidate who represented my beliefs and
philosophies,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Larrivee, a delegate from Massachusetts, said he would
``go for Bush, but not because I really want to. I think the
country would be better off with McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   While some Republican delegates will grudgingly support Bush,
Marshall Witmann, an analyst at the conservative Heritage
Foundation, said the Texas governor will have a harder time winning
over the former McCain supporters who are unaffiliated with either
party.
</P>
<P>
   ``This deal with the independent voters will not be closed until
November,'' said Wittman, who served as a McCain adviser during the
primary election season.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
