<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-30 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7652 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-TWINS-NYT &LR;      07-30 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TWINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'NEILL AND YANKS FLASH OLD FORM AGAINST TWINS
</HEADLINE>
  By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Every time Paul O'Neill tries to beat out an
infield hit, he gradually slows after crossing the first-base bag,
stops, bends at the knees and then shakes out his legs, as if he
wants to make sure all his parts are still in working order.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the very few signs that O'Neill is 37 years old.
It is impossible to tell by his production: He had three hits and
three runs batted in Sunday, increasing his batting average to
.307, as the Yankees beat Minnesota, 7-4, and completed a road trip
in which they won 5 of 7 games.
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Tino Martinez drove in three runs Sunday with a
first-inning double, staking Andy Pettitte (11-6) to a 4-0 lead.
Chuck Knoblauch, hampered by a sore elbow, returned to the lineup
and collected two hits and two walks, scoring two runs.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have won 18 of their last 26 games, aided by the
additions of Denny Neagle, David Justice, Glenallen Hill and Jose
Vizcaino. They will probably add more players before Monday's 4
p.m. trade deadline, if one of two major proposals involving the
San Diego Padres goes through. ``Coming into this road trip, you
got the feeling everything was starting to come together,'' O'Neill
said.
</P>
<P>
   He has 120 hits and 72 RBI after 100 games, which puts him on a
pace to finish the year with 194 hits _ that would represent a
career high _ and 117 RBI, a total that would match his career
high. He had 12 hits in 26 at-bats on the road trip and 12 RBI,
driving in a run in the first, fourth and sixth innings today.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is so solid,'' Joe Torre, the Yankees' manager, said. ``He
is right now really having good plate coverage. He's really hitting
the ball sharply; he's knocked in a lot of runs on this trip. I
think he'll hit until he decides to quit.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill spoke vaguely of retirement last season, suggesting at
one point that he might quit before the 2000 season. This spring,
O'Neill said he would evaluate that option from year to year. His
current contract expires at the end of this season. Perhaps,
O'Neill said wistfully, he could play with the Cincinnati Reds in
2001, if the Yankees were not interested in keeping him.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees are expected to approach O'Neill about a
contract extension in the next two months. Brian Cashman, the
Yankees' general manager, would not address the question of the
extension Sunday, but he said: ``He's done a good job. He's been
steady, like he always is. He's someone you can count on.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the best baseball blooper highlights is a clip of O'Neill
when he played for Cincinnati. He charged a base hit, dropped it,
tried to pick it up again and dropped it, before his temper finally
overcame him and a frustrated O'Neill punted the ball _ incredibly,
right to the cutoff man.
</P>
<P>
   A gaffe he made Sunday will not have the staying power of that
mistake, but it did cause great hilarity in the Metrodome. In the
sixth inning, O'Neill scrambled in to pick up a ground-ball hit,
took the ball out of his glove and tried to throw _ but the ball
squirted out of his hand, like a water balloon, flipping high into
the air and falling about 20 feet or so in front of him. Both
runners took an extra base on his first error of the season, and
when O'Neill's blunder was replayed, laughter erupted from the
stands.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill turned and glanced seriously at the scoreboard; his
acute self-deprecating humor kicked in after the game. ``It must be
the way I throw the ball or something,'' O'Neill said. ``Definitely
wasn't one of my finer moments. Definitely wasn't a web gem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
