<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-CHENEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHENEY DEFENDS VOTING RECORD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Delivering a low-key performance Sunday in his
first solo rally as George W. Bush's running mate, Dick Cheney
defended his voting record in Congress and promised that he and
Bush would restore respect to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Greeted by the ``Rocky'' musical theme and a red, white and blue
confetti drop on his arrival in Philadelphia for the Republican
National Convention, Cheney spoke for only about four minutes to a
crowd that had waited for as long as two hours in a downtown hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Joining him were most of the country's Republican governors,
including several he beat out for the No. 2 spot on the GOP ticket,
and convention delegates from his home state of Wyoming, who will
help nominate him for vice president this week.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, who spent 25 years in Congress as a presidential aide,
congressman from Wyoming and secretary of defense under his running
mate's father, former President Bush, said he was ``proud of those
years there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm especially proud of my record, voting to support smaller
government, lower taxes, stronger national defense _ policies of
Ronald Reagan,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney has been on the defensive about his congressional voting
record since Bush tapped him for his running mate last Tuesday and
Democrats started hammering away at Cheney's votes in Congress in
the late 1970s and 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney has particularly been criticized for voting against such
things as Head Start, a ban on armor-piercing, cop-killer bullets
and a resolution to free Nelson Mandela, the then-imprisoned hero
of the struggle to end apartheid in South Africa. Democrats have
used those votes to question the Bush-Cheney ticket's
``compassionate conservative'' credentials and efforts to appeal to
moderate voters.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Sunday, Cheney did a round of national TV interviews,
explaining that many of his votes were designed to cut spending and
reduce the huge deficit that then loomed over the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to have a big deficit in the 80s. Now we've got a
surplus. So we can afford to do some things from the standpoint of
programs and support as Governor Bush has indicated that we
couldn't have done 20 years ago,'' he said on CBS-TV's ``Face the
Nation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't apologize for my record. It's there. It's my
record. I'm proud of it,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   On ABC-TV's ``This Week with Sam Donaldson and Cokie Roberts,''
Cheney indicated he voted against Mandela's release because the
African National Congress that he headed was ``then viewed as a
terrorist organization.``
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Cheney said on CNN's Larry King Live that he wouldn't
vote now against Head Start, a preschool program for low-income
children.
</P>
<P>
   The longtime Washington insider told the Philadelphia rally that
he also valued the past five years that he has spent in the ``real
world'' of private business in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about being out in the real world ... away from that
hothouse environment in Washington, is the fact that you're out
there where people are building companies and communities, creating
jobs, inventing technologies that are transforming our lives,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He also praised governors, such as Bush, for making government
work.
</P>
<P>
   He said Bush had demonstrated an ability ``to unite the
Republican Party and to reach across the aisle and bring aboard the
discerning Democrats to achieve great things. That's what we're
trying to re-establish in Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney said he and Bush ``want to make Americans proud again by
giving them a president they can respect.``
</P>
<P>
   ``Our party's united, our purpose is clear, our cause is just,
and Gov. George Bush will be the next president of the United
States,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Although Cheney's criticisms of the Clinton-Gore administration
were mostly indirect and mild, he was introduced by Gov. Christine
Todd Whitman of New Jersey, who openly attacked Vice President Al
Gore, the likely Democratic presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore's been vice president for eight years. Tell me, what's
he done? Where's his leadership? What issue do you associate with
him as a leader?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   Other governors attending the rally included Tom Ridge of
Pennsylvania, John Engler of Michigan and Frank Keating of
Oklahoma, all believed to have been considered as possible running
mates by Bush.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
