<HEADLINE>
WHITMAN IS ONSTAGE, BUT HER ROLE IS LESSENED
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS 2nd and 3rd grafs with actions at ceremony)  By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMDEN, N.J. _ For Gov. Christie Whitman, the contrast to four
years ago could not have been more stark.
</P>
<P>
   At 8:55 p.m. Sunday night, the New Jersey governor was took
center stage at the ``Welcome America'' festivities here and spoke
for 68 seconds. And alongside Gov. Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania, threw
a switch lighting the Ben Franklin Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   With that, before the Republican National Convention had even
begun, Whitman's official duties for the week were done.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 Whitman was on Bob Dole's short list of potential
running mates. This year, as Whitman has had to acknowledge in one
interview after another, she wasn't even asked to submit personal
background material to the campaign of Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 she was thought of as an eventual presidential candidate
in her own right. Now, if Bush wins, Whitman's prospects are widely
seen as limited to a Cabinet post, at best, or maybe an
ambassadorship _ the political equivalent of being put out to
pasture.
</P>
<P>
   At the Republican National Convention in San Diego four years
ago, Whitman, who shared leadership duties with Bush, was on stage
every night. She delivered a prime-time speech, and she was mobbed
by autograph seekers wherever she went. Now, the only people
following Whitman around are her state police bodyguards.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman's stature has been on the decline since 1997, when she
vetoed a ban on the late-term abortion procedure that its opponents
call partial-birth abortion, though it had been passed by both
Republican-controlled houses of the state Legislature. That an
appellate court just last week overturned the ban, passed after the
Legislature overrode her veto, would prove small consolation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That sealed her political future,'' said John Tomicki, a
lobbyist for right-wing causes in Trenton.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1997, Whitman, despite her national celebrity,
failed to win a majority of the votes in her re-election bid, and
barely squeaked past her Democratic challenger, James McGreevey,
the little-known mayor of Woodbridge.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, the governor's national image has been marred by
the controversy over racial profiling by state troopers. And her
political potency within New Jersey was called into question once
again when she abruptly canceled a run for the Senate last fall,
saying the burden of raising money was too great.
</P>
<P>
   By this year, even Whitman's most ardent supporters held little
hope that she would be given a spot on the national ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``She'd become the bete noire of the pro-life movement,'' said
former Rep. Dick Zimmer, a Republican running to recapture the 12th
District seat from Rep. Rush Holt. ``So that even if Governor Bush
were inclined to choose a pro-choice running mate, it probably
wouldn't have been her.''
</P>
<P>
   Admirers of Whitman here lamented the storm of criticism she
endured this month after a snapshot surfaced showing her grinning
as she frisked a black man, apparently at the urging of a state
trooper, while on a ride-along in Camden in 1996. ``It's one of the
most unfair things in politics I've ever seen,'' Zimmer said.
</P>
<P>
   At least there were no ``I'm frisky for Christie'' buttons for
sale among the hundreds with Bush's smiling face. But the image
seemed to hover like a too-obvious punch line upon any mention of
Camden.
</P>
<P>
   Some eyes rolled, for example, when the governor told New Jersey
delegates on Saturday that Sunday night's festivities on the Camden
waterfront _ the only part of the city that has been rebuilt _
would ``show off the kind of good things that happen when
Republicans get involved in cities.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Whitman, 53, is doing her best to sound content with her
role at this convention, and to appear relevant. She tried hard in
several early interviews to pump up the Republican ticket, minimize
the importance of its platform and change the subject from her
party's opposition to abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   During the convention, the governor noted, she will be appearing
on more than 20 television programs. And she says she takes solace
from her continued cachet as a talking head.
</P>
<P>
   ``After having been the co-chair, to then speak on Monday
afternoon at 3:30 holds no great attraction,'' Whitman said. ``If
you're not speaking in prime time, it's better to do the kinds of
things I'm doing. And the fact that they've asked me to do so much
of that is, to me, an indication that there's still something that
goes along with my name.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
