<SLUG> BC-GOP-BUSHTRAIL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH'S WARM-UP SPEAKERS ROAST CLINTON, GORE AT RALLY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLUE ASH, Ohio _ Republican presidential candidate George W.
Bush may want his convention to present a positive message to the
nation, but the warm-up speakers at his rally Sunday fired up the
crowd with old-style, red-meat rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who thought you'd see Microsoft split up and the Clintons
stick together,'' U.S. Rep. Steve Chabot, R-Ohio, told the crowd of
2,000 at a replica of the Cincinnati Reds former stadium, Crosley
Field.
</P>
<P>
   Area radio host Bill Cunningham of WLW-AM in Cincinnati told the
crowd to ignore a heavy rain as they waited for Bush to arrive at
the rally. He hammered repeatedly on President Clinton and Vice
President Al Gore with references to the Monica Lewinsky sex
scandal. Gore is the presumptive Democratic presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``After eight years of Clinton/Gore, America needs a bath, and
we're getting one right now,'' Cunningham said.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham likened Bush to former President Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty years ago a governor road out of the West on a mighty
steed and he scoured those damn Democrats out of the White House,''
Cunningham said. ``Let's elect another governor from the West to
scour out the White House of the filth and degradation. God bless
America!''
</P>
<P>
   Blue Ash Mayor Jim Sumner told the crowd that it is time for a
change in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you ready for your daughter to serve as an intern?''
Sumner said, referring to the White House job Lewinsky held when
she had an affair with the president. ``Are you ready for a return
of integrity and morals to the White House?''
</P>
<P>
   Chabot, Cunningham and Sumner set a tone that gave a harsh edge
to Bush's standard stump speech conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I put my hand on the Bible, January 2001, I will swear
not only to uphold the laws of the land, I will swear to uphold the
honor and the integrity of the office to which I have been elected,
so help me God,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is touring some key battleground states on his way from
Texas to Philadelphia, the site of the Republican National
Convention. Bush is spending Sunday and today in Ohio, a state that
has voted for every presidential winner since 1948 and has not gone
to a Republican presidential candidate since Bush's father won in
1988.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's arrival was delayed for about 30 minutes when a
73-year-old woman collapsed in the audience. Helen Geiger of
Cincinnati later died.
</P>
<P>
   As Bush's bus rolled onto the baseball field, the theme from
``Chariots of Fire'' played while fireworks burst in the sky. As
Bush walked from the bus to the podium before the Crosley Field
scoreboard, the loudspeakers blared the theme from the baseball
movie, ``The Natural.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush from 1989-99 was one of the owners of the Texas Rangers
baseball team. He spent the night at the home of his former team
partner, financier Bill DeWitt of Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on our way to Philadelphia, and we're on our way to
victory,'' Bush said, referring to the Republican National
Convention where he will secure the GOP presidential nomination
this week.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore and family continued their vacation under cloudy
skies on the North Carolina coast, the Democratic National
Committee kept the pressure on Bush by releasing a new 30-second ad
attacking running mate Dick Cheney's voting record from two decades
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The ad says, ``Cheney was one of only eight members of Congress
to oppose the Clean Water Act, one of the few to vote against Head
Start (a preschool program for low-income children). He even voted
against the School Lunch Program ... against health insurance for
people who lost their jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney appeared on all five national television talk shows
Sunday morning, criticizing the Democrats for focusing on
``trivia'' from his past, and defending his record. ``They're
spending all of their time poring over my voting record from 20
years ago,'' Cheney told CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney did not apologize Sunday for his votes, though he now
concedes he might vote differently than he did in the 1980s. Cheney
said on NBC's ``Meet the Press'' that he frequently voted against
legislation in those big deficit years because he thought the
requested funding was excessive.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
