<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-SENIOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEISHER CONTINUES SENIOR TOUR DOMINANCE
</HEADLINE>
  By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERICHO, N.Y. _ It was an exaggeration, but it made a point. All
through the rain and the slop of the final day of the Lightpath
Long Island Classic Senior PGA tournament Sunday, it was a battle
between Bruce Fleisher, Dana Quigley and Allen Doyle. They started
the day as the leaders, were put together as a threesome, and
finished 1-2-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three guys,'' Quigley said, ``when we all turned 50 we were
pretty much broke, and now we're out there competing for millions
of dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleisher's status as the Senior Tour's top money winner was
enhanced with Sunday's $225,000 winner's check thanks to his
closing 3-under 69, which gave him a three-day total of 198 and the
victory at the Meadow Brook Club. His 18-under total _ a record for
the Lightpath _ gave him two strokes on Quigley (who shot a 67
Sunday) and three on Doyle (69).
</P>
<P>
   This continuing senior saga of second chances spotlighted those
three _ but it has also been a boon for many others on the Tour.
Fleisher, though, personifies what this tour has done for an
assortment of players. He played on the regular PGA Tour for almost
30 years and won one tournament. He joined it after winning the
U.S. Amateur title but then had limited success as a pro.
</P>
<P>
   As a senior, though, he was a rookie sensation with seven
victories last year. And with four victories this season, he has
vaulted to the earnings lead with more than $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three guys without any pedigree _ without any credentials,
certainly _ were competing for all that money,'' Quigley said. ``I
guess you can call us Larry, Curly, Moe.''
</P>
<P>
   Quigley never earned $40,000 on the regular tour but has just
passed the million-dollar mark for the third consecutive year as a
senior.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for Fleisher, there was a tiredness about him after it was
over. He said he had not been home for 10 weeks and had been
looking forward to ending this tournament as soon as it began. He
admitted that last year's seven victories _ bringing most of the
$2.5 million he earned _ had taken a toll.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was not fun,'' he explained. ``I won today with my
heart. I'm tired. I don't want to be overwhelmed by it, controlled
by it, as I was last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleisher may have been playing down how well he performed in
successfully defending the title he won as a rookie. But neither
Quigley nor Doyle was having any of it. For Quigley, who entered
the final round four strokes behind and said he planned to charge
from the beginning, there was a disappointment on the par-5 first
hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started out real aggressive _ I hit a great drive over the
trees on 1 and knocked it on the green in two _ and three-putted,''
he said. ``That kind of took a little sting out of the way I
felt.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleisher, meanwhile, eagled the par-5 third hole. His lead was
never fewer than two strokes, and he was steady, if disappointing
to himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was wet, kind of sloppy, and when you're leading you have
to prove to somebody you can do it,'' Fleisher said. ``These are
the demons you deal with, thousands of people watching, people at
home, all armchair quarterbacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Doyle, though, who started the day three back, saw none of that
in Fleisher's game. Rather, he said: ``He's tough when he's in
front. You knew you couldn't shoot 3 under and win.''
</P>
<P>
   Doyle, like Quigley, never won on the regular tour. But like
Quigley, he will pass $1 million for this year alone.
</P>
<P>
   And why do players like these become such instant hits when they
turn 50 and join the seniors? Quigley joined the group in 1997 and
Doyle was a rookie last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we have a little more fire in the belly,'' Doyle said.
``Maybe the more famous players don't work as hard as we do. The
three of us, when we were in our 40s, we were scrambling for places
to play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
