<HEADER>
A7669 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-ART-540     07-30 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-ART-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON CITES OPPONENT'S DRUG-INDUSTRY TIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT15 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SOMINI SENGUPTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Trying to portray her opponent in the Senate race as
out of touch with mainstream voters, Hillary Rodham Clinton
described Rep. Rick Lazio on Sunday as beholden to the
pharmaceutical industry for taking contributions from drug makers
and voting against a bill to subsidize prescription drugs for the
elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters Sunday afternoon in the courtyard of the
Municipal Building, Clinton voiced her support for the Democrats'
prescription-drug bill. She reiterated her own proposal to legalize
the importing of medicine from abroad, where drugs are frequently
cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``My opponent is on the side of drug companies and the
Republican leadership,'' said Clinton, who was ringed by a small
group of elderly and disabled New Yorkers assembled by a consumers
group, Citizen Action. ``Time and time again he has demonstrated
where his heart and his allegiance really rests.''
</P>
<P>
   As she has in several recent appearances, including an address
to an enthusiastic audience of churchgoers in Harlem on Sunday
morning, Clinton tried to draw _ sometimes with tart sarcasm _ a
sharp line between herself and Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   ``My conservative Republican opponent often says he's
mainstream,'' she said. ``But it's neither compassionate nor
mainstream to leave millions of your fellow citizens without the
guarantee of affordable prescription-drug coverage, especially when
you're a member of Congress and you get top-of-the-line medical
coverage, including prescription drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Lazio voted for a Republican prescription-drug plan
that looked to private business to provide new coverage. Under that
measure, federal subsidies would be used to encourage insurance
companies to offer drug coverage to the elderly and offer Medicare
beneficiaries a choice of two drug plans.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Lazio's spokesman, Bryan Flood, denounced the
Democrats' plan as a ``one size fits all'' approach that did not
offer consumers a choice. He scoffed at Clinton's suggestion that
donations from drug makers had colored Lazio's views.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a desperate charge by an increasingly desperate
campaign,'' Flood contended. ``As a legislator, Congressman Lazio
votes in the best interests of New Yorkers. It's absurd to suggest
that his votes are related to who gives him campaign
contributions.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's campaign aides did not try to refute Clinton's charge
that he had benefited from $30,000 in donations from the
pharmaceutical industry. They simply pointed out that his campaign
had raised over $9 million so far.
</P>
<P>
   They also used Clinton's comments on prescription drugs to
recall her unsuccessful bid for universal health coverage in the
early years of President Clinton's administration. ``Hillary
Clinton doesn't have a record on very much; she does have a record
on this,'' Flood said. ``It wasn't too long ago she was trying to
socialize our nation's health-care system.''
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion polls show that drug prices and the need for
prescription-drug coverage are major concerns of many voters. And
Clinton, joined Sunday by elderly New Yorkers angered by steep
monthly increases in prescription-drug expenses, has a potentially
huge base among senior citizens, an important voting bloc.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Beyond that, Clinton's attack on her opponent's position on
prescription drugs appeared to be part of a larger effort to cast
him as a far-right Republican concealed in moderate garb.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear a lot of talk about compassionate conservatives,'' she
said sarcastically on Sunday at Metropolitan AME Church in Harlem.
``I guess that means somebody who feels really bad when your doctor
doesn't give you the treatment you need because he's been told he
can't by the HMO.''
</P>
<P>
   Attacks like this one got her a good response from the crowd.
There were shouts of ``Amen!'' and loud murmurs of affirmation. And
every time her name was mentioned by a speaker, the people in the
pews rose for a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   Her audience included several members of the city's black
Democratic leadership, from Bill Lynch, vice chairman of the
Democratic National Committee, to U.S. Rep. Charles Rangel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compassion without action is not enough,'' Clinton bellowed,
as the crowd erupted in applause.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to hear the real tune that's being played,'' she
added.
</P>
</TEXT>
