<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-30 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7671 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-CHAVEZ-VENEZUELA-BOS &LR;      07-30 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAVEZ-VENEZUELA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAVEZ RIDES A VOW OF CHANGE TO REELECTION IN VENEZUELA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS _ President Hugo Chavez of Venezuela, whose promise of a
social revolution appeared to outweigh concerns over rising crime
and a severe economic crisis, won a resounding reelection victory
Sunday, exit polls indicated.
</P>
<P>
   According to the polls, released soon after voting ended,
Chavez, 46, won 54 percent of the vote, while his closest rival,
Francisco Arias, won 34 percent. Arias, 49, a former governor of
Zulia state, once helped Chavez in a failed 1992 coup attempt but
broke away in February amid concerns the president was accumulating
too much power and alienating the middle class.
</P>
<P>
   The exit polls, released by El Nacional, one of the country's
leading newspapers, showed a margin of victory similar to that
which many preelection opinion polls had predicted.
</P>
<P>
   The result seemed less clear, however, over the makeup of the
165-member National Assembly, and whether Chavez's leftist
coalition would have enough seats to secure a majority to pass
future proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's ``mega-election,'' as it was known among voters and
media, was part of a new constitution that Chavez pushed through
last year. It was also the latest step in his attempts to overhaul
Venezuela's corrupt political system, as he had promised after
winning the presidency in December 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In the coastal town of La Guaira, about 40 miles north of the
capital, voters lined up outside St. Peter the Apostle Church to
cast ballots under a blazing sun. Seven months ago, the white
church and most of the hillside town were covered with mud during
several days of torrential rains that killed thousands and left
nearly half the town's families homeless.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family was left nearly naked, and the government gave us a
new home and a new beginning, so I feel obligated to come vote,''
said Julio Ortiz, 30, a policeman who traveled three hours by bus
to the polls. ``The problems today are from past politicians, but
Chavez will solve them.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone in this impoverished town agreed. Carrying a bag of
groceries as she walked along a row of abandoned brick houses where
her friends once lived, Maritza Vallejo criticized the government
for not doing enough to help those who survived last December's
floods.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been tricked into thinking things will change,'' Vallejo
said, looking around at the rubble and idle tractors that
surrounded her. ``Some people get gifts from the government, but we
all need help.''
</P>
<P>
   Electoral officials acknowledged some irregularities in Sunday's
voting. The biggest problem was with the automated system, which
had difficulty tabulating some of the ballots. The glitches created
delays at several polling places, where voters were forced to wait
in line for as long as seven hours. Officials kept the polls open
an additional two hours.
</P>
<P>
   Turnout appeared to be heavier than the 50 percent expected,
although there were no official estimates immediately available
Sunday night. As part of the revised constitution, members of
Venezuela's military branches were, for the first time, also
allowed to cast ballots.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of Venezuela have acted democratically and in an
orderly manner, and for this we should be proud,'' said Cesar
Penas, director of the National Electoral Council. Sunday's vote
was also monitored by about 300 international observers.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Chavez appeared relaxed as he cast his ballot in
Caracas and, later, as he played in his regular baseball game with
aides at the Miraflores presidential palace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is quiet,'' Chavez told reporters between innings.
``All is quiet except for the people who are voting today and
strengthing our revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with Sunday's apparent victory, Chavez's movement appears
to be weaker than the one that began with so much fervor when he
was swept into office 18 months ago. Despite record-high prices for
the country's top export, petroleum, Venezuela's economy shrank by
7 percent last year, and investors pulled billions of dollars from
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, crime has risen sharply throughout the country of 23
million, but most dramatically in the capital and along the
Venezuelan-Colombian border.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Chavez continues to enjoy strong support among
Venezuela's poor, who have not yet grown tired of his tirades
against the old political ``oligarchy,'' and who do not fear that
he is more concerned with gaining more power than managing the
country's problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forty years of corrupt democracy created many problems for
this country,'' said Luis Rodriguez, a 63-year-old machinist who
lives in Sierra Maestra, one of the many hillside slums that skirt
the capital. ``It will take Chavez a while to clean up that mess,
but he's got the nerve and the passion to do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
