<SLUG> BC-WORLDFEST-LADN </SLUG>
 
FESTIVAL PROMOTES ABSTAINING FROM ANIMAL PRODUCTS &HT;    (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER HAMM 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Meditation booths, henna body art and plenty of
vegan vittles _ such as bamboo burgers _ helped draw thousands to
the first-ever WorldFest Los Angeles on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The solar-powered music, environmental and animal festival at
Woodley Park in Van Nuys was aimed at promoting social
consciousness, organizers said. Setting the event in the San
Fernando Valley _ more widley known as L.A.'s bourgeois bastion
than as an embracer of change _ surprised some.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anything like this in the Valley,'' said Pat
Collins, 43, of Pacoima, who held his dread-locked hair back with a
rubber band. ``To me, the Valley is a giant work camp. To see
something like this is a breath of fresh air.''
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures reached 96 degrees but that didn't keep more than
4,000 people from enjoying the bands, celebrity guests or food at
the free festival.
</P>
<P>
   Some ate vegan hotdogs while others danced to a wide variety of
music, including soul-filled Brazilian rhythms from Ana Gazzola and
Sonia Santos with the Brasil Brazil Band.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrities Alicia Silverstone, Woody Harrelson and Kevin Nealon
were on hand to promote veganism, which means avoiding foods which
contain any animal products including meat, dairy and eggs.
</P>
<P>
   John Robbins, author of the best-selling ``Diet for a New
America,'' and Howard Lyman, co-defendant with Oprah Winfrey in the
libel lawsuit brought by a Texas cattleman, also spoke at the
event.
</P>
<P>
   Silverstone, who has been a vegan for two years, said she sticks
to the diet because she wants to help animals and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a hard-core vegan who wants everybody to be vegan,'' said
Silverstone, who starred in ``Clueless.'' ``It's a healthier,
happier way to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   Scores of people attending the festival seemed to agree. By
mid-afternoon, the All Natural Vegan Express Cafe booth had a long
line.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Ciervo, who wore a blue T-shirt that read ``VEGAN,'' said
it was a thrill to attend an event that served only vegan food.
Since becoming a vegan more than a year ago, Ciervo, 22, of
Riverside, Calif., still eats all the delicious foods he used to
enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to give up all the food you like,'' he said.
``You just find a substitute.''
</P>
<P>
   But there were meat lovers to be found in the crowd. Raymond Hsu
said he came from San Gabriel, Calif., to enjoy the bands that
played throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to eat healthy,'' said Hsu, 23, who admitted he enjoys
eating hamburgers. ``I'm not sure how vegan that is.''
</P>
<P>
   But the message Sunday was clear _ eating anything made with
animals or animal products is cruel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people know in their hearts it's not right to eat
animals,'' said Sangeeta Kumar, one of the festival organizers.
``In the nine hours of WorldFest, 9 million animals will be
slaughtered. It's an animal holocaust.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the pro-animal efforts, the festival was also used to
promote other traditionally liberal political causes. One booth,
for example, distributed leaflets on human rights violations in
war-torn Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose is to promote compassion,'' Kumar said.
``Compassion is cool. It's in.''
</P>
<P>
   x x x
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-00 2244EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
