<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-30 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7675 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-RNC-CALIFORNIA-LADN     07-30 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RNC-CALIFORNIA-LADN </SLUG>
 
CALIFORNIA'S DELEGATION TO REPUBLICN CONVENTION DIVERSE, BUT
LEADERLESS &HT;    (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ To Reagan revolutionaries like Lancaster insurance
broker Frank Visco, the trip to the Republican National Convention
in Philadelphia feels like the good old days: a party united, a
front-running candidate and high hopes of retaking the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Visco, a former chairman of the state GOP, is attending his
seventh convention and sees similarities between conventions that
nominated Ronald Reagan in 1984 and 1988 and this year's, where
Texas Gov. George W. Bush will be anointed by the party faithful.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is absolutely as together as the party has been,'' Visco
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are getting people excited and dealing with some of our
internal issues. I think what we're doing is taking a pragmatic
approach and not letting issues like choice on abortion divide us.
We are looking for areas of common ground.''
</P>
<P>
   With the convention's opening today, veteran California
delegates say the national party is more unified than it has been
in nearly a decade.
</P>
<P>
   California, the largest contingent at the convention with 162 of
the 2,066 delegates, is also bringing the most diverse group with
83 women and at least 20 percent minority.
</P>
<P>
   But, at the same time, the delegation is seen as having the
least influence in a number of years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the most inconsequential delegation
California has ever sent,'' said Republican consultant Allan
Hoffenblum. ``This is a state that sent delegations lead by a
Reagan, a (Pete) Wilson, a (George) Deukmejian. We have no
Republican governor, no Republican senator to lead it.
</P>
<P>
   ``While it is the most diverse _ I understand there are even two
or three members from the (gay) Log Cabin Club _ there is no real
leader. I guess if you can't send the most powerful, you send the
most diverse.''
</P>
<P>
   The California GOP was routed in the elections two years ago,
holding on to only two statewide offices. And it lost one of those
with the resignation of Insurance Commissioner Chuck Quackenbush
because of the scandal involving settlements by insurance companies
from the 1994 Northridge Earthquake. That leaves Secretary of State
Bill Jones as the top Republican in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The diversity is seen as important to members of the delegation
as the GOP attempts to rebuild and as Bush has attempted to reach
out to Latino voters.
</P>
<P>
   Celeste Grieg, a longtime activist who is going to her sixth
convention, said it was important for the state party to send a
message to minorities that they are welcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush has a message he wanted to bring people together,
regardless of where they stand,'' Grieg said. ``And the Hispanic
community is one of the largest and it's about time it was
recognized for its tremendous heritage and the work we have done in
this country. I'm pleased with the delegation.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Becerra, who works for Southern California Edison Co.,
said he sees the party as heading toward the ``big tent'' theory
advanced by Lee Atwater, the political strategist who engineered
the first campaign of former President George Bush. The convention
is the first for Becerra, who said he is looking at it as a chance
to participate in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is monumental,'' he said. ``And I have a sense the party
at every level is coming together. We will agree to disagree, but
be united in backing George W. Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Another GOP activist, Bruce Bialosky, a certified public
accountant and real estate broker, is attending his third
convention and sees the party as more unified than it has been in
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Houston in 1992, a lot of people were upset with the way
the campaign was being run and then Pat Buchanan stood up and made
that divisive speech,'' Bialosky said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, four years ago in San Diego, no one was very
enthusiastic and there was so much infighting. You don't sense that
going into this convention,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For Scott Schmidt, a spokesman for the San Fernando Valley
Industry and Commerce Association, his first convention is an
opportunity to get involved and rebuild the state GOP.
</P>
<P>
   ``While conventions seemingly become less and less important
since we know who will be nominated, it's still an opportunity to
deal with policy issues and let people see the diversity of our
delegation,'' Schmidt said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the (San Fernando) Valley delegation alone, we have several
Asian, Jewish and Latino members as well as two from the Log Cabin
Club. This is the direction that the Republican Party has to go.''
</P>
<P>
   x x x
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-00 2247EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000730.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-30 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7678 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GOP-BUSH-ROAD-ART-710     07-30 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-BUSH-ROAD-ART-710&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SEEMS SERENE AND CONFIDENT ON EVE OF CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating add photo note) (ART ADV: Photos _ NYT13,16 _ are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLUE ASH, Ohio _ As he rides toward his moment of triumph,
George W. Bush speaks with extra punch. He belts out his speeches
now, his face flushing, arms waving. Yet once off the stage, he is
unusually introspective, talking of family. History. Legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm mindful of the Adams family factor,'' he said on his
campaign plane this past weekend, bringing up unprompted the last
father and son in American history to both win the presidency: John
Adams and John Quincy Adams, so very long ago.
</P>
<P>
   So confident is he that he jokes fondly about his new running
mate's flat campaign style, calling it with notable understatement
``a little more laid-back than mine.'' And though usually allergic
to psychobabble, Bush does not brush off questions about his
relationship with his father, former President George H.W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't all that long ago that he himself was the president
of the United States, which will make the story unique and
different,'' Bush mused.
</P>
<P>
   There is poignancy to this conversation on the plane. At his
rallies, Bush speaks of his popular mother. He revels in telling
the tale of his courtship of his wife, Laura. But the only
acknowledgment of his father is oblique.
</P>
<P>
   It comes when he bellows, ``I understand that the last two
presidential elections haven't gone well,'' and promises to change
that for Republicans come November. Left unmentioned is that one of
those defeats was his father's.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Bush clan is gathering once again, just as it did to
watch the father's triumphant nomination by two Republican National
Conventions. This time it is the eldest son who will take his
moment on the stage, capping a remarkable 17-month transformation
from a governor with less than two full terms in office to his
party's great hope for reclaiming the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll be there, sure, I think all of my brothers and
sister,'' Bush said. ``I can't think of any boycotters.''
</P>
<P>
   Day after day as Bush gets ever closer to Philadelphia, the
pyrotechnics become more elaborate. On Sunday he stole a technique
from his primary rival John McCain and showed up on a campaign bus
for a rally here at the replica of the historic Crosley Field.
Fireworks shot into the sky to dazzle the crowd of 2,000, who had
waited for hours on the open field despite several rainstorms.
</P>
<P>
   In a blue shirt and no jacket, dancing on his heels, Bush spoke
of himself in the third person. ``You got to understand about
George W.,'' he said. ``I don't take polls to tell me what to
think. I do what I think is right.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush seems serene, though at times emotional too. At the
governor's mansion in Austin late last week, he almost choked up
when he said he would recognize his wife, his daughters and his
parents in his convention speech.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bush is at his side at rally after rally, beaming, as he
weaves her into his stump speech by promoting her own convention
speech, which is planned for Monday night. ``The first speaker will
be the first lady of the state of Texas,'' he tells his audiences.
</P>
<P>
   He gives them a thumbnail history of the public school librarian
from dusty Midland, Texas. ``I said, `Would you marry me?''' he
says. ``She wasn't particularly interested in politics and
politicians. She said, `I will, except don't ever make me give a
speech.' I said, `OK.''' He pauses and then adds, to rising
laughter from his audiences, ``It's the only political promise I've
ever broken.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Republican convention will be about Bush and the Bush
family and the Bush platform, beginning in prime time on Monday
with Laura and ending Thursday night with Bush's acceptance speech.
``That puts the Bush family arms around the convention,'' said
Karen P. Hughes, Bush's communications director.
</P>
<P>
   Many other Republican officeholders _ the ones who remind the
public of the the hard-edged Gingrich years _ have been pushed
offstage or to nonprime time.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the edge is gone completely. Revving up the drenched
crowd before Bush's arrival on Sunday, Bill Cunningham, the host of
a local radio talk show, asked, ``Are we going to permit an eighth
of an inch of rain to keep us from scouring out the White House
from the filth and degradation of Clinton-Gore?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No!'' the audience thundered back.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Rep. Steve Chabot, who served on the House Judiciary Committee
during the impeachment of President Clinton, wondered jokingly who
would have expected to see ``Microsoft split up and the Clintons
still together.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's speeches by contrast have few hard edges, except for his
promise to restore ``honor and dignity'' to the presidency, and the
dig at President Clinton that is implicit when he says that Dick
Cheney ``understands what the definition of `is' is.''
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the speeches is the concept of family, a soft
and subtle way to appeal to his party's conservatives yet also
sound right to suburban soccer moms. ``Love your children all the
time,'' he croons. ``Tell them you love them.'' Or else he shouts,
``I got a kind of special feeling for moms _ if you know what I
mean.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes he sounds more like a revivalist preacher than a
politician. Before 5,000 people in Joplin, Mo., on Friday night,
Bush thundered: ``My administration will rally what I call the
armies of compassion, the decent, kindhearted souls that act not
because of government, that act because they hear our call to
people all across America.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the confetti and the balloons, and on outdoor stages, Bush
throws out his arms maniacally to give oomph to the old familiar
stump speech. He gets help in looking animated from the contrast
with his new running mate.
</P>
<P>
   On his one day of campaigning with Bush last Friday, Cheney
shook hands fast along the receiving line waiting to greet the Bush
plane. Then he stood alone at the waiting car. Bush was still
working the line, grabbing a hand here, a shoulder there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a different campaigning style,'' Bush said the next
day. ``That's the way it is. He's going to be a great partner. He's
warming up.''
</P>
<P>
   And if these are glory days, well, Bush says he learned
something else from his father, who watched his sky-high approval
ratings after the Gulf war collapse, leaving him unable to stave
off defeat in 1992 by a young, untested governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to get overconfident,'' said this year's
governor of the moment. ``You know why? I know what can happen. I
have seen poll numbers crumble. I have seen defeat firsthand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
