<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-SARATOGA-555&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERITAGE OF GOLD TRIUMPHS IN DUEL AMID PUDDLES 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE DRAPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ They staggered back toward the winner's
circle, splattered with mud, in a cleansing drizzle. One mare,
Beautiful Pleasure, had been crowned a champion in 1999. The other,
Heritage of Gold, had just run Beautiful Pleasure down to validate
her intention to take that crown. The crowd rose to its feet and
thundered applause for the two rivals' effort in a duel down the
stretch at Saratoga which splashed drama as well as puddles all the
way to the wire.
</P>
<P>
   The bare facts are that for the second time this year, Heritage
of Gold bested Beautiful Pleasure, ran her victory record for the
year to 5 of 5 and poured $150,000 more into her owner's coffers by
capturing the $250,000 Go For Wand Stakes. That, however, does not
reflect the anguish that the trainer Tom Amoss and the owner Jack
Garey muddled through trying to decide whether Heritage of Gold
might have a chance to duel.
</P>
<P>
   Garey, who is from Texas, told Amoss two days ago that if the
track turned sloppy by Sunday's race, he wanted to wait to take on
Beautiful Pleasure, last year's champion older filly, some other
day.
</P>
<P>
   In 22 career races and 14 victories, Heritage of Gold, a
5-year-old daughter of Gold Legend, had run on turf and dirt, long
and short, on at least seven tracks. But she never puddle-jumped on
a soggy track. Amoss stalled his owner. Wait and see, he told him,
for most of the afternoon. Finally after the fourth race, it was
time to decide.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there is something about Saratoga and being here,'' Amoss
said. ``If he was back at home in Austin, I'm sure he wouldn't have
run. He got all caught up in it and said to me, `What do you want
to do?' I told him I was speaking very subjectively, but I want to
take her on.''
</P>
<P>
   When the gates popped open on the 1 1/8-miles-race, Amoss
admitted, he thought he should have listened to his boss. Beautiful
Pleasure, who in winning three previous races on wet tracks looked
as if she had webbed feet, torpedoed to the rail and built what
appeared to be an insurmountable seven-length lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were in trouble,'' Amoss said. ``All of a sudden,
we were back so far and you start to wonder if the race is over. I
turned to my family and said, `At least we're starting to pick her
up.'''
</P>
<P>
   He did not really believe it, however, until the jockey Shane
Sellers hustled Heritage of Gold around the turn and subtracted
four lengths from Beautiful Pleasure's lead. Sellers said he knew
that he had Beautiful Pleasure in trouble when her rider, Jorge
Chavez, turned back and looked him in the eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Choppy look back,'' said Sellers, referring to the
nickname the Peruvian rider has developed for his short whip
strokes. ``He still had us. But my mare was moving easy and I had
the momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of 58,584 sensed it and bounced to its feet as
Heritage of Gold collared Beautiful Pleasure, the heavily bet 1-5
favorite, at the quarter pole. Sellers and his mare ran in stride
with Beautiful Pleasure for 30 yards until Heritage of Gold
catapulted ahead in the middle of the track for a one-length
victory that paid $7.90 for a $2 bet to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fair and square; no excuses,'' Beautiful Pleasure's
trainer, John Ward, said of his mare, who has earned more than $2.2
million in purses. ``We'll get a rematch.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It will probably not come until November, however, and the
Breeders' Cup Championship at Churchill Downs in Kentucky. But for
an afternoon at least, Amoss overruled his owner and got away with
it. He was at once gracious and relieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who really appreciates horse racing, no matter who the
horses were involved, saw a super race,'' Amoss said.
</P>
<P>
   Garey agreed but could not help beating his chest a bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``She didn't get any respect coming into this race, and didn't
get any respect from the bettors either,'' Garey said. ``We proved
that we have the best dirt female in the country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
