<SLUG> BC-GOP-CONVENTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHENEY GRILLED ON RECORD; BUSH SEEKS UNITY AT EVENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALAN BERNSTEIN 
and CLAY ROBISON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Dick Cheney went on the griddle about his
government record Sunday as Republicans and Gov. George W. Bush's
campaign tried setting the tone for a harmonious, soft-sell
national convention.
</P>
<P>
   The results were mixed.
</P>
<P>
   After engaging in a battle of wits with the hosts of TV's
morning political talk shows, Cheney came here in his still-fresh
role as Bush's vice-presidential running mate. He was welcomed by a
joyous Republican rally, complete with a confetti shower.
</P>
<P>
   It was a preview of GOP celebrations to come in the four-day
convention that starts Monday and culminates in the nomination that
will let the Texas governor make a run at the White House, whose
last Republican occupant was his father. In the spirit of Bush's
``compassionate conservative'' pitch, the convention is programmed
to showcase minorities and appeal to moderate voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make Americans proud again by giving them a
president that they can respect,'' Cheney told supporters _ a
reference to President Clinton's moral failings. Cheney's last
government stint, as President Bush's defense secretary, ended when
Clinton took over the presidency in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   On the TV programs, Cheney said some questions about his
conservative voting record as Wyoming's representative in the House
are ``kind of trivia.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressed about his votes against funding for the Head Start
preschool program and a ban on armor-piercing bullets, Cheney
remarked, ``I might find a couple I would do differently.''
</P>
<P>
   The questions also exposed a policy rift between the running
mates.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, retiring as chairman and CEO of Halliburton, an oil
industry engineering and construction firm that does business with
Middle East countries, said U.S. trade sanctions against Iran and
other countries have been ineffective. He acknowledged that Bush
thinks it's premature to lift the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might go in and argue a different point of view with him,
but I'll do it privately,'' Cheney said. ``And when he's made his
decision, then I'll salute smartly and support the policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans reveled in the latest voter surveys, which show that
Bush has widened his lead over Vice President Al Gore since picking
Cheney less than a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   Bush led 49 percent to 37 percent in an ABC-Washington Post poll
made public Sunday. The same survey of 1,028 registered voters
showed Bush with an edge of five percentage points a week ago. The
poll has a margin of error of three percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Bolstering the Bush campaign's play for unity at the convention,
Sen. John McCain of Arizona told the nominating delegates whom he
had won in primaries against Bush that they should vote during the
convention for the Texas governor's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who will deliver a speech to the convention Tuesday
night, choked with emotion as he formally released the more than
200 delegates he won in the Republican battles of winter.
</P>
<P>
   With campaign finance reform as his hot issue, McCain won over
independent voters and defeated Bush in the primaries of New
Hampshire and six other states.
</P>
<P>
   The senator's show of support for Bush on Sunday ran into
resistance on two fronts.
</P>
<P>
   A few of his delegates said they couldn't stomach voting for
Bush's nomination. And earlier Sunday, McCain's praise of Bush was
interrupted by hisses and boos from some of those attending a
Shadow Convention highlighting campaign finance reform and
alternative issues.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Texas delegation applauded the party platform,
which the convention is scheduled to adopt Monday, because it
supports a total ban on abortion and calls for local control of
public schools.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, some Texans were unhappy over plans to have
Rep. Jim Kolbe of Arizona, the only openly gay Republican member of
Congress, talk to the convention Tuesday night about trade issues.
</P>
<P>
   Cathie Adams, a delegate from Dallas and president of the Texas
Eagle Forum, called on the Bush campaign to remove Kolbe from the
program. And some conservative Texas delegates said they were
thinking about boycotting the speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be embarrassing to the Bush team,'' Kolbe said.
``They could uninvite him.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams said another delegate suggested that Texas delegates pray
during Kolbe's speech.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Republican Chairwoman Susan Weddington said a walkout
would not be productive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly the majority of people (delegates) don't see it
(Kolbe's address) as an endorsement of the gay rights agenda,''
Weddington said. ``But they feel like it doesn't advance our
purpose here in Philadelphia.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Ray Sullivan said Kolbe was selected to address
convention delegates because of his expertise on foreign trade, not
because of his sexual orientation. One of a group of gay Republican
activists who met with Bush in April for a discussion of gay issues
had recommended Kolbe as a convention speaker.
</P>
<P>
   After that meeting, Bush reaffirmed his opposition to gay
marriages and to tougher penalties for crimes motivated by hate of
homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   In downtown Philadelphia, a few miles north of the convention
site, a crowd police estimated at 5,000 marched in favor of causes
that clash with many philosophies of Bush and the delegates.
</P>
<P>
   The Unity 2000 group demonstrated against capital punishment,
the health care system and nuclear weapons and in favor of the
environment and human rights.
</P>
<P>
   The event, whose organizers hoped would turn out many more
people than the number police counted, was virtually free of
skirmishes with police and counter-demonstrators, such as a group
who chanted: ``More guns, less people.''
</P>
<P>
   The daytime cries for social justice gave way to evening
socializing as state convention delegations attended parties. At
the top of the party agenda was a bridge lighting, boat parade and
fireworks display over the Delaware River, which runs between
Pennsylvania and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's scheduled convention events, under the theme ``Leave
No Child Behind,'' include speeches by Bush's wife, Laura, and
retired Army Gen. Colin Powell.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
