u p BC-GOP-CALDWELL-HNS &LR;      07-30 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-CALDWELL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON PASTOR TO PLAY KEY ROLE AT CONVENTION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JULIE MASON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ When party officials called the Rev. Kirbyjon
Caldwell recently about appearing at the Republican National
Convention here, Houston's influential black pastor thought it
would be a minor deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I assumed I was being asked to appear at a prayer breakfast,''
said Caldwell, minister of the Windsor Village United Methodist
Church.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Caldwell is scheduled to make what is among the most
high-profile appearances on the convention podium: introducing
Texas Gov. George W. Bush to accept the GOP presidential nomination
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they called back and said the governor wanted me to
introduce him the night he accepts the nomination, I almost dropped
the phone,'' Caldwell said. ``In fact, I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Caldwell's relationship with Bush, which he describes as
``resonant,'' made accepting the invitation easy.
</P>
<P>
   But as pastor to a predominantly African-American congregation
of 14,000 and growing, the decision to make his national convention
debut on behalf of the Republican presidential nominee was a move
he said he prayed over.
</P>
<P>
   Although closely aligned over the years with Democratic causes
and candidates, the high-profile former stockbroker said he is
politically independent.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 18 years I have never publicly supported a person running
for office, so this is a major move for me,'' Caldwell said. ``I
expect to catch some heat for it, and if I do it won't be the first
time. But I am not going to be defensive about it.''
</P>
<P>
   If Caldwell does catch heat for supporting Bush, it will likely
be delivered to him in private. On Sunday, several Democrats
questioned about his role at the convention declined to criticize
the move.
</P>
<P>
   As to the relationship, Caldwell met Bush five years ago at a
reception in downtown Houston after Bush had read a newspaper
article about the faith-based community programs with which
Caldwell was involved.
</P>
<P>
   Various local organizations launched by Caldwell and his
southwest Houston church provide housing, job training, counseling,
outreach and other services to low- and middle-income residents.
</P>
<P>
   They are the same types of faith-based solutions that Bush
advocates in his campaign. But there is more in Caldwell's appeal
for Bush, who also shares his Methodist faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kirbyjon represents a new type of pastor from a black church,
in that his involvement in Houston is as much at the corporate
board level as it's been at the pulpit,'' said state Rep. Garnet
Coleman, D-Houston, a longtime friend of the Caldwell family.
</P>
<P>
   Caldwell, a successful developer, investor, author and more, is
a graduate of Carleton College with an MBA from the University of
Pennsylvania's Wharton School of Business and a master's in
theology from Southern Methodist University.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, working to reach out to ethnic minorities and
diversify the party, Caldwell is a comfortable fit. Although he's
not involved in politics, Caldwell moves easily among the powerful
and affluent because he is one of them.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Caldwell said he appreciates what Bush is doing in
his campaign for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I look at his plan for America, it is absolutely awesome,''
Caldwell said. ``Because here we have a governor running for
president, regardless of his label, who is being very intentional
and bold by casting the net out farther and deeper than any
president has ever done.''
</P>
<P>
   In the five years since they met, Caldwell and Bush have stayed
in touch. For the governor's 1999 inauguration, he asked Caldwell
to coordinate a private worship service for family and friends on
the day he was sworn in.
</P>
<P>
   Although he says he is not ``a big lever-puller'' affiliated
with either political party, Caldwell said he is supporting Bush
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Key to that support for Caldwell are Bush campaign proposals on
homeownership, financial savings, faith-based initiatives,
education and more.
</P>
<P>
   But heavy on Caldwell's mind as he prepares to head to
Philadelphia are some key differences he has with Bush politically,
notably on the death penalty and gun control.
</P>
<P>
   On issues such as affirmative action, which Bush opposes and
Caldwell supports, the latter said increases in state contracts for
minority businesses during Bush's term are more relevant than his
political statements on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, while the GOP struggles to diversify from its
historically Anglo base, Caldwell said he is impressed with Bush's
record on appointing women and minorities to key positions.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Murray, University of Houston political scientist and
pollster, said Caldwell is not likely to bring in the black vote
for Bush, but that giving the influential pastor a role at the
convention helps both men to a certain degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Bush wins, there won't be many African-American clergy Bush
has been helped by in getting there,'' Murray said. ``And if he
loses, well, he's still the governor of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, giving Caldwell such a prominent slot on the
podium signals to black voters that Bush is not someone they should
fear, Murray added.
</P>
<P>
   What Caldwell may risk with his congregation, whom he said he
assumes is predominantly Democratic, and the rest of the city's
black leadership, remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman said he doubts there will be a downside to Caldwell's
appearance. Despite the pastor's protestations about staying out of
politics, he is in many ways a deft politician.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously there is symbolism in this, because everything that
anyone does in politics these days has to do with image,'' Coleman
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's symbolic, sure. But I don't think there's a problem in
that at all.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
