<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEST-NILE-LOBSTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG ISLAND SOUND LOBSTERMEN BLAME PESTICIDE FOR DEATHS OF
LOBSTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORWALK, Conn. _ John Makowski is a fourth-generation lobsterman
_ at least he was until the mysterious death of most of the lobster
population in western Long Island Sound last fall.
</P>
<P>
   And though he does not have a degree in marine biology,
Makowski, like many of his former colleagues, said he believed that
millions of lobsters were killed by the pesticide spraying last
September to kill mosquitoes that could potentially carry the West
Nile virus.
</P>
<P>
   It is a suspicion some scientists are taking seriously, saying
there are plausible indicators _ but not definitive proof _ that
the pesticides could have played a role in the lobster kill. On
July 25, just hours after New York City concluded pesticide
spraying in Central Park, Makowski and about a dozen other
lobstermen were in the offices of the Norwalk Seaport Association
submitting paperwork to get federal disaster money authorized by
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The lobstermen said they were skeptical about theories last year
that a micro-organism, a paramoeba, could have killed the lobsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a lot of talk about this paramoeba,'' Makowski
said. ``But paramoeba is in the water all the time. It's not
something that in 200 years has ever wiped out a fishery.''
</P>
<P>
   Like insects, lobsters are arthropods and susceptible to
pesticides, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's die-off, marine scientists say, was the worst ever
to hit the Long Island Sound.
</P>
<P>
   Game officials estimate that about 11 million lobsters, more
than 90 percent of the full-sized population, died in the Sound
last fall, putting hundreds of lobstermen out of business in
Connecticut and New York. The Sound is the nation's third-largest
lobster source, after Maine and Massachusetts, generating $45
million in annual sales.
</P>
<P>
   Lobsters, like other crustaceans, are vulnerable to many things,
including changes in water temperature and oxygen content and the
effects of dredging and sewage treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Many lobstermen said believe that the pesticide spraying last
September and the die-off were not a coincidence. They theorize
that the pesticides were washed into the Sound by heavy rain,
including Tropical Storm Floyd, and that those chemicals combined
with chlorine and sewage from water treatment plants weakened the
lobsters' immune systems, allowing the paramoeba to kill them.
</P>
<P>
   Some scientists regard the theory as plausible and worth
researching.
</P>
<P>
   The deaths in marine life last year included other crustaceans
like crabs and starfish.
</P>
<P>
   Richard French, a veterinary pathologist at the University of
Connecticut, who identified the paramoeba in the dead lobsters,
said investigators had ruled out several known causes of lobster
deaths, including bacterial, viral and fungal agents. He said
researchers have been collecting lobsters since June 1 to test the
pesticide theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had any concerns, it would be that there are
concentrations that could affect the animals in a way that makes
them more susceptible to other causes of mortality,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Seaport Association, Jeff Samson, 44, brought
documentation to the declining lobster catch: 50,989 pounds caught
in 1997; 53,792 pounds caught in 1998; 18,496 pounds caught in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year I might get 1,000 if I'm lucky,'' Samson said.
</P>
<P>
   Many lobstermen are questioning whether politicians overreacted
to the West Nile virus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they really overdid it,'' said Anthony Coviello, 56, a
lobsterman who lives in Rowayton. ``If you are going to spray to
protect lives and it's going to protect lives, then pay me for my
damages because I'm out of business.''
</P>
<P>
   The Western Long Island Sound Lobster Association has hired its
own researchers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Congress has authorized $13.9 million in response to
the lobster deaths. Half will go to unemployed lobstermen and half
will go to research. And Friday, federal the Environmental
Protection Agency announced it will conduct a separate six-month,
$125,000 environmental study of the Sound, not focused on
pesticides, to help determine what killed the lobsters.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bayer, the director of the Lobster Institute at the
University of Maine, which is testing the effects of pesticides,
said the situation in the Sound is complicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are other pollutants that could fit into the
picture and it's hard to define what those might be in Long Island
Sound when you have got the megalopolis around it, which actually
could affect the way lobsters respond to many things, including
pesticides,'' Bayer said.
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Beckwith, the chief of the Connecticut Department of
Environmental Protection's marine fisheries division, was more
cautious. He said there was also evidence suggesting the pesticides
were not involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we have proven anything yet,'' he said. ``We had
lobsters dying in places where we didn't have spraying going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Marine scientists say it will take at least five to seven years
for the lobster population to recover, if it recovers at all.
Makowski has put his boat up for sale and plans to sell his house.
He has two daughters, one about to start college. To pay bills, he
has taken a job on land.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
