<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-30 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7801 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-WELLES-MINISERIES-777     07-30 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WELLES-MINISERIES-777(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAGNIFICENT WELLESIAN FLOP TO BE REMADE AS MINISERIES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Ind.)  By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ When Orson Welles completed ``The Magnificent
Ambersons'' in 1942, he considered the film superior to his
previous movie and masterpiece, ``Citizen Kane.'' But a disastrous
preview screening before a teen-age audience led RKO Studios to
take ``The Magnificent Ambersons'' out of Welles' hands and delete
more than 40 minutes of the saga of a wealthy Midwestern family at
the turn of the century. Welles said he never recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``They destroyed `Ambersons,' '' Welles remarked years later.
``And it destroyed me.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the studio's editing of the film shattered Welles'
career or whether he himself contributed to his downfall, the event
remains a turning point in the elusive career of a director, actor
and writer who was, like ``The Magnificent Ambersons,'' brilliant
and flawed. The outtakes of the film were left in vaults and either
turned to dust or were burned because of a shortage of space.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never seen the film the way Welles intended it to be
seen, and there's always been a sense of loss here about those 40
minutes,'' said Ted R. Hartley, chairman of RKO Pictures. ``What we
now want to do is complete our homage and obligation to Welles.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is that the original 131-minute shooting script is
being made into a four-hour miniseries on the A&AMP;E cable network
(the additional material will come from the Booth Tarkington novel
of the same name, on which the film was based). The miniseries,
directed by Alfonso Arau (``Like Water for Chocolate''), will be
released as a film in Europe, where Welles is probably even more
popular than in the United States. Production of the remake starts
in Dublin in August, and the television series and film are to be
released early next year.
</P>
<P>
   What's unusual about this plan is that television rarely if ever
seeks to remake a film that failed commercially like ``The
Magnificent Ambersons.'' Recently, George Clooney was the executive
producer for and acted in a CBS remake of the 1964 drama
``Fail-Safe,'' about a U.S. bomber accidentally ordered to attack
Moscow with a nuclear weapon. But that original movie was a
success. ``The Magnificent Ambersons,'' on the other hand, was
given only a modest release and lost $625,000 at the box office,
making it a big commercial flop.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the edited film is viewed by some film scholars as
a dazzling but sometimes odd work. Other scholars say that the
film's main interest is as an integral piece of the puzzle in the
long decline of Welles, who was 27 when he made ``Citizen Kane''
and 29 when he completed ``The Magnificent Ambersons.''
</P>
<P>
   He died at age of 70 in 1985, a tragic artist who spent his
final years appearing in television commercials, narrating
documentaries, appearing as a guest on comedy shows hosted by Dick
Cavett and Merv Griffin and struggling in vain to make movies.
</P>
<P>
   What led to the remake of ``The Magnificent Ambersons'' was a
meeting that Hartley held in his office in Beverly Hills with two
of the three producers of the miniseries, Norman Stephens and James
Kirkwood. The third producer is Jonas Bauer.
</P>
<P>
   Hartley told them that RKO, by then virtually dormant, was
looking in its archives to remake some of its classic films for
television and movie theaters. Among the films owned by the studio
are ``Suspicion,'' ``Gunga Din'' and ``Beyond a Reasonable Doubt,''
as well as ``The Magnificent Ambersons.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked to see the complete script of `Ambersons,' ''
Stephens said. ``They dug it out. We fell in love with it. Then we
went back to the book, which the original screenplay tracks very
closely. We added scenes from the book.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1942 film starred Joseph Cotten, Tim Holt, Dolores Costello,
Anne Baxter and Agnes Moorehead. It was based on the 1918 Pulitzer
Prize-winning Tarkington novel about a patrician Midwestern family
facing decline and despair with the arrival of the automobile.
Welles' Mercury Theater had initially adapted the novel as a radio
play.
</P>
<P>
   Arau took over the miniseries project recently when the original
director, Herbert Ross, dropped out because of illness.
</P>
<P>
   The cast is tentatively set to include Madeleine Stowe, Jennifer
Tilly, James Cromwell, Jonathan Rhys-Myers and Thora Birch.
Contracts are expected to be signed in the next few days. The cost
of the production is about $14 million, relatively high for a
television drama. Most of the financing comes from an Italian
company, the DeAngelis Group as well as A&AMP;E.
</P>
<P>
   ``The original film was mutilated, but we have the original
script,'' Arau said. ``That script was very faithful to the novel.
The challenge is to make the film based on that script.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
