<P>
   (NYT5) WASHINGTON -- July 30, 2000 -- GOP-DC-DELEGATE --
Betsy Werronen, chairwoman of the D.C. Republican Committee, admits
that when she took the job last month of running the party's local
organization, "people thought I was nuts - some people think it's
hopeless." One out of every ten D.C. citizens identify themselves as
republican. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) CHINCOTEAGUE, VA -- July 30, 2000 -- SHIP-SALVAGE-1 --
Now, for the first time, Spain is laying claim to its thousands of
lost ships, and it has won a legal battle over the issue. On July 21,
a federal appeals court in Virginia ruled that Spain owned the
remains of two warships lost off the Virginia coast two centuries
ago. Ben Benson, a salvor, with the anchor of the Juno, which sank in
1802. Benson has spent nearly $2 million on preliminary recovery work
and legal fees to retrieve two Spanish ships. (Michael Geissinger/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- July 30, 2000 -- WINTOUR-BETTS-MEDIA-2 --
There are few areas of modern society that are as nasty, brutish and
just plain catty as the world of fashion magazines. Recently rumors
have been flying about Ketherine Betts, who became editor in chief at
Harper's Bazaar last year. Advertising sales have risen in recent
months, but still trail competitors like Elle and Vogue. (Chester
Higgins Jr./The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- July 30, 2000 -- WINTOUR-BETTS-MEDIA-1 --
There are few areas of modern society that are as nasty, brutish and
just plain catty as the world of fashion magazines. Recently rumors
have been flying about Ketherine Betts, who became editor in chief at
Harper's Bazaar last year. Advertising sales have risen in recent
months, but still trail competitors like Elle and Vogue. (Chester
Higgins Jr./The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
