<HEADLINE>
PHOTO:
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of
tonight's New York Times Photo Package, moving Sunday, 07/30/00.
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
213-237-4577 or PressLink at 800-888-6195. Non-clients can make
individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- July 30, 2000 -- INSANITY-DEFENSE-2 -- On
March 14, 1980, Dennis Sweeney, now 57, walked into a law office in
Rockefeller Plaza and shot dead Allard Lowenstein, the former
congressman whose liberal passion helped shape a decade of
civil-rights and anti-war activism. On June 30, Justice Brenda Soloff
of State Supreme Court in Manhattan ordered a conditional release
that will end Sweeney's visits to a mental hospital. Lowenstein in
1980. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- July 30, 2000 -- INSANITY-DEFENSE-1 -- On
March 14, 1980, Dennis Sweeney, now 57, walked into a law office in
Rockefeller Plaza and shot dead Allard Lowenstein, the former
congressman whose liberal passion helped shape a decade of
civil-rights and anti-war activism. On June 30, Justice Brenda Soloff
of State Supreme Court in Manhattan ordered a conditional release
that will end Sweeney's visits to a mental hospital. Sweeney leaving
the 54th police station in 1980. (Larry C. Morris/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   On March 14, 1980, Dennis Sweeney, now 57, walked into a law office
in Rockefeller Plaza and shot dead Allard Lowenstein, the former
congressman whose liberal passion helped shape a decade of
civil-rights and anti-war activism. On June 30, Justice Brenda Soloff
of State Supreme Court in Manhattan ordered a conditional release
that will end Sweeney's visits to a mental hospital.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) COVINGTON, KY -- July 30, 2000 -- GOP-LAURA-BUSH --
Laura Bush is scheduled to deliver the first major address of the
Republican Committee, with thousands of people spread out before her,
the invisible eyes of a national television audience on her, and the
responsibility for properly jump-starting a four-day jubilee in her
hands. Laura Bush stepping onto the national stage with her husband.
(Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) CINCINNATI -- July 30, 2000 -- GOP-BUSH-ROAD-2 -- The
Bush clan is gathering once again, just as it did to watch the
father's triumphant nomination by two Republican National
Conventions. This time it is the eldest son who will take his moment
on the stage, capping a remarkable 17-month transformation from a
governor with less than two full terms in office to his party's great
hope for reclaiming the White House. Gov. George W. Bush leaving the
Hyde Park Community United Methodist Church in Cincinnati Sunday
after attending services there. (Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- July 30, 2000 -- NY-MRSCLINTON -- At
Metropolitan A.M.E. Church in Harlem Sunday, the congregation, led by
Ruth Morgan, sang "All of My Steps in the World," as Hillary Clinton
joins in. Her address at the church was warmly recieved. (Chester
Higgins Jr./The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) PHILIDELPHIA -- July 30, 2000 -- GOP-RDP -- A
Decorator, Gregory LoMonaco, puts finishing touches Sunday onm the
V.I.P. delegates seating area at the First Union Center in
Philidelphia. (Andrea Mohin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) BLUE ASH, OHIO -- July 30, 2000 -- GOP-BUSH-ROAD --
As Republicans prepare to open their connvention on Monday in
Philidelphia, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas and his wife, Laura,
campaign Sunday in a pelting rain in Blue Ash, Ohio, on their way to
the convention. (Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) PHILIDELPHIA -- July 30, 2000 -- GOP-PROTESTS --
Among the thousands of protesters who began their demonstrations
Sunday as the Republicans prepared to begin their convention in
Philidelphia were members of a group called Refuse and Resist. (Chang
W. Lee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) PHILIDELPHIA -- July 30, 2000 -- GOP-MCCAIN --
Senator John McCain leaving a "shadow convention" Sunday in
Philidelphia, where he asked the audience to support Gov. George W.
Bush. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) CHINCOTEAGUE, VA -- July 30, 2000 -- SHIP-SALVAGE-3
-- Now, for the first time, Spain is laying claim to its thousands of
lost ships, and it has won a legal battle over the issue. On July 21,
a federal appeals court in Virginia ruled that Spain owned the
remains of two warships lost off the Virginia coast two centuries
ago. Ben Benson, a salvor, with the anchor of the Juno, which sank in
1802. Benson has spent nearly $2 million on preliminary recovery work
and legal fees to retrieve two Spanish ships. (Michael Geissinger/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) PHILIDELPHIA -- July 30, 2000 -- GOP-INFO --
Philadelphia is host to the first convention to be given the full
Internet treatment. This point was made several times, on several
channels. Indeed, a whole new press area has been set up for Web
journalists. It is being called "Internet Alley." Wade Powers, in
charge of motor-pool transportation for the Republican convention,
arranged to pick up delegates yesterday in Philadelphia. (Ruth
Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNDATED -- July 30, 2000 -- SHIP-SALVAGE-2 -- Now, for
the first time, Spain is laying claim to its thousands of lost ships,
and it has won a legal battle over the issue. On July 21, a federal
appeals court in Virginia ruled that Spain owned the remains of two
warships lost off the Virginia coast two centuries ago. The research
ship of Ben Benson, a salvor. Benson has spent nearly $2 million on
preliminary recovery work and legal fees to retrieve two Spanish
ships. (Ben Benson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) SAN FRANCISCO -- July 30, 2000 -- E-COMMERCE-COLUMN --
The number of available e-comerce workers has grown, but as employees
jump off sinking ships or swim away from ones already capsized, they
are being much more selective about where they dock next. Five
employees of Bluelight.com, who opted to leave failing start-ups for
the security of an established firm. From left, Adrian Kohn, Paul
Caiozzo, Kimberly Lyons, Abigail Lyons and Sasha Petrosky. (Jenny
Thomas/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WASHINGTON -- July 30, 2000 -- GOP-DC-DELEGATE --
