<DOCNO> NYT20000730.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-30 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7808 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-WELLES-MINISERIES-2ND     07-30 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WELLES-MINISERIES-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 HOLLYWOOD: that script. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arau said the notion of remaking an Orson Welles movie ``was not
very attractive to me.'' He added: ``It's almost like a lack of
respect. But at the same time it's based on screenplay by Welles,
not the movie. It's a great, great family drama. And I look at it
as if I were doing a classic like `Romeo and Juliet' or `The
Miser.' I don't feel as if I'm stepping in Shakespeare's shoes or
Moliere's.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the producers, Arau said he believed that ``Ambersons'' was
not dated and hoped that it would stir contemporary audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``The novel and film were a critical and intelligent view of the
upper class at the turn of the century,'' he said. ``It showed how
all these huge fortunes, which they thought of as their divine
right, collapsed with the advent of the automobile.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well look what's happening now at the millennium: new fortunes
are being made because of the Internet and computers. Old fortunes
are dying. The world is changing radically. Values are changing.
Just like 100 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his life, Welles viewed ``The Magnificent Ambersons''
_ that is, his original version _ as his masterpiece. In ``This Is
Orson Welles'' (First Da Capo Press), a series of interviews with
the director Peter Bogdanovich, Welles said he had once reluctantly
seen the edited film in Paris with Andre Gide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was most unpleasant,'' Welles said. ``I would have been
happier never to know and just hear what they had done to it. For
five or six reels things weren't so bad. I thought: `Well, that
isn't so bad. They didn't do too many things _ only a few stupid
little cuts.' And then all hell broke loose. It was a much better
picture than `Kane.' If they had just left it as it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartley, the RKO chairman, said that the company initially
considered turning the drama into a feature film. But this would
have meant making a three-hour film costing $50 million to $60
million. ``It would not be a good investment,'' he said. ``The odds
are you would not find a big enough audience to make a feature film
set in this period.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, he said, making television films is much
cheaper than producing feature films _ partly because of lower
salary and production costs. Moreover, the films can be played
numerous times on A&AMP;E to recoup the investment.
</P>
<P>
   Hartley said that when he joined RKO nine years ago, the staff
there began searching through vaults for footage from various
films. They found a film can that was thought to be the footage
from ``Ambersons.'' ``There was this momentary thrill,'' Hartley
said. ``But when we opened the can the film was unrecognizable. It
had fallen apart.''
</P>
<P>
   But Robert L. Carringer, author of ``The Magnificent Ambersons:
A Reconstruction'' (University of California Press, 1993) said that
outtakes of the film were burned because of a shortage of storage
space.
</P>
<P>
   In his authoritative book on the film, Carringer said that
Welles himself shared considerable blame for the outcome of the
edited film. ``It was a string of questionable judgments and rash
actions on his part that paved the way to the film's undoing,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   This included Welles' decision to accept a proposal by the
government's Office of Inter-American Affairs, run by Nelson
Rockefeller and John Hay Whitney, to make a film in Brazil to
foster relations with Latin America. Welles left ``The Magnificent
Ambersons'' in the hands of subordinates. ``When serious
difficulties did arise, there was no one to take charge on Welles'
behalf, and his surrender of the right of final cut left the studio
free to act as it chose.''
</P>
<P>
   RKO took over the editing of the film while Welles was in Rio.
This was after a devastating preview in Pomona, Calif., before a
largely teen-age audience that had just seen the wartime musical
``The Fleet's In.'' Welles himself had ordered cuts and editing
changes before the preview _ including an almost explicit Oedipal
relationship in the movie. So what the audience members saw was a
slow-paced period drama that bored them.
</P>
<P>
   RKO's studio president, George Schaefer, gave Robert Wise, who
edited ``Citizen Kane,'' the responsibility of cutting ``The
Magnificent Ambersons.'' Wise later directed such classics as ``The
Sound of Music.'' Forty-three minutes of the Welles film were cut.
The film was tested again and virtually abandoned by the studio.
Schaefer was soon deposed as studio chief, and Welles' contract
with RKO was dropped. ``It soon became clear that he would never be
entrusted with a major production again on his own terms,'' said
Carringer.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Wise said he still recalled the first
preview. ``It was a disaster _ the audience laughed at the wrong
places,'' he said. ``It was terribly long.'' Wise, editor of the
original version, said that the studio asked him to trim the movie.
``We previewed it again, and it still wasn't right,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After further cuts, and the addition of one scene that Wise
himself directed while Welles was in Brazil, the film was played
before another preview audience. ``There were no bad laughs,'' Wise
said. ``And that's the film that went out.''
</P>
<P>
   Wise said it was absurd that Welles felt ```Ambersons'' had
destroyed his career. ``All wrong,'' he said. ``It was just a bad
time for that film. War had been declared. And audiences were not
interested in the problems of the Amberson family in Indianapolis
at the turn of the century.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen Sabinson, senior president for programming at A&AMP;E, said he
hoped that the cable network's largely adult audience would turn to
the new version of a film that may only stir vague memories now.
``It's been more than 50 years since the edited film was
released,'' Sabinson said. ``And there's a tragic story behind that
film. `The Magnificent Ambersons' was truly the passion of Orson
Welles. And his version was never released.''
</P>
</TEXT>
