<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-30 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7811 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-GOP-NYT &LR;      07-30 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GOP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: REPUBLICAN PLEASANTRIES 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, July 31:
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush knows that he cannot be elected president
unless he gets votes from many people who do not agree with him or
the Republican Party platform on issues such as abortion, gun
control, capital punishment and the privatization of Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   That is why today is gear-shifting day in Philadelphia. The
selection of Richard Cheney as his running mate and the
deliberations of the platform committee all emphasized the
conservative part of Bush's background and core vote. Once the
first session of the Republican National Convention opens Monday
evening, the nation will see four nights devoted to what Frank
Luntz, a Republican pollster, calls the politics of pleasantry.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhat paradoxically, Bush has imposed what he calls an
``iron-fist rule'' to make sure that ideology does not trump his
preferred themes of tolerance and inclusion. That means most of the
party's hard-line orators will be kept away from the microphones
inside First Union Center, site of a convention that is, in
essence, a $65 million exercise in recruiting the moderate swing
voter.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's plan for this convention reflects the lessons of 1992,
when his father's lax campaign team gave Pat Buchanan and other
polarizing speakers prime-time roles. By way of contrast, Bill
Clinton used his party's 1992 convention to play down the
Democrats' liberal tradition and to emulate the Republicans'
emphasis on fiscal responsibility and welfare reform. In
Philadelphia, Bush will attempt to borrow the positive imagery long
associated with such Democratic issues as education and the saving
of Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Given the blunt, contrary language of much of the Republican
platform, this will require some serious spinning and deft
television imagery. The effort began Sunday with such figures as
Govs. Tommy Thompson and George Pataki giving the platform a decent
burial by declaring it basically irrelevant to the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the restrictive language on abortion. According to
Pataki, what matters more is Bush's vision. In fact, whereas former
President George Bush stumbled over the vision thing, his son is
determined to make it a central theme. His emphasis will be on
positive evocative language about character, principles,
leadership, faith, hope, love, rather than on the Republican policy
positions that could make him appear authoritarian, elitist or
hostile to the interests of women and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   To offset the sparse minority representation, convention
planners have given starring roles to Bush's most prominent black
advisers, Colin Powell and Condoleezza Rice, and included a large
number of Hispanic Republicans. The prominence of entertainment
figures and musical numbers also bespeaks an effort to steer this
convention away from wedge issues.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in his role of the Democrats' uber-strategist, tried to
blow the whistle Saturday on what he sees as Bush's desire to make
this a campaign about good feelings rather than hard issues.
``That's the message, isn't it? Blur, blur, blur,'' the president
complained. Such critiques are not likely to dent the faith that
Bush and his advisers have in polls showing that voters prefer
lofty, positive generalities to bitter partisan wrangling.
</P>
<P>
   Another ``iron-fist rule'' imposed by Bush is that there should
be no prolonged attacks on Clinton, Vice President Al Gore or
Hillary Rodham Clinton. The campaign will try to be more deft in
invoking Clinton fatigue. Cheney has taken to depicting the
president as a tragic figure. In a television commercial, Bush
speaks of the Clinton years as bringing a budget surplus, but a
deficit in values.
</P>
<P>
   Not all Republicans agree with these soft tactics and the gauzy
approach summed up in Bush's slogan of compassionate conservatism.
But suppose he succeeds this week in having undecided voters focus
on his soothing, positive statements about education, health care,
Social Security and taxes, rather than on the harsh and often
unfair policy positions espoused by the platform and the Republican
congressional majority. Then Bush will be able to count this
convention a success, and Gore can count on having his hands full
this fall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-00 2313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000730.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-30 23:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7814 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-AFRICAN-OIL-NYT &LR;      07-30 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-AFRICAN-OIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE PETRO-CURSE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, July 31:
</P>
<P>
   Equatorial Guinea is a poor Central African nation that is
hoping to become a rich Central African nation. In 1996, American
companies began to pump major oil deposits from the waters around
Equatorial Guinea and production has been rising steadily. If the
new oil revenue is managed well, it can educate, heal and provide
jobs for the country's half-million people.
</P>
<P>
   But oil brings risks as well as opportunities. Rarely have
developing countries used oil money to improve the lives of the
majority of citizens or bring steady economic growth. More often,
oil revenues have caused crippling economic distortions and been
spent on showy projects, weapons and Paris shopping trips for
government officials. The people of misgoverned Equatorial Guinea
may see few benefits from their nation's oil.
</P>
<P>
   Petroleum helps a nation most when its government already has
democratic accountability, fiscal discipline and a bureaucracy that
is based on merit and is relatively free of corruption. Norway,
which first struck oil in the North Sea in 1969 and started getting
substantial income from it 10 years later, has managed its
resources wisely. Norway used oil money as a catalyst to broaden
the country's manufacturing base. It required oil investors to put
money into other industries as well. Thanks to oil, Norway now
sends three times as many people to college as it did in the
mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Most oil producers, however, do not have Norway's advantages. In
many cases, such as Nigeria, oil revenue has simply disappeared
into the overseas bank accounts of dictators and their cronies. Oil
is particularly corrupting because it is hard to keep track of and
easy to turn into cash. It is tempting to spend the sudden windfall
on pharaonic works or arms. OPEC countries spend more of their GNP
on weapons than other developing countries.
</P>
<P>
   Oil-producing countries also score lower in health and education
than many poorer nations. Kuwait has twice the per capita income of
Barbados, for example, but people in Barbados live better. The
biggest problem is that even though petroleum provides few jobs,
fluctuates wildly in price and will some day run out, the sudden
profits can lead to a reliance on oil and a withering of the rest
of the economy. Norway was cautious because it studied the
experience of the Netherlands, which suffered in the 1960s when
natural gas revenues were allowed to hide problems in other
industries.
</P>
<P>
   In Venezuela, oil allowed the central government to hire huge
numbers of unneeded workers, finance inefficient state enterprises
and obtain large loans. Oil exports also led the government to set
exchange-rate policies that made the rest of its exports
uncompetitive, which reinforced its dependence on oil.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s, when other Latin American countries were carrying
out needed economic reforms, Venezuela's oil cushion sapped the
political will for needed austerity programs. Many Venezuelans
believe that oil has also undercut the importance of personal
initiative by offering wealth without work.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of Equatorial Guinea say they are determined not to
make the mistakes of oil-rich but still-impoverished Cameroon,
Gabon and Nigeria. But even leaders aware of the pitfalls of oil
will not be able to avoid them if corruption and mismanagement are
endemic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
