<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-30 23:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7816 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-PRIESTS-AZR &LR;      07-30 1405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIESTS-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-PRIESTS-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    BILINGUAL PRIESTS ARE IN SHORT SUPPLY(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By DANIEL GONZALES(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PHOENIX) - Every Sunday after the 11 a.m. Mass ends at St.
Daniel of the Prophet Church, the pews immediately begin filling up
again - this time with Latinos who have come to worship in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Sanchez, the church's Spanish-speaking deacon, pulls back
curtains at the rear of the sanctuary, making space for an
additional 100 seats as parishioners stream into the south
Scottsdale church.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, hundreds of Latinos, the majority young couples
with children, have packed the 12:30 p.m. Mass, filling the
900-seat church.
</P>
<P>
   The explosive growth of Hispanic Catholics - fueled by
immigration and large families - is one of the biggest challenges
facing the Roman Catholic Diocese of Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The diocese, which covers Maricopa, Coconino, Mohave, and
Yavapai counties, is home to one of the fastest-growing Latino
populations in the nation. And the majority of Latinos, between 65
and 85 percent, are Catholic, said Alejandro Aguilera-Titus,
associate director for the Secretariat for Hispanic Affairs at the
National Conference of Catholic Bishops.
</P>
<P>
   The bishops concluded that the Phoenix Diocese ranks ninth among
the dioceses nationwide with the fastest-growing Latino
populations. That report was based on U.S. Census Bureau estimates
which show the Latino population in the Phoenix area grew from
113,075 to 163,385, or 44.5 percent, between 1990 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's overwhelming, the number of monolingual Spanish-speaking
people. They seem to be coming out of the woodwork,'' said the Rev.
Thomas Zurcher, vicar of priests for the Phoenix Diocese.
</P>
<P>
   The influx of Hispanic Catholics is reinvigorating many older
parishes where numbers had been declining. But a serious shortage
of Hispanic leaders, especially bilingual Latino priests, is making
it difficult to minister to the new parishioners.
</P>
<P>
   Church officials fear that some newcomers will drift away from
the Catholic Church or to Protestant sects working hard to reach
Latinos.
</P>
<P>
   So they're reaching out. More than half of the 86 parishes that
make up the Phoenix Diocese have added at least one weekly Mass in
Spanish. Several have added two or more.
</P>
<P>
   In the past three years alone, the Phoenix Diocese has added
nine Spanish Masses, bringing the total per week to 60, church
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, however, the Spanish Masses are celebrated by
White, non-Latino priests. And the Masses themselves have created
additional challenges: They allow Hispanic Catholics to maintain
their own identity and culture, but they create a divided community
within the same parish, one largely White that worships in English,
the other largely Latino that worships in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a great pastoral concern. How do you bring two diverse
groups together to form one community?'' Zurcher said.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, diversity within the Latino community also poses
a challenge for the church, Zurcher said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some Hispanics have been here generation after generation, and
others have just arrived from Mexico, so you've got multiple
concerns within the same community,'' Zurcher said.
</P>
<P>
   CHANGING DEMOGRAPHICS
</P>
<P>
   St. Daniel the Prophet Parish, at Hayden Road and Roosevelt
Street in Scottsdale, was formed in the early 1960s to serve
Motorola employees who lived and worked nearby.
</P>
<P>
   But south Scottsdale is now home to a majority of the estimated
12,490-plus in Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   As the number of Latinos attending St. Daniel's Church grew, the
parish added a Mass in Spanish, first monthly, then weekly. In the
past five years, attendance at the Spanish Mass has skyrocketed,
and it now draws Latinos from neighboring Tempe and east Phoenix,
said Sanchez, the deacon, who has been attending St. Daniel's for
20 years.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Colombia, Sanchez, 59, is fluent in English and
Spanish, and is an ordained deacon. Dressed in a long white robe
and sash, he plays a key leadership role during the 12:30 p.m. Mass
at St. Daniel's each Sunday, standing behind the pulpit to deliver
the homily in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   But the Hispanic leadership that St. Daniel's enjoys is
something missing at many Roman Catholic churches around the
Valley, capped by a severe shortage of Latino priests, church
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 247 priests serving in the Diocese of Phoenix, only 14
are Latinos. And only six of the 26 seminarians studying to become
priests in the diocese are Latinos.
</P>
<P>
   The growing pool of male Hispanic newcomers is a potential
source of new Latino priests, according to recent report by the
National Council of Catholic Bishops in Washington, D.C. But
education, language and cultural barriers work to limit their entry
into the seminary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The importance of family in the Hispanic community has such a
strong attraction to Hispanic men that it's difficult for them to
forgo that value for celibate priesthood,'' Zurcher said.
</P>
<P>
   Italians, Irish and other immigrant groups in the 19th and early
20th centuries brought their own clergy to the United States, but
that hasn't happened with newer waves of Latino immigrants, Zurcher
said.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL ISSUE
</P>
<P>
   The rapid growth of Hispanic Catholics is not isolated to border
states such as Arizona, said Armando Contreras, executive director
for the National Council for Hispanic Ministry. It is a national
issue for the Roman Catholic Church.
</P>
<P>
   The growth is being fueled at two levels: migration, both legal
and illegal, from Mexico and other parts of Latin America; and the
children of earlier arrivals, Contreras said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A large number of Latinos coming from Mexico or Central
America happen to be Catholics,'' Contreras said. ``That's part of
their culture. It's pretty much a way of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Plus, the number of Hispanic Catholics is greater than church
registration numbers indicate, church officials say.
</P>
<P>
   There are 440,226 registered Catholics in the Phoenix Diocese,
but the majority of new parishioners coming from Mexico and Central
America don't register.
</P>
<P>
   Church officials hesitate to estimate the number of unregistered
Latinos attending Masses in the Phoenix Diocese, but Jose Robles,
outreach coordinator for the Phoenix Hispanic Ministry, guesses
it's between 80,000 and 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a different worldview and I suspect a lot of them
don't register because they are fearful of difficulties with
immigration and the like,'' said Father R. Clements, pastor at St.
Mary's Catholic Church in Chandler, where one-third of the
parishioners are Latino.
</P>
<P>
   He fears that the church will lose many of the new parishioners,
who are accustomed to a more charismatic style of worship than that
found in the United States, and bring with them a different
worldview.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been my sense that they will drift away from the
(Catholic) Church or into Protestant sects that have been making
great efforts to reach this population,'' Clements said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's an issue of considerable import and gravity.
Because this influx has occurred so suddenly, the diocese has not
been able to keep up as well as we would have liked.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Clements is trying. He added a second Mass in Spanish
last October and is considering a third. He learned Spanish in the
seminary and uses it extensively in his ministry.
</P>
<P>
   The Diocese of Phoenix, like many Catholic dioceses across the
country, now requires all seminarians studying for the priesthood
to learn Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's standard operating procedure in the seminary,''
Clements said. ``You study Latin, you study biblical Greek and you
study Spanish.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Folz Sr., 69, has seen the positive side of the influx of
Catholic Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   A semiretired executive of an office equipment supplier, Folz
has been attending St. Francis Xavier Church on North Central
Avenue in Phoenix since 1941. The number of people attending Mass
on Sunday had been decreasing, but that's changing as more
Hispanics arrive, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the church added a noon Sunday Mass to
accommodate the newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go to church on Sunday and you hear children crying
again,'' Folz said. ``Which to me is invigorating. We had gotten to
be a church of old people.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach the reporter at daniel.gonzalez(a)arizona republic.com or
(602) 444-8312.
</P>
</TEXT>
