u s BC-BBO-YANKEES-TRADE-NYT     07-30 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-YANKEES-TRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAILED TRADE FORCES YANKS TO LOOK WEST
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.) (EMBARGOED until 3 a.m. for electronic media) 
By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ After working on another blockbuster three-team
deal that fell apart, the New York Yankees moved closer to
completing a trade with San Diego for pitcher Matt Clement and
outfielder Eric Owens, according to baseball officials.
</P>
<P>
   With Monday's 4 p.m. trade deadline looming, Yankees officials
were considering proposals that would improve this year's team _ at
the expense of more prospects _ as it tries to become the first
team since the 1972-74 Oakland Athletics to win three consecutive
World Series titles.
</P>
<P>
   The talks for a three-team trade with San Diego and Baltimore
that would have sent B.J. Surhoff to the Yankees broke down Sunday,
and the chances for a two-team deal including Surhoff also ended.
But the Yankees were continuing to explore a deal for Milwaukee
outfielder Jeromy Burnitz, after another proposed three-way deal
that included Montreal's Rondell White fell apart.
</P>
<P>
   This is the deal the Yankees seemed poised to make Sunday night:
Clement and Owens from San Diego for the Yankees' top prospect,
infielder Alfonso Soriano, middle reliever Jason Grimsley and a
minor league pitcher, Brandon Knight.
</P>
<P>
   Owens, a 29-year-old right-handed hitter, would play left field
for the Yankees; he is hitting .304 with four home runs and 32 runs
batted in with 20 stolen bases in 32 attempts, and is considered to
have average skills on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``What getting a left fielder would mean to us is freeing up
David Justice to DH a little bit more,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre
said. ``Otherwise, he'd play the outfield a little more than you'd
want him to, and that would be OK, too. That's what I mean, it's
not an emergency where you have to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Yankees would do with Clement is unclear. He is a
highly touted young starting pitcher who has struggled lately,
surrendering nine earned runs in 3 1/3 innings to Pittsburgh on
Friday, with a Yankees scout in attendance. The Yankees could
insert Clement into their rotation immediately and bump the
struggling David Cone, or they could try to use Clement as a middle
reliever now and put him in the rotation next year. Adding Clement
would also give the Yankees the depth and flexibility to trade
Ramiro Mendoza, who is becoming more expensive to keep each year.
</P>
<P>
   In the three-team deal with San Diego and Baltimore that was
considered, San Diego would have served as the conduit _ a
necessity because the Orioles have repeatedly rejected Yankees
offers for Surhoff. The Padres would have shipped Owens, catcher
Carlos Hernandez and a minor league outfielder, Jeremy Owens, to
the Orioles for Surhoff and the veteran catcher Greg Myers.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego then would have relayed Surhoff to the Yankees, along
with Clement _ a hard-throwing sinkerballer with a 9-10 record and
a 5.62 earned run average _ and Donne Wall, a serviceable
right-handed reliever. The Padres would have received the Yankees'
two best Triple-A prospects, Soriano and pitcher Adrian Hernandez,
as well as Grimsley and a minor league outfielder, Marcus Thames.
</P>
<P>
   But late Sunday, the Orioles began to have reservations about
the deal _ possibly because Soriano, whom they had hoped to extract
from the Yankees in return for Surhoff, would end up in San Diego.
Yankees officials also have long suspected that Baltimore would
have difficulty making a deal with a division rival.
</P>
<P>
   Surhoff has been a trade target of the Yankees since early May.
His hitting style fits in perfectly with that of the other Yankees:
He is a line-drive hitter who makes a lot of contact, and like
Justice, is a left-handed batter who hits left-handed pitchers as
well or better than right-handers. That quality presents matchup
problems for the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres want Soriano, hoping he will realize his potential to
be a top-flight offensive shortstop. The Yankees have held Soriano
out of many proposed trades because they did not want to swap a top
commodity for an outfielder. Rather, they wanted to wait until they
could acquire a good pitcher for Soriano, and the inclusion of
Clement in the trade would fill that requirement.
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Hernandez, 25, defected from Cuba, signed a $4.5 million
contract with the Yankees this summer and has ascended quickly
through the farm system. He pitched a one-hitter for Triple-A
Columbus last week, with the San Diego executive Ted Simmons in
attendance to watch Soriano play shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have also explored a trade for Burnitz, but once the
Brewers scuttled a proposed three-way deal with Montreal and the
Yankees because of White's history of injuries, the Yankees turned
to the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   But a deal for Burnitz, who is batting .218 with 22 home runs
and 61 RBI, remained a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees discussed and dismissed the possibility of trading
the Triple-A pitcher Randy Keisler to Oakland for outfielder Matt
Stairs and have known all along that if other larger deals fall
through, they can make a trade for the Rangers' Chad Curtis, a
former Yankee.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis left the Yankees in the off-season convinced that his
strong religious beliefs and his clash with Derek Jeter might have
contributed to his departure.
</P>
<P>
   Torre said Sunday: ``We're concerned about winning, and the
whole makeup of our team is that way. If someone fits
professionally on the team, that's what we concern ourselves
with.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
