<HEADER>
A7823 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-R-GOP-LAURA-BUSH-ART-     07-30 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-GOP-LAURA-BUSH-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-910(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPOTLIGHT WILL BE ON LAURA BUSH AS CONVENTION OPENS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add photo note)  (Eds: Changes dateline. Inserts names of Laura Bush's parents in
graf that begins ``Laura Bush said that her own ...'')  
(ART ADV: Photo _ NYT 17 _ is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Of the various stories about their relationship
that Laura and George W. Bush like to tell, not one gets a more
frequent and thorough workout than this: She married him only after
they had reached an agreement that she would never have to make a
political speech on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   She must have been skeptical. It was the end of 1977, and Bush
was gearing up for what would turn out to be an ill-fated campaign
for a congressional seat from west Texas, and his father was laying
the groundwork for his own ill-fated presidential bid in 1980.
These were the Bushes _ politics was in their plasma. Her vow of
silence was doomed from the start.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bush's appearance at the Republican National Convention in
Philadelphia on Monday night will be the latest _ and by far the
most nerve-frazzling _ illustration of that. She is scheduled to
deliver the first major address of the event, with thousands of
people spread out before her, the invisible eyes of a national
television audience on her, and the responsibility for properly
jump-starting a four-day jubilee in her hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get butterflies a little bit, thinking about it,'' she said
in a recent interview, adding that she remained a bit baffled by
how she got from there to here, from a placid career as an
elementary school librarian in the 1970s to the turbulent reality
of a presidential campaign that put her on a national stage,
whether she wanted to be there or not.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, too, marveled at that trajectory. ``If I'd have
said, `Honey, you'll be the kickoff speaker at the Republican
convention in the year 2000,' she would have said, `You've totally
lost your mind, and I'm not marrying you,''' he told several
reporters at the governor's mansion last week.
</P>
<P>
   The couple's remarks point to one of the most intriguing aspects
of Laura Welch Bush, a trait that sets her apart from many of her
predecessors on this path: She never aspired to it, never planned
it, never looked across the broad expanse of the future and saw
herself in a wash of light, with a microphone under her chin.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, several of her friends and acquaintances say, she
could trade it all for long afternoons of reading or mornings of
gardening and be utterly happy _ perhaps even happier.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, friends and relatives say, she has adapted to her role
in the limelight and her part as a political spouse with relative
ease and remarkable vigor, drawing on a serious (albeit quiet)
intellect to become an active first lady in Texas and to develop a
public voice and style more mellifluous than her husband's, and
maybe even more assured.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the voters who take note of Laura Bush for the first
time on Monday night will undoubtedly be surprised and impressed by
that, and will get little sense of the reluctance she openly
expressed before Gov. George W. Bush launched his campaign for the
White House last year.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Bush, the former first lady, said in a recent interview
that her daughter-in-law adhered to ``a great philosophy in life _
you can either like it or not, so you might as well like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bush said that her convention speech was, in fact, a
harbinger of more activity and a higher profile for her. With the
couple's twin 18-year-old daughters, Jenna and Barbara, heading for
college around Labor Day and leaving the Bushes with an empty nest,
Laura Bush plans to hit the campaign trail full-time, at her
husband's side and on her own.
</P>
<P>
   ``An unbelievable life experience,'' she called it in one of
four interviews over the last two months. ``An unbelievable
privilege.''
</P>
<P>
   But there were ever-present hints, in her words and gestures and
the observations of those who know her best, that her attitude
about this whole crazy pageant was much more complicated than that.
After her husband literally got choked up when he talked about her
during an event in Greensboro, N.C., three months ago, he explained
in an interview, ``I know she's making a huge sacrifice.''
</P>
<P>
   And Laura Bush made it clear that her interest was in helping
him, not promoting herself, and that she was not offering voters
two for the price of one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not running for office,'' said Laura Bush, 53. ``George is
running for office. I don't really even want to talk about issues
that much. I'm not that knowledgeable about most issues.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know about education,'' she added, mentioning the topic of
her convention speech. ``I know about things that I've worked on.
But you know, most other issues I don't know that much about. And
just to put in my 2 cents to put in my 2 cents _ I don't think it's
really necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   What a difference from four years ago, when Elizabeth Dole,
roaming among the delegates at the Republican convention with a
mobile microphone and Oprah-esque panache, was not simply singing
the praises of her husband, Bob Dole, the party's presidential
nominee, but also strutting her own political stuff. It turned out
to be a prelude to her short-lived bid for the presidency last
year.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the aisle hovered Hillary Rodham Clinton, a
first lady who had never been shy about throwing in her thoughts,
and who also had a candidacy in her future.
</P>
<P>
   But their counterparts this time, Tipper Gore and Laura Bush,
seem to be more ambivalent recruits, as content in the background
as in the foreground, yanked by their husbands' desires into races
and places that they might never have chosen for themselves.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bush, an intensely private woman, shares none of her
husband's showmanship or garrulousness; toward the end of an
interview with her aboard his campaign plane, when the governor
exuberantly jumped in to compete for the attention of the reporter
seated beside her, she promptly turned away, pulled out several
pieces of stationery and began writing thank-you notes to
acquaintances.
</P>
<P>
   ``George is always bouncing off the walls,'' observed Anne
Johnson, who has known the couple for decades and whose husband,
Clay, is the chief of staff in the governor's office. ``Laura is so
quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bush says that contrast is one reason that their union,
both personally and politically, works well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I temper that personality,'' she said, referring to
her husband's brashness, ``but I also think that he makes life much
more exciting for me.''
</P>
<P>
   But both she and her husband's advisers seem unsure at times of
how exactly to cast Laura Bush's degree of reserve.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, they clearly see her detachment from the
messier, more vainglorious dimensions of politics as an advantage:
evidence to support her husband's assertion that he, too, is a
grounded, down-to-earth person not driven by an insatiable ego or a
partisan blood lust. The way Bush praised her in a recent interview
was telling.
</P>
<P>
   ``She cuts right through, through the posturing and
positioning,'' Bush said proudly. ``America's starved for
something. I'm telling you: They're starved for something real. And
that's what she brings. She's a real person.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the Bush campaign also does not want to
present her as a bashful, timid throwback or blandly dutiful
helpmate _ an inaccurate portrait that might not play well with
female swing voters and that decidedly sells Laura Bush short.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews with other journalists in the past, Laura Bush
readily called herself shy, but she now emphatically rejects that
label. Some of her friends go out of their way to do likewise. It
is as if they all received the same memo.
</P>
<P>
   And an expression of distaste swept over her face recently when
this reporter brought up a story, which had appeared elsewhere in
print, that she had once answered a question from George W. Bush's
paternal grandmother about what she did with her life, by saying,
``I read, I smoke and I admire.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's totally made up,'' Laura Bush said. ``I'm sure I said
`I read.' But I certainly didn't say `I admire.''' (As for smoking,
Laura Bush eventually quit.)
</P>
<P>
   But Barbara Bush said in a recent interview that she remembered
both her daughter-in-law's three-part answer and her
mother-in-law's reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Bush darn near collapsed,'' Barbara Bush said, recalling
the reaction of the former president's mother.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, Laura Bush had a busy professional life as an
elementary school teacher and librarian for a decade before she
began dating George W. Bush, and she remained single, without pangs
of worry, longer than any of her close female friends. She was 31
when she and Bush married in November 1977, three months after they
met.
</P>
<P>
   Her avidity for reading is really an abiding love of literature,
and when she and Bush were living in Dallas and raising their two
daughters in the 1980s, Mrs. Bush, who had given up her career
around the time of her wedding, used her spare time to take classes
on William Faulkner, Greek tragedy and other literary topics.
</P>
<P>
   During the Republican primaries earlier this year, she was on a
Truman Capote binge, but had to interrupt it because she found
herself in the middle of ``In Cold Blood'' around the time that
Bush lost the New Hampshire contest to Sen. John McCain of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so foreboding,'' Laura Bush said of Capote's masterwork,
``and I was reading it during the most anxiety-provoking time, and
I had to quit.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to name her favorite book, she cited part of one: the
``Grand Inquisitor'' section of ``The Brothers Karamazov'' by
Dostoevsky.
</P>
<P>
   Although she said that she moved into the first lady's office in
Austin in 1995, after her husband was first elected governor, with
the expectation that ``cobwebs would grow on the phone,'' she did
not let that happen.
</P>
<P>
   Right away she became a driving force behind the inception of
the annual Texas Book Festival, which has raised about $900,000 for
the state's public libraries, and in 1998 and 1999 she helped
write, lobby for, and secure the passage of legislation that
allocated $17 million a year to improve programs to teach preschool
children in Texas to read.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bush also has a sassy streak that gets scant attention.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, George W. Bush occasionally joked in public speeches
that his wife had a librarian's narrow concept of oratory, and it
amounted to a single syllable: ``Shhhh!'' Laura Bush was not
amused.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a speech, to kid him, to get back at him, I said he was a
gregarious businessman who thought that a bibliography was the
biography _ the story _ of the person who wrote the Bible,'' she
recalled. She laughed heartily at the memory of her little act of
revenge.
</P>
<P>
   And she has an adventurous impulse: For her 40th and 50th
birthdays, she went river-rafting with four close female friends,
including a Democratic state senator from Kansas and a midwife from
San Francisco who recently visited Indonesia to teach classes on
childbirth. Around Austin, Laura Bush maintains a similarly
eclectic mix of social acquaintances.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives and friends say that the governor often solicits her
advice, asking for her intuition about people and situations, and
she serves as his filter for much of what gets written about him in
newspapers and magazines, which she seems to monitor more closely
than he does. He often tells reporters not what he thought of their
articles but what she did.
</P>
<P>
   It is not at all clear that she shares his positions on
sensitive issues. He opposes abortion; she declines to elucidate
her feelings. He has presided over more executions than any other
governor; she does not comment on the death penalty either.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in so many ways, she has followed his lead. He ran for
governor despite her expressed fears about the privacy that their
family would lose. Then he upped the ante by running for president,
even though she had talked publicly about her trepidation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never say to George, for something that he really
wanted to do, that he couldn't do that,'' Laura Bush said, adding
that he, too, would never deny her something that she deemed
important. People who know the couple well have said that his
decision to quit drinking 14 years ago was partly a response to her
entreaties and to a growing worry that he was endangering his
marriage and family life, which he cherished.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bush said that her own family life had been a stable and
deeply loving one. She grew up as an only child in Midland, where
her father, Harold B. Welch, was a successful home builder and her
mother, Jenna Welch, kept his books. Although neither of her
parents finished college, they let Laura know early that they
expected her to do so, and she was a conscientious, excellent
student who never got into trouble.
</P>
<P>
   She was acutely aware of her mother's other failed attempts to
have a child, several of which ended in premature babies who died
within days, and, perhaps as a result, she said: ``I felt very
obligated to my parents. I didn't want to upset them in any way.''
</P>
<P>
   She and George W. Bush, who also grew up in Midland, went to
different elementary schools but were in the seventh grade together
at the same middle school, although neither of them remembers
knowing the other well. She stayed in Midland while he went to
Philips Academy in Andover, Mass. She and her friends described her
high school years as happy and generally uneventful.
</P>
<P>
   But one day in 1963, when she was 17, she drove through a stop
sign and hit another car. Its occupant, a boy who happened to be a
close friend, was killed in the collision, which was deemed an
accident; no charges were filed against her. Laura Bush said that
she was steeled for the incident to come up during her husband's
presidential campaign, as it did earlier this year, but she
nonetheless tensed at the mention of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a terrible, terrible thing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1964, she headed to Southern Methodist University
in Dallas, where her major was education. It was a conventional
choice, and one that she briefly doubted in the years after her
graduation in 1968. Feminism had come into vogue; she was reading
some of the books that the movement had spawned, and she said she
told her father that he should not have ``programmed'' her to be a
teacher when she could have been a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Daddy almost immediately pulled out his wallet,'' she
recalled, ``and said, `I'll send you to law school.' He would have
loved to.''
</P>
<P>
   But she remembered: ``I had to admit, when he did that, that I
didn't want to be a lawyer. I wanted to be a teacher.''
</P>
<P>
   She taught in inner-city elementary schools in Dallas and
Houston for three years, living at one time in the same apartment
complex in Houston as her future husband, who was then a pilot in
the Texas Air National Guard. But her place was on the quiet wing,
and his was on the rowdy one, and they never crossed paths.
</P>
<P>
   After getting a master's degree in library science from the
University of Texas in 1973, she settled in Austin, where she
worked as an elementary school librarian. She said that she never
lacked for dates but did not find the right man until, in the
summer of 1977, she visited Midland, where Bush was making his way
in the oil business. A couple who knew them both invited them for a
backyard barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   Bush talked and talked. Laura Welch listened and listened. The
next night, he took her out for a game of miniature golf. And three
months later they married.
</P>
<P>
   Adjustments were necessary. She was persuaded to make her first
political speech the next year, when he waged his unsuccessful
campaign for Congress. He learned to conform to her standards of
tidiness and order, which were so high that one of her friends, Jan
O'Neill, recalled that Laura Bush organized the books in the
couple's bedroom in accordance with the Dewey decimal system.
</P>
<P>
   At Bush family gatherings, she made an unusual addition to the
sometimes rambunctious clan. Her husband recalled his parents and
siblings sitting around the table in Kennebunkport, Maine, their
plates clean, while they watched and waited patiently for his wife
to pick her way through her meal.
</P>
<P>
   The couple wanted a large family of their own, tried for several
years without success, and had already begun the adoption process
when she finally learned that she was pregnant with fraternal
twins.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, the outlook was uncertain; she developed toxemia, and
her doctor told her that she would be lucky to deliver one healthy
child. Laura Bush said that whenever she went to the grocery store,
she avoided the aisle with diapers and baby-related items, because
she did not want to stoke her hopes.
</P>
<P>
   Friends say she has been a fiercely devoted mother. They also
say she has been an integral part of her husband's success, not
because she is a second engine of his ambition but because she is a
shock absorber, keeping him calm and stable, and occasionally
keeping his mischievous and arrogant streaks in check.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rein it in, Bubba,'' she told him one day on his campaign
plane, as he held forth at length in front of reporters. Privately,
when she catches him ribbing people mercilessly or strutting
shamelessly, she simply murmurs, ``Bushieee,'' her voice rising at
the end. He knows what that means.
</P>
<P>
   She says she has not given extensive thought to what kind of
first lady she might make, but her mother-in-law has some ideas.
Barbara Bush said her daughter-in-law would be different from
Hillary Clinton because she would ``not get into foreign affairs or
controversial subjects.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she would rather make a positive impact on the
country,'' Barbara Bush said. ``And I'm not criticizing Mrs.
Clinton. But it's like oil and water. We're talking about two
different subjects. They're two different people. I think Laura
thinks of others.''
</P>
<P>
   She also said her daughter-in-law would be ``better, much
better'' in the role than she was. ``She won't be a fat,
white-haired old lady,'' Barbara Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   She would also be less voluble, and in many ways less
accessible, because there are tight boundaries around what Laura
Bush is willing to offer for public consumption.
</P>
<P>
   That was evident last September, when she accompanied her
husband to an outdoor memorial service for the seven people killed
by a gunman at a church in Fort Worth. She wore sunglasses, which
she never took off. But every so often, she lifted a tissue to her
face, delicately tucked it behind her dark lenses and then quickly
put it away.
</P>
<P>
   The gesture was easy to miss, as she clearly intended it to be.
Campaign or no campaign, Laura Bush was not about to share her
tears.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
