<DOCNO> NYT20000730.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-30 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7834 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GOP-POLL-1STLD-WRITET     07-30 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-POLL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP DELEGATES ARE TO THE RIGHT OF RANK AND FILE, POLL FINDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ADDS editor's note; ADDS margin of error in 8th graf)  
 (Eds: This is now the lede of the paper) 
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY with JANET ELDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ At a time when Gov. George W. Bush of Texas has
sought to portray the Republican Party as increasingly moderate,
the majority of delegates assembling here Sunday to nominate him
for president are notably conservative in thought and spirit,
according to a New York Times/CBS News poll of delegates.
</P>
<P>
   On a host of important issues, from affirmative action to
environmental concerns to abortion, the poll found that delegates
stand significantly to the right of much of the nation, and even of
rank-and-file Republican voters.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a majority of the 2,066 delegates described themselves
as somewhat or very conservative, and their views on a variety of
topics reflected that.
</P>
<P>
   The delegates by and large supported large tax cuts and school
vouchers, and oppose gun control, restrictions on trade,
environmental safeguards, abortion rights, prescription drug
subsidies for the elderly and campaign finance regulation. In one
notable example of the contrast between the delegates and
Republican voters, the Times/CBS poll found that fewer than half
the delegates said they supported mandatory child safety trigger
locks on guns, a measure that was supported by eight out of 10
registered Republican voters.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush has sought for much of this year to distinguish
himself from his party's conservative wing and history, most
delegates interviews Sunday viewed him as conservative, if not
necessarily as conservative as they considered themselves. They are
also, overwhelmingly, enthusiastic about the qualifications and
political skills of the man they will nominate for president on
Thursday night, and confident about his chances against Vice
President Al Gore, the presumptive Democratic nominee, in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``The party has a conservative wing and a moderate wing and both
sides are comfortable with him,'' Eric Melgren, a delegate from
Kansas, said of Bush. ``Republicans are hungry enough that there
is, to at least some degree, things that all are willing to
overlook.''
</P>
<P>
   The finding in the Times/CBS poll, as well as in follow-up
interviews conducted Sunday with delegates, suggested one of the
tasks Bush faces this week: convincing independents and moderate
Democrats, in particular, that his is the face of the Republican
Party, rather than of the delegates who will be celebrating his
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The poll of the delegates was conducted by The New York Times
and CBS News by telephone, mail, fax, e-mail and over the Internet
from June 26 through July 28. Of the 2,066 Republican delegates,
1,055 responded to the questionnaire. &UR;  &LR; The poll had a margin of
sampling error of plus or minus two percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   The delegates who began arriving here this weekend are, the poll
found, overwhelmingly white _ almost 90 percent _ and mostly male
and middle-age. By profession, they are more likely to be lawyers
and executives than teachers or farmers. They are relatively
wealthy: one in five put their net worth at $1 million or more.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly one in five said they belonged to the National Rifle
Association, and over half said they or someone in their house
owned a gun.
</P>
<P>
   For much of this campaign, Bush has sought to draw some distance
between himself and conservatives in the party _ and, it seems, he
has paid little price for that among the Republicans here. In
contrast to surveys of rank-and-file Republican voters, the poll of
the delegates found that they were more apt to describe Bush as
conservative. Indeed, in a tribute to Bush's political skills,
delegates who described themselves as moderate viewed Bush as one,
too, while self-described conservatives called him conservative.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Buxton, a delegate from Maine who described herself as
moderate, offered this description of the governor on Sunday: ``I
see him as a moderate with some conservative areas.''
</P>
<P>
   But another delegate from Maine, Elaine Bridge, who described
herself as conservative, challenged the description almost as soon
as it left Buxton's mouth. ``I think he's a conservative,'' she
said. ``More so than his dad.''
</P>
<P>
   As a rule, people who attend political conventions tend to be
more informed and more partisan, and past polls have noted similar
differences in views between the delegates and the public. Still,
this year's poll suggested a wide disparity between voters and
delegates at a time when Bush has been trying to pull the party to
the center as Republicans seek to win the White House for the
Republican Party, which has lost the last two presidential
elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a conservative party,'' Mike Davis, an alternate
delegate from South Carolina, said Sunday afternoon as he sat on a
bench outside Independence Hall. ``We want lower taxes. Less
government.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the prevailing national sentiment found in other
polls, the delegates said they believed that the nation's budget
surplus should go to cutting taxes, rather than assuring the
solvency of Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   They overwhelmingly opposed a ban on the kind of largely
unregulated campaign contributions known as soft money. They also
opposed a proposed plan to help make prescription drugs more
affordable to the elderly by having the federal government pay
subsidies to insurance companies, allowing insurers to pass the
cost savings along to customers.
</P>
<P>
   Four out of 10 delegates said they believed the federal
government was doing too much when it came to regulating the
environmental and safety practices of business.
</P>
<P>
   And the delegates were also more likely to support the death
penalty, and oppose life in prison without parole, as an
appropriate punishment for convicted murderers. Nearly 80 percent
of the delegates said their views on the death penalty had not been
changed by reports of people on death row who later were found to
be innocent.
</P>
<P>
   Although the delegates were overwhelmingly opposed to abortion
rights, only two in 10 said that Bush would consider the issue when
nominating judges to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Howard, 48, a California delegate, said that Bush's views of
government closely hewed to her own.
</P>
<P>
   ``He believes in less government and more individual
responsibility,'' Howard said. ``He probably leans toward the
conservative side, but he's accepting of people and he doesn't
focus on areas where we disagree.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush sees a lot of potential and wants to keep government out
of the way,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, reflecting the spirit of the occasion, the delegates
viewed Bush's candidacy with enthusiasm _ indeed, with more
enthusiasm than had been voiced by registered Republicans.
Forty-two percent of Bush's supporters across the nation said they
supported him with reservations. Only 4 percent of the delegates
said they felt the same way.
</P>
</TEXT>
