<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BIOSCOPE (COLUMN) _ &LR;  Most people think of cloning as the production
of carbon-copy creatures, a practice that might be acceptable when
it comes to making sheep, but morally suspect when it comes to
making babies.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Eibert, an attorney and cloning advocate in Half Moon Bay,
thinks most people are wrong.  &UR; COLUMN BY TOM ABATE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; RADIATION _ &LR;   &LR;   &LR; Marybelle Riley sat in the hospital waiting room
making small talk, with a patch over one eye _ the one caught in
the grip of a virulent tumor that clutched at her optic nerve.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cancer is way up under here,'' said Riley, 89, brushing
her lower left eyelid.
</P>
<P>
   In a lead-lined room down the hall, technicians prepped the
computer-driven linear accelerator that would soon travel in a wide
arc over Riley's body. Along that path, it would emit hundreds of
high-energy X-ray bursts of varying intensity, following a firing
pattern calculated to disintegrate the tumor without damaging the
eye.  &UR; BY TOM ABATE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TECH21 (COLUMN) _ &LR;  There will be no Tech 21 column this week.
Henry Norr is on vacation.
</P>
</TEXT>
