<HEADLINE>
CHANG'S TEARS FLOW AFTER VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GERRY GITTELSON  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Michael Chang was so emotional about winning
Sunday's Mercedes-Benz Cup over Jan-Michael Gambill that Chang
broke down and cried immediately afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Chang later said even he was a little surprised by the tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, in public I'm pretty good,'' Chang said. ``I can't
remember getting that emotional in public since 1989 when I won the
French Open. Usually I'm pretty tough. But right before I started
crying I could actually kind of feel it coming up. I started
thinking about other things so I wouldn't cry.''
</P>
<P>
   At least they showed up: Considering all the star power the
tournament lost - the biggest blows were top-seeded Andre Agassi's
injury-related withdrawal and third-seeded Marcelo Rios' default in
his first match because of profanity - attendance wasn't so bad.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament drew 76,987 over the seven days, 7,027 on Sunday.
Last year Agassi and Pete Sampras played in the final, and the
tournament drew 81,433 for the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say the crowds were pretty good actually, considering all
the players we lost for injuries and other reasons,'' spokesman
Toby Zwikel said. ``The people who did attend saw some really good
tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   Striking the iron: Chang, who grew up in Orange County, won't
have much time to whoop it up with old friends. He's scheduled to
compete in the Tennis Masters Series in Toronto this week. He'll
probably start Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Lighting the fire: Gambill became very angry at the officials in
the first-set tiebreaker over a disputed call.
</P>
<P>
   The point gave Chang a 3-2 lead in the tiebreaker, but Gambill
was inspired. He won the next five to take the set, including four
aces.
</P>
<P>
   Rocket power: In the first set Gambill's serve was a monster. He
registered 12 aces - the most Chang has given up in recent memory -
compared to Chang's two.
</P>
<P>
   Gambill finished with 16 aces in two sets. He said he purposely
gave his serves everything he had because his sore knee hampered
his mobility.
</P>
<P>
   In case anyone was wondering: Considering Gambill wasn't able to
finish the Chang match because of a sprained ankle, there was no
way he was going to compete in the evening doubles championship
with partner Scott Humphries against Paul Kilderry and Sandon
Stolle. The match was forfeited.
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers: Chang, who entered the tournament ranked No. 34
in the ATP, probably will move up to 22 today, according to
officials. Gambill, who entered at 32, figures to be ranked 25th
today.
</P>
</TEXT>
